<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PREDICTIONS OF CARNAGE MISS THEIR MARK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A recent Cato Institute analysis of higher speed limits brought
more bad news for nanny-state advocates.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did the research reveal how motoring has become safer
by almost every measure, but also estimated the net economic
benefit of repealing the federal speed-limit law at between $2
billion and $3 billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   The report, which bases many of its findings on data from the
National Highway Traffic Safety Administration and National Safety
Council, was written by Stephen Moore, Cato's director of fiscal
policy studies.
</P>
<P>
   When Congress repealed the 55-mph federal speed limit, the
president of Advocates for Highway and Auto Safety predicted on
national television that it would result in 6,400 more deaths a
year and millions more injuries. Ralph Nader predicted ``history
will never forgive Congress for this assault on the sanctity of
human life.''
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, what Congress really assaulted was the claim that
speed kills, which has never been validated by either real-life
experience or scientific inquiry. It also assaulted a law most
motorists openly flouted with the unspoken cooperation of many in
law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   In the two years after repeal of the ``double nickel,'' the Cato
study notes, the traffic death rate dropped to a record low level.
As for road injuries, there were 66,000 fewer in 1997 than in 1995,
and the injury rate per 100 million vehicle miles traveled dropped
to the lowest rate ever recorded.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the injury rate had been as high in 1997 as it had been in
1995,'' Moore said, ``approximately 17,000 more Americans would
have been injured on roads.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cato study echoed earlier such analyses showing how higher
speed limits had failed to produce the carnage opponents had
predicted. Such good news usually has been met with claims that the
explanation lies in improved vehicle safety features and better
roads instead of anything having to do with speed limits. Thus,
advocates of the 55-mph limit argue, the results would have been
even better if speed limits hadn't been increased.
</P>
<P>
   The Cato study controlled for other safety factors, however, by
taking into account the number of crashes. While crashes did
increase by 65,000 from 1995 to 1997, crashes nevertheless fell as
a percentage of miles traveled. Also, Moore said, pedestrian
fatalities declined, which indicates that motorists aren't driving
more recklessly as a result of higher speed limits.
</P>
<P>
   Proof that the latest findings aren't an anomaly, Moore said, is
that fatalities and injuries also declined as a percentage of miles
traveled after the federal government eased speed-limit
restrictions on some interstates in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Another prediction that failed to materialize was the $20
billion in extra costs to taxpayers and insurance policyholders
that were forecast to result from more accidents, injuries and
deaths. As it turned out, both claims and insurance premiums began
declining, which reversed a decade-long trend.
</P>
<P>
   Are those who predicted more death and suffering happy they were
wrong? Not so you can tell. When the person who predicted 6,400
more deaths was asked about the missed forecast, her reply was,
``We didn't say it was going to happen overnight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
