<HEADLINE>
TEENS TRY TO KEEP YOUNG DRIVERS FROM HOPPING HILLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ERICA WOOD  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kansas City, Mo. _ Twice this week, Jordan Miller and a bunch of
his friends descended on Argo Road in rural eastern Jackson County,
Mo., hoping to stop another tragedy from happening this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Eight to 10 teens flagged down cars and encouraged drivers to
cut their speed in memory of two friends killed while ``hill
hopping'' on that road last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Drivers who hill hop try to gain speed while climbing a hill so
they become airborne when they reach the crest. The practice
produces a thrill similar to riding a roller coaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``They go down there just to see if they can break 100,'' said
Miller, 17, of Independence.
</P>
<P>
   Miller's 16-year-old friends, Eric L. Wion and Charles E.
Brennam, both of Independence, were killed last Saturday when Wion
lost control of his maroon Ford Probe and hit a utility pole.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities have speculated that hill hopping in June caused the
death of Independence teen-ager Mike Motter, who was riding in a
car that also hit a power pole.
</P>
<P>
   Both accidents occurred on a hilly stretch of Argo Road, just
east of Independence and north of Blue Springs.
</P>
<P>
   Wion's mother, Nancy Wion, says she intends to put up a
billboard on Argo Road listing the names of the three dead teens
and asking drivers to think about them before speeding.
</P>
<P>
   She also wants to put the Ford Probe in front of Truman High
School during fall registration as a reminder of what can happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a dangerous thing, and the kids are drawn to it (hill
hopping),'' Wion said. ``I'd like to see kids think a couple of
times before they go speeding on Argo Road.''
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Graham Kempster of the Jackson County Sheriff's Department
said the surviving teen-ager in Saturday's crash, Brennam's younger
brother, had acknowledged that the teen-agers were ``hill
hopping.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill hopping is not a new phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   Two Grandview High School students died in March 1997 after hill
hopping on East 129th Street in south Kansas City. In March 1996,
four North Kansas City High School students were similarly killed
in a 1966 Ford Mustang on North Cleveland Avenue near Russell Road.
</P>
<P>
   And last year Shawnee officials took steps to prevent hill
jumping on a stretch of West 67th Street.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, the teen who warned motorists on Argo Road, knows his
message wasn't heeded by everyone. Most people did slow down, but
others simply ignored the teens and continued speeding.
</P>
<P>
   He wonders whether it would help to widen the shoulders on Argo
Road and to add more police patrols _ and possibly speed bumps _ in
the area.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson County Sheriff's Capt. Ron Kellogg said speed bumps and
widened shoulders would be of little help. He said that the
Sheriff's Department did what it ccould with periodic speed traps
but that drivers needed to obey the 35 mph speed limit.
</P>
<P>
   Kempster suggests parents educate their children on the dangers
of hill hopping. He said inexperienced drivers don't realize how
easy it is to lose control at high speeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sorry situation that some of the decisions young people
are making are costing them their lives and other people's lives,''
Kempster said, ``along with severely injuring and disabling
others.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
