<SLUG> BC-POLLUTION-PROBE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EPA OFFICIALS ANNOUNCE INVESTIGATION INTO GIANT HOG PRODUCER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MANSUR  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kansas City, Mo. _ Federal officials announced Friday that they
have begun a new pollution investigation into the giant hog
producer Premium Standard Farms in north Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation, although in its early stages, ``has already
revealed significant violations of the Clean Water Act,'' U.S.
Environmental Protection Agency officials said.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the U.S. Department of Justice, on behalf of the
EPA, filed legal motions in U.S. District Court in Kansas City to
intervene in a federal lawsuit filed against Premium Standard Farms
by citizens of north Missouri. The citizens group has accused
Missouri's largest hog producer of repeated discharges of animal
wastes into streams in violation of federal clean water laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not aware of any violations,'' Charlie Arnot, a
spokesman for Premium Standard Farms, said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   EPA officials from Washington have recently been on Premium
Standard Farms property, Arnot said, but reports from those
inspectors sounded positive.
</P>
<P>
   He said his company saw no new allegations in the Justice
Department's motion to intervene. ``The claims have not changed and
the facts have not changed.''
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department, if allowed into the case, would seek
fines of $25,000 per day for each violation before Jan. 31, 1997,
and $27,500 for violations after that date.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Missouri Attorney General Jay Nixon is
negotiating to settle allegations of pollution violations in a
state lawsuit against the hog producer.
</P>
<P>
   But federal officials made clear Friday that their concerns go
beyond the allegations in that case. They include new violations,
identified only recently in the EPA's investigation begun out of
the agency's Washington offices, not its regional offices in Kansas
City, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   The statement, prepared jointly by the EPA and the Justice
Department in Washington, suggested the federal motion to intervene
may affect the state negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``EPA and the Department of Justice are hopeful that the
motion...will encourage all parties to come together to discuss a
settlement that will bring Premium Standard Farms in compliance
with federal and state laws, improve water quality and protect the
welfare of the residents of the three county area.''
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general's office had a representative in Washington
to meet this week with Justice Department attorneys about the new
legal motions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We welcome their involvement for this important issue,'' said
Mary Still, a spokeswoman for the attorney general. ``At this point
we don't know how it will affect our settlement talks.''
</P>
<P>
   The EPA initiated the investigation at the request of Citizens
Legal Environmental Action Network, a request made 45 days ago.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Speer, an attorney for the environmental group in its
federal case, said the EPA's actions this week will have national
significance.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be, I believe, one of the most closely watched
environmental cases in the nation,'' Speer said.
</P>
<P>
   Premium Standard Farms, the third largest hog producer in the
nation, raises more than 2.5 million hogs a year in the north
Missouri counties of Mercer, Putnam and Sullivan. The operations
produce 750 million gallons of hog wastes, stored in lagoons and
later sprayed onto more than 40,000 acres of Missouri farm fields.
</P>
<P>
   The company has had numerous pollution problems over the years
including fish kills and waste spills. The most recent occurred
this month when a work crew left open a valve on its spraying
equipment, allowing up to 2,000 gallons of wastes into Raccoon
Creek, according to a Premium Standard Farms statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Incidents like this are unacceptable,'' said John Meyer, the
company's chief executive. ``An incident like this is particularly
disappointing in light of the hard work and substantial resources
we have dedicated to environmental improvements in the last three
years.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ozark chapter of the Sierra Club, which has worked closely
with the citizens network in its legal actions against Premium
Standard Farms, welcomed the federal intervention efforts, as well
as the new investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thankfully, the federal government has stepped in to save
Missouri from itself,'' said Ken Midkiff, program director for the
Sierra Club in Missouri. ``The settlement negotiations appeared to
provide more protection for the polluter than the public health and
welfare.''
</P>
<P>
   The terms of the settlement have not been revealed. But Midkiff
said last week that a draft settlement has proposed that Premium
Standard Farms pay a $1 million fine and install up to $25 million
in new anti-pollution equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Midkiff has criticized the settlement, saying the fines were not
steep enough and the terms didn't ensure that the new pollution
equipment would be installed.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Dye, agriculture coordinator for the Missouri Sierra Club,
said intervention from Washington was needed because state
regulators and officials in the EPA's regional office have failed
to act.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been talking to them for years, and it doesn't smell any
better today in north Missouri,'' Dye said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
