<SLUG> BC-Y2K-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW CENTURIES ARE OLD HAT FOR OLATHE BANK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FINN BULLERS and DAVID HAYES  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kansas City, Mo. _ The 112-year-old First National Bank of
Olathe has been down this road before.
</P>
<P>
   After opening on June 15, 1887, as the first nationally
chartered bank in Johnson County, the bank has been through one
moment of end-of-century angst without the world ending. And it
says it's ready to do it again.
</P>
<P>
   To prove their point, bank officials in Olathe plan to open
their doors at 9 a.m. Jan. 1, 2000 _ a Saturday and a national
holiday. The doors will stay open until noon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't think of a better way to celebrate the new year
and the new millennium than to provide our customers this special
convenience and reassurance that their bank is ready to serve
them,'' said Dennis Meyer, president and chief executive officer of
the bank.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday hours on a national holiday ``sends a message to
customers, `Yeah, we're ready for Y2K, bring it on,' '' said Jim
Maag, executive vice president of the Kansas Bankers Association.
</P>
<P>
   Maag said he thought the plan to be open Jan. 1 was a first for
Kansas, but he expects other ``We're ready for Y2K'' campaigns to
sprout in the next six months. Federal regulators require banks to
inform customers of their efforts to battle the bug.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're leaving nothing to chance,'' said Mike Major, chairman
of the bank's Y2K committee.
</P>
<P>
   Having met the June 30 deadline set by federal regulators to
test its mission-critical systems, the Olathe bank is focusing on
reassuring its customers that their money is safe.
</P>
<P>
   Similar efforts are playing out across the country, where 98
percent of all banks are considered Year 2000-ready. Bank tellers
are wearing ``Ask Me About Y2K'' buttons, and banks are having Y2K
Community Conversations and sponsoring radio spots to warn about
potential scams.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing all kinds of advertising and public service
announcements,'' said Charlotte Birch, public relations director
for the American Bankers Association, which represents 6,000 large
and small banks across the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what else you can do but stand on your head and
spit nickels.''
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve Board isn't spitting nickels but has taken
an unusual step. This week, central bank governors voted to make
special loans to banks, thrifts and credit unions that might need
emergency funds because of consumer fear about Y2K.
</P>
<P>
   The loans, to be offered from Oct. 1 to April 7, are designed to
help financial institutions ``more confidently commit'' to making
loans to other banks during the Year 2000 transition.
</P>
<P>
   The interest rate charged by the Fed will be slightly higher
than the prevailing federal funds rate of 4.97 percent, which banks
charge each other for overnight loans.  &LR; brk:Cleared for takeoff
 &LR; tx:Y2K problems in the nation's air traffic control system have
been eliminated, the Transportation Department said this week.
</P>
<P>
   An independent firm examined and approved system repairs
completed June 30 by the Federal Aviation Administration. The FAA's
independent inspector general's office also has certified the
system as Y2K-ready.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K watchers have been dogging the FAA for more than a year,
contending the agency that monitors the nation's aircraft traffic
wouldn't be ready for the Jan. 1 date change. The Transportation
Department, the FAA's parent agency, has repeatedly received
failing grades on Y2K report cards filed by a congressional
committee.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA has 628 computer systems. Of those, 424 were designated
mission-critical, meaning they are vital to the operation of the
agency. Of the 424 systems, 152 required Year 2000 repairs.
</P>
<P>
   The Y2K certification came from Science Applications
International Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA, which in April conducted a live test in Denver, will
continue tests for the rest of the year, agency officials said. The
FAA is also drawing up contingency plans for power outages or other
outside problems.  &LR; brk:Pentagon passes muster  &LR; tx:Based on tests
earlier this month, Pentagon officials are confident that their
network of 1,069 computer systems designed to track the hardware of
warfare will work without a glitch during 21st-century combat.
</P>
<P>
   To carry out tests for ordering, shipping and receiving
everything from toilet paper to bullets, logistics officials
created a parallel computer environment that mimicked the real
system. The virtual time machine simulated the 64th day of the year
2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know what we don't know, so at some point we could
have some surprises,'' military official Roger Kallock told Reuters
news agency.
</P>
<P>
   During testing, three glitches appeared in mission-critical
systems that previously were certified as Y2K-ready. Those glitches
occurred during efforts to transfer data to outside sources from
the Army, Navy and U.S. Transportation Command.
</P>
<P>
   The problems were considered minor and are being fixed, said the
U.S. Joint Interoperability Test Command.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Department officials said they considered the test to be
the largest of a linked U.S. computer system.
</P>
<P>
   The Office of Management and Budget says the military will spend
$3.65 billion on Y2K, nearly half the entire federal year 2000
budget of $8.2 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
