<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-ANALYSIS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME ANGELS ARE BAD LOSERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Word is that Chuck Finley did some serious damage to a water
cooler and a TV at Edison Field after a game the other day. This
action is not unusual after a bad game during a frustrating Anaheim
Angels season.
</P>
<P>
   The difference is that Finley had just finished pitching his
best game in six weeks. He gave up only one run and three hits in
72/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Finley's performance, the Angels lost the game in the
10th inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels have had to deal with many losses this season. Losses
on the field, and the loss of many key players to injury.
</P>
<P>
   Losing happens, but the issue here is how to deal with it.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels are 13{ games out of first in the AL West, mired in
an eight-game losing streak. The season, barring a miracle, is all
but lost.
</P>
<P>
   So how do they deal with it?
</P>
<P>
   Not well, if history is any indication. Each player has his way
of dealing with losing. Who is to say which is right and which is
wrong?
</P>
<P>
   Some Angels apparently have decided their way of dealing with
losing is the only way. Players and others close to the team say
the clubhouse is divided because of it.
</P>
<P>
   There's a group of players that dislikes seeing others leave the
clubhouse with smiles on their faces after a loss. Maybe these
Angels should take their own advice, as displayed on a T-shirt that
some wear under their jerseys: ``Shut up and play.''
</P>
<P>
   No better example of that came late last season as the Angels
lost their division lead in September to the Texas Rangers. Players
were upset because Jim Edmonds maintained a friendly disposition
during the collapse. Because he bounced around the clubhouse with a
carefree attitude.
</P>
<P>
   But Edmonds and Tim Salmon were the only players to produce in
September. Edmonds hit .340 with a team-high five homers and 20 RBI
that month.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds is still recovering from shoulder surgery, so the team
has found others to worry about.
</P>
<P>
   Gary DiSarcina made a good point last month when his return from
injury coincided with the contract extension of manager Terry
Collins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes the focus gets blurred,'' DiSarcina said.
``Situations with what the manager is doing, or what (general
manager) Billy Bavasi is doing blurs your focus from what the team
needs to focus on, which is winning each game.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the focus has shifted from Collins' situation to demeanor in
the clubhouse. And the result is the club has gone from 6{ games
out at the All-Star break to the brink of trading Finley and others
because the season is lost.
</P>
<P>
   Bavasi now must deal with a lost season himself. Does he trade
Finley, Ken Hill, Garret Anderson? Bavasi has about a week to
decide, all the while knowing that a trade of Finley sends a
message to the clubhouse: We're done, get ready for next year.
</P>
<P>
   For Angels fans, the message is a little different: Are you
ready for some football?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-99 0030EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
