<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-CUBS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME FEELS A LITTLE BIT LIKE THE ROAD AS METS TOP CUBS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On Merengue Night at Shea Stadium, the theme played
out so strongly that manager Bobby Valentine of the Mets criticized
the timing of turning the evening into what appeared to him to be
basically another road game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a nice night for the fans,'' a steaming Valentine said
after the Mets had rallied from three runs down for a 5-4 victory
over the Chicago Cubs to pull within 1 1/2 games of the Atlanta
Braves for the first time since May 26. ``But I wish they all were
Mets fans. It's a shame this team never gets any appreciation in
its own home park.
</P>
<P>
   ``To honor a visiting player the night after Orel Hershiser
records his 200th victory, and there's nothing on the scoreboard.
Rickey Henderson set some records on the road trip that just ended
and he comes up to pinch hit and they're playing merengue. Maybe
we'll get it together one of these days. I think they'll get it
together.''
</P>
<P>
   In his own words, Valentine was venting the feelings of his
players, who were upset at the sometimes unfriendly atmosphere with
the Mets in a pennant race and just back from a 6-2 road trip.
</P>
<P>
   To the delight of the sellout crowd of 52,135, Sammy Sosa, the
guest of honor and the Dominican Republic's favorite son, hit a
three-run home run off Masato Yoshii in the first inning not long
after Sosa had been honored for the 66 home runs he hit last
season.
</P>
<P>
   The fans cheered almost as hard in the seventh inning, when Mike
Piazza, who once spent a winter in the Dominican Republic to work
on his catching skills, shattered his bat but still lined what
turned out to be the game-winning single off Scott Sanders to break
a 4-4 tie.
</P>
<P>
   And the night's biggest cheers were reserved for Turk Wendell,
who struck out Sosa in the eighth to preserve the lead, and the
Dominican right-hander Armando Benitez, who struck out two in
pitching a perfect ninth for his ninth save of the year.
</P>
<P>
   On a day the Mets traded for a new No. 2 starter in Kenny
Rogers, the speculation was whether Yoshii would eventually be
shifted to the bullpen when Valentine returns to a five-man
rotation in what is, for at least one turn, a six-man starting
staff.
</P>
<P>
   The question arose because Yoshii struggled through his third
rough outing in his last four starts. The 34-year-old right-hander
has been inconsistent this season. He was nearly sent to the minors
after losing three of his first four starts. Yoshii then pitched
like an ace from May 2-25, a span of five starts, in which he
picked up four straight victories and the Mets won all five games.
</P>
<P>
   Yoshii followed that stretch with two rocky outings, both
losses, and then put together four straight good starts, winning
once and losing once, 1-0, to Greg Maddux in Atlanta, while not
receiving a decision in the others.
</P>
<P>
   This month, however, Yoshii's roller-coaster pace has been in
dive mode again. He left Friday night with one out in the sixth
inning, runners on first and third, and the Mets down by 4-1. Rigo
Beltran bailed Yoshii out of the jam, and then the Mets' hitters
took him off the hook when they tied the game with three runs off
Kevin Tapani in the bottom of the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   But Yoshii still allowed seven hits and four runs in his five
and a third innings. In 21 innings in July, he has allowed 18
earned runs for an earned run average of 7.71.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets have not announced what they will do when they activate
Rogers. They might place Greg McMichael on the disabled list,
retroactive to July 17, with shoulder stiffness. But McMichael
threw from a mound Friday for the first time since taking a
cortisone shot on Monday, and he pronounced himself fit to pitch in
a game.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets could also option Jason Isringhausen to Triple A
Norfolk or demote Octavio Dotel, should he struggle against the
Cubs at Shea Saturday afternoon. Of course, Phillips could pull off
another trade; Isringhausen believes he will be traded before next
Saturday's deadline, perhaps to Baltimore for hard-throwing
left-handed reliever Arthur Rhodes.
</P>
<P>
   No matter the future, Yoshii was spotty Friday night, serving up
a three-run homer to Sosa in the first inning, then shutting the
Cubs out over the next four innings, even catching Sosa looking at
a third strike in the third with a follow-through that turned into
a somersault for Yoshii.
</P>
<P>
   But Yoshii could not get out of the sixth. And the Mets, who had
scored their first run on a Brian McRae groundout, looked as if
they were going to waste an opportunity to gain ground on the
Braves.
</P>
<P>
   But they finally got to Tapani in the sixth, with a little help
from Tyler Houston. With runners on second and third and one out
after Piazza had popped out, Robin Ventura popped a ball off in
foul territory off third base. It was an easy play for Houston, but
he momentarily looked back to see if he was going to collide with
Manny Alexander, who had just entered the game at shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander was covering third, however, and when Houston looked
back up, he lost the ball. His one-hand grope was too late. Given
the reprieve, Ventura grounded to second with the infield back, and
it was now a 4-2 game with two out.
</P>
<P>
   McRae then worked a walk and Benny Agbayani sliced a line drive
to right-center field. The ball eluded center fielder Curtis
Goodwin and went to the fence. Two runs scored on the triple, the
score was tied at 4-4 and the Mets were on their way to gaining on
Atlanta.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
