<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIRE-HERO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEROIC EFFORTS SAVE NEIGHBORS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY LISA VAN PROYEN AND JESSE HIESTAND  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A 35-year-old man was hailed as a hero after
guiding his elderly and disabled neighbors to safety during a fire
that killed a woman and injured several others.
</P>
<P>
   The early morning fire Friday killed Ileen Shane, 54, as she
tried to escape flames and smoke on the third floor of the
Owensmouth Gardens apartments in the Woodland Hills community of
Los Angeles' San Fernando Valley, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of the building said 35-year-old Steve Katz escorted a
visually impaired man and his wife in a wheelchair away from a rain
of embers on the third floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it wasn't for him, we would have gotten hit from the
falling debris,'' said Gerald Robles, who has partial sight in one
eye. ``He caught us and pulled us to the back door.
</P>
<P>
   ``It still seems like a bad dream.''
</P>
<P>
   Katz shied away from the attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Others were helping out, too,'' he said. ``I don't consider
myself a hero.''
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said the fire began in a common room, and its
cause does not appear to be suspicious.
</P>
<P>
   As smoke spread through the third floor shortly before 3 a.m.,
Shane tried to flee but collapsed in front of the third-floor
elevator, officials said. Her apartment was the closest to the
fire.
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters found Shane dressed in a bathrobe with her purse
tightly clenched under her arm as they extinguished the fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had she stayed inside her apartment, she probably would not
have succumbed to the smoke,'' said Battalion Chief Robert Rose of
the Los Angeles Fire Department.
</P>
<P>
   Residents said Shane had only recently moved into the building,
and she kept to herself. Neighbors said she had a sticker on her
door that read, ``In case of fire, please rescue cat.''
</P>
<P>
   Shane's son arrived at the apartment and took out a cat, but he
declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was a very private person, very quiet,'' said one of
Shane's neighbors, Laurie Joyce. ``She used to love to read and
minded her own business.''
</P>
<P>
   Five people were taken to hospitals, where they were treated and
released, said Jim Wells, a spokesman for the Los Angeles Fire
Department. Eight others were treated at the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters doused the fire within 34 minutes and used ladders
in some cases to rescue several elderly residents from their
windows.
</P>
<P>
   About 50 tenants of the 200-unit complex were evacuated. The
federally subsidized apartments house disabled and elderly people
capable of living independently.
</P>
<P>
   Katz, who described himself as ``educationally handicapped,''
said he awoke to the sound of the fire alarm and screams from his
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Left with no electricity, he grabbed his lantern and staggered
through smoke before finding Robles and his wife, Ruth, trying to
escape in the hallway.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were going to go out the front entrance where it was
raining embers. He was screaming, `Oh my God!' I turned them around
and guided them in the right direction,'' Katz said.
</P>
<P>
   After looking out the window and seeing flames above his
second-floor unit, he ran up the stairs toward the third floor,
where he found other people struggling to find their way down
stairs with pets in tow in complete darkness.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were no lights in the stairwell. I slowly walked them
down to safety, using my lantern,'' Katz said.
</P>
<P>
   Another resident, Joan McGurrin, said Katz helped her and her
friend, along with each of their poodles, down the darkened
stairwell.
</P>
<P>
   ``He helped me down. The light was out in the stairwell, and I
couldn't see,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Some evacuees opted to stay with families, and others will be
temporarily housed at the Holiday Inn in Woodland Hills.
</P>
<P>
   The low-income complex, owned by the Los Angeles Housing
Authority, just celebrated its 20th anniversary and underwent
$2million in renovations about two years ago to remedy earthquake
damage, said George McQuade, a Housing Authority spokesman. City
building inspectors recently made a routine check of the complex
and found it to be up to code.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing suspicious, but there is a thorough
investigation whenever there is a fatality in a fire,'' Rose said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
