<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   S&AMP;P AND DOW JONES DROP ON INTEREST RATE CONCERNS
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index dropped 4.03 points, or
three-tenths of a percent, to 1,356.94, and the Dow Jones
industrial average declined 58.26 points, or half a percent, to
10,910.96. But the NASDAQ composite index rose 7.96 points, or
three-tenths of a percent, to 2,692.40.
</P>
<P>
   The S&AMP;P 500 fell 4.4 percent for the week, its worst performance
since the week ended Sept. 4, on concern that interest rates are
headed higher. The chairman of the Federal Reserve, Alan Greenspan,
said Thursday that the central bank might raise borrowing costs to
head off inflation. The concern over interest rates overshadowed
corporate profits that are growing at the fastest rate since the
third quarter of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK EXCHANGE TO GO PUBLIC
</P>
<P>
   America's two largest stock markets, the New York Stock Exchange
and the NASDAQ market, are moving quickly to convert from nonprofit
institutions to for-profit corporations, with the New York exchange
confirming that it could be ready to sell shares to the public as
early as mid-November.
</P>
<P>
   It is impossible to know what the New York Stock Exchange would
be worth if its own shares were traded on the Big Board. But using
a back-of-the-envelope method of calculation produces a rough
market value for the Big Board of $15 billion.
</P>
<P>
   AMERICA ONLINE BLOCKS COMPETITORS
</P>
<P>
   America Online closed its service to people using software
introduced Thursday by two of its fiercest rivals, Microsoft and
Yahoo. The programs were written to tap into one of America
Online's most popular features: instant messages, which appear in
an open window on the recipients' computer screens only seconds
after they are sent.
</P>
<P>
   SAFEWAY TO BUY RANDALL'S MARKETS
</P>
<P>
   The supermarket chain Safeway will buy the Randall's Food
Markets chain for about $1.4 billion in cash and stock. The
combined company will operate more than 1,645 stores in 19 states
and in Canada, employing more than 183,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   TAX BILL OFFERS BREAKS FOR BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   The far-reaching $792 billion tax cut passed by the House on
Thursday is full of fiercely sought but little noticed special
provisions for business and industry.
</P>
<P>
   BANKERS' ARRESTS REPORTED IN JAPAN
</P>
<P>
   Six former executives of Nippon Credit Bank, a failed Japanese
bank, were arrested on suspicion of covering up more than $830
million in losses, the state-run NHK television reported. It said
the investigation of the cover-up might spread to the Ministry of
Finance, which might have known that the bank was in trouble but
took no steps, out of fear of provoking its collapse. Among the six
arrested was Shigeoki Togo, a former president.
</P>
<P>
   US WEST PROFITS INCREASED 9.4 PERCENT
</P>
<P>
   US West, the regional phone company being acquired by Qwest
Communications, reported a 9.4 percent gain in second-quarter
income, buoyed by data and Internet services.
</P>
<P>
   UNEMPLOYMENT INCREASES IN BRAZIL
</P>
<P>
   Brazil's unemployment rate increased to 8.4 percent in June from
8.37 percent a month earlier, as hiring by industrial conglomerates
failed to offset a wave of corporate cutbacks. Two state-controlled
companies said they were considering layoffs. Cemig, an electric
utility, may dismiss 400 workers, while Copasa, a water treatment
company, could discharge 200.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOLOGY VIA THE ISRAELI ARMY
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli army's elite computer corps, Mamram, is gaining
recognition as a business training ground. Last August, for
example, two Mamram veterans, Ori and Israel Mazin, sold Memco
Software to Platinum Technology for $550 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
