<SLUG> BC-SOSA-HONORED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOSA TOTES WEIGHT OF HIS WORLD WITH EASE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill.)  (mk) 
 By STEVE POPPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Striding to the players' entrance at Shea Stadium,
Sammy Sosa was surrounded by eight police officers even though
there is little doubt that it would be hard for him, with biceps
the size of an officer's leg, to find an obstacle too tough to get
around.
</P>
<P>
   The obstacles these days are the type that muscle cannot help
overcome, as the Chicago Cubs slugger copes with the adoring fans
that follow his every step, begging for an autograph, a photo or a
smile.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa obliges when he can, signing as he walks, smiling the smile
that became as familiar as his home run stroke last season. But
becoming a man of the people means the people want him all the
time. The Mets honored Sosa before the game Friday night, which was
Merengue Night at Shea Stadium. But hours before plaques and
trophies were handed to him, Sosa got his due from the fans.
</P>
<P>
   Kids waving Dominican flags sprawled across the top of the
visitors' dugout, chanting his name and waiting for a glimpse of
Sosa. Police, who pulled the teen-age boys back, had about as much
luck containing the feverish fans as they had containing teen-age
girls when the Beatles played Shea Stadium. For Sosa, this was a
day in the life.
</P>
<P>
   Gathering trophies, as well as checks to his charitable
foundation, before the game, Sosa promptly brought the fans to a
frenzy with his 35th home run of the season, a three-run shot, in
the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unbelievable, all the support that I have from my
people,'' Sosa said before the game. ``It's not only my own people,
but all the people.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not quite like this everywhere, Sosa acknowledged. New
York, with a strong Latin population, provided him with a parade
last year after his season of 66 home runs. And on this night
celebrating the Dominican culture, it was Sosa who was the center
of attention. His last appearance here was on April 16 of last
season, 97 home runs ago for Sosa and long before he and Mark
McGwire pounded their way into the record book. He entered Friday
night's game leading the major leagues with 34 home runs, one ahead
of McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is like home,'' Sosa said. ``It's a great night, with
great support. That's something that doesn't happen every day. When
it happens to someone like me, I have to thank God for giving me
the opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   The notoriety that Sosa gained last season has made him not just
a magnet for youths, but also for politicians. Sosa, who has worked
hard to give back to his country, was passing out a letter to
Congress on Friday, a letter that he said had been given to him by
the president of the Dominican Republic, Leonel Fernandez, asking
Congress to support passage of Caribbean Basin enhancement
legislation that he believed would provide economic benefits for
his country.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason I'm doing this is because it's for my people,'' he
said. ``It's going to create a lot of jobs, help a lot of people.
The economics are going to be much better. I'm not a politician,
but anything that's to do with my country, I will do it. One of the
reasons I do have influence is because I'm not a politician. I have
an opportunity to help my country.''
</P>
<P>
   Juan Marichal, a Hall of Fame pitcher and now the secretary of
sports in the Dominican Republic, said during the pregame
presentation, ``Sammy Sosa, you are a hero to everybody, not only
because you play great baseball, but because you are a great human
being.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Sammy Sosa Charitable Foundation taking up his
attention, Sosa avoided much of the talk about a run at the home
run record of 70, which McGwire set last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no pressure,'' Sosa said. ``I don't put any pressure
on myself. I'm physically and mentally a strong guy. I know what it
takes to get ready. For me, everything that happens right now I
feel happy about. I enjoy everything. I'm so happy that Mark is
getting hot again. We're right there, but there is still a long way
to go. We'll do our job and see what happens.''
</P>
</TEXT>
