<HEADLINE>
U.S., CANADIAN TRIBES PLEDGE KINSHIP, SUPPORT TO EACH OTHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANCOUVER, B.C. _ In a ceremony rich with religious pageantry,
pride and hope, major Native American groups from the United States
and Canada on Friday pledged to work in tandem to expand political
rights and protect cultural values on both sides of the border.
</P>
<P>
   The ``sacred document,'' as it was described by the groups'
leaders, declares that while boundaries were drawn between the two
countries by ``others' hands,'' these ``arbitrary lines have not
severed, and never will, the ties of kinship among our peoples.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This event is a statement to the world, and to the leadership
of Canada and the United States, of a sovereignty that has always
existed and will always prevail,'' said Ron Allen, president of the
National Congress of American Indians.
</P>
<P>
   The declaration pledges that U.S. and Canadian tribes will
support each other as they work for a variety of goals, from
raising children ``in the loving traditions of our peoples'' to
promoting the right of Native Americans to move freely across the
border.
</P>
<P>
   Among 3,000 Native American delegates gathered in Vancouver,
however, the Declaration of Kinship and Cooperation had a much
deeper meaning for peoples who have often found themselves
fragmented, confined to reservations and living in poverty.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a coming back to strength, it's a uniting of Red nations.
There is power in numbers. Now we can attack our issues as a single
people,'' said Kiko-Lee Montilla, 17, a high school student and
member of the Arawak First Nation in California.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Fontaine, national chief of the Assembly of First Nations
in Canada, described the accord as ``a defining moment in our
cultural history. ... Governments are going to have to pay
attention to our issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen, a member of the Jamestown-S'Kallam Tribe on Washington
state's Olympic Peninsula, said the declaration will have many
practical applications.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Canada's federal government has formally
apologized to the country's 633 ``first nations'' for once taking
Native American children from their villages and putting them in
boarding schools, where native languages could not be spoken and
many youngsters were abused.
</P>
<P>
   Tribes in the United States are using Canada's example as they
seek to have President Clinton deliver a similar apology for past
mistreatment and land takings. In turn, Canadian tribes are
studying and seeking to copy legal strategies used by U.S. tribes
to open gambling casinos.
</P>
<P>
   The declaration on Friday capped what was the first joint
assembly of major U.S. and Canadian Native American groups in 60
years, and the largest convocation of indigenous leadership in
North America in the 20th century. A total of 54 chiefs signed
Friday's declaration.
</P>
<P>
   The scene at the Vancouver Convention Center was a curious
mixture of the modern economic world in which Native Americans
exist, and the traditional cultural world their leaders seek to
preserve.
</P>
<P>
   One exhibition hall was filled with displays of native-run
enterprises from the Red Feather Investment Corp., offering
pre-paid phone cards, to the Omaha Nation Tobacco Co. Big
corporations like Weyerhaeuser Canada and the Canadian Imperial
Bank of Commerce bought booth space.
</P>
<P>
   ``It almost seems like a corporate partnership with a trade
show. The cultural values are missing,'' complained Joe James, a
young man from the Nuu-cha-nulth Nation on the west coast of
Vancouver Island.
</P>
<P>
   But in the main meeting hall, however, the U.S.-Canadian
document was treated as a ``sacred document.'' It was covered with
cloth, a traditional protection against hostile spirits. A long
procession led by drummers ushered in the signing ceremony, with
Fontaine clad in full headdress. Cedar branches were waved over the
declaration. The air filled with smoke, a Coast Salish blessing was
pronounced over the declaration.
</P>
<P>
   ``The spirits are watching us; they look kindly on us,'' said
Salish elder Fred Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   Native Americanss are also watching out for themselves. They
face very different challenges on both sides of the 49th Parallel.
</P>
<P>
   In British Columbia, which was settled without agreements with
Native peoples, Native Americans bands are seeking treaties giving
them control of land, the right of self-government, fishing and
hunting rights, and money for economic development. A major
agreement between British Columbia and the Nisga'a Tribe awaits
ratification by Canada's House of Commons.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, by contrast, Native Americans are fighting
legislation sponsored by Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., that would
repeal the sovereign immunity of tribes on reservations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sovereignty is the fundamental authority of tribal governments
to govern their own affairs,'' Allen said. ``Specific leaders, such
as Slade Gorton on our side of the border, cannot abrogate those
rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Fontaine added: ``Sovereignty is all about defining one's place
in our land. It is not about independence or succession.''
</P>
<P>
   Native American leaders said Friday that various government
agencies in both countries, such as the U.S. State Department, have
been uncooperative and aloof from claims of sovereignty. The
declaration Friday ``brings our struggle onto the international
stage,'' Fontaine said.
</P>
<P>
   One man cheering as the agreement was signed was Maurice Eben,
who lives near Pyramid Lake in Nevada. Eben leads a Native American
group called the Burial Site Protection Commission. It seeks to
track down and repatriate human remains and artifacts from Native
American burial sites that were once looted and have found their
way to museums and universities.
</P>
<P>
   Eben has had trouble working across the border, and in securing
the clout needed to bring bones and burial instruments back to
their native tribes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This declaration will give us as a people another tool with
which to work on the federal governments of both countries,'' Eben
said. ``Because of laws in some cases, and inaction in others, we
have been stopped from completing our responsibility to our
ancestors.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
