<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY STAR ASKS COURT TO LIFT RESTRICTIONS OF ANTITRUST
RULING 
</HEADLINE>
 2nd take-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES R.T. CRUMPLEY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   regular classified advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the newspaper argue that the world is different
today. The Star no longer has a monopoly. The reported 96 percent
penetration the newspaper enjoyed in the 1950s (although Brisbane
believed that figure was inflated) is now down to about 40 percent.
(However, Brisbane said, about 60 percent of adults read the daily
newspaper.)
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, there are national newspapers, cable television,
e-mail newsletters and all other manner of competing news and
advertising outlets available to Kansas Citians today.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the ad prohibitions hurt advertisers by disallowing steep
discounts, and it could even hurt local small-newspaper publishers
by eliminating The Star _ a big potential buyer _ from bidding for
their paper when they want to sell.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers also said that similar judgments today usually die
automatically after 10 years. The judgment against the newspaper
has gone on for 42 years.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, managers and owners from the 1950s are long gone.
For example, Roberts and Sees, who left the paper in the mid-1960s,
died in 1967 and 1971, respectively.  &LR; brk:Easing restrictions
 &LR; tx:The Justice Department, in filing its motion in support of The
Star's motion, said provisions in the old judgment were aimed at
preventing the newspaper from engaging in anti-competitive conduct.
``However, they also now appear to be preventing The Star from
engaging in certain pro-competitive and efficient conduct, to the
detriment of advertisers and consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   The motions were filed Friday in U.S. District Court in Kansas
City. They don't ask to kill the judgment from 1957, but to replace
it with a greatly watered-down version.
</P>
<P>
   The significant new provision would require The Star to inform
the Justice Department if the newspaper proposed to spend more than
$5 million to buy a local publication. Normally, the paper _ like
other newspapers _ wouldn't need to inform the Justice Department
unless it wanted to buy another publication for $15 million or
more. That $5 million provision would end in 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Tim O'Donnell, who owns Keltatim Publishing Co., which publishes
the Olathe Daily News and the Lee's Summit Tribune, was concerned
about that provision.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if Knight Ridder, the parent of The Star, wanted to
buy his publications, ``I'd be flattered.'' But the $5 million
trigger point would add a roadblock to any negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It retards the dynamic of capitalism,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Advertisements notifying the public of the motion will be
published in two Sunday editions of The Kansas City Star, as well
as in editions of the Wall Street Journal and Editor &AMP; Publisher, a
trade publication.
</P>
<P>
   After the ads are published, a so-called comment period of 60
days begins during which objections can be filed. That will be
followed by a 30-day period during which the Justice Department
will answer the comments. The Justice Department could change its
mind, although that is viewed as unlikely because the department
has spent years thinking through this matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm confident that nothing will occur in the comment period to
make them change their minds,'' said Benjamin Mann, a lawyer with
Blackwell Sanders Peper Martin, who is also representing The Star.
</P>
<P>
   After that, an order could be entered that essentially ends the
old judgment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
