<SLUG> BC-FBN-DRUCKENMILLER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON PRO FOOTBALL: AN ATHLETE IS FORCED TO LEARN CAUTION
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va.)  (rk) 
 By   MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jim Druckenmiller, the San Francisco 49ers' reserve quarterback,
sounded tired. He said he had slept about three hours on Wednesday
night, the day before his rape trial went before a 12-member jury
in Christianburg, Va. He thought about his future, and the very
real possibility that he might spend the rest of his life in
prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you play quarterback in the NFL, you're used to
controlling things,'' Druckenmiller said in an interview Friday,
one day after being acquitted of a rape charge. ``But now my fate
was in the hands of other people. It was a terrible place to be.
Not being able to do anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was terrified, yes. The whole experience was one of those
life-altering things. I was scared, but I was also angry at the
same time because I knew I was innocent. The whole thing was a
learning experience. I have completely changed the way I approach
my life now. I will be much more careful.''
</P>
<P>
   Druckenmiller was charged in April with raping a 22-year-old
graduate of Virginia Tech, the school where Druckenmiller was a
star player, after Druckenmiller and the woman spent the night
drinking at a Blacksburg, Va., party. The woman said she had passed
out from too much drinking and awoke to find the 6-foot-4-inch,
240-pound Druckenmiller on top of her; in closing arguments, the
assistant prosecutor, Skip Schwab, said, ``Druckenmiller took
advantage of a drunken girl.'' Druckenmiller's lawyers said the sex
was consensual.
</P>
<P>
   After a four-day trial that often included graphic sexual
testimony, it took a jury of nine men and three women about one
hour to acquit Druckenmiller of the charge. If he had been found
guilty, he faced five years to life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother, my family, are so relieved,'' Druckenmiller said.
``But they were devastated by all of this. It has been really tough
on me and everyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Druckenmiller said that he was considering suing his accuser for
defamation of character and that he had spoken to several lawyers
who might represent him. ``That is something I am definitely
looking at right now,'' he said. ``I think I have a pretty good
case.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``If she regretted what we did that night, that is one
thing. To try and ruin someone's life by lying, that is another. I
regret what happened, but what we did was consensual. We both
wanted what happened. Then all of a sudden she was making false
accusations.''
</P>
<P>
   It has become so commonplace to read about athletes' being
accused of crimes that there is a tendency to believe the charges
are true. That may have been the case when the accusations against
Druckenmiller became public. But the 26-year-old Druckenmiller, who
has no history of these sorts of accusations, was found not guilty.
</P>
<P>
   One thing the Druckenmiller case represents is a cautionary tale
for athletes. Druckenmiller now says he will cut down on the amount
of time he spends in bars and clubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be a fool if I did not learn a lesson from this,'' he
said. ``Unfortunately, when you are an athlete, you are a target.
You are forced to isolate yourself. That's what I'm going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Druckenmiller's agent, Gary Wichard, is constantly preaching to
his clients that they need to be cautious and can trust no one.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what can happen if you're not careful,'' Wichard said.
``You can end up in front of 12 people. You had better be smart
enough not to be caught in that situation, whether it is a
businessman who comes to you with a scam, or a woman, or anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was innocent and his life has been dragged through the mud.
I hope a lot of players were watching closely.''
</P>
<P>
   Druckenmiller is scheduled to report next week to the 49ers'
training camp in Stockton, Calif. He realizes how close he came to
reporting somewhere else. ``For the first time in months,'' he
said, ``I will be thinking only about football.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
