r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANTITRUST-JUDGMENT 1sttake-KAN &LR;    07-24 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTITRUST-JUDGMENT, </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY STAR ASKS COURT TO LIFT RESTRICTIONS OF ANTITRUST
RULING 
</HEADLINE>
 1st take-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES R.T. CRUMPLEY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kansas City, Mo. _ The Kansas City Star, which was found guilty
of wielding monopoly powers in the 1950s and has operated under a
special judgment since, on Friday asked that most provisions of
that judgment be ended.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department _ which prosecuted The Star in the 1950s
_ filed its own motion on Friday, supporting the newspaper's
request. The Justice Department's motion basically said its
restrictions were no longer needed.
</P>
<P>
   If that happens, the biggest practical effect would be to allow
The Star to buy small, local publications in the metropolitan area.
It also could allow the newspaper to change its advertising rate
strategy. Among other restrictions, the special judgment prevented
the newspaper from extending steep discounts to reliable
advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Star would pretty much be able to operate the way other
newspapers operate,'' said Arthur S. Brisbane, the newspaper's
president and publisher.
</P>
<P>
   A final ruling on the newspaper's request could come in a little
more than 90 days.
</P>
<P>
   A federal grand jury in 1955 found The Star and its advertising
director guilty on an antitrust indictment for monopolizing the
market.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper _ which then had a commanding market presence and
which owned the only television station in the city through the
early 1950s _ played hardball. If companies advertised with other
media outlets, The Star assigned them poor ad location or even
refused their ads.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1957 final judgment, the newspaper was forced to sell
WDAF-TV and WDAF radio. The newspaper also was slapped with the
judgment that imposed the special rules. Among other things, those
rules prevented The Star from buying other newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been an outmoded, special regulation of The Star,''
said James S. Campbell, a lawyer with the Wilmer, Cutler and
Pickering law firm in Washington who represents the newspaper.
``This would be the deregulation, if you will, of The Kansas City
Star.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Rose, the chairman of Sun Publications Inc., said
metropolitan daily newspapers are no longer the monopolies they
once were, so he was not surprised that the change appears
imminent.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was more concerned about the loss of different news
perspectives. ``There may be a subtle stifling effect on the
diversity of opinion,'' Rose said.
</P>
<P>
   Rose's parents, who started Sun Publications, got a settlement
from The Star as a result of the antitrust litigation. Sun, now
owned by Lionheart Newspapers, today publishes the Johnson County
Sun, Northland Sun-News, College Boulevard News and others.
</P>
<P>
   Another area newspaper publisher was less sanguine about the
motion.
</P>
<P>
   ``My only concern is, the giant would get larger and more
powerful and it would not be to the benefit of the market,'' said
Ben Weir Jr., publisher of the Independence Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Less competition would benefit no one in the market except The
Kansas City Star,'' Weir said.  &LR; brk:Subpoenas, indictments  &LR; tx:The
litigation against the newspaper began in the summer of 1952, when
the Justice Department subpoenaed a truckload of records from the
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1953, a federal grand jury indicted The Star; Roy A.
Roberts, its president; and Emil Sees, its advertising director,
for alleged violations of the Sherman antitrust act.
</P>
<P>
   There was a political tint to the case. The Justice Department
probe was one of the final acts of the administration of President
Harry S. Truman, a Democrat. Sen. Frank Carlson, a Kansas
Republican, charged on the Senate floor that the probe was a
punitive act against the newspaper for exposing corruption in the
Pendergast political machine in Kansas City, which had ties to
Truman.
</P>
<P>
   But in the trial that followed, dozens of witnesses said they
were strong-armed by The Star. One advertiser of an auto show said
the newspaper told him ``we can make or break your show'' and then
informed him of how much he needed to spend on advertising.
</P>
<P>
   A baseball player, who was co-owner of a flower shop that
advertised in the now-defunct Journal-Post, was told he'd get no
coverage in sports stories, even if he hit 100 home runs, unless he
switched his flower shop ads to The Star.
</P>
<P>
   The charge against Roberts, the newspaper's president, was
dropped. But Sees, the advertising director, was found guilty of
one count of attempted monopolization and fined $2,500 in 1955. The
newspaper was found guilty of two charges of monopolization and
fined $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   Appeals were fruitless, and in 1957 the newspaper was forced to
accept the judgment. It had to divest itself of the television and
radio station. It was prohibited from buying other local newspapers
and was ordered not to arbitrarily refuse to publish ads,
discriminate as to their placement or grant discounts greater than
35 percent to regular classified advertisers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
