<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-KAYAKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTDOORS: THE KEYS BY KAYAK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., Fla.) (mk) 
 By KEN SCHULTZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was a bright, still early morning as the skiff motored along
the Spanish Channel into the National Key Deer Refuge in Big Pine
Key, Fla., about 28 miles east of Key West. Mike Wedeking shut the
motor and let the boat drift as he and Bill Keogh lifted a 14
1/2-foot kayak into the water and stabilized it while I gingerly
maneuvered onto the open deck. I felt almost as if I were on top of
a surfboard, and while I was still gauging my low-profile balance,
Bill gave me instructions on how to stand up and pole along.
</P>
<P>
   Stand up? Not this gimpy-legged guy. Leave that to natives in
dugout canoes. Besides, I had spent a total of five hours in a
kayak before, all of that on a placid freshwater pond. Not on a
tidal tropical flat with prowling stingrays, sharks and barracuda.
</P>
<P>
   Mike was soon in an identical kayak and we were paddling around
the tip of a mangrove key. The kayaks moved effortlessly over just
a few inches of water, and in the shallows blue crabs scurried
along near darting schools of small mojarra. A needlefish leaped
out of the water, its line-drive trajectory taking it 8 to 10 feet
through the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``See the round green blobs on the bottom?'' Mike said. ``Put
your paddle under one and flip it over. They're a type of jellyfish
and a sure sign that there's not much current in this spot.''
</P>
<P>
   The telltale stringy tentacles underneath proved him right.
</P>
<P>
   Around the back of the island we sneaked into a winding channel.
The water was only six inches deep, surely a spot that only a canoe
or kayak could possibly visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are red mangroves,'' Mike said in a near whisper.
``They're the most saltwater tolerant of the dozen or so mangrove
species.''
</P>
<P>
   We moved on easily and silently, entering a shaded inner sanctum
with a leafy canopy and an eye-level labyrinth of roots. Mike
pointed out a mangrove snail fixed to the underside of an arched
limb about 20 inches above the water. There was a loud splash back
in the dense thicket. Moments later Mike motioned me toward him.
Suddenly four large white birds, 15 feet away, jumped from the
inner treetops and flew behind us. They were clearly different from
the herons and ibises so prominent in the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roseate spoonbills,'' Mike said. ``There's only 30 in the
whole Lower Keys, and we haven't seen any in this vicinity since
Hurricane Georges last October.''
</P>
<P>
   An increasing number of people are kayak-touring this area,
adding to its reputation for great fishing, diving, bird watching
and snorkeling. Wedeking, a native of England who moved to Florida
with his parents as a boy, runs a kayak-touring and
wildlife-exploring business called Reflections (305-872-2896),
which has grown in each of the four years it has existed.
</P>
<P>
   Keogh, a naturalist and photographer who co-produced a book
about the marine life of the Keys, emigrated from Connecticut
nearly 20 years ago and recently started guiding back-country
kayakers with his business Lost World Adventures (305-872-8950).
The two frequently collaborate with large parties.
</P>
<P>
   Kayaks are terrific for probing great expanses of ultrathin
water around many of the mangrove islands and for quietly
approaching and observing bird and marine life. Many of the people
who do this have no kayaking experience and prefer quiet paddling
to riding a noisy personal watercraft, which are popular elsewhere
in the Keys but prohibited in this area. On full-day trips, kayaks
are transported to the outer keys by skiffs, then paddlers get into
a one- or two-person open-deck kayak, rendezvousing with the skiff
later.
</P>
<P>
   Interest in fishing from kayaks is also growing, and the
pleasure and effectiveness of this is one of the Keys' better-kept
secrets. While scores of powered skiffs take anglers out on the
flats each day for tarpon, bonefish and permit, only a handful of
people use their own muscles to get to the fish. But those who do
can pursue smaller species, some of which are far back in skinny
water where a skiff would run aground.
</P>
<P>
   Keogh has caught bonefish and permit from kayaks, and lots of
barracuda, and he once was guiding kayakers who spooked several
tarpon in a shallow channel, causing a four-foot specimen to leap
over one of the kayaks in its flight.
</P>
<P>
   The first fish I caught, a barracuda, appeared suddenly and
slammed a lure just a few feet from the boat. Startled, I reared
back to set the hook, nearly tipping the kayak and momentarily
spiking my heartbeat. We caught a bunch of small barracuda and
briefly hooked a good-sized bonefish in a few half-serious fishing
diversions from wildlife viewing.
</P>
<P>
   We probably could have caught several sharks had we tried as
there were many lemon, bonnet-head and nurse sharks in the
shallows. My kayak floated over a stationary nurse shark on a flat
that was so shallow it looked as if the kayak's hull would scrape
the back of the long brown creature.
</P>
<P>
   There were also many rays on the flats where the bottoms were
covered with turtle grass, pockmarked with loggerhead sponges, or
composed of hard wadeable sand. Both Bill and Mike proved very
adept at standing in their kayaks, which was a great benefit to
seeing marine life at greater distances, as well as spotting fish
to cast to. I tried it but quickly felt uncomfortably
wobbly-legged.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to top the close, mobile and personal experience that
kayaking provides. I was still thoroughly enjoying it when it was
time to quit in midafternoon. Just before we stopped, a barracuda
that I had caught was thrashing near the kayak when a
four-foot-long lemon shark streaked in and suddenly swirled off
about a foot away. Had the shark grabbed the barracuda he would
have probably towed me over the reef into the Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
