<SLUG> BC-INS-CARS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RULING FORCES INS TO SPELL OUT CAR SEIZURE PROCEDURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MAGGIE LEUNG  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A trip across the U.S.-Canadian border that has cost
some owners their cars is now less risky, thanks to a ruling issued
Friday in U.S. District Court.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1989, the Border Patrol has seized thousands of vehicles,
alleging that the owners were illegally transporting people into
the United States without the proper immigration papers.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Judge Thomas Zilly ruled that the car owners were denied
due process and gave the Immigration and Naturalization Service 60
days to revamp its procedures. The INS must now let owners know
exactly why their cars were seized and let them see INS reports so
the owners can argue their case before INS administrators.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past decade, about 1,300 cars have been seized from
Seattle to the Canadian border.
</P>
<P>
   In some instances, the owner wasn't even in the car when it was
seized, having lent it to friends. But in trying to recover the
car, the owner would be told he couldn't see the report that
determined he was a smuggler and would receive a form letter saying
he wasn't getting his car back.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (INS appeals) process is a joke in terms of the way it's
run,'' said lawyer Bob Pauw, who filed the class-action lawsuit
that resulted in Friday's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Said spokesman Harold Malkin of the U.S. Attorney's Office,
which defended the INS in court: ``We respect the court's decision
although it's adverse to our position. And... we are reviewing and
considering our options.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, graduate student Zenebe Gete had few options when his
car was seized.
</P>
<P>
   Gete was driving to Seattle from Vancouver, B.C., to spend the
weekend with friends. He wound up losing his car _ a 1980 Toyota
that he could not afford to replace _ after the Border Patrol
determined that one of his buddies was not a Canadian citizen and
lacked a visa to enter the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Gete, now a research engineer at the University of British
Columbia, was pleased by Zilly's ruling. ``That's great. At least
it won't happen in the future. They have to be more specific and
look at each case on its own merits. I'm happy,'' Gete said by
phone Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling doesn't give him any compensation or recourse,
however. Zilly still has to rule on a separate appeal, one that
seeks redress for owners whose cars have been seized over the past
10 years in the Northwest, covering Washington, Oregon, California,
Arizona, Alaska and part of Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   Scores of people each year lose their cars under circumstances
similar to Gete's. In some cases, they were nowhere near a border
checkpoint, where immigration papers typically must be shown. With
probable cause, immigration authorities can stop anyone anywhere in
the United States if they suspect they are smuggling immigrants.
Those stopped must produce citizenship or immigration papers.
</P>
<P>
   If they cannot, they must choose between taking their case to
federal court _ a financial hardship for many _ or going through
INS administrators. Going the INS route often has resulted in their
cars being auctioned off by the INS or being kept for government
use. Some owners have recovered their cars after paying fines
ranging from hundreds to thousands of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   In Gete's case, his visa was in order and he was never charged
with a crime. But he has been refused entry into the United States
since his car's seizure, severely limiting his career, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've missed lots of job opportunities and conferences'' in the
United States, he said. ``I cannot apply for jobs there. It has had
a great impact on me. I'm really bitter about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle Post-Intelligencer reporter Lise Olsen contributed to
this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
