<SLUG> BC-GORDON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORDON IN CIA, FIRED, SOURCES SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS MOESER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - State Rep. Tom Gordon worked for the Central
Intelligence Agency at one time and received extensive intelligence
training in the Navy, according to sources familiar with Gordon's
background and records obtained Friday by ''The Arizona Republic.''
</P>
<P>
   Congressional sources said Friday that Gordon was fired by the
CIA prior to his stints in the offices of U.S. Sen. John McCain,
R-Ariz., and Rep. J.D. Hayworth, R-Ariz. When asked whether he was
fired by the CIA, Gordon responded: ``I left my government service
voluntarily.'' He did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon served with a Navy SEAL unit in the late 1980s and
trained in terrorism counteraction, political warfare,
indoctrination and naval special warfare intelligence, according to
naval reserve records.
</P>
<P>
   The details of Gordon's military history come to light as the
FBI investigates whether Gordon lied his way onto a free flight to
Bosnia arranged by Hayworth. Hayworth fired Gordon after learning
that he is not an active naval reservist.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Hayworth refused to release additional details
regarding Gordon's hiring and firing. Hayworth's office declined to
say anything else on the matter, citing the ongoing federal
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   As the new details emerged, it remained unclear whether Navy
officials authorized Gordon's bizarre Balkans trip. And questions
outnumbered answers.
</P>
<P>
   Was Gordon, a former Navy lieutenant commander, authorized to
board a National Guard plane in Phoenix around May 5 that would
eventually take him to Bosnia? What did he do from the time he
arrived until he returned to Arizona last week? And how did he do
it?
</P>
<P>
   In a statement Thursday, Gordon, a Republican from Peach Springs
in northwestern Arizona, acknowledged that he had no formal orders
to travel to Bosnia in May. But in an interview, he said he was
involved in intelligence gathering in the region. He also said he
was trying to persuade a naval official, with whom he has worked
for 15 years, to admit he authorized the controversial trip.
</P>
<P>
   The dilemma? Coming forward could jeopardize current operations
in the area, Gordon said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I get this particular naval officer to do this . . . it
gives away to a degree what the circumstances are over there,''
Gordon said.
</P>
<P>
   Anya Guilsher, a spokeswoman for the CIA, said she could provide
no information on Gordon, including whether he had at one point
been employed by the agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a matter of policy, we don't confirm employment in the
agency,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Documents confirm that Gordon did have training in intelligence
and other covert operations.
</P>
<P>
   According to naval reserve records, Gordon was attached to a
SEAL unit in 1988 in Coronado, Calif., as an inactive duty officer.
His connection to the unit was terminated at his request on May 6,
1988, due to scheduling conflicts with drill training.
</P>
<P>
   A note on the form said Gordon would reaffiliate with the unit
when the ``job conflict'' was resolved. A later document, filed on
October 1988, requested Gordon to report for ``inactive duty
training.''
</P>
<P>
   In his Thursday statement, Gordon said most of his naval career
involves service in ``intelligence or special operations.''
</P>
<P>
   He has received scuba and parachute training and is rated an
``expert'' by the Navy at using pistols and rifles.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon graduated from Brigham Young University in 1982 with a
degree in political science and completed a master's in public
administration at Harvard's Kennedy School of Government in 1992.
Much of his study at Harvard focused on Arabic languages, according
to the Harvard registrar's office.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon has been under fire since July 16, when Hayworth accused
the freshman state lawmaker of misleading Hayworth's office to get
on a National Guard flight to Bosnia. Gordon worked for Hayworth's
office at the time, providing constituent services in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI and the Navy are investigating the matter, and Hayworth
has called for a state House ethics probe of Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon said he has not been contacted by either the FBI or Navy
investigators since he has returned to Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   He has said since the flap erupted that he was an intelligence
officer for a Navy SEAL unit. He lists service in the Navy from
1984 to 1987, and service in the naval reserves from 1987 to the
present.
</P>
<P>
   Hayworth has said that several weeks after Gordon left for
Bosnia, an Army general in the Balkans contacted Hayworth's office,
saying Gordon was involved in disruptive activities. Hayworth then
checked with the naval reserve, who said Gordon had not been called
into active duty.
</P>
<P>
   A June 17 letter from the Department of the Navy to Hayworth
shows that ``Lieutenant Commander Gordon has not been recalled to
active duty.''
</P>
<P>
   A search began for Gordon, who was eventually detained at a base
in Sarajevo.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon's wife, Camille, has suggested that he was captured by
the Serbs, detained for several weeks, and beaten. Gordon has
declined to answer questions to account for his time in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon worked as a part-time constituent liaison in the northern
part of Hayworth's district.
</P>
<P>
   From March 1997 to January of 1998, Gordon worked in the
Washington office of Sen. John McCain, handling Native American
issues. Gordon is fluent in Navajo and lives in the heart of the
Hualapai Indian Reservation in northwestern Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Ives, a McCain spokeswoman, said July 16 that Gordon was
``let go.'' On Friday, she said Gordon and McCain had a mutual
parting. She declined to elaborate, citing the FBI investigation.
Gordon told ``The Republic'' July 16 that he left McCain's office
because he was tired of living in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Eule, Hayworth's chief of staff, said his office was aware
``there had been some problems'' with Gordon during his time in
McCain's office. But they assumed it was because Gordon's family
was still in Arizona and he was homesick.
</P>
<P>
   When asked how Gordon's references were checked, Eule refused to
comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've already dealt with the matter. We're confident his
termination was justified. . . . We're not going to comment anymore
about it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
