<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HOSP-KIDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN 2001, ODYSSEY TO A CHILDREN'S HOSPITAL WILL LEAD TO A SPACE
STATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (yn) 
 By KATHERINE E. FINKELSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It is not enough to be just a hospital anymore. The
fierce competition of the managed-care era has given rise to the
health-care network, the center for treatment of a single disease,
the suite with five-star amenities.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Montefiore Medical Center in the Bronx is taking that
approach one step further. After Saturday's ground-breaking
ceremony, it will begin construction of a children's hospital at
Bainbridge Avenue, near the main hospital complex, that is
designed, essentially, as a space station.
</P>
<P>
   Montefiore officials say the $120 million building, scheduled to
open by mid-2001, will have 106 beds and will provide a full range
of medical services, from a children's emergency room and trauma
center to cancer treatment and organ transplants. It will have a
center for speech, hearing and language difficulties, and another
for epilepsy and neurological disorders.
</P>
<P>
   But there will also be a domed rooftop planetarium, a video link
with NASA's space shuttle program, and an audio link that will
allow children to listen to the wind on the surface of Mars.
</P>
<P>
   This learning center cum new-age theme park was designed by
David Rockwell, known for chic restaurants like Nobu in TriBeCa and
entertainment venues like the new Disney World headquarters of the
Cirque du Soleil. Its science theme is dedicated to the work of the
astronomer Carl Sagan, who died in 1996 after a battle with bone
marrow disease.
</P>
<P>
   The Children's Hospital at Montefiore will be the New York
region's third free-standing hospital for children, after Schneider
Children's Hospital at Long Island Jewish Medical Center in Glen
Oaks, Queens, and Babies Hospital at the New York-Presbyterian
Hospital in Manhattan. And the Westchester County Medical Center is
planning a 110-bed children's hospital, expected to open in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   While Montefiore doctors originally planned to build a Carl
Sagan Discovery Center within the new hospital, ``the planning
evolved to characterize the hospital itself,'' said Dr. Irwin
Redlener, a pediatrician who will serve as the new hospital's
president.
</P>
<P>
   As Rockwell explains it, the challenge that Montefiore faced was
to transform the typically frightening and impersonal hospital of
endless corridors into a place of ``way finding.''
</P>
<P>
   Hence children will be encouraged to think of themselves as what
he called explorers on a journey to healing. Each child admitted to
the hospital will get an explorer's passport, a wristband and
baseball cards with his or her digital photograph.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, they will get an explorer's kit that will include a
compass, a kaleidoscope, a periscope _ and even a fuzzy stuffed
star.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most high-tech special effects will be reserved for
the lobby, which will contain an electronic map of the Bronx with
pinpricks of light to show where some of the patients live.
</P>
<P>
   As Rockwell acknowledged, ``The lobby is the solar system _ or a
wonderful lobby _ depending on how deeply you want to get into
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-99 0057EDT &QL; 
