r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTO-REVIEW-AZR &LR;      07-24 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-REVIEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMOOTHER STYLING LOOKS TO THE FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB GOLFEN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Buick's challenge was daunting: redesign its very successful
full-size LeSabre for a new generation without alienating the old
one.
</P>
<P>
   This is an important goal for Buick, because even though its
LeSabre is the best selling full-size sedan in the nation, its
loyal, conservative customer base is rapidly aging. The mission was
to change the focus from the elderly to the merely middle-aged.
</P>
<P>
   So the LeSabre for 2000 has been revamped nose to tail without
being too blatant about it. Until you take a closer look, it's easy
to mistake the new LeSabre for the 1999 model. All the cues are
still there, but they've been smoothed out and better integrated,
not quite modernized but more in touch with today's styling trends.
</P>
<P>
   Sharing the same chassis as the Pontiac Bonneville and
Oldsmobile Aurora, the LeSabre has grown a couple of inches in all
directions, with its wheels pushed out to the corners and an
interior that is more commodious than ever. The Buick grille with
its vertical bars and tri-shield insignia is familiar, but now it's
an interesting oval shape. Character lines crease the hood, roof
and trunk lid in a complementary pattern.
</P>
<P>
   Gone are the huge, chrome door handles with the big thumb
buttons that looked like they came off a Hudson Hornet, replaced
with modern monochromatic pull handles.
</P>
<P>
   And gone is the staid dashboard, replaced with an up-to-date
cockpit-style dashboard with a modern ergonomic look. But even this
update has been softened, looking new but still familiar to
traditional drivers of General Motors cars.
</P>
<P>
   These evolutionary changes are well-done, looking to the past
and future, but Buick should have made a cleaner break with the
past, something more along the lines of the late, lamented Riviera,
whose concept-car styling should have pointed the way for the
entire Buick line. The new LeSabre is attractive, but hardly
exciting.
</P>
<P>
   The ride is firmer than it used to be, especially with the
optional Touring Package on the test car, and maybe a bit too firm
for those favoring the plush rides of yesteryear's luxury barges.
</P>
<P>
   The new LeSabre has a more solid and competent feel than the
old, no doubt attributable to the 62 percent greater rigidity and
27 percent more bending resistance, according to Buick engineers.
Handling is fairly precise and balanced, though no one is going to
mistake the LeSabre for a sports sedan. For one thing, the steering
has a bit too much power boost and numbness, and the body roll in
corners is still fairly acute.
</P>
<P>
   One aspect that requires no excuses is the sparkling performance
of the 3.8-liter V-6, a standout among GM engines since it was
introduced in 1995. Despite putting out more than 200 horsepower,
the 3.8 is smooth, quiet and economical, and has a reputation for
exceptional durability.
</P>
<P>
   And despite the strong acceleration from the engine, torque
steer was nearly non-existent in this front-drive car.
</P>
<P>
   The powertrain is one of the reasons why LeSabre has more than
50 percent repeat buyers, and why Buick has sold more than 1
million of these big boys in the past seven years.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason is dollar value; for a totally optioned-out big
car like the LeSabre to cost less than $30,000 is certainly worth
taking note. There's also a Custom model available at a lower
price.
</P>
<P>
   Safety concerns are strongly represented, including seat belts
mounted directly to the seats; newly designed air bags with a safer
type of propellent, and seat-mounted side-impact air bags; standard
anti-lock brakes; and a battery system that will turn off any lamp
left on 10 minutes after the car has been parked.
</P>
<P>
   There's also a nicely engineered seat/headrest system designed
to protect front-seat passengers from whiplash injuries in the
event of a rear-ender.
</P>
<P>
   The test car was a good runner, with roomy comfort for five. A
bench seat in front makes the LeSabre a full six-seater. Actually,
I would have preferred the bench seat over the weird console in the
tester.
</P>
<P>
   I was told that this large, plastic setup was a nod to those
drivers who enjoy similar consoles in GM's pickup trucks and
sport-utility vehicles. Indeed, it has a huge storage area and the
flip-up writing surface similar to those on the big trucks.
</P>
<P>
   However, it felt cheap and tacky, very out of place with the
high quality of the rest of the interior, and it took up a
ridiculous amount of space. Specifically, much of it was built to
house a huge, flip-up cup holder that could double as a banquet
table. Well, nearly. The whole assembly was just jarring and over
the top.
</P>
<P>
   Still, I point out the LeSabre to anyone pondering a large
family sedan, especially those looking at Lexus or Infiniti.
</P>
<P>
   It seems likely that the LeSabre remake fulfills its mission,
and by all rights should bring some younger drivers into the fold. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
