<SLUG> BC-OBIT-BROSIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HENRY BROSIN, 94, LED PSYCHIATRIC GROUPS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz., Va., Ill., Wis.)  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. Henry Walter Brosin, a former president of the American
Board of Psychiatry and Neurology, the American Psychiatric
Association and the American College of Psychiatrists, died in
Tucson, Ariz., on July 3, three days short of his 95th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Brosin had been a resident of Tucson since 1969, when he was
named a professor of psychiatry at the University of Arizona
Medical School, where he helped organize its department of
psychiatry.
</P>
<P>
   He was a native of Blackwood, Va., and was a 1927 graduate of
the University of Wisconsin, where he received his M.D. in 1933.
Brosin studied psychiatry at the Chicago Institute and was
associated with the University of Chicago. From 1950 to 1969 he was
on the faculty of the University of Pittsburgh, and was chairman of
the department of psychiatry and director of the Western
Psychiatric Institute and Clinics.
</P>
<P>
   Brosin served in Europe in World War II as a colonel in the Army
Medical Corps, interviewing prisoners and compiling a profile of
the typical battlefield deserter.
</P>
<P>
   He retired from the University of Arizona in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Brosin is survived by a son, Lloyd Wisdom of Tucson; two
sisters, Dorothy Brosin and Margaret Bahr, both of Wisconsin, and
two granddaughters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-99 0058EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990724.0032 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-24 01:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2506 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-HERSKOWITZ-COLUMN     07-24 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-HERSKOWITZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Ryan and Co. near head of the classes
<TEXT>
<P>
   By MICKEY HERSKOWITZ
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   Cooperstown is where baseball fans take their children to
fulfill the fantasies of H.G. Wells and travel back in time. It is
where you go to revisit baseball through the ages, including when
the 20th century was just dawning. It is where you remind yourself
how strong this game really is, able to survive two World Wars and
a World Series where one team tried to lose.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball keeps colliding with its past, which is among its most
enduring charms. Of the seven members of the class of '99, three _
Nolan Ryan, George Brett and Robin Yount _ were voted into the Hall
on their first ballot. To find a more distinguished class, you
arguably have to go back to the first one, in 1936, which included
such swingers as Ty Cobb, Babe Ruth and Honus Wagner and pitchers
Walter Johnson and Christy Mathewson.
</P>
<P>
   Do you enjoy historical links? The baseball purist wallows in
them. Try these:
</P>
<P>
   Bob Feller pitched his last full season in 1955, the year a
rookie lefthander named Sandy Koufax made his debut with the
Brooklyn Dodgers. Koufax struck out his last hitter in 1966, the
year Nolan Ryan, a farm kid from Alvin, struck out his first, Pat
Jarvis, a pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   We have attempted to trace this line of succession back to
Johnson, known as the Big Train, making him the spiritual ancestor
of the Ryan Express. The best thing we could uncover was that
Johnson's last strikeout occurred in 1927, the season of Ruth's 60
home runs. The man who would break Ruth's lifetime record, Hank
Aaron, was a teammate of Jarvis for seven years.
</P>
<P>
   Gads, it is almost enough to make one believe in reincarnation,
or possibly Juan Encarnacion, Detroit's young outfielder.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, the First Timers will be inducted into the Hall along
with Orlando Cepeda, umpire Nestor Chylak, Frank Selee, an
old-timer who managed when it was OK to refer to the Gay '90s, and
Smokey Joe Williams, a Texan from Seguin who dominated the Negro
Leagues for 20 years but whose brilliance as a pitcher went unseen
by white America.
</P>
<P>
   Cepeda will represent the most teams, six, having enjoyed his
most productive years with the Giants and Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   But Ryan has the distinction of going bi-coastal, playing for
the New York Mets and California Angels, and for both of his home
state teams, the Astros and Rangers. He is not only the game's
strikeout king _ and, yes, it's good to be the king _ he pitched
seven no-hitters and lasted longer in his sport than anyone in any
other team sport.
</P>
<P>
   You would think there is nothing new to be said or discovered
about the sturdy righthander, who was still delivering serious heat
in his 40s. But the search continues, and in this endless process,
we stumbled across a strange but intriguing trivia note.
</P>
<P>
   Of the most durable athletes in the four major professional
sports, each of the leaders carried with him a piece of Houston:
Ryan; Moses Malone, tied with Robert Parish in basketball at 21
seasons; George Blanda, in football, 26 seasons; and Gordie Howe,
hockey, with 32 years on the ice.
</P>
<P>
   This is a terrific tribute to the fluoride in Houston's water,
or perhaps our temperate weather, although how this fits into the
festivities at Cooperstown isn't clear. Look for further bulletins.
</P>
<P>
   Brett and Yount have described themselves as borderline nervous
wrecks, and Cepeda has cried openly, but Ryan has approached the
Cooperstown spectacle as he did most of his best moments _ pretty
much in stride.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the final chapter of my career,'' he said. ``It's the
highest honor.''
</P>
<P>
   You won't get much more emotion than this out of him, although
he could surprise us Sunday. He has wavered a few times in picking
his supreme thrill, at various moments choosing his 300th win, his
5,000-plus strikeouts and his seventh no-hitter. Once, he said it
was hard to top the first time he was picked to the Little League
All-Star team in Alvin and got to wear a new cap.
</P>
<P>
   You tend to believe Ryan whenever he makes one of his aw-shucks
kind of claims. With almost any other modern athlete, you would
know you were being conned. But if we have learned nothing else
over the years, we have learned Ryan isn't anyone else. He doesn't
lie. He doesn't boast.
</P>
<P>
   When Nolan broke Johnson's career strikeout record at Montreal
in 1983, he acknowledged the moment and the ovation of the crowd
with a flicker of a smile and a tip of the cap. The hitter was
young and unaware Brad Mills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was more interested in Mills' reaction,'' Ryan said. ``He
was looking around as he walked back to the dugout. All he did was
strike out, and the crowd went crazy. He had no idea what was going
on.''
</P>
<P>
   The noise goes to another level Sunday, and yes, most of us know
exactly what is going on. Nolan Ryan is.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
