<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CAMPAIGN-REFORM-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz., Texas, Wis., Ky.)  
 EDITORIAL: CAMPAIGN REFORM GAINS AN ALLY  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, July 24:
</P>
<P>
   The congressional proponents of campaign finance reform gained
an important ally this week when Bill Bradley called for
overhauling the system. Bradley suggested fundamental changes in
the ways elections are financed and promised to reject soft-money
donations to his Democratic presidential campaign, if Republicans
do the same.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley is not the first presidential candidate to show
leadership on this issue. That honor belongs to Sen. John McCain,
R-Ariz. Together, perhaps, they can exert pressure on their
parties' front-runners, Vice President Al Gore and Gov. George W.
Bush of Texas. So far, both men have shown a disappointing
tolerance for the old cash-for-influence system.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, who formerly represented New Jersey in the Senate,
called for free television time for candidates and the introduction
of some federal funding for congressional campaigns. He also called
for elimination of soft money, which is the main focus of the
bipartisan legislation sponsored by McCain and Sen. Russell
Feingold, D-Wis.
</P>
<P>
   These unregulated donations to political parties are poisoning
the political process by allowing wealthy individuals, corporations
and unions to use the ``party-building'' dodge to evade the federal
limitations on direct contributions to candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier last week, McCain got a firm promise from Senate leaders
to hold a full debate on the issue no later than mid-October.
Waiting until autumn had not been the senator's preferred strategy,
nor was it ours. But McCain made a tactical judgment to accept a
delay that will give him time to round up votes.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement negotiated with the majority leader, Trent
Lott, R-Miss., the issue will be brought to the Senate floor by
Oct. 12. There will be four days of debate, and amendments can be
considered. The opportunity to offer amendments gives McCain a
chance to build the 60 votes needed to break the filibuster
expected from Lott and Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., the GOP's chief
opponent of strong campaign laws.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate agreement places a heavy obligation for fairness on
House Speaker Dennis Hastert. He promised a September vote in the
House, which approved campaign finance reform by a substantial
margin last year. A similarly resounding victory this year would
send the Senate a clear message that the American people want
McCain's soft-money reforms. Passage of McCain-Feingold could, in
turn, open the way to the additional reforms outlined by Bradley.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
