<SLUG> BC-NINTENDO-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPECULATION GROWS THAT MARINERS EXEC MAY GET LARGER ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANGELO BRUSCAS AND JOHN COOK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Howard Lincoln, who helped build Nintendo into a
household name in the United States, is planning to resign from the
giant video game maker next year.
</P>
<P>
   The move is sparking speculation that Lincoln, a co-owner of the
Seattle Mariners who has played an active role in the financing of
Safeco Field, could be in line for the team's chief executive post.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could signal a significant shift in who carries the torch
for the ballclub,'' said one source close to the team.
</P>
<P>
   Another Mariners executive said Friday that he has no knowledge
of how Lincoln's retirement affects the baseball ownership group.
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln will give up his day-to-day responsibilities as chairman
of Redmond-based Nintendo of America on Feb. 14, the day he turns
60. He will continue to sit on Nintendo's board and will assist
with the company's launch of its next-generation game system.
</P>
<P>
   A replacement has not yet been named.
</P>
<P>
   But a spokeswoman for Nintendo said the company may look at
reorganizing its management structure. Minoru Arakawa will continue
to serve as president.
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln, who was traveling, could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   In the past six months, Lincoln, who is described by those who
know him as a baseball fanatic, has taken a more active role with
the Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   When the team announced it was trying to recover $60 million of
the $100 million in cost overruns on $517 million Safeco Field, it
was Lincoln who made the team's case to the Public Facilities
District, along with current CEO John Ellis.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis has said he's looking at taking a less active role with
the team, but maintained in an interview July 15 that he saw no
immediate reorganization of the ownership group. Ellis, 70, has
served as the chairman and CEO of the Baseball Club of Seattle
since the group assumed control of the Mariners from Jeff Smulyan
in July 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln, however, represents one of the most powerful arms of
the Mariners ownership group: The Nintendo faction. Others include
Hiroshi Yamauchi of Kyoto, Japan, president of the Nintendo Co. of
Japan; Minoru Arakawa of Bellevue, president of Nintendo of America
and Yamauchi's son-in-law; and John Bauer, executive vice president
of Nintendo of America.
</P>
<P>
   In his role with the Mariners, Lincoln has been the most visible
of the Nintendo-based owners, while Yamauchi, the majority investor
who put up an initial $75 million to buy the team, has been a
minority partner in ownership decisions and has not seen a game in
person.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview last week on the opening of Safeco Field,
Lincoln said he believed the full story of the cost overrun dispute
had yet to be told and said the owners were being cast in an unfair
light after putting up $125 million to buy the team and keep it
from being moved in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, ownership claims to have lost as much as $30 million
a year on the team, despite winning the division championship in
1995 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back in 1992, it was such a difficult struggle to save this
for Seattle and keep it from going to Tampa Bay,'' Lincoln said.
``The other side of it was in 1995 when we had that wonderful
playoff experience. Then you say to yourself that every minute the
ownership spent on this was worth it because it was so exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with the new stadium and the estimated $25 million in new
revenue it will produce for the club annually, Lincoln sees some
trouble on the horizon due to baseball's volatile labor situation
and escalating payroll. The next round of labor negotiations is
scheduled to commence by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody expects that we will go through another traumatic
experience. It seems to be the nature of the sport,'' Lincoln said.
``But let's not worry about that now. Hopefully, everybody will
come to their senses.''
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln acknowledged that Mariners owners made an unpopular
decision to ask to be reimbursed for the cost overruns on the new
stadium out of tax money collected to retire the bonds.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a popular thing to do,'' Lincoln said. ``But it is
the right thing to do. I realize there's a lot of people who don't
agree with us. But even baseball owners are entitled to their day
in court.''
</P>
<P>
   Under his leadership since 1983, Nintendo of America, the U.S.
subsidiary of the Japanese game maker, grew from a tiny startup
with a half-dozen employees to a major powerhouse in the video game
business. By 1987, the Nintendo Entertainment System was the No. 1
toy in the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   Before joining Nintendo, Lincoln worked as a corporate lawyer
for the Seattle firm Sax &AMP; MacIver.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
