<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
M'S SEE ANOTHER ONE SLIP AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ There was little elbow room on the Metrodome
infield in the bottom of the ninth inning Friday night. The game
was tied, the bases were loaded and all five infielders _ yes, five
_ were playing up.
</P>
<P>
   It looked like the world was encroaching on the pitcher, Jose
Paniagua. He had company, but he was all alone. Nobody was warming
in the Mariners bullpen when Matt Lawton flaired a single to left
to bring in the winning run for the Minnesota Twins in a 5-4
victory that dropped the Mariners to 10 games behind the Texas
Rangers in the American League West.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to get hot,'' catcher Dan Wilson said. ``We've got
to start doing what it takes to win. That's what we need to worry
about right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Paniagua had entered the game with a 4-2 lead and no outs in the
seventh. When that inning was over, the Twins had tied it. After a
scoreless eighth, Paniagua stayed in for the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Only twice this season had the right-hander pitched more than
two innings. But Paul Abbott had worked 22/3 on Thursday and was
not available. Closer Jose Mesa is not a preferred option in tie
games on the road. That left Frankie Rodriguez, who threw five
innings Tuesday night, rookie Ryan Franklin and the struggling Ken
Cloude.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Coomer singled to start the ninth. Marty Cordova doubled and
Todd Walker was intentionally walked. Manager Lou Piniella removed
left fielder Ozzie Timmons, inserting Rafael Bournigal as a fifth
infielder to play in front of and slightly to the first-base side
of second.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way to get out of that situation is a ground ball, a
strikeout or a pop-up,'' said second baseman David Bell. ``If he
gets it over the infielders' heads it's over, basically. It's worth
taking the chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawton, who had driven in the tying run on a fielder's choice in
the seventh, sliced a 2-2 pitch in front of Ken Griffey Jr., who
was covering the left side of the outfield. The only throw Griffey
could make was his flip to a fan above the dugout as the Mariners
filed off the field.
</P>
<P>
   It was Paniagua's major-league leading ninth relief loss,
breaking a tie with former Mariner Mike Timlin of the Baltimore
Orioles. Only Timlin has more blown saves than Paniagua's seven.
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, of course, Piniella would have preferred to have a
left-hander pitching to the left-handed Lawton in such a crucial
situation.
</P>
<P>
   But the Seattle bullpen has no lefties, and Jeff Fassero is not
headed there soon. The erratic starter would not have been
available Friday night anyway, but before the game, he told
Piniella he has corrected some of his recent problems and Piniella
decided to keep Fassero in the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It (the need for a left-handed reliever) has jumped at me for
about three or four years,'' Piniella said. ``I'm talking about a
reliable one.''
</P>
<P>
   Three Minnesota relievers held the Mariners scoreless.
Ex-Mariner Bob Wells, Eddie Guardado and Hector Carrasco blanked
the Mariners over the last three innings as the Twins overcame a
4-0 deficit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should have won that game,'' Bell said. ``I think we should
have scored more runs than we did. It wasn't our defense. It wasn't
our pitching _ they didn't really crush the ball. It's part of the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners had gotten their lead in classic Seattle fashion.
In the fourth inning, Timmons hit his first major league home run
since 1996, smashing a two-run shot over the center field wall just
out of Torii Hunter's reach.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey followed the next inning with another two-out, two-run
homer off LaTroy Hawkins, an opposite-field poke that was his 31st
of the season, tying the injured Jose Canseco of Tampa Bay for the
American League lead. That homer was the Mariners' 25th against the
Twins this season, setting a club record for homers against an
opponent in one year _ with five games still left between these
teams.
</P>
<P>
   Mariners starter John Halama worked six-plus innings, allowing
three runs on nine hits. One of Halama's trademarks has been his
effectiveness with runners on base, and he did it again Friday
night, stranding five runners in the first two innings before
settling in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found myself cutting the ball off in the first and second
inning,'' Halama said. ``I wasn't throwing the ball where I was
supposed to be. Dan mentioned it ... and told me to stay on top of
the ball and just go to the catcher. That next inning, it clicked
in right away, and I started throwing the ball well after that.''
</P>
<P>
   But Cristian Guzman doubled to lead off the seventh, Brent Gates
singled him in and the Twins had begun the rally that would erase
the Mariners' lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
