<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-NOTEBOOK-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASSERO, SEGUI TOP NAMES ON BLOCK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Last July 26, the Mariners were 8{ games out of
first place. At the start of play Friday night, they were nine
games behind.
</P>
<P>
   Last July 31, the Mariners traded Randy Johnson. But just
because their position in the standings has not improved much,
don't expect the M's to let go of soon-to-be free agents again.
</P>
<P>
   First baseman David Segui and pitcher Jeff Fassero can be free
agents after this season, and neither is a sure bet to return to
the Mariners. Longtime designated hitter Edgar Martinez also is
unsigned past '99. But that doesn't mean Woody Woodward, the team's
vice president for baseball operations, is eager to trade them.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's a pretty good player (who stays through this season
but does not re-sign), there's a chance we'll at least get another
draft pick in return,'' Woodward said. ``It's not like all is lost.
I have no problem with that if we play the baseball I think we're
capable of playing.''
</P>
<P>
   How the Mariners perform in the week before the trading deadline
next Saturday may not influence Woodward's decisions. To him, the
Mariners still have a chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're approaching the trading deadline as if we are in the
race, and so any deal we're trying to make will be made with an eye
to the race now, and players that can help us down the road,'' he
said. ``That'll be the No. 1 objective, although we'll also take a
look at a possible deal where we acquire a player who is only here
for the short term. We're still looking at both types of deals.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners could make a deal in which they move one of their
potential free agents while acquiring players who could help now.
One such scenario could involve the Yankees' Andy Pettitte, who may
be on the trading block. Mariners scouts have attended Pettitte's
past two outings, and Fassero might be a fit with New York for
several reasons.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees need left-handed relief help _ their roster includes
departed Mariner Allen Watson _ and despite his struggles, Fassero
could help there. They also would like to cut payroll, and since
Pettitte is eligible for arbitration and could make perhaps $7
million next year, a pitcher in the last year of his deal, like
Fassero, would save them money.
</P>
<P>
   Another possible partner is the Boston Red Sox, whose general
manager and pitching coach (Dan Duquette and Joe Kerrigan,
respectively) held those positions in Montreal when Fassero played
for the Expos. Injuries have made pitching a priority for Boston,
but it's unclear whether the teams' proximity in the wild-card race
will preclude any deals.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens, Woodward apparently is not working under the
same constraints as many of the teams he has contacted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked to a couple of clubs the last few days, and
they've either said they're not going to do anything because they
can't add payroll, or they've decided to move as many players as
they can,'' Woodward said. ``We are not in those positions. We're
going to at least continue to explore.''
</P>
<P>
   CLASS OF '99: Mariners broadcaster Dave Niehaus will be calling
the Mariners-Twins game on Sunday, but there's one place he'd
rather be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could be there in Cooperstown, because two of my
great friends are going in,'' Niehaus said.
</P>
<P>
   Niehaus was an Angels broadcaster during Nolan Ryan's glory days
with California in the '70s. He also has developed a close
friendship with George Brett, another player who will be inducted
into the Hall of Fame this weekend. Niehaus called Ryan's first
four no-hitters and was there for Ryan's final game, in the
Kingdome with the Texas Rangers in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Niehaus remembers Ryan routinely throwing 150 to 160 pitches a
game, sometimes exceeding 200. The only physical worries Niehaus
recalled were blisters on Ryan's fingers, made better when the
pitcher soaked them in pickle brine. Ryan autographed Niehaus'
scoresheet from his first no-hitter; the Nolan Ryan Museum in
Alvin, Texas, has been calling about that.
</P>
<P>
   The last pitch of Ryan's no-hitter against Baltimore in 1975? A
knee-buckling change-up, of all things, to the Orioles' Bobby
Grich.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan's all-time strikeout record? Niehaus knows it's 5,714 _
``It's an easy number to remember: you just take Babe Ruth's home
runs and add 5,000.'' The knockout blow to Ryan's career? A grand
slam by the Mariners' Dann Howitt just before the elbow-destroying
fastball that was Ryan's last pitch.
</P>
<P>
   After that game, Niehaus shared a heartfelt hug with Ryan and
his wife, Ruth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think anybody who is a parent would be proud to have Nolan
Ryan as a son, not only because of his baseball prowess but because
of his moral character,'' Niehaus said.
</P>
<P>
   Robin Yount will join Ryan and Brett as inductees. Yount got his
3,000th hit off Mariners closer Jose Mesa in 1992, when Mesa was
with Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   AROUND THE HORN: Golfer Tiger Woods will be Ken Griffey Jr.'s
guest at the Metrodome Saturday. ... Griffey has a term for the
0-for-5 he took in Thursday's win over Oakland: the pineapple.
Pineapple? ``Hawaii _ 5-0,'' Griffey said. ... The Metrodome is
Griffey's favorite road park for home runs. He has hit 21 lifetime
homers here, two more than at Yankee Stadium, which ranks second.
... Minnesota is known better for snowmen than sandmen, but don't
tell that to the folks at Sand-tastic Promotions. They're building
a 15-ton sand sculpture of Twins legend Kirby Puckett outside the
Metrodome Saturday. ... The Twins will borrow from the Mariners'
promotions department tonight when they stage ``Turn Ahead The
Clock'' night. Both Seattle and Minnesota will wear futuristic
uniforms, as Seattle did in a home promotion last season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-99 0139EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
