u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      07-24 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S HARD TO TELL WHO'S THE CHUMP: UMPS OR BASEBALL? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ If you think the Mariners' Class AAA pitchers got
knocked around during ill-advised stints in the big leagues, just
wait until the minor-league umps get their shot.
</P>
<P>
   Think they'll survive a home-plate showdown with the likes of
Sweet Lou Piniella, Davey Johnson or Bobby Cox?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, baseball commissioner Bud Selig has hired 20 minor-leaguers
for major league duty starting Sept. 1 _ one day before the major
league guys have threatened to resign _ which will be wildly
entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   But what baseball really needs is not a war with the umps, but a
solution to the small-market death march. Who has time to argue
balls and strikes when the fiscal foundation of the industry is in
a torpor?
</P>
<P>
   The commish has promised on many occasions that baseball will
address the chasm between big-market teams and the guppies who
aren't owned by a Ted Turner, George Steinbrenner or Rupert
Murdoch. But now the immediate issue concerns the umpires, who have
voted to take their $15 million severance package and resign.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, baseball needs to use this opportunity to gain more
control of its umpires, who may have misjudged not only their
leverage but their union membership's unity and resolve.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA doesn't stand for referees interpreting rules according
to individual whims and flights of self-important fancy. Why should
baseball umps have free reign? Are you listening, Richie Phillips?
</P>
<P>
   Now Selig and other baseball officials are delirious that the
umps have made the fatal decision to quit. The umps are doing the
dirty work all on their own. All Selig has to do is sit back and
gloat.
</P>
<P>
   But who'll be laughing come October?
</P>
<P>
   Most bosses like to believe that an entire segment of the work
force is as dispensable as paper plates. But a postseason with
minor-league umps behind the plates is a disaster waiting to
happen.
</P>
<P>
   That's why it behooves the lords of baseball to negotiate with
these splintering, not-all-are-rotten group of umpires _ some are
actually in shape and competent _ and then move on, as promised, to
the industry's real problem, which is disparity between the Haves
and Have Nots.
</P>
<P>
   TOUGH CHOICE: Trouble in the Bone Yard?
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, we all know about the uncertainty of Ken Griffey Jr.'s and
Alex Rodriguez's futures with the Mariners. But the M's have an
option on Jay Buhner's contract and Edgar Martinez is a free agent
after this season, too.
</P>
<P>
   In another time and place, you could rationalize Buhner as a DH,
but the M's will be hard-pressed to spend big money for both
beloved veterans, especially with the injuries that have plagued
Buhner the past two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a pleasant call, but unless Buhner takes a monstrous
salary cut and/or Buhner's buddy in center field does not insist
Buhner stays, the M's will stick with Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   DUNN DEAL: The new head coach of Seattle's prospective WNBA
franchise was on the job less than 24 hours when she scored her
first victory, as pitchwoman extraordinaire.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes after she was announced as coach and general manager of
the professional women's basketball expansion franchise, Lin Dunn's
Tennessee accent has been heard on TV and radio all across the
Puget Sound.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn's mantra? ``That's 217-WNBA. That's 217-WNBA. Now y'all go
out and get yourself a season ticket, ya hear?''
</P>
<P>
   FROM SPOKANE TO MINNEAPOLIS?: For Gonzaga basketball coach Dan
Monson, it could go from beat a Gopher, to be a Gopher.
</P>
<P>
   QUOTE OF THE WEEK: From umpire Rocky Roe on his union's vote for
mass resignation Sept. 2:
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got 58 or 59 Type A personalities in a small room and
we got worked into a frenzy. People say, `How could you guys do
that?' You can correlate it to the Jonestown massacre. How in the
world did they get people to suck down all that Kool-Aid.''
</P>
<P>
   Turns out not all the umps wanted to take a sip.
</P>
<P>
   FREE-AGENT BONANZA: Next weekend gives sports fans a potentially
unprecedented blitz of comings and goings. At midnight on July 31,
there is the double witching of baseball's trading deadline and the
Aug. 1 start of the NBA's free-agent signing period.
</P>
<P>
   Ladies and gentlemen, get out your scorecards.
</P>
<P>
   SPEAKING OF THE SONICS: Mitch Richmond may be 34 and on the
downside of his career, but a backcourt of Gary Payton and Richmond
would be tasty ... if Hersey Hawkins gets to stay, too.
</P>
<P>
   FASSERO PREDICTION: If the Mariners trade the veteran lefty, he
will come back next season and pitch great for someone else.
</P>
<P>
   IRON MAN MOYER?: Any more regrets about Piniella taking Jamie
Moyer out of the game in favor of Jose Mesa on Safeco's opener need
only see that 129 pitches was all Moyer could handle.
</P>
<P>
   MICHELLE AKERS, BRANDI CHASTAIN &AMP; CO.: Just wondering: Are they
still enjoying their 15 minutes of fame. Or should we vote to
extend it?
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
