<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-INDIANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH ONE SWING, YANKS' JETER KNOCKS OUT INDIANS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ No, these are not the 1998 New York Yankees. Roger
Clemens and Andy Pettitte have struggled, Joe Torre missed more
than a month because of prostate cancer, and Jorge Posada and Scott
Brosius and Paul O'Neill all slumped early in the year. And still
they have the best record in baseball, after they beat the
Cleveland Indians, 9-8, in a raucous 10-inning game Friday night at
Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees were down to their final out in the bottom of the
10th when Derek Jeter _ 0 for 5 with three strikeouts in the first
nine innings and cajoled by his anxious mother _ drove home the
tying and winning runs with a bases-loaded single off Mike Jackson,
thrilling what remained of the original crowd of 52,704. The game
lasted 4 hours 33 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   David Cone, in his first appearance since his perfect game last
Sunday, lasted four innings, allowing six runs _ four of those
after a two-out error by Chuck Knoblauch. ``It's the type of win
that really feels good, because I had squandered the lead,'' Cone
said.
</P>
<P>
   Many leads and opportunities were squandered. Roberto Alomar's
grand slam off Cone gave the Indians a 6-5 lead, and Richie Sexson
added to that with a solo shot. But the Yankees came back with two
runs in the bottom of the eighth, tying the score at 7-7 on a
two-run double by Chad Curtis _ his first hit with runners in
scoring position since May 28.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians had a runner at second in the top of the ninth and
could not score. Knoblauch reached second in the bottom of the
ninth with a walk and a stolen base, and he was stranded.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Grimsley retired the first two batters in the top of the
10th, but he walked Einar Diaz on four pitches, and Diaz stole
second. Enrique Wilson lashed a single to center and Diaz trotted
raced home with the go-ahead run. Jackson, the Cleveland closer,
jogged in from the bullpen, aiming to finish off the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   But Chili Davis singled to open the 10th inning, and was
replaced by the pinch-runner Luis Sojo, who moved to second on a
sacrifice bunt. Brosius popped out, and Jackson quickly jumped
ahead in the count to Posada, one ball and two strikes; the Yankees
were one strike away from defeat. That's when Jackson lost control:
he threw three straight balls to Posada, fell behind Knoblauch
three balls and no strikes, mixed in a strike, and walked
Knoblauch, too. Bases loaded, two outs, Jeter walking to the plate.
</P>
<P>
   It had been a bad night for the Yankees' shortstop. After the
second of his three strikeouts, he made eye contact with his
mother, Dorothy Jeter, who was sitting a few rows back in the
stands with Jeter's father. Do something, she communicated to her
son. Do something.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in the Yankees' dugout, manager Joe Torre tries to
imagine why good things should happen. When Knoblauch batted, he
imagined Knoblauch would get a game-tying hit, to redeem himself
for the error. Now Jeter was ready to bat, and Torre thought to
himself that Jeter's batting average had slipped under .370. ``He
needs to get back to .370,'' Torre said aloud, just as Jackson
reared back and fired his first pitch to Jeter.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter was looking for a fastball; Jackson threw him a slider,
but this stayed over the plate, and Jeter powered it to
right-center. Manny Ramirez, Cleveland's right fielder, chased the
ball and ran, but Jeter and Torre knew he had no chance. Jeter
threw a fist into the air as he rounded first, and his parents
traded high-fives as the rest of the Yankees streamed onto the
field to congratulate Jeter.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are 58-37; the Indians 57-38.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians lorded over the American League for more than two
months, and for a time they played at a pace above and beyond that
of the '98 Yankees. But the rigors of the baseball season are
gnawing at the Indians: third baseman Travis Fryman tore a knee
ligament and may never return to full strength, and similarly,
there is no guarantee that catcher Sandy Alomar will rebound to
form.
</P>
<P>
   But their pitching staff is most troubling to the Indians. Jaret
Wright, once projected as a can't-miss ace because of his
96-mile-an-hour fastball, is on the disabled list with a strained
muscle and a scout who saw Wright's last start said his fastball
topped out at 89 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Dwight Gooden has been pounded, and Dave Burba's earned run
average is close to 5.00. Now the Indians are said to be focusing
on the possible acquisition of Chuck Finley, the Anaheim
left-hander who has dominated the Yankees in the past; Cleveland
officials sat and talked Friday with Mark Langston, a former
teammate of Finley, to debrief him.
</P>
<P>
   Cone seemed somewhat anxious early, his fastball sailing high,
and walked the first batter he faced, Kenny Lofton _ so much for
back-to-back perfect games. After O'Neill banged a two-run homer in
the bottom of the first, Sexson singled to open the second _ so
much for back-to-back no-hitters.
</P>
<P>
   With one out, Cone hung a splitter and the rookie Russell
Branyan laced it over the right-field wall. It was going to be that
kind of game, more like a Hagler-Hearns slugfest than an artful
baseball game.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees continued to blister Tom Candiotti, the Cleveland
starter, in the second inning. Ricky Ledee doubled, Brosius drove
home Ledee with a single, and after Brosius advanced to second on a
wild pitch, Knoblauch stroked a hit and Brosius scored. O'Neill _
whose first-inning home run caromed off the facing of the upper
deck in right field _ lined a ball to right-center, where it rolled
all the way to the wall for a triple. Yankees 5, Indians 2.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
