<P>
   HAPPINESS (Undated) _ The secret to happiness, it turns out, may
not be wealth or power. Or love or success or faithful friendship.
Or Ray Charles crooning ``Georgia on My Mind'' or even chocolate
mousse. Finding happiness may mean going no further than your very
own forehead _ the left prefrontal cortex of your brain, to be
exact. The more the sparks fly from this sliver of gray matter, the
more electrical impulses it generates, the happier you are.
Researchers are beginning to use gene mapping, brain imaging and
scientific surveys to understand what makes people happy. By Pam
Belluck. (1800 words)
</P>
<P>
   ROMAN-DEMOCRACY (Undated) _ To most historians of this century,
the Roman republic was seen as a corrupt oligarchy ruled by a rich
and decadent aristocracy, despite its democratic constitution,
popular assemblies and regularly elected officials. Yet several
scholars have been nibbling away at Republican Rome's undemocratic
reputation, arguing that it was an imperfect but still recognizable
democracy. Political office was less controlled by the aristocracy
than assumed. What's more, they say, in some ways, Rome had even
more in common with modern notions of democracy than Athens,
revered as the birthplace of a purer show-of-hands democracy. By
Paul Lewis. (1100 words)
</P>
<P>
   OPERA-RESURRECTION (Undated) _ Resurrection from the dead may be
the most universal of mythic ideas: a devoted savior descends to
the netherworld to restore a loved one to life. But there is always
a price to be paid: natural law is rarely overturned without
penalty and pain. Persephone must return to Hades. This myth is
also at the heart of two 400-year-old operas. In the Chinese opera,
``The Peony Pavilion,'' the slightly cocky young scholar Liu
Mengmei brings his beloved back to life. And in Monteverdi's
``Orfeo,'' Orpheus, whose playing of the lyre could wring tears
from stones, uses his music to rescue his Eurydice from Hades. By
Edward Rothstein. (1000 words)
</P>
