<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SURVIVOR-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOLE SURVIVORS LEARN TO FILL LIVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KARINA BLAND  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Now, there is only Caroline Kennedy Schlossberg, the
sole survivor of her immediate family, bearing the deaths of first
her father, then her mother and now her brother.
</P>
<P>
   And there is only Douglas Whitneybell.
</P>
<P>
   The Phoenix man, too, is the sole survivor of his immediate
family, losing first his father, then his brother and then his
mother.
</P>
<P>
   But Whitneybell has two delightful sons, ages 15 and 11, a
successful career as an architect and companionable relationships
with his ex-wife, extended family and good friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is what fills my life, so I don't feel orphaned at all,''
Whitneybell, 58, said. ``If I was just out there by myself, that
would have been more difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Caroline Kennedy Schlossberg is not alone, either. She has a
husband and three children, ages 12, 9 and 6, and a large extended
family. That is likely what will sustain her, experts on grief say.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing is to have a support system around
you,'' said Marty Tousley, a bereavement counselor for Hospice of
the Valley, a non-profit agency that provides care and services for
terminally ill people and their families.
</P>
<P>
   Schlossberg waited out the search for first her brother's plane
and then his body at her Long Island home with her husband and
children. She did not join the rest of the Kennedy clan in Hyannis
Port, Mass., where they were gathered for the wedding of Rory
Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. William Worden, author of ``Grief Counseling and Grief
Therapy'' and director of Harvard's child bereavement study, said
Caroline _ though the death of her brother likely is devastating _
has probably revamped her definition of her ``family'' to mean her
husband and kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though it was dreadful to lose her brother, it probably
is not quite as dramatic as it is made to be because she has her
kids and her husband,'' Worden said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, when loved ones die suddenly and unexpectedly, it can
shatter a person's sense of security, Tousley said.
</P>
<P>
   And it likely would take longer to get over the initial grief of
yet another death after suffering so much loss, the experts agree.
</P>
<P>
   Whitneybell was 10 when his father was killed in a plane crash
in Korea.
</P>
<P>
   It was 1950, and Whitneybell remembers his mother sending him
and his brother, 5, upstairs when the base commander knocked on the
front door. This was a time of war, and everyone knew what it meant
when the officers in uniform came to your house, Whitneybell said.
</P>
<P>
   The family returned to the United States via a military
transport, and settled in Arizona, where a friend lived, and where
Whitneybell grew up without a dad.
</P>
<P>
   He did not play on a Little League team. ``I had never caught a
football, batted a bat,'' Whitneybell said, though he did run track
in high school. His mother didn't talk about the boys' father, so
they didn't either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I put it all on hold, sort of tucked it away,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Whitneybell was 34 when his brother, Don, killed himself. Then,
14 years ago when Whitneybell was 44, his mother died.
</P>
<P>
   Six months before she died, she told her oldest son that his
father might be buried at Arlington National Cemetery. A year after
his mother died, he visited the grave.
</P>
<P>
   The deaths, Whitneybell said, have made him a better father to
his own boys. James is now 15. Whitneybell's younger boy, Benjamin,
is 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't know how long you are going to be around for your
kids, so try to really leave them with important things, and,
obviously, these are not physical things,'' he said. ``I don't
think hardly a day goes by that I don't think, `I am so glad I am
here for my sons.' ''
</P>
<P>
   When his mother died, Whitneybell put together a collage of
photographs of his parents, brother, himself and their dog, George.
</P>
<P>
   There are pictures of them on a boat to Japan, one of his father
at the Pentagon. Another shows the family at home in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a way of saying goodbye with respect and love, really,
to all three,'' Whitneybell said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
