<DOCNO> NYT19990724.0042 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-24 02:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2519 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     07-24 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS, DIAMONDBACKS SWITCH FORTUNES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A couple of years ago, if you'd asked the man on
the street to define ``Dodgers,'' you'd have been told of 21
National League pennants, reliable family ownership and a field
manager honored with a likeness on a jar of spaghetti sauce. The
Dodgers were a ballclub envied all the way from here to George
Steinbrenner's front porch.
</P>
<P>
   If you'd prevailed on that same man on the street to define
``Diamondbacks,'' you'd have heard something about venomous
rattlers indigenous to the American Southwest. The word
Diamondbacks had yet to be stitched across an athletic jersey.
</P>
<P>
   That same man _ whom we hope is off the street by now _ must be
shocked to read the baseball standings these days. The Los Angeles
Dodgers are battling for last place in the NL West. The Arizona
Diamondbacks are fighting for first.
</P>
<P>
   As the two teams began a weekend series in Phoenix on Friday
night, the Diamondbacks were eight games higher in the standings.
It could be stated almost literally that the Dodgers were lower
than a snake's belly, though not as low as a Marlin's.
</P>
<P>
   It's one thing to trail the Giants, descendents of Mel Ott, Carl
Hubbell and Willie Mays. Or even the Padres, pennant winners
themselves once or twice. But the Diamondbacks, who trace their
history all the way back to Andy Stankiewicz, Todd Erdos and Marty
Janzen?
</P>
<P>
   How could the Dodgers have fallen behind the Diamondbacks so
quickly, in the Arizona team's second season on the field? Viewed
from the sidewalk, it defies common sense.
</P>
<P>
   The answer is that after the Dodgers were 18 games the better
team in 1998, and after the two clubs faced similar challenges
going into the winter, the Diamondbacks got the better of almost
every offseason maneuver.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, look back beyond the winter. Consider all the comings
and goings from the two clubs' rosters since early '98, when the
Diamondbacks took their first shy steps to the plate and the
Dodgers tacked up the Under New Management sign.
</P>
<P>
   Each team got a new left fielder _ the Dodgers trading with
Florida for Gary Sheffield in May '98, the D'Backs signing Luis
Gonzalez away from Detroit as a free agent in December.
</P>
<P>
   _Advantage: D'Backs. Gonzalez, a former free-swinger making his
fourth address change in as many seasons, began the week as one of
the league's top hitters at .358, on pace for 100 runs and RBI.
Sheffield, even in a solid year, hasn't matched that.
</P>
<P>
   Each team got a new center fielder _ the Dodgers signing Devon
White away from Arizona in November, the D'Backs replacing him by
signing Steve Finley away from San Diego a month later.
</P>
<P>
   _Advantage: D'Backs. Finley, fighting disk problems at 34, has
bounced back to his 28 homer-101 run form of '97. White, 36, seems
to have left his heart in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Each team got a new starting ace _ the Dodgers signing Kevin
Brown from San Diego in December, the D'Backs signing Randy Johnson
in November.
</P>
<P>
   _Advantage: D'Backs. Johnson: a major-league-high 265
strikeouts, a league-best 2.65 ERA, a 10-7 record. Brown: 10-6 but
an NL-career-high 3.78.
</P>
<P>
   Each team got one of those starters you think you can count on
for a double-figure win total _ the Dodgers trading with the Expos
for Carlos Perez at the July '98 trading deadline, the D'Backs
signing Todd Stottlemyre from Texas in November.
</P>
<P>
   _Advantage: D'Backs. Stottlemyre: four wins _ he's been on the
disabled list with a shoulder tear since May. Perez: two _ he's
perfectly healthy.
</P>
<P>
   Each team got a veteran set-up reliever _ the Dodgers signing
Alan Mills from Baltimore in November, the D'Backs signing
left-hander Greg Swindell from Boston the same week.
</P>
<P>
   Call that one even.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the Dodgers got the position-for-position edge with a
couple of Tom Lasorda's and Kevin Malone's moves.
</P>
<P>
   You'd rather have bullpen closer Jeff Shaw (acquired in
Lasorda's Cincinnati trade in July '98) than 26-year-old Matt
Mantei (brought in from Florida in a desperate trade for young
pitchers by Arizona GM Joe Garagiola Jr. earlier this month).
</P>
<P>
   You'd rather have shortstop Mark Grudzielanek (with Perez in
Lasorda's Montreal trade) than Andy Fox.
</P>
<P>
   You'd rather have catcher Todd Hundley (acquired in Malone's
Mets trade in December) than the Arizona combination of Kelly
Stinnett and Damian Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, given Hundley's inability to hit the broad side of
Tony Gwynn with a throw to second base in the first half-season,
you could easily say that between the Dodgers and the D'Backs, so
far catcher has been a toss-up.
</P>
<P>
   To improve themselves, the D'backs spent a lot of free-agent
money and traded away Karim Garcia (to get Gonzalez). The Dodgers
spent a lot of free-agent money and traded away Mike Piazza and
Todd Zeile (for Sheffield and three major-leaguers no longer in Los
Angeles), Roger Cedeno and Charles Johnson (for Hundley) and at
least five promising young players (in the Shaw and Grudzielanek
deals).
</P>
<P>
   Biggest edge of all: D'backs' front office.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers could say the standings reflect the D'backs' good
luck. How could they have known Jay Bell, moved from short to
second base, would turn into a regular Davey Johnson (circa 1973)
with the bat? Or that Gonzalez would appropriate the soul of Joe
DiMaggio? Or that Finley wasn't washed up?
</P>
<P>
   True, they're partly luck, those eight games in the standings.
But wasn't it an old Dodger who said luck is the residue of design?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
