<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990724.0053 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-24 02:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2542 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-KHMER-ROUGE-NYT &LR;      07-24 0469
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-KHMER-ROUGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: BRINGING THE KHMER ROUGE TO JUSTICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, July 24:
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even as some of those who committed genocide in Rwanda and
Bosnia are being brought to international justice, perpetrators of
one of history's most horrifying slaughters have escaped. Now,
however, the United Nations is moving closer to establishing a
court to try leaders of the Khmer Rouge, whose members killed more
than a million of their countrymen when they ruled Cambodia from
1975 to 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary-General Kofi Annan is deciding on the details of the
court he will recommend that the U.N. support. The court will be in
Cambodia and needs the approval of Cambodia's strongman, Hun Sen.
But it must also feature effective international controls to insure
that it can do real justice and will not be manipulated by Hun Sen.
</P>
<P>
   The Khmer Rouge leader Pol Pot is dead, but many of his
lieutenants are alive and free in Cambodia. As part of Hun Sen's
attempt to conquer the last remnants of the Khmer Rouge still
waging war from the jungle, he cut deals that effectively give the
top Khmer Rouge officials Ieng Sary, Nuon Chea and Khieu Samphan
immunity in exchange for their loyalty. The sole high-ranking Khmer
Rouge officer in prison, Ta Mok, earned Hun Sen's wrath because he
kept on fighting, not for what he did during Khmer Rouge rule. If
the others are not turned over for trial, the process will be a
sham.
</P>
<P>
   The structure of the court will matter. Hun Sen has used the
issue for his political gain and keeps firm control of Cambodia's
judicial system. The fairest court would have been an international
tribunal such as those for Bosnia and Rwanda. Hun Sen rejected that
idea, which led to the perception that China, which has backed him
on this issue, would veto the necessary Security Council
resolution. Anticipating such a veto, The Security Council did
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Now the U.N. will recommend some form of a Cambodian court with
international participation. If done correctly, such a court can
not only dispense justice, but also show Cambodians what fair
trials look like and demonstrate that leaders can be held
accountable.
</P>
<P>
   But Hun Sen, who has endorsed a mixed tribunal in principle, has
much opportunity for mischief. He could delay the process
indefinitely, try only his political opponents, stack the court
with his acolytes or create a show trial. The U.N. should hold out
for close Security Council supervision, and must be willing to stop
the process and disown it if it produces a whitewash. Hun Sen will
resist, but he is going along with a court largely to improve his
image abroad. Strong international pressure is needed to ensure
that Khmer Rouge trials are just.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-99 0212EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
