</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-REWRITE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON PLANS CHANGES AFTER LATEST DODGERS LOSS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(OPTIONAL: Adds quotes, details) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ It was a disaster, disgraceful, and after the latest
abomination Los Angeles Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said no
longer can things remain status quo.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' fourth straight loss, a 10-1 pasting by Arizona in
the first of a three-game series at Bank One Ballpark on Friday,
was full of everything that's wrong with the club these days.
</P>
<P>
   The remnants of the loss were right fielder Raul Mondesi
watching the top of the fifth from the Dodgers bullpen instead of
the bench, and a lengthy meeting between Eric Young and Johnson
afterward that could spell the end to Young's starting time at
second base.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to have to start making some changes around here
tomorrow,'' Johnson said. ``Look at a few things I think might help
our ballclub. We gave them too many outs. I'm going to start doing
a little tweaking.''
</P>
<P>
   By the way, the Dodgers managed just two hits. One came on left
fielder Gary Sheffield's homer to lead off the sixth. It was his
17th of the season, but first since June 27.
</P>
<P>
   Omar Daal didn't allow a hit until Young singled off shortstop
Edwin Diaz's glove with one out in the fifth. He improved to 9-5
and beat the Dodgers for the second time this season after allowing
one run on two hits in seven innings. And though Daal walked five,
the Dodgers failed to take advantage of his wildness.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to understand the game, you have to have knowledge of
the game,'' Sheffield said. ``You can't just go up there and hack
away. Sure, you can hit 30 homers and drive in 100 runs, but it
doesn't mean anything if it doesn't help the team.''
</P>
<P>
   But enough about the offensive ineptitude for now.
</P>
<P>
   Tops on Johnson's list of changes could be Young, who drew the
ire of teammates after failing to turn what should have been a
double play, jump-starting Arizona's five-run fourth inning.
</P>
<P>
   On what was a perfect double-play grounder to shortstop Mark
Grudzielanek, Young failed to turn the double play and made an
off-target throw to first with slow-footed catcher Damian Miller
batting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was textbook,'' Grudzielanek said of the
grounder. ``What are you going to do? I don't know if he was
playing too far over. It was pretty legit. I don't know what else
to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of two outs and none on, the inning digressed with
left-hander Carlos Perez misplaying Daal's bunt to load the bases.
Jay Bell and Luis Gonzalez each doubled in two runs to give the
Diamondbacks a 7-0 lead. Gonzalez went to third when Mondesi's
throw to second was off line and went into left field.
</P>
<P>
   Diamondbacks third baseman Matt Williams, who hit a two-run
homer in the first, ended the inning with an RBI single to right as
Arizona went ahead 8-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just didn't have a grip on it,'' Young said. ``(It) was just
a bad game. It could have been from fatigue. It seemed like we
didn't have any jump.''
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't the end, though. After the third out was recorded,
Mondesi opted to sit in the right-field bullpen instead of on the
Dodgers bench, re-emerging from the bullpen for the bottom of the
fifth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care where he goes if he wants to sit down,'' Johnson
said. ``It's OK for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the players didn't even notice Mondesi wasn't on the
bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't notice that, but if I was closest to it, I probably
would have done it also,'' Grudzielanek said. ``I don't know what
to say about (the Dodgers' play). It's pretty bad. Pretty bad, to
say the least.''
</P>
<P>
   Another possible move could be with starter Perez, who gave a
typical performance and did not speak afterward.
</P>
<P>
   As remarkable as it seems in what's been a lost season, Perez
reached a new low despite going six innings. He allowed a
career-high 10 runs, all of which were earned. His
already-unthinkable 6.88 ERA rose to 7.43 and he fell to 2-10. His
position in the rotation could finally be lost.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
