</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-IRWINDALE-SCHEDULE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRWINDALE RACERS SET FOR END OF FRIDAY NIGHT RACING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH LAIR  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRWINDALE, Calif. _ Life might return to a little bit of
normalcy for Rod Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of spending both Friday and Saturday nights at Irwindale
Speedway, the track's most prolific driver -- he's in the Top 5 in
two divisions -- will be able to spend at least one night at his
Canyon Country home. And no more lost vacation time to go racing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad it's over,'' the Super Late Model points leader said.
``It's hard to be here on Fridays. It frees up my Fridays so I can
spend time with my family.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to curtail the Friday-night show, which will end
after next week, came about two weeks ago, track chief operating
officer Ray Wilkings said. The track has averaged a crowd of 2,296
on Fridays, of which about half are children, and are free. Each
division will lose between four and six races under the schedule,
which was released on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all drivers were in agreement with Johnson; they wish
they could race five or six more times this season, but it's too
hard to race on Friday nights and it will be better to race before
larger crowds on Saturdays. They also understood the move from a
business standpoint, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was kind of hoping they would finish out the year,'' said
Gerrit Cromsigt, whose Late Model division has raced almost
exclusively on Fridays. ``But I think it will be a good thing all
around because I think we can get a higher car count.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Schrader, the track's competitions director, said he did
not receive one complaint from a driver.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were saying thank you, thank you,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Schrader says the move will help improve car counts and make
racing better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our car counts have been consistent, but everyone has said
that we're racing too much.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cars aren't getting proper maintenance. Last week, the No.
85 car's (Cromsigt) motor broke and the No. 94 car's (Dusty
McDonald) valve spring broke. You know that the people in the No.
85 stayed up all night (Thursday) getting the motor in and now
they're sleepy and operating at 10 percent. We won't have drivers
who are tired, have no patience and are bound to run into others.''
</P>
<P>
   Mini Stock points leader Lee Ladd says Irwindale is his favorite
track, but he understands the dilemma facing the track; too few
cars and people in attendance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had to be,'' he said about the end of the Friday nights.
``The only mistake with Fridays is that they needed help with
traffic. It's too hard to get here. I love to race this track and I
just say `thank you' for the opportunity to race on Fridays.''
</P>
<P>
   A frequent Friday night Irwindale sight were drivers arriving
after qualifying. Sometimes, the only people in the pit area was
drivers; they'd help each other unload cars.
</P>
<P>
   When Ascot first opened, the Gardena facility had Friday and
Saturday night racing, but had to discontinue the Friday night
shows because of the same problems Irwindale is experiencing. About
the only metropolis in America that currently supports Friday-night
racing is Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Late Model leader McDonald said he'd race any day of the week,
but he knows why there isn't the draw on Fridays.
</P>
<P>
   ``People expect to watch baseball, basketball and football on
television in the middle of the week,'' the Simi Valley resident
said. ``They expect it be on. People think of racing and they think
of Saturdays and Sundays. They don't think of racing in the middle
of the week, or on Fridays.''
</P>
<P>
   The only disagreement in the schedule change came from some
people in the grandstands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like it,'' said Bart Yelton of Ontario, who has
attended every Irwindale event. ``I like bringing my grandchildren.
Everything's cheaper.''
</P>
<P>
   But some fans understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is pretty good for a reasonable amount of money,'' said
Arcadia resident Robert Angles, who brought his 10-year-old son,
Robbie. ``We come Saturdays, and we're disappointed they're
eliminating Fridays. We're disappointed that we don't see more
people here.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilkings said he knew the Friday schedule would be a tough sell.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too tough,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Except for special shows, which would require more than one
night, Wilkings says the Friday shows are history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we'll go back,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
