<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-24 10:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2558 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  AM-NYT-BUDGET &LR;      07-24 1414
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(th) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Sunday, July 25:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-RUSSIA-MOB (Washington) _ A few years ago, British
intelligence and law enforcement agencies began investigating the
money-laundering activities of Russian organized crime in Britain.
At the center of their concerns was Semyon Yukovich Mogilevich, a
man described by British authorities in one classified report as
``one of the world's top criminals, who has a personal wealth of
$100 million.'' When the British shut him down in 1995, Mogilevich
began laundering his illicit profits into a new venture: an
American company listed on the Canadian stock exchange. Current and
former American officials say Mogilevich is the harbinger of a
disturbing new trend: the Russian mobster masquerading as crack
capitalist. By Raymond Bonner. (With a graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-ECONOMY (Beijing) _ China's top leaders fled the stifling
heat of Beijing this week for their annual retreat at a seaside
resort, leaving behind a city swirling with propaganda about the
crackdown against a spiritual movement known as Falun Gong. But
while the Communist Party has mounted a relentless media assault on
the group, which it outlawed on Thursday, economics rather than
politics are likely to occupy the leaders as they gather in the
tranquil resort of Beidaihe. Specifically, analysts here say they
will have to confront China's economy, which is sputtering, and a
reform effort that is in danger of stalling. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   (A photo, NYT18, moved Friday, July 23.)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-GULAG-VISIT (Magadan, Russia) _ On the outskirts of town,
a former Stalinist prison stands behind a row of concrete slabs.
Undaunted by warnings from local residents who wish to remember
Stalin's horrors but are acutely aware that this is still state
property, the Chinese-American guest scrambled up the wall. The
guest, Harry Wu, a former Chinese dissident, spent 19 years in
Maoist prisons. Now that he was visiting the Russian city that was
once the center of a sprawling archipelago of sub-Arctic prison
camps, he wanted a better look. By Russell Working.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SERB-DEATHS (Gracko, Yugoslavia) _ The mutilated bodies
of 14 Serbian farmers were discovered Friday night grouped around
their combine harvester in the worst single assault against the
dwindling pockets of Serb civilians left in Kosovo since NATO
troops arrived in the province last month. By Chris Hedges.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-SCHROEDER (Berlin) _ After nine months of confused
inertia in economic policy, Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder has at
last set out where his New Middle in politics lies _ and it is a
long way to the right of anything previously embraced by the German
leader's Social Democratic Party. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   VENEZUELA-CONSTITUTION (Caracas, Venezuela) _ The fate of South
America's longest-running, if turbulent, democracy hangs in the
balance in the vote on Sunday to select delegates to write a new
constitution _ the 27th in Venezuela's history, although the first
since 1961. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-CRIMINAL-COURT (United Nations) _ The United States is
expected to continue its campaign against politically inspired
war-crimes prosecutions at a conference about the proposed
International Criminal Court that begins Monday. By Paul Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   CZECH-GYPSY-STUDY (Prague, Czech Republic) _ According to a
study published by the European Roma Rights Center, a human rights
organization based in Budapest, Hungary, the Czech educational
system shows signs of widespread segregation and discrimination
against Gypsies. The study shows that a Gypsy child is at least 15
times more likely to be labeled mentally retarded than a Czech
pupil.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-PARKS-OVERUSE (Yellowstone National Park, Wyo.) _
Yellowstone is broken, but it is not the only national park
suffering. With the nation's 378 national park areas expected to
attract almost 300 million visitors this year after a record 286
million in 1998, many parks are deferring urgently needed capital
improvements. By Michael Janofsky. (With map and photos.)
</P>
<P>
   REM-GEORGIA-POLITICS (Athens, Ga.) _ A grassroots campaign
against a local hospital's plan to expand into surrounding
neighborhoods here has all the hallmarks of civic activism that
this college town is known for: yard signs, petitions, meetings,
protests and, of course, the support of one of the world's most
successful rock bands, R.E.M. By Tom Lassiter.
</P>
<P>
   CAPE-COD-ICECREAM (Centerville, Mass.) _ The Four Seas, a white
cottage with blue shutters and a white formica counter with 12 blue
stools, has been an institution on South Main Street of this Cape
Cod village for 65 summers. By Sara Rimer.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL-BRIEFS _ Short political items from around the nation.
By B. Drummond Ayres Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (Moving in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DEMS-CAMPAIGN-FUNDS (Washington) _ With George W. Bush sitting
atop a $37 million political war chest, the Democratic Party is
seeking to raise an unprecedented amount of the unregulated party
donations known as soft money, perhaps as much as $200 million by
November 2000. By Don Van Natta Jr.
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE-DISPARITIES (Washington) _ New government data show
huge disparities in what Medicare pays to train doctors in
different parts of the country, with some teaching hospitals in New
York getting three or four times as much for each trainee as those
in Los Angeles or Cleveland, and seven times as much as those in
Houston. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   TAXCUT-POLITICS (Washington) _ In the midst of the bitter debate
this week over the Republican tax bills moving through Congress, it
was easy to lose sight of the emerging consensus in both parties
that there should be a tax cut this year. The question now is where
the middle ground on taxes might be _ and how the White House and
Congress can get there. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   ESTATE-TAX-STUDY _ Congressional opponents of the estate tax say
it discourages savings, costs the economy more than it raises for
the government and makes it very difficult for a family-owned farm
or business to be passed to the next generation. But all of those
arguments are contradicted by government tax and economic data,
according to a new book-length study. By David Cay Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-REVIVAL (Washington) _ After his galling defeat by the
governor of Arkansas in 1992, President George Bush became
something of an outcast in his own party. At Republican functions,
speakers rattled on longingly about Ronald Reagan. But never about
Bush. It was as if Republicans had collective amnesia about the man
who led their party and the nation from 1989 to 1992. Not anymore.
By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   PRIVATE-PLANE-SAFETY (Washington) _ Each year, about 1 in 100 of
the nation's private planes have an accident, and 1 in 300 have an
accident that kills somebody. How can a traveler considering using
something other than a commercial airline spot the risky flights in
advance? By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
