<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-24 11:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2565 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEMS-CAMPAIGN-FUNDS-7     07-24 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-CAMPAIGN-FUNDS-735(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS AIM FOR RECORD IN UNREGULATED DONATIONS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, N.J., Colo., Wis.)   (jw) 
 By DON VAN NATTA Jr.     
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With George W. Bush sitting atop a $37 million
political war chest, the Democratic Party is seeking to raise an
unprecedented amount of the unregulated party donations known as
soft money, perhaps as much as $200 million by November 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Party officials and fund-raisers conceded in
interviews that they were trying to amass a record amount of soft
money as possibly the party's only chance to close the enormous
money gap with Bush, the governor of Texas. Soft money refers to
large contributions from corporations, wealthy individuals and
labor unions that fall outside the limits of federal election law.
</P>
<P>
   But the Democrats' aggressive soft-money drive places the party
and its eventual nominee in a politically awkward, possibly
vulnerable position. President Clinton, Vice President Al Gore and
former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey have all called on Congress
to ban soft money as part of a far-reaching overhaul of the
campaign-finance system.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Bradley, who is Gore's only rival for the Democratic
nomination, highlighted the issue confronting the party early last
week when he portrayed both Gore and Bush as hypocrites on
campaign-finance reform because they intended to rely heavily on
soft-money donations next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both reportedly have directed their top fund-raisers to begin
raising soft money to the general election,'' Bradley said.
``Before the money machine starts humming, let's pause and think
about a better way.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are hoping to collect nearly twice as much soft money
as they did for the 1996 elections because they fear that Bush will
have millions more to spend during the nomination battle early next
year. Bush, Republican front-runner, is not constrained by federal
spending limits in the primaries because he has decided not to
accept federal matching funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``There certainly is talk that they are going to beef up the
D.N.C. to raise more soft money,'' said a longtime Democratic
fund-raiser, who spoke on the condition that he not be identified.
``With the Bush numbers going off the chart, there is more of a
sense of urgency about the need to raise even more money sooner.''
</P>
<P>
   In interviews last week, nearly two dozen Democratic
fund-raisers, strategists and party officials voiced concerns that
their national committee was not equipped to meet its goal of
raising $200 million. One problem, fund-raisers say, is that both
Gore and Bradley trail Bush in most national polls by wide margins.
``People want to give to the candidate they believe will win,'' one
fund-raiser said.
</P>
<P>
   The worries were expressed as the Democratic National Committee
began to play host to a summer retreat for its large donors in
Aspen, Colo., over the weekend, with the president scheduled to
attend. Clinton has also agreed to headline more fund-raising
events for the DNC as part of its soft-money drive, but
fund-raisers say his drawing power has ebbed in recent weeks
because he is perceived to be a lame duck.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Engel, the DNC's executive director, said the committee was
on track to meet its fund-raising goals. ``We are ahead of our
projections _ not far ahead, but we are ahead of what we raised in
1995,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Engel disagreed with Democratic fund-raisers who described the
party's financial situation as dire, saying he doubted that they
had been actively involved in the party's planning. In April, DNC
officials came up with a fund-raising strategy that included a
strong push for soft money, and they have not wavered from it,
Engel said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know what we have to do to communicate our message,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   With the 2000 election calendar front-loaded with early contests
in expensive states such as New York and California, the Democratic
nominee could hit the primary spending ceiling of nearly $40
million or run out of money by late March.
</P>
<P>
   That could mean that in the spring and early summer next year,
Bush would still have ample money to spend, while his Democratic
challenger would be constrained from spending any money. After the
party conventions, the Republican and Democratic nominees will each
receive some $66 million in public money to run their campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Although the parties' soft money is not supposed to be spent to
aid candidates directly, the federal election laws are so riddled
with loopholes that this prohibition is routinely ignored.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the Democratic National Committee and the Republican
National Committee both spent tens of millions in soft money to buy
television advertising that promoted the agendas of the
Clinton-Gore ticket and Bob Dole, the Republican nominee. In 2000,
the DNC could again use soft money for so-called issue advertising
to keep the Democratic nominee afloat after his campaign runs out
of money or reaches the spending limit.
</P>
<P>
   DNC officials and leaders of Gore's campaign are hoping to
persuade Terence McAuliffe, a close friend of Clinton's and the
chairman of the Clinton-Gore campaign in 1995, to take a leadership
role in the Democratic committee, or at the very least become more
involved in the party's bid to raise large contributions from
wealthy donors.
</P>
<P>
   McAuliffe, who has already agreed to raise tens of millions for
the president's legal defense fund, the Clinton presidential
library and Hillary Rodham Clinton's all-but-certain Senate bid in
New York, is widely considered the best fund-raiser in the
Democratic Party. The most successful DNC fund-raising event this
year was a June 7 tribute to McAuliffe at the Washington home of
Beth Dozoretz, the committee's finance chairwoman, which raised
$3.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   But McAuliffe has been noncommittal about assuming an official
leadership role, committee officials say. He did not return phone
calls.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Russell Feingold, D-Wis., co-sponsor of the bill that would
ban soft money, said the Democratic Party should distinguish itself
from Bush's cash-flush campaign, which he said ``looks as if they
are trying to buy the presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it looks ugly; the presidency should not be bought and
sold,'' Feingold said. ``I would call this a missed opportunity to
show what the Democratic Party is all about. It is supposed to be,
and I believe it can be, the party of the average person _ not of
big money interests _ and I think this disparity with George Bush
gives the Democrats the opportunity to show it. It is a very
populist message.''
</P>
<P>
   If they fail to meet their soft-money goals, the Democrats may
have no choice but to adopt the Feingold strategy. In the first six
months of 1999, the Republican National Committee raised $30
million, party officials said. The Democratic National Committee
raised $21 million, but $6 million of that came from direct-mail,
which costs 50 cents on the dollar to raise, party officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the concerns of many fund-raisers, the committee
announced earlier this month that it had extinguished a stubborn,
2{-year-old debt and that it would have the resources to help elect
the Democratic nominee as president next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a new day in the Democratic Party,'' the committee's
national chairman, Joe Andrew, declared on July 1. ``We now have
more cash on hand than debt, and we are on a very solid footing
heading into the 2000 elections.''
</P>
<P>
   But Democratic Party officials, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said they feared that Andrew was being overly
optimistic. The committee still owes $4.8 million more, and has
about $5.5 million in the bank, leaving it with a surplus of just
under $700,000, they estimated.
</P>
<P>
   In the two years leading up to the congressional election in
1998, the Republican Party outraised the L Democratic Party in soft
money by $17 million.
</P>
<P>
   In two years before the 1996 presidential election, the
Democrats raised $102 million in soft money, according to the
Federal Election Commission, but it had the advantage of raising
large amounts through White House coffees and Lincoln Bedroom
overnight stays.
</P>
<P>
   A large infusion of soft money early in 1995 allowed the party
to broadcast pro-Clinton issue advertisements beginning in
September 1995 all over the country, a strategy that some say was
important to the president's building an early, insurmountable lead
over Dole.
</P>
<P>
   Several Democratic fund-raisers said the DNC's soft-money goals
were unrealistically lofty. As one Democratic strategist put it,
``They're going to need to raise $180 million in 15 months. It's an
impossible task.''
</P>
<P>
   Party officials said that their fund-raising efforts were
hampered the by war in Kosovo and the Columbine High School
shootings, which forced Clinton, their marquee draw, to cancel some
fund-raising events in March and April. It cost the committee an
estimated $6 million in contributions, officials said. But even
Clinton, who leaves office in less than 18 months, does not attract
as much money as he once did. Early last week, an event here, which
was attended by the president, raised $225,000, a sum that some
officials said was disappointing.
</P>
<P>
   Several fund-raisers said that they were especially concerned
that Gore has $9.4 million in the bank, just $2 million more than
Bradley and more than $20 million less than Bush's cash reserves.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can't raise money for the candidate in $1,000 checks,
how can you expect someone to give you $100,000 or $250,000
checks?'' said one longtime Democratic fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   Both Gore and Bradley have refused to accept contributions from
political action committees. But Bush does take PAC donations, just
one of many advantages he has in the money chase.
</P>
<P>
   Early last week, Gore's campaign released the names of 25
supporters who had raised at least $100,000 each. Several
fund-raisers said this caused alarm because the list did not
include some longtime fund-raisers for the party who have helped
the president.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
