<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-DISPARITIES-775&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY FINDS DISPARITIES IN AID FOR DOCTOR TRAINING
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ohio, N.Y., Texas, Pa., Mass., Conn.)   (jw) 
 By ROBERT PEAR    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ New government data show huge disparities in what
Medicare pays to train doctors in different parts of the country,
with some teaching hospitals in New York getting three or four
times as much for each trainee as those in Los Angeles or
Cleveland, and seven times as much as those in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Federal health officials have known for some time that Medicare
payments for such training varied from hospital to hospital. But a
study published last week in The New England Journal of Medicine
highlights the disparities and provides more detail than had ever
been publicly available.
</P>
<P>
   The disclosures come at a time when hospitals across the country
say they have been severely hurt by federal budget cuts, and
Congress is considering substantial changes in the financing of
graduate medical education, including proposals to sever the link
between Medicare and the federal support for teaching hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Hospital executives in New York City said the payments they
received for medical education were justified by high wage costs
and because they served large numbers of Medicare patients. But
hospital executives in California, Texas and Ohio said they saw no
justification for such large disparities because they, too, serve
large numbers of elderly patients. Moreover, they said the doctors
they produced were just as good as those trained in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The disparities, while real, are partly attributable to
accounting practices adopted years ago. Many hospitals in the
Northeast billed Medicare for faculty time, while elsewhere,
hospitals covered that cost in other ways.
</P>
<P>
   The study in The New England Journal presents data from the
Health Care Financing Administration, the federal agency that runs
Medicare. At the top of the list, it shows that Beth Israel Medical
Center in Manhattan has received an average Medicare payment of
$57,010 a year for each resident it trains, while Montefiore
Medical Center in the Bronx has received an average of $55,073.
Albert Einstein Medical Center in Philadelphia also received
relatively high payments, averaging $44,355 for each resident.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the Medicare payments for graduate medical
education averaged $29,843 for each resident at Massachusetts
General Hospital in Boston; $24,444 at Columbia-Presbyterian
Medical Center in Manhattan; $17,055 at Yale-New Haven Hospital;
$16,518 at the Cleveland Clinic Hospital, and $11,908 at the
University of California, Los Angeles, Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   Hermann Hospital in Houston, a major teaching hospital for the
University of Texas, received an average of $6,938 for each
resident.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, who has authority over Medicare as
chairman of the Ways and Means Committee, said, ``Clearly there are
inequities in the financing of graduate medical education.'' But to
date he has not endorsed any specific remedy.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare's primary mission is to finance health care for the
elderly and disabled, but the program has also become the main
vehicle for federal aid to teaching hospitals, providing some $7
billion annually. About a third of that money helps pay the direct
costs of medical education, including salaries and benefits for
doctors in training and their instructors, as well as a share of
hospital overhead costs.
</P>
<P>
   New York hospitals fear they could be harmed by any changes in
Medicare's complex formula for subsidizing medical education. Some
academic leaders in other parts of the country said they wanted to
increase their own payments without necessarily cutting New York's.
But that would require additional money.
</P>
<P>
   John Iglehart, a health policy expert who compiled the data,
said, ``The payments vary substantially, even in New York, because
of differences in the way teaching hospitals accounted for the
costs of residency training'' in 1984, the year used as a starting
point to compute payments for graduate medical education.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Nickelson, director of government relations for the
Cleveland Clinic Foundation, said: ``We had never billed Medicare
for faculty time _ doctors teaching residents in the hospital,
working with them on clinical research _ so the cost did not show
up in our Medicare cost report for 1984.''
</P>
<P>
   David Langness, a spokesman for the University of California at
Los Angeles, said: ``We want to find a way to achieve some parity.
Our costs are in the same league as the East Coast universities',
but we get paid a great deal less.''
</P>
<P>
   Langness said the five medical schools in the University of
California system would send top executives to Washington this week
to urge Congress to ``raise the payments to teaching hospitals that
have historically been underpaid.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Jim Mandler, a spokesman for Beth Israel Medical Center in New
York, said the president of the hospital, Dr. Matthew Fink, had
reviewed the data in The New England Journal and had no comment.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Spencer Foreman, president of Montefiore Medical Center,
said the disparities in Medicare payments, were rooted in the
different ways that medical education was financed in different
parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are legitimate costs,'' Dr. Foreman said. ``They have
been audited repeatedly. It's not cheaper to train a resident on
the West Coast than on the East Coast. But there's a difference in
how the costs are borne. In the older teaching hospitals of the
Northeast, the costs have been borne, to a large degree, by the
hospital. In California, the state government and the medical
schools have paid more of the faculty costs.''
</P>
<P>
   But some of the California teaching hospitals, like Cedars-Sinai
Medical Center in Los Angeles, are not affiliated with the state
university. Medicare payments at Cedars-Sinai average $19,479 for
each resident, which is 35 percent of the average at Montefiore.
</P>
<P>
   Montefiore officials estimate that 40 percent of their Medicare
payments go toward residents' salaries, while 30 percent go toward
faculty costs and the rest for overhead costs like classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Shlomo Melmed, senior vice president of Cedars-Sinai, said:
``We are a private hospital. We don't get any state subsidy for our
medical education program. We have to pay 100 percent of the costs
that are not covered by federal Medicare payments.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last decade, members of Congress from both parties have
suggested gradually reducing the disparities, so Medicare payments
for each resident would be closer to the national average. Dr.
Foreman said, ``That would kill some institutions like Montefiore
and would create windfalls for other places that have a lot of
state support.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
