<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-24 12:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2572 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-SERB-DEATHS-AR     07-24 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-SERB-DEATHS-ART-600(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
14 FARMERS KILLED IN WORST ASSAULT ON SERBS SINCE PEACE AGREEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Map is being
sent to NYT graphics clients. Nonsubscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 1-888-603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By CHRIS HEDGES    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRACKO, Yugoslavia _ The mutilated bodies of 14 Serbian farmers
were discovered Friday night near their combine harvester in the
worst single assault against the dwindling pockets of Serbian
civilians left in Kosovo since NATO troops arrived in the province
last month.
</P>
<P>
   The killings, in which several of the men appeared to have been
disfigured with blunt instruments, seemed likely to undermine still
further the effort by the international community to keep the
Serbian minority from fleeing Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   More than 80,000 of the estimated 200,000 Serbs living in Kosovo
when NATO's bombing of Yugoslavia ended have left since alliance
troops arrived in mid-June. The soldiers have proved so far
powerless to stop what Kosovo Serbs say is daily harassment, with
repeated rumors of kidnappings and killings. The discovery of the
bodies seems certain to accelerate the exodus.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials, who have promised to track down the attackers,
and senior Kosovo Liberation Army leaders, who denied involvement
in the attacks, on Saturday condemned the killings. The rebel army
of Kosovo Albanians waged a guerrilla war against Serbian forces
for a year, but has since called for Serbian civilians to remain in
the province.
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Kouchner, the U.N. transitional administrator for
Kosovo, called the killings ``inhumane and senseless'' and vowed
that the gunmen would be apprehended and brought to trial.
</P>
<P>
   British Special Investigations Branch officers sealed off the
site and were combing the field for evidence.
</P>
<P>
   The village of Gracko, centered on a rectangular green, was
muted and still on Saturday. Groups of women, all wearing
kerchiefs, black skirts and shawls, along with men in ill-fitting
suits, walked in hushed clusters to pay their condolences to
distraught families. Dust was kicked up on their shoes or rubber
boots as they passed flocks of geese and chickens.
</P>
<P>
   The forlorn troupes pushed open wooden fences and entered yards
outside simple stucco or red cinder block homes. They sat on
blanket-covered planks placed on the tops of cinder blocks, sipped
coffee in chipped demitasse cups or downed shots of clear-colored
local brandy. They said what they had come to say, most not able to
speak above a whisper, and moved on.
</P>
<P>
   The killings had all the hallmarks of a premeditated ambush,
British investigators said. The Serbian farmers, who were
harvesting wheat in a field about a mile from Gracko, were slain
swiftly in bursts of automatic fire that came from several
directions.
</P>
<P>
   Although Gracko, a village of some 300 people, is predominantly
Serbian, the surrounding villages are Albanian. Villagers said
Saturday that harassment and threats are a daily occurrence. They
said that an elderly man was kidnapped while riding his bicycle a
few days ago and has disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the Serbs now in Gracko have already fled from other
villages, where they had lived among Albanians. Most of these
farmers said they have lost everything they owned. No Serb ventures
out of Gracko, villagers said, even for food and supplies, unless
traveling in a convoy of vehicles. At night, the villagers shutter
themselves inside their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Since arriving in Kosovo, the NATO-led force has detained 200
people, nearly all Albanians, for violent crimes, including murder,
arson and looting against the Serbian minority. On July 6,
according to two officers with the NATO force, systematic burning
of Serbian homes began, often preceded by organized looting, and
security has deteriorated further for the Serbs.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Canadian and British troops, part of the 36,500 NATO
peacekeepers in the province, moved slowly throughout Gracko
Saturday in six-wheeled armored personal carriers, their great
green vehicles belching clouds of diesel smoke. Canadian or British
flags, mounted on the sterns, whipped out in the light breeze.
Sheets of gray clouds obscured the sunlight and left the air thick
with moisture.
</P>
<P>
   A NATO spokesman said British troops were on a routine patrol
near the village, which is six miles south of the provincial
capital, Pristina, when they heard automatic fire. A British Rapid
Reaction Unit arrived 40 minutes later, and at around 10 p.m.
Friday discovered the bodies of 13 male farmers lying around their
combine harvester.
</P>
<P>
   ``The harvester was still running,'' said Maj. Ian Seraph of
Britain. ``About five minutes later they found another body on top
of a tractor. They were all killed in a most horrible and gruesome
manner.''
</P>
<P>
   Dostana Stojanovic, who fled with her husband, Nikola, from a
nearby village six weeks ago to live with one of her sons, said she
knew something was terribly wrong when she heard gunfire. Her
husband, 63, had gone to the fields to help his neighbors harvest
wheat. The volleys came from that direction, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not have a car and could not go check,'' she said,
standing in a dirt yard next to a shed made of stripped branches
and patched with mud and loam. ``I sent one of my sons to call
KFOR,'' she said, using the acronym for the NATO-led force. ``He
called five or six times before they came. We are all frightened.
We hear shots every night. We see houses go up in flames. We have
no protection.''
</P>
<P>
   British troops who were at the site of the killings called the
scene disturbing. The killers, not content with gunning down their
victims, had run over some with the farm vehicles and repeatedly
thrust blunt objects into the faces to disfigure them, according to
Serbs who viewed the bodies later.
</P>
<P>
   When relatives went to the Pristina Hospital Saturday morning to
identify the bodies, the British soldiers told them to enter the
room in pairs. They warned them that it would be hard to recognize
their family members.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were people lying there who I have known all my life,
but who I could not identify,'' said Milivoje Arsic, 45, who is
Mrs. Stojanovic's son-in-law and who agreed to view her husband's
remains. ``There were puncture wounds in the necks, perhaps from
screwdrivers, and the faces had been badly maimed. My father-in-law
was hard to recognize because of all the blood and disfigurement.''
</P>
<P>
   The killings seemed for many the final blow in the flagging
effort to hang onto villages and homes. In Gracko Saturday, several
residents told stories of beatings, knifings, flights from villages
where Serbs can no longer reside or open threats. No one seemed
surprised by the attack.
</P>
<P>
   One of the mourners, Dusan Mladinovic, 42, has a scabrous red
line across his face that he says he received from an Albanian who
attacked him with a knife three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was forced out of my village of Donje Godance three days ago
and am here with my cousin,'' said Djordje Stolic, 66. ``Albanians
in uniform, not from our village, came and took my house, my car
and my farm equipment. But I do not care about that now. Two weeks
ago, they took away my son Mica who is only 18. Neighbors tell me
he is being held in a KLA jail in the village of Petrovo. I only
want him home, then I will leave Kosovo as they wish.''
</P>
<P>
   The village of Petrovo, 10 miles from Gracko, is emptied of
Serbs. The scorched and gutted shells of homes dot the roadside. A
mosque, with a silver-painted dome, has several large gaping shell
holes, left either from last year's fighting when the Serbian
police battled guerrillas, or from the Serbs' assault on Albanian
settlements during NATO's bombing.
</P>
<P>
   The Albanian rebel force, despite the disarmament agreement that
forbids fighters to carry automatic weapons, had uniformed soldiers
with AK-47 assault rifles stationed Saturday around a small school
that it uses as a local headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   The fighters said they knew nothing of kidnapped Serbs. In a
scene reminiscent of Serbian security forces who denied any crimes
against Albanians, they said their side had done no wrong. ``This
story of 14 Serbs being killed is a lie,'' said one officer, who
would not give his name. ``Serbs are not being killed here. Only
the Serbs murder innocent men and women.''
</P>
</TEXT>
