<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUTTERFLY-PRESERVE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUTTERFLIES MAKE COMEBACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BETH BARRETT  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In the deserted dunes just west of Los Angeles
International Airport, where crumbling foundations of homes testify
to past expansions, nature has made a startlingly beautiful
comeback _ with the help of millions of public dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The endangered El Segundo blue butterflies that two decades ago
numbered fewer than 500 have multiplied to more than 80,000 today,
turning the 200 acres of airport habitat into the world's largest
preserve.
</P>
<P>
   The cultivation of the butterflies, or (begin ital)Euphilotes
battoides allyni(end ital), has not been without cost or a mixture
of motives, however.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles World Airports has spent millions to foster the
delicate and finicky insects that grow to thumbnail size on a diet
of coastal buckwheat before expiring in a few days during the
mating season that runs from about mid-June through mid-August.
</P>
<P>
   The airport runs a buckwheat nursery on the premises and has
installed an extensive sprinkler system to make sure the plants
thrive once they are transplanted.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Crowther, the airport's environmental manager, estimates
it costs the airport about $250,000 a year _ or about $3.20 a
butterfly _ for an environmental consulting firm, airport staff and
gardeners to groom the dunes for invasive plants that threaten the
buckwheat, in particular ice plants and acacias.
</P>
<P>
   The airport is voluntarily making the expenditures in hopes that
some day the El Segundo blues _ named after the male's
purplish-blue wings _ will become numerous enough to be removed
from the federal government's list of endangered species. That
would lift some of the constraints airport officials now face in
going onto the dunes to fix or relocate airport navigational
devices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone's ultimate goal is to get them delisted,'' Crowther
said. ``The preserve would remain, but it would be easier for us to
work out here.''
</P>
<P>
   The El Segundo blues won't affect LAX's proposed $12 billion
expansion, however, he said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service biologist Carol Gorbics said the
airport has run an excellent program. But she said that before the
butterflies can be relisted in the less restrictive ``threatened''
category, more years of progress will have to be documented and
three other, smaller habitats outside the airport's jurisdiction
will also have to show gains.
</P>
<P>
   ``While the airport dunes are close to achieving these things,
we still have to ensure that the other populations are exhibiting
the same trends,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The El Segundo blues' habitat runs roughly from Palos Verdes to
the Ballona Wetlands.
</P>
<P>
   Fenced off from the public, the airport's preserve is the
providence of scientists and surveyors with now-and-then signs of
animal life, including rare sightings of the red fox.
</P>
<P>
   The surveyors await the hatching of the pupae, which spend most
of the year burrowed into the soil or leaf litter, then try to do a
visual count as the insects zip about the white and pink buckwheat
flowerheads.
</P>
<P>
   Though the butterflies usually don't stray more than a few
hundred feet from their birthplace before they die, they move so
quickly it's almost impossible not to double-count some and to miss
others, said Andrew Huang, the airport scientist overseeing the
butterfly project.
</P>
<P>
   The female butterfly is less garish, with only a subtle orange
stripe marking her brownish wings. She lays up to 120 eggs before
expiring, often devoured by crab or lynx spiders.
</P>
<P>
   Huang said more studies are needed to better determine exactly
how the El Segundo blues, one of six subspecies of the more
abundant San Bernardino blues, differ genetically, as well as to
explore whether they can survive on a wider variety of plant food _
issues that could bear on a delisting decision.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the studies on blues in general have been funded by
former Chicago White Sox owner Arthur C. Allyn, a butterfly
enthusiast, for whom the subspecies (begin ital)allyni(end ital) is
named.
</P>
<P>
   Huang said the anticipated studies also will help the airport
better manage the preserve.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
