<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-24 12:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2579 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CSUN-FOOTBALL-2ndTAKE     07-24 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CSUN-FOOTBALL-2ndTAKE-LADN </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES: in terms of gender.
</P>
<P>
   At CSUN, 59 percent of the students are women, meaning that,
under the agreement, 54 percent of athletics resources must be
earmarked for women.
</P>
<P>
   Northridge has improved markedly, offering the NCAA-maximum
scholarships in many of its women's sports. It has also added
women's soccer and women's golf in recent years. Northridge is
spending $827,410 on women's scholarships and, excluding football,
only 45percent of that ($354,382) on men's scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   Most of CSUN's men's sports are operating on a shoestring. The
men's soccer team, for example, operates on $84,000. The women's
soccer team has $198,000. Likewise, the men's volleyball team has
$126,000 to the women's $282,000.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, many of the men's teams have little chance to be
competitive at a national level.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its efforts, though, CSUN remains out of compliance with
the Cal-NOW agreement. The problem is, there is no female
equivalent to football and its 50 to 60 scholarships and large
staff of specialized coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Eliminating football would immediately solve the gender-equity
dilemma while allowing Northridge to pump up its remaining men's
sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a model for schools without football,'' Fullerton's
Franks said. ``(Dropping football) certainly made it easier. We
have been at the forefront of compliance.''
</P>
<P>
   And it isn't just the remaining men's sports that benefit. While
Fullerton softball coach Judi Garman said her program received an
extra $30,000 after football was axed, the real payoff came from
greater access to support services. Without football, Garman's
players had an easier time using the training rooms, securing
academic advisement and using meeting rooms. Plus, Garman hired a
new assistant coach.
</P>
<P>
   When Fullerton had football, it had trouble attracting fans even
in the best of times. The Titans finished 1984 with an 11-1 record
and were ranked 19th in the final United Press International poll.
</P>
<P>
   The next season, it drew just 6,000 to its home opener.
</P>
<P>
   Since dropping football, both Fullerton and Long Beach have made
regular appearances in the baseball College World Series, and
Fullerton has won it. Both also rebuilt their baseball stadiums.
</P>
<P>
   The Long Beach volleyball programs have thrived. The women went
undefeated in 1998 and won the national championship. The men
reached this past spring's final.
</P>
<P>
   Malibu's Pepperdine University, a private school, also has
fielded a top-notch Division I athletics program despite the lack
of football since 1961.
</P>
<P>
   In this decade, the baseball (1992), men's volleyball (1992),
men's golf (1997) and men's water polo teams (1997) have won
national championships.
</P>
<P>
   And Pepperdine does this with an operating budget of just
$995,000 for 14 sports. By contrast, Northridge's operating budget
is $2,233,381 for 20 sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``We simply could not afford to have a quality football team, so
we started focusing on the sports that we think could do well,''
Pepperdine athletic director John Watson said.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN has had only modest success in recent years, with several
conference titles and an appearance in the 1993 championship game
by the men's volleyball team.
</P>
<P>
   Former and present players say it is easier to recruit excellent
athletes with excellent facilities and support.
</P>
<P>
   ``This program's too good (to be neglected),'' said Rob
Crabtree, a minor-league baseball player who played at Northridge
in 1995-96. ``They should do something. Then you'll get teams
coming in instead of us going to Texas to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Northridge officials know they can't have it all. While
officials have acknowledged discussing eliminating football, no one
appears to have the will or political standing to make a decision.
</P>
<P>
   Former athletic director Paul Bubb and his boss, vice president
Ron Kopita, made the decision two years ago to cut four men's
sports and keep football in order to meet financial and
gender-equity goals. Ultimately, both were forced to resign.
</P>
<P>
   Most athletes and alumni want to see football continue, and Dick
Dull _ the new athletic director _ said the school benefits from it
with improved fund-raising and increased exposure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like it or not, the public appetite is men's basketball and
football,'' Dull said. ``When you drop one of them, the attention
of the other sports could be affected.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
