<DOCNO> NYT19990724.0081 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-24 12:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2586 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CSUN-FOOTBALL-2TAKES-     07-24 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CSUN-FOOTBALL-2TAKES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRIDIRON'S FAILURE MAY BOOST OTHER SPORTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- California State University, Northridge,
officials insist the school will field a football team in 2000 and
raise enough money from the community to build a stadium and put
the program on solid financial footing in three years.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, after going through three coaches in four years and in the
midst of an embarrassing investigation of a program that devours
nearly a quarter of the school's intercollegiate sports budget,
football at CSUN is in trouble and may inevitably be dropped just
as it has at so many similar colleges.
</P>
<P>
   Acting President Louanne Kennedy believes CSUN committed
``serious and substantial'' violations of National Collegiate
Athletic Association and university rules _ which she intends to
make public in a week.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the school has fired head coach Ron Ponciano and
pressured offensive coordinator Rob Phenicie to resign. Jeff
Kearin, hired as an interim replacement on Thursday, becomes the
fourth head coach since 1996. He has a six-month contract.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest reason why CSUN would eliminate football is that
it makes the most sense for an athletics program that can't afford
the sports it has, doesn't have a realistic hope of building modern
facilities for all of them, is struggling to meet gender-equity
requirements and is just one downturn of the economy away from
disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``The San Fernando Valley has the feeling,'' said Mike Bird, a
Northridge graduate and former volleyball player, ``that if it
wants to watch big-time, Division I football, they're going to go
to USC or UCLA.''
</P>
<P>
   Northridge fields 20 intercollegiate sports teams and, in
1998-99, is spending $6.8million to pay for them _ about $4million
going directly for programs. Of that, football costs Northridge
just under $1million annually.
</P>
<P>
   The disproportionate costs of football and the men's
scholarships it requires are major reasons that none of the five
other California State University campuses in Los Angeles and
Orange counties has a football team. In fact, none offers as many
sports as CSUN.
</P>
<P>
   The Long Beach and Fullerton campuses _ similar institutions as
CSUN with athletics budgets about the same size _ both dropped
football this decade. They refocused their money and support staff
on other sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't play Division I football economically,'' CSU
Fullerton sports information director Mel Franks said. ``In this
market, USC and UCLA don't sell out, unless they're playing each
other. The pros have bailed out of here, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Northridge intends to build a modern football facility to
replace North Campus Stadium, decrepit and woefully below standards
mandated by the Big Sky Conference, which CSUN joined in 1995. (It
is difficult to compete in the NCAA without a conference
affiliation).
</P>
<P>
   Northridge must build a stadium or lose its Big Sky membership _
conference officials have given CSUN 18 months to demonstrate it
has sufficient funding. And the Big Sky requires member schools to
have a football team.
</P>
<P>
   However, neighboring homeowner groups are opposed to a new
stadium and have promised a vigorous fight.
</P>
<P>
   Northridge also desperately needs a modern basketball arena. Its
baseball facility was named the country's worst in Division I by
Collegiate Baseball Magazine, and plans to build a state-of-the-art
softball complex died earlier this year when private funding failed
to materialize.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to imagine any scenario in which all of those
needs can be met.
</P>
<P>
   And while Northridge couldn't belong to the Big Sky without
football, there has been recent talk of reconfiguring the Big West
Conference into an all-California, no-football conference. Travel
costs would fall dramatically for CSUN, and it would be competing
against schools more like itself.
</P>
<P>
   At Northridge now, football takes up almost 50percent of the
men's sports budget, and Athletic Director Dick Dull acknowledges
very few football programs pay for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Northridge continues to talk of improving its fund-raising
abilities, yet has little to show for it. It doesn't even have a
fund-raising officer at the moment. Michael Rehm, the athletic
department's most recent officer, was forced to leave the
university by former athletic director Sam Jankovich after
Jankovich determined Rehm didn't have the ability to pull in the
type of cash CSUN needs, according to sources.
</P>
<P>
   The question is, is there someone else who does have the right
touch, who is willing to work for the relatively modest salary
Northridge pays?
</P>
<P>
   The CSU system and the California chapter of the National
Organization of Women reached an agreement following Cal-NOW's 1993
lawsuit that mandates funding, participation and scholarship levels
that nearly mirror each campus' undergraduate student body in terms
of gender.
</P>
<P>
   (CONTINUED ON NEXT TAKE)
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES: in terms of gender.
</P>
<P>
   At CSUN, 59 percent of the students are women, meaning that,
under the agreement, 54 percent of athletics resources must be
earmarked for women.
</P>
<P>
   Northridge has improved markedly, offering the NCAA-maximum
scholarships in many of its women's sports. It has also added
women's soccer and women's golf in recent years. Northridge is
spending $827,410 on women's scholarships and, excluding football,
only 45percent of that ($354,382) on men's scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   Most of CSUN's men's sports are operating on a shoestring. The
men's soccer team, for example, operates on $84,000. The women's
soccer team has $198,000. Likewise, the men's volleyball team has
$126,000 to the women's $282,000.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, many of the men's teams have little chance to be
competitive at a national level.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its efforts, though, CSUN remains out of compliance with
the Cal-NOW agreement. The problem is, there is no female
equivalent to football and its 50 to 60 scholarships and large
staff of specialized coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Eliminating football would immediately solve the gender-equity
dilemma while allowing Northridge to pump up its remaining men's
sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a model for schools without football,'' Fullerton's
Franks said. ``(Dropping football) certainly made it easier. We
have been at the forefront of compliance.''
</P>
<P>
   And it isn't just the remaining men's sports that benefit. While
Fullerton softball coach Judi Garman said her program received an
extra $30,000 after football was axed, the real payoff came from
greater access to support services. Without football, Garman's
players had an easier time using the training rooms, securing
academic advisement and using meeting rooms. Plus, Garman hired a
new assistant coach.
</P>
<P>
   When Fullerton had football, it had trouble attracting fans even
in the best of times. The Titans finished 1984 with an 11-1 record
and were ranked 19th in the final United Press International poll.
</P>
<P>
   The next season, it drew just 6,000 to its home opener.
</P>
<P>
   Since dropping football, both Fullerton and Long Beach have made
regular appearances in the baseball College World Series, and
Fullerton has won it. Both also rebuilt their baseball stadiums.
</P>
<P>
   The Long Beach volleyball programs have thrived. The women went
undefeated in 1998 and won the national championship. The men
reached this past spring's final.
</P>
<P>
   Malibu's Pepperdine University, a private school, also has
fielded a top-notch Division I athletics program despite the lack
of football since 1961.
</P>
<P>
   In this decade, the baseball (1992), men's volleyball (1992),
men's golf (1997) and men's water polo teams (1997) have won
national championships.
</P>
<P>
   And Pepperdine does this with an operating budget of just
$995,000 for 14 sports. By contrast, Northridge's operating budget
is $2,233,381 for 20 sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``We simply could not afford to have a quality football team, so
we started focusing on the sports that we think could do well,''
Pepperdine athletic director John Watson said.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN has had only modest success in recent years, with several
conference titles and an appearance in the 1993 championship game
by the men's volleyball team.
</P>
<P>
   Former and present players say it is easier to recruit excellent
athletes with excellent facilities and support.
</P>
<P>
   ``This program's too good (to be neglected),'' said Rob
Crabtree, a minor-league baseball player who played at Northridge
in 1995-96. ``They should do something. Then you'll get teams
coming in instead of us going to Texas to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Northridge officials know they can't have it all. While
officials have acknowledged discussing eliminating football, no one
appears to have the will or political standing to make a decision.
</P>
<P>
   Former athletic director Paul Bubb and his boss, vice president
Ron Kopita, made the decision two years ago to cut four men's
sports and keep football in order to meet financial and
gender-equity goals. Ultimately, both were forced to resign.
</P>
<P>
   Most athletes and alumni want to see football continue, and Dick
Dull _ the new athletic director _ said the school benefits from it
with improved fund-raising and increased exposure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like it or not, the public appetite is men's basketball and
football,'' Dull said. ``When you drop one of them, the attention
of the other sports could be affected.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
