<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAFIA-GANGS-2TAKES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GANG VIOLENCE INCREASING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
Staff writer Yvette Cabrera contributed to this story 
BY LISA VAN PROYEN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Gang-related homicides, rapes and other crimes
have risen in Los Angeles' San Fernando Valley, despite a plunge in
serious crimes Valleywide in the first six months of 1999, new LAPD
statistics show.
</P>
<P>
   Crime attributed to gangs was up 3.65 percent in the Valley
between Jan. 1 and June 30, compared to the same period in 1998.
Even with gang-related offenses, serious crime was down 10 percent
overall in the Valley, police said.
</P>
<P>
   New rivalries for gang turf in the Foothill Division of the
Valley, an area that accounts for a large portion of such crimes,
are partly to blame, said LAPD Capt. Ron Seban.
</P>
<P>
   ``Recently we have seen gangsters who in the past have not
fought with one another but are now fighting with one another, and
we are trying to figure out why,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   What police and gang members say they know for sure is that the
gang truce brokered several years ago has fallen apart because of
new rivalries as membership changes.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said the prison-based Mexican Mafia, known as La
Eme, is responsible for fostering violence among gangs by setting
one against the other to collect ``drug-dealing taxes'' in the
Northeast Valley.
</P>
<P>
   A gang member, who declined to give his name for fear of
retaliation, predicted that recent arrests will only spur the
Mexican Mafia to operate more aggressively with street gangs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can't stop anybody. It's going to get worse. They're
getting mad because they're busted,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, the Mexican Mafia has for some time encouraged
rival gang members to assault or kill Pacoima Project Boyz members,
according to indictments returned June 24.
</P>
<P>
   ``On Sept. 20, 1998, defendant Frank Fernandez instructed
defendant Robert Cervantes to attack members of the Pacoima Project
Boyz gang until `they cry for mercy,' '' said one indictment.
</P>
<P>
   Ten days later, Mexican Mafia members told members of the
Langdon Street gang to ``hit'' members of the Pacoima Project Boyz
``as often as they can.''
</P>
<P>
   In October 1998, La Eme members agreed to gather with San
Fernando Valley gangs and supply some of them with guns to enlist
their help in attacking the Pacoima Project Boyz, according to the
indictment.
</P>
<P>
   And in January, a La Eme member said he needed guns because they
were ``going to start a war with the Pacoima Project Boyz.''
</P>
<P>
   ``On Jan. 19, defendants Frank Fernandez and Dominick Gonzales
told gang representatives that they were organizing the San
Fernando Valley gangs for the Mexican Mafia,'' according to the
indictment.
</P>
<P>
   The two indictments returned June 24 led to the arrests of 40
people, at least seven of whom lived in the Valley, for murder,
drug trafficking and racketeering acts.
</P>
<P>
   Federal and state law enforcement officers characterized the
arrests as a ``major crackdown'' on the notorious prison-based gang
that is also known as ``La Eme,'' which they say is seeking to
expand control over drug distributions throughout Southern
California by organizing local street gangs.
</P>
<P>
   But Valley gang members say the arrests from the indictment
won't make much difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's business as usual,'' said a member of the Pacoima Project
Boyz, who declined to give his name. ``Some people go in and some
go out (of jail). It's a whole routine. Other people might just
take over in a couple weeks, a month _ sooner or later. The
pressure's still there. It'll always be there.''
</P>
<P>
   William ``Blinky'' Rodriguez, who brokered the Valley Unity
Peace Treaty among more than 1,000 Northeast Valley gang members,
said that as a new generation of gang members have hit the streets,
the treaty has slowly unraveled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't honestly say that the peace treaty is still in effect
at a certain level, but I can say there are people out there who
are still committed to the peace effort,'' Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
   Some gangsters who signed on to the treaty, created in October
1993, have left gang life behind. Others abide by the treaty's
premise to refrain from attacking rival gangs, Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
   Younger gang members were barely entering elementary school when
the treaty was made, and Rodriguez has been faced with the
challenge of connecting with this generation. Rodriguez's nonprofit
Communities In Schools, which offers intervention and prevention
programs for at-risk youth, sends counselors to probation camps,
continuation high schools and the streets to get the treaty's
message across.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime there was a rash of violence, people said (the peace
treaty is) over,'' said Rodriguez. ``But it's not over 'til we say
it's over. We continue to bring gangs together to talk things
out.''
</P>
<P>
   (CONTINUED ON NEXT TAKE)
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
