seemed almost inevitable; Orlando Cabrera, the ninth-place hitter
for the Expos, said that in the sixth inning, he already was
thinking about being the last out in a perfect game. Throwing just
88 pitches, Cone completed the 16th perfect game in history _ 27
batters, no hits, no walks, no errors.
</P>
<P>
   Then there were stranger-than-fiction coincidences: Don Larsen
threw the first perfect game for the Yankees in the 1956 World
Series and attended the same high school as David Wells, who threw
the second Yankee perfect game last year _ and by chance or fate,
Larsen was in Yankee Stadium to throw out the first ball before
Cone's gem, and was in the clubhouse afterward to greet him with a
bear hug. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ By BUSTER OLNEY
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Tax Cut Passes but a Veto Lies Dead Ahead  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Evoking memories of Ronald Reagan's big tax cut in 1981,
Republicans in the House passed a $792-billion tax reduction plan.
It stands little chance of becoming law but sets out the
conservative view of how the nation should allocate projected
budget surpluses.
</P>
<P>
   Its centerpiece is a 10-percent reduction in personal income tax
rates. It also includes a cut in capital gains taxes and a repeal
of inheritance taxes. President Clinton promised a veto but says he
is open to negotiating a compromise.
</P>
<P>
   _ By RICHARD W. STEVENSON  &QR;
</P>
<P>
   A Test for North Korea  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   North Korea plans to launch its long-range ballistic missile
this summer despite warnings from the United States, Japan and
South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, the missile has a range of 3,750 miles, theoretically
making it capable of reaching Alaska or Hawaii, say diplomatic and
security officials from Western and Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
   Retaliation would be swift. South Korea, Japan and the United
States say they would cut off foreign aid, including much-needed
food and agricultural products to ease North Korea's widespread
famine. Western diplomats did not rule out last-minute diplomacy
from China, which maintains close ties to North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Landing on the Wrong List  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Conservative critics have long complained that public
broadcasting has a liberal bias, and now they believe they have the
evidence needed to phase out the industry's $250-million
taxpayer-funded subsidy. The president of the Corporation for
Public Broadcasting said at least 28 of the nation's 353 public
television stations had given the names of their donors to various
political organizations. It turns out that those organizations were
affiliated not only with Democrats but also with Republicans,
including Bob Dole's 1996 presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   _ By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE
</P>
<P>
   A Virus Found  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For years, scientists have been unable to find a virus to
account for a significant number of hepatitis cases not caused by
the liver ailment's five main known viruses. Italian scientists
reported strong evidence that they had discovered a new virus, the
last major piece of the puzzle of blood-borne hepatitis. But
confirmation and further research is needed to learn whether blood
banks should routinely test for it.
</P>
<P>
   _ By LAWRENCE K. ALTMAN
</P>
<P>
   A Plan to Share Organs  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is a question worthy of Solomon: With donated livers in short
supply, who should get one? A report from the Institute of Medicine
offered an answer: Scarce livers should be distributed across city
and state lines, within areas of about 9 million people each, so
the sickest patients get them first. The report backs a Clinton
administration plan to force broader sharing. But Congress, which
ordered the study, will have the final say.
</P>
<P>
   _ By SHERYL GAY STOLBERG
</P>
<P>
   Smuggled Human Cargo  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Golden Mountain'' is what many poor Chinese call North
America, and the interception of a boatload of more than 100
illegal immigrants in a ship off British Columbia shows once again
what people will endure to reach these shores. Some paid more than
$35,000; all endured filthy conditions for more than a month. Now
Canadian immigration judges must decide if they will stay, or be
deported to China.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ANTHONY DePALMA
</P>
<P>
   A Good Deficit  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The more American consumers spend, the more the trade deficit
rises _ last month to a record $21 billion, according to figures
just released. And eventually that's bad news. But for now, it's
good.
</P>
<P>
   The deficit is soaring because the economy is running flat out.
Countries are shipping Americans as much as they will buy. And
because the goods are relatively low cost, they help keep down
inflation, while taking few jobs away from Americans.
</P>
<P>
   But sooner or later the economy will slow. And then today's
inflation-fighting trade deficit will turn into tomorrow's threat
to American jobs. Someday.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID E. SANGER
</P>
<P>
   Crackdown on Chinese Sect
</P>
<P>
   Its members are mostly female and middle-aged. Its practices
consist of an amalgam of Buddhism, Taoism and deep breathing
exercises. And its adherents say they seek only to improve their
mental and physical health.
</P>
<P>
   To China's Communist rulers, however, the spiritual movement
known as Falun Gong constitutes a ``massive threat'' to the
stability of Chinese society. Declaring the group illegal, Beijing
carried out a vast nationwide crackdown on the group.
</P>
<P>
   The government turned the group's founder, Li Hongzhi, into
public enemy No. 1, branding him in the state-run news media as a
charlatan seeking to create a ``political force in rivalry with our
party and government.'' Li, who has lived in New York since 1998,
defended himself on the Internet _ a medium he often uses to
communicate with his followers.
</P>
<P>
   _ By MARK LANDLER
</P>
<P>
   Creative Banking  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Three former executives of Bankers Trust Corp. were indicted on
federal charges that they diverted $15.1 million of unclaimed
customer funds into the bank's own accounts from 1993 to 1996 in
order to boost their department's financial results, cover budget
shortfalls and even pay for the office Christmas party. Four months
ago, Bankers Trust itself pleaded guilty to similar charges,
agreeing to pay fines totaling $63.5 million. But the three
executives, including a member of the bank's 12-man operating
committee, plan to contest the charges.
</P>
<P>
   _ By EDWARD WYATT
</P>
<P>
   Hospital Inspections Crticized
</P>
<P>
   Patients face life-threatening risks because the private
organization inspecting the nation's hospitals is ``unlikely to
detect substandard patterns of care,'' federal investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   June Gibbs Brown, inspector general of the Department of Health
and Human Services, harshly criticized the work of the inspectors
from the Joint Commission on Accreditation of Healthcare
Organizations, who announce their visits in advance and rely on
hospital employees to select records, so clinical problems could be
easily hidden.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ROBERT PEAR
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon Misspending Spree  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon defied the law and the Constitution by spending
hundreds of millions of dollars on programs Congress never
approved, the House Appropriations Committee charged. The Defense
Department acknowledged failing to notify Congress about how it was
spending taxpayers' funds, and admitted that the Air Force had
started a super-secret ``black program'' without telling anyone, an
act the House panel said broke the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do we have to do to make them understand what we mean
when we say no?'' said Rep. Jerry Lewis, Republican of California
and chairman of the committee's defense spending panel.
</P>
<P>
   _ By TIM WEINER
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
