<P>
   Tax Cut Passes but a Veto Lies Dead Ahead  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Evoking memories of Ronald Reagan's big tax cut in 1981,
Republicans in the House passed a $792-billion tax reduction plan.
It stands little chance of becoming law but sets out the
conservative view of how the nation should allocate projected
budget surpluses.
</P>
<P>
   Its centerpiece is a 10-percent reduction in personal income tax
rates. It also includes a cut in capital gains taxes and a repeal
of inheritance taxes. President Clinton promised a veto but says he
is open to negotiating a compromise.
</P>
<P>
   _ By RICHARD W. STEVENSON  &QR;
</P>
