   A Test for North Korea  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   North Korea plans to launch its long-range ballistic missile
this summer despite warnings from the United States, Japan and
South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, the missile has a range of 3,750 miles, theoretically
making it capable of reaching Alaska or Hawaii, say diplomatic and
security officials from Western and Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
   Retaliation would be swift. South Korea, Japan and the United
States say they would cut off foreign aid, including much-needed
food and agricultural products to ease North Korea's widespread
famine. Western diplomats did not rule out last-minute diplomacy
from China, which maintains close ties to North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Landing on the Wrong List  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Conservative critics have long complained that public
broadcasting has a liberal bias, and now they believe they have the
evidence needed to phase out the industry's $250-million
