<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-24 12:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2592 &Cx1f; var-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIDEAST-JEWS-REVIEW-2     07-24 1231
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-JEWS-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE ISLAMIC MIDEAST, SCANT PLACE FOR JEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 By JOHN F. BURNS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   To those who monitor events in Iran, the arrest of 13 Iranian
Jews on spying charges this year is a menacing sign that bigger
trouble may lie ahead _ trouble that, unchecked, could cause one of
the last two Jewish communities of any size in the Islamic Middle
East to follow most of the others into virtual oblivion.
</P>
<P>
   Until the arrests, Jews in Iran had survived the 20-year
dominion of Iran's ruling ayatollahs better than many feared in
1979, when the Islamic republic was declared. In fact, the 30,000
Jews in Iran, while down from the 80,000 who lived there before the
revolution, constitute the largest Jewish community to have
survived in the Muslim Middle East and North Africa. The only other
one of similar size is in Turkey, another non-Arab country, where
about 20,000 Jews remain.
</P>
<P>
   The Iranian Jews' significance becomes clearer when their
endurance is measured against what happened elsewhere after the
birth of Israel. From Morocco through Algeria, Tunisia, Libya,
Egypt, Yemen, Lebanon, Syria, Iraq and Turkey, Jewish communities
that totaled perhaps 1 million people in 1948 dwindled between the
1950s and 1980s to the point that barely 60,000 _ including the
50,000 in Iran and Turkey _ remain.
</P>
<P>
   But now, Iran's Jews must worry that tactics used against Jewish
minorities elsewhere could erode their security, making migration
more attractive. For the time being, the U.S. and European
diplomats who have been leading a discreet campaign to persuade
Iran to drop the spying charges remain hopeful. They point to the
opprobrium that would be sure to fall on Iran if the cases come to
trial, or _ improbable, but still possible, in the view of experts
on Iran _ if the Jews were convicted and sentenced to long prison
terms or death.
</P>
<P>
   The case has unfolded slowly. When the first of the 13 was
arrested in January, the State Department kept the matter quiet,
hoping diplomacy could resolve the issue. But that had not happened
by early June, when Iran announced the arrests over the state
radio.
</P>
<P>
   The spying charges bear every earmark of a trumped-up case.
Those arrested _ including a rabbi, three Hebrew teachers, a kosher
butcher and even, by some reports, a 16-year-old boy _ were
originally picked up for alleged infringements of Iranian laws that
conflict with Jewish practices. The rabbi was charged with teaching
Hebrew, the language of Jewish prayer; others were accused of
closing their shops on Saturday, the Jewish Sabbath.
</P>
<P>
   Their actions were condemned as evidence of disloyalty to Iran,
and thus as proof that those arrested were in the service of
``world arrogance'' and ``the Zionist entity,'' meaning the United
States and Israel. By escalating infractions of religious laws into
treason, the conservatives who control Iran's police and courts
evidently hoped to stir antagonism toward the West and place fresh
obstacles before Iran's reformist president, Mohammed Khatami.
</P>
<P>
   By no coincidence, the charges originated in the southern city
of Fars, a stronghold of Islamic conservatives loyal to Ayatollah
Ali Khamanei, Iran's supreme leader. Although the violent clashes
earlier this month between students supporting Khatami and security
forces loyal to the Muslim clerics have now abated, the underlying
dispute between those favoring a broadening of freedoms and the
clerics' insistence on tight control remains. With it, at least
theoretically, remains the risk that other Jews might become
political pawns.
</P>
<P>
   It is a situation redolent of the hazards Jews have faced
throughout history, made more poignant in Iran by the fact that
Jews there seemed, until the spying case, to have a more secure
place than elsewhere in the Muslim Middle East. The Islamic
constitution recognizes Jews as a religious minority, allows them a
representative in Parliament and accepts Jewish laws on burial and
divorce. In Tehran, 27 synagogues function, Jewish schools flourish
and the Jewish hospital is among the city's most respected.
</P>
<P>
   Now all this could be at risk, and with it a crucial vestige of
the Jewish settlement that has left a deep imprint on virtually
every country in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   According to estimates in the ``Atlas of the Jewish World,'' a
survey by Dr. Nicholas de Lange of Cambridge University, as many as
4 million Jews lived in parts of the Roman Empire beyond Judea, the
Jewish homeland, at the dawn of the first millennium; most of these
lived in the Arab lands that now surround Israel. On the eve of the
third millennium, these countries together could not muster a
Jewish population as numerous as those that were once to be found
in many of the major cities of the region.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq, where there were about 150,000 Jews in 1948, has about 70
now. In Syria, there are about 300, in Lebanon about 80, in Jordan,
Egypt and Yemen fewer still. In Saudi Arabia there are no Jews, at
least by official count. In Morocco, which had about 300,000 Jews
in 1948, about 6,000 remain. In Algeria, which saw 115,000 Jews
emigrate hastily to France at independence in 1962, the count is
down to a few hundred. In Tunisia, which counted 105,000 Jews in
1950, there are no more than 2,500. In Libya, where a 1931 census
counted 24,500 Jews, one recent count put the number of Jews
remaining at 5. In Turkey, a community of 90,000 in 1948 has shrunk
to less than a quarter of that now.
</P>
<P>
   While flight from the Muslim lands has been precipitous in the
last 50 years, a slower decline dates from the Middle Ages, when
the rise of Christian Europe attracted large westward migrations
among Jewish populations in the Middle East. Other factors,
including local pogroms, prompted Jews to leave over the centuries.
</P>
<P>
   But in the modern era, the watershed was the creation of Israel.
Living in a Jewish state was an attraction in itself; a surge of
hostility among Arabs toward Jews, or at least toward Zionism, was
another factor.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many of those who left did so reluctantly, and many chose
not to leave until much later. This attests to something widely
accepted among Jews who have lived as minorities in Muslim nations
_ that the Islamic world has been less fertile ground for
anti-Semitism than the Christian lands of Europe. Why this has been
so has been endlessly debated, but Islamic scholars cite stories
from the life of the Muslim prophet, Mohammed, to show that respect
for Jews was close to his heart.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing in Jewish experience in the Middle East came remotely
close to the Holocaust. But even long before Hitler's killing
machine, Jews in Muslim countries were comparing their experiences
favorably with those of Jews in Europe. In his survey, de Lange
quotes a Jew writing from Constantinople to Jews in the Rhineland
in 1454. ``Is it not better for you to live under Muslims than
under Christians?'' he wrote. ``Here, every man may live at peace
under his own vine and fig tree.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-99 1213EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
