 Attn Sports Editors:  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sports stories in sight at this hour from The New York Times
News Service for use in papers of Sunday, July 25:
</P>
<P>
   BBA-YANKS-INDIANS (New York) _ The Cleveland Indians try to
avenge Friday night's extra-inning loss to the New York Yankees at
Yankee Stadium. 4:35 p.m. start. By Buster Olney.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-METS-CUBS (New York) _ Sammy Sosa and the Chicago Cubs visit
the New York Mets, 1:15 p.m. start. By Gerald Eskenazi.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-HALL-FAME (Undated) _ Three weeks apart in September 1992,
George Brett and Robin Yount became the 17th and 18th baseball
players to reach 3,000 hits, and on Sunday they take another joint
step _ going into the Hall of Fame in Cooperstown, N.Y. Pitching
great Nolan Ryan and slugger Orlando Cepeda will be inducted with
them. By Murray Chass.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-LIPSYTE-COLUMN (Undated) _ If you've ever spent any private
time with major league umpires, you might mistakenly think that
their egos are even bigger than their bellies. The self-importance
of umpires is astonishing; they pretend to see themselves as
somewhere between the thin red line that protected the British
Empire from its own barbarism and the U.S. Supreme Court. When more
than five umpires appear together, you expect them to start
singing, ``We Are the Game.'' By Robert Lipsyte.
</P>
<P>
   TOURDEFRANCE-ARMSTRONG (Futuroscope, France) _ Relaxed and
excited at the same time, Lance Armstrong lounged in a team trailer
shortly before he was to ride his bicycle into Paris and talked
about everything that came to mind _ except for the fact that on
Sunday he will win the Tour de France. Until the moment that he
pulls the final yellow jersey of the winner over his head, he
refuses to refer to more than ``my potential victory.'' By Samuel
Abt.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-NOTEBOOK (Undated) _ News items from the NBA. By Chris
Broussard.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-NOTEBOOK (Undated) _ News items from the NFL. By Mike
Freeman.
</P>
<P>
   RAC-SARATOGA _ With 25,000 people expected to show up for the
opening Wednesday of America's most popular, most successful and
arguably most beautiful race track, it's hard to believe that
Saratoga's viability was ever questioned. In fact, it did not
always enjoy the overwhelming success it has today. By Tom Durkin.
</P>
<P>
   For information and repeats call the News Service at
1-888-603-1036. And be sure to look for other sports stories from
our partners: Bloomberg News, The Boston Globe, Cox News Service,
Hearst News Service, The Arizona Republic, Kansas City Star, Fort
Worth Star-Telegram, Los Angeles Daily News, San Francisco
Chronicle and Seattle Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
