<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-24 12:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2602 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIDEAST-PEACE-NYT &LR;      07-24 0503
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-PEACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELI'S PEACE INITIATIVE PAUSES AFTER DEATH OF MOROCCO'S KING
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Because of the death of King Hassan II of Morocco,
the whirlwind peacemaking itinerary of Ehud Barak, the new prime
minister of Israel, has been slowed down.
</P>
<P>
   A midnight meeting planned for Saturday with Yasser Arafat, the
Palestinian leader, has been postponed, as has a visit to
Alexandria, Egypt, to meet with President Hosni Mubarak on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   It is possible that the king's funeral on Sunday will bring
together in Rabat, Morocco, all the key players in the Middle East
peace efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Most significant, it could produce a first face-to-face
encounter between the Israeli prime minister and President Hafez
Assad of Syria. The two have been sending clear messages back and
forth of their intention to restart Israeli-Syrian negotiations,
but they have not yet exchanged even a phone call.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear late Saturday afternoon, though, whether either
leader would attend.
</P>
<P>
   Barak's meetings were expected to be rescheduled for early this
week.
</P>
<P>
   One political analyst here has called Barak ``the Energizer
bunny'' for his relentless full-speed throttle on the efforts
toward peace. After establishing a rapport with Arafat two weeks
ago in their first meeting, Barak was reportedly intent on
hammering out some working understandings with the Palestinian
leader Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts had said they believed the meeting would produce
at least one significant Israeli gesture toward the Palestinians to
allay their concerns that Barak was trying to bluff them with talk
of peace. They had speculated that it could be a release of
political prisoners or the announcement of a date for the next
handover of West Bank land to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Zvi Stauber, a foreign policy adviser to the prime minister,
said Barak was planning to try to persuade Arafat not to ``waste
energy'' in haggling over the plans for carrying out the Wye peace
memorandum.
</P>
<P>
   Barak wants Arafat to agree to rethink the pact, which was an
interim agreement, and to consider combining it with the final
status peace accord. He has said he will not force the issue if
Arafat is opposed, and the Palestinians have expressed a good deal
of opposition and alarm to Barak's idea.
</P>
<P>
   Returning from hours of meeting with Clinton in Washington this
month, Barak made it clear that he personally intended to oversee
the revival of the peace effort. As was the case in Washington, he
is not planning to relegate the first steps to subordinates, but
rather to talk leader-to-leader, man-to-man.
</P>
<P>
   Barak seems intent on convincing everyone involved to rise above
himself. On a local level, he wants the Israeli press corps to rise
above its interest in leaking diplomatic tactics _ for the good of
the country. Similarly, he wants Arafat to get beyond his immediate
demands that Wye be carried out _ for the good of the larger peace
effort.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
