<HEADLINE>
YOU COULD LOOK IT UP: WHAT HE PROMISED. AND WHAT HE DID. 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ At his news conference last week, President Clinton
was asked why he ridiculed George W. Bush's slogan of
``compassionate conservatism.'' Another questioner wanted to know
what the president found objectionable about the Texas governor's
``trying to present a new moderate face for his party, just like
you did for the Democrats.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton responded that Bush had not met the responsibility of
presidential candidates to ``make their positions clear on the
great debates going on now and make their positions clear on what
they would do if they got the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, Clinton offered this version of his own race for president
in 1992: ``The first thing I did was tell the American people what
I thought was going on in our country and what I would do. And if
you remember, the late Senator Paul Tsongas and I were actually
almost ridiculed at the time because we both put out these very
detailed plans of what we would do. If you go back and get one of
those plans now, you'll see that virtually everything we said we'd
do we did do, except for the things we tried to do and were
defeated on.''
</P>
<P>
   Is that right or not?
</P>
<P>
   No one can challenge Clinton's point that he offered a detailed
agenda, which he refined over the months. By the fall, he and Al
Gore had published a 240-page book called ``Putting People First''
that offered explicit proposals on issues running the alphabetical
gamut from agriculture to women.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the promises were grand, like cutting the budget deficit
in half, guaranteeing Americans affordable medical insurance,
``ending welfare as we know it'' and providing equal economic
opportunity for all.
</P>
<P>
   Other promises were microscopic in their detail, like saving $2
million in 1993 by adjusting nuclear waste disposal fees for
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   And some were simply unmeasurable, like the pledge to give
America ``the best-educated, best-trained workforce in the world,
linked together by transportation and communication networks second
to none.''
</P>
<P>
   But if the quantity, breadth and specificity of Clinton promises
cannot be contested, one can quibble with his view that he
accomplished, or at least tried to accomplish, ``virtually
everything'' he promised to do.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, Clinton did reach many of the goals he set in 1992,
was thwarted by political opponents on some, and never even tried
to achieve others.
</P>
<P>
   On the central issue of the 1992 campaign, the economy, his goal
of halving the deficit was left in the dust. The budget was
balanced, and Clinton is now able to foresee enormous surpluses in
government accounts. The unemployment rate fell to the lowest level
in decades and millions of new jobs were created. Inflation was
tamed. The U.S. economy became, as Clinton pledged it would, second
to none.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, over the opposition of Republicans in Congress,
Clinton fulfilled promises to enact a tough gun-control law,
finance 100,000 new community police officers, increase the minimum
wage, start a national service program, give workers time off to
deal with family emergencies and block efforts to restrict
abortions.
</P>
<P>
   Working with and in many cases following the Republicans' lead,
he expanded international trade, ended the 60-year-old national
welfare system, reduced the size of the government work force, gave
tax breaks to cities for special empowerment zones and won
authority for a line-item veto, which was ultimately found
unconstitutional by the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   On some other goals established in 1992, Clinton made an effort
but was stopped by Congress. His most spectacular failure, of
course, was his proposal to provide affordable health insurance
coverage for all Americans through local networks of insurers,
hospitals and doctors. As a campaign theme, it sounded workable.
When Clinton submitted a plan along those lines after he became
president, it proved to be unwieldy and unpopular and died while
Democrats still controlled Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents forced the president to withdraw his promise to let
homosexuals serve in the military. He instead instituted the
compromise policy of ``don't-ask, don't-tell,'' which satisfies no
one.
</P>
<P>
   Congress also stopped the president from keeping his promises to
``rebuild America'' by spending billions on a jobs and public works
program. And it rejected his proposal that companies with striking
workers be prohibited from hiring replacements.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton simply broke other promises. Here are some of the ones
he reneged on:
</P>
<P>
   Even before he took office, he dropped his proposal for a
middle-income tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   He never tried to repeal the limit on how much money people over
65 can earn before their Social Security benefits are reduced.
</P>
<P>
   He gave lip service to campaign finance reform but exerted no
effort to attain it.
</P>
<P>
   He quickly forgot a plan to require businesses to spend 1.5
percent of their payroll on continued education and training of
workers.
</P>
<P>
   He never ended tax breaks for companies that shut down American
plants and ship jobs overseas.
</P>
<P>
   He never made improvement in China's human rights record a
condition for favorable trade status.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of fighting an increase in the gasoline tax, he
sponsored legislation that raised it by 4.3 cents a gallon.
</P>
<P>
   Paradoxically, the fewer promises from 1992 Clinton kept, the
more popular he became. His grandest achievements were in 1993, his
first year in office, and the public did not seem particularly
grateful. Late in 1994, his second year, Clinton's presidency was
in a shambles, and Republicans won control of both houses of
Congress for the first time in four decades.
</P>
<P>
   Then Clinton began thinking small bore. He won re-election in
1996 without big promises and has concentrated since then on
blocking Republican ambitions. ``There was a misreading of how much
change people wanted,'' explained Clinton's former adviser, Harold
M. Ickes.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that is why Bush is promising so little. And maybe, just
maybe, it's why Clinton is egging him on.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-99 1228EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
