</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAKESHIFT-SHRINES-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEEKING SOLACE WITH FINAL GESTURES 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 By JANE GROSS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A snub-nosed California child who loves to dance in glittery
costumes is kidnapped from her bed during a sleep-over and
murdered. An infant in day care, just turned a year old, is crushed
to death when the Oklahoma City federal building explodes at the
hand of terrorists. A Colorado teen-ager, proclaiming her faith in
God, is shot at close range by a rampaging schoolmate.
</P>
<P>
   Like John F. Kennedy Jr., who few knew but many mourned, Polly
Klaas, Baylee Almon and Cassie Bernall became America's nearest and
dearest, however briefly, through the unique intimacy of
television, which brought them, brimming with life, into our living
rooms and bedrooms.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, people knew more about them than about their
neighbors and colleagues. But it was impossible to pay a condolence
call, deliver a casserole, offer a hug or cry at the funeral. And
so they built shrines.
</P>
<P>
   For Polly, there were mountains of teddy bears in a parking lot
in Petaluma, Calif. For Baylee, there were letters in childish
script, pushed through the gaps in the chain-link fence that
contained the rubble of the Murrah Building. For Cassie, there was
a handmade wooden cross not far from Columbine High School.
</P>
<P>
   And now, for Kennedy, there are flickering candles, poems and
prayers, bouquets heaped upon bouquets, outside his New York
apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Memorials to the dead date from the beginning of time, an
impulse hard-wired in the human psyche to comfort the soul of the
dead and relieve the sadness of the living. But ``the size and
elaboration of these public displays of grief are a new phenomenon
of the pop culture,'' said Phillips Stevens Jr., a professor of
anthropology at the State University at Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   Some see these shrines _ the largest by far was for Princess
Diana outside Kensington Palace _ as distasteful exhibitionism,
another version of venting on talk radio or confessing sleazy
secrets on daytime television. Others believe the celebrity culture
has made it possible for people to replace the joy and heartbreak
of real intimacy with phony _ and undemanding _ emotional
connections.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a more sympathetic way to view these makeshift
shrines to strangers, be they celebrities or unknown victims of
great public tragedy. Joshua Meyrowitz, a professor of
communication at the University of New Hampshire, calls them
``media friends'' who enter our lives with such intensity that our
feelings for them are both powerful and genuine.
</P>
<P>
   Meyrowitz described his own interior conversations with such
people. In 1980, after a gunman killed John Lennon outside his New
York apartment building, the scene of one of the earliest of these
shrines, Meyrowitz wished with an intensity usually reserved for
loved ones that Lennon had chosen a different moment to exit his
car. So, too, with Kennedy's fatal flight. ``John, why didn't you
wait until morning?'' Meyrowitz said he asked himself, this time
aloud.
</P>
<P>
   With attachments so deep, there must be rituals for mourning,
and so people invent them. ``We have to find a place to hang these
feelings,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Levinson, a professor of media studies at Fordham
University, agreed. ``Funerals exist in all human societies,'' he
said. ``We are a communal species, and throughout history we have
worked out ways to express communal grief. So this is what we do
when we're not invited to the funeral.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-99 1232EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
