<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-24 12:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2616 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANTHROPO-ANIMALS-REVI     07-24 1074
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTHROPO-ANIMALS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MY DOG LOVES ME, AND OTHER DELUSIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO NTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 By NICHOLAS WADE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``If you want a friend in Washington,'' the saying goes, ``get a
dog.''
</P>
<P>
   The trouble with this advice is that it's not nearly cynical
enough. All that can be said about a dog's state of mind is that
its behavior is hard-wired to encourage that belief.
</P>
<P>
   If this sounds paranoid, recent research has exposed, yet again,
the copious pitfalls of deceit in human-animal relationships.
</P>
<P>
   Dogs are con artists, according to Stephen Budiansky, author of
``If a Lion Could Talk.'' ( Budiansky's dog snookered him into
sharing the author's photograph on the book's dust jacket, and
doubtless into a 50-50 split of the royalties too).
</P>
<P>
   Dogs are particularly adroit at manipulating human emotions;
they have inherited a sharp sensitivity to social cues from their
wolf forebears. They can read human body language and tones of
voice, divining just what is required of them. When you yell at
your dog for soiling the carpet and he cringes, you are probably
mollified by his obvious regret. It may be obvious, but is it
sincere?
</P>
<P>
   ``The cringe is a successful technique for deflecting
aggression,'' Budiansky wrote in the July issue of The Atlantic
Monthly. ``Millions of years of wolf evolution have selected such
behaviors because they are socially effective; thousands of years
of dog evolution have fine-tuned such behaviors so that they are
socially effective on people.''
</P>
<P>
   In kicking the wolf way of life for that of a hanger-on in human
societies, dogs have achieved extraordinary success. Wolves number
no more than 150,000 worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   There are 50 million dogs in this country alone, costing their
owners $5 billion a year in dog food, $7 billion in veterinary care
and $250 million in insurance claims for the 800,000 people bitten
seriously enough to warrant medical attention, Budiansky writes.
</P>
<P>
   Dogs couldn't pull off this monstrous trick without a lot of
help from their victims. The way that people relate to another
species, dolphins, shows how strong is the urge to project their
desires and expectations onto animal behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Dolphins, unlike dogs, are wild mammals with no experience in
interpreting or manipulating the weird behavior of higher primates.
Yet they have acquired a saintly image. They save drowning sailors.
They like playing with swimmers. New Age dolphins have healing
powers. They are wise, gentle and love people.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers have recently learned that bottlenose dolphins, far
from being the pacifists of the Pacific, are ferocious killers of a
related species, the harbor porpoise. The protective behavior
imputed to dolphins arises from misconstruing aspects of their
natural behavior. Dolphins don't get a kick from swimming alongside
boats: They're just enjoying a free ride in its wake. They are not
trying to save you from a shark attack: They are just
rubber-necking at your fish-out-of-water antics and sharks know to
stay out of the way of these dangerous animals.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Herbert Terrace, a Columbia University psychologist who
studies cognition, says animal aggression is not a popular topic,
even among scientists, in part because it is hard to study.
``People will persist in their preconceived notions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing a highly intelligent animal like a dolphin or a
chimpanzee, people cannot resist imputing to it whatever they would
feel in the same context. This is probably part of our genetic
programming. The whole art of living in social groups, after all,
is to figure out other members' intentions and act accordingly.
People do this instinctively, and almost any fellow mammal will
trip the reflex.
</P>
<P>
   Even a horse. The classic case of human self-deception is that
of Clever Hans, a performing horse in Berlin around 1900. By
tapping his hoof a certain number of times, the horse could count,
make correct change, tell time and calculate the day and date in a
given calendar year. He would perform these feats not only for his
trainer, a schoolteacher named Wilhelm von Osten, but for many
others too, provided they knew the answer beforehand.
</P>
<P>
   The Clever Hans phenomenon was solved by a clever psychologist,
Oskar Pfungst, who found that the testers, ever eager to be
astounded, were unconsciously cueing the horse. As Hans approached
the right number of hoof taps, expectant questioners would betray
their interest with an involuntary tensing of the body. Dr. Pfungst
ascertained that Hans could detect head movements as small as
one-fifth of a millimeter. The psychologist even played the role of
horse himself, finding that 23 out of 25 questioners cued him as to
the correct answer.
</P>
<P>
   His findings, first published in English in 1911, failed to put
an end to the charade. By 1937 there were more than 70 cats, dogs
and horses with marvelous cognitive powers. Many of the recent
attempts to teach chimpanzees language may have been marred by the
same fallacy.
</P>
<P>
   When Odysseus returned to Ithaca from the Trojan wars after 20
years, he disguised himself as a beggar to survey the palace where
his wife's suitors were partying and to plan their slaughter. No
one perceived the hero beneath his contemptible rags and grime _
none save his dog Argos. The dog thumped his tail, Homer records,
but expired in the effort to greet Odysseus, making even the
hardened warrior shed a tear that nearly betrayed him.
</P>
<P>
   Are animals uncanny judges of human character? Do they know us
better than we know ourselves? Who can tell what they really think?
Their actions are as opaque as a mirror, reflecting the projections
of our innermost desires, not theirs.
</P>
<P>
   Human relationships that go sour are often attributed to
misunderstanding, even when the obvious cause is that the parties
understand each other only too well. Total misunderstanding can
frame the perfect basis for a relationship: In such a setting,
one's partner fulfills every expectation, never rejects,
disappoints or betrays. And how else can you achieve such
gloriously happy misunderstanding, except with a dog?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-99 1244EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990724.0111 </DOCNO>
