<HEADLINE>
BOMBING WON IN KOSOVO. AFRICA IS A TOUGHER CASE. 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 By DONALD G. McNEIL Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ Now that NATO's bombers have forced
the Serbs to capitulate in Kosovo, the question naturally arises:
Couldn't the world's big powers try the same thing in Africa, which
has been in dire need of peacemaking and peacekeeping for so long?
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Victor Malu of Nigeria hinted at one answer two years ago,
when he led a Nigerian army unit overseeing an election in Liberia.
Having warned the warring militias that his peacekeepers would
``pour fire into anyone trying to disrupt the vote,'' he taunted a
reporter: ``What's the matter with you Americans? You lost your
stomach for peacekeeping in Somalia after you lost, what, 21 men?
I've lost 500 here already.''
</P>
<P>
   An American looking at the Nigerian peacekeepers might well
wonder, as the Cowardly Lion did: ``Whadda they got that I ain't
got?'' Well, stomach for that kind of warfare, for one thing. But
whether to wade into Africa's wars involves a lot more than just
courage.
</P>
<P>
   The question is especially pointed now, because two cease-fire
deals have recently been negotiated in Africa _ in Sierra Leone,
where there is some promise that the truce will hold, and in Congo,
where such prospects seem bleak. In both, outsiders are being
called on by the warring parties to send peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   Will they be from the West? Not likely.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine, for a moment, that the United States and Europe would
actually try to make peace in an African war. What lessons from
Kosovo might apply in Congo, Angola, Sierra Leone or Eritrea?
</P>
<P>
   For instance, can an African war be won with air power? Can
ground troops be inserted without putting them in harm's way? If
so, would they do any good?
</P>
<P>
   Military and political analysts here say the first question is
easy to answer. Air power has never been much use in Africa,
because rural Africans already lack factories, electricity, bridges
and armored divisions. ``Bomb what?'' said Claude Kabemba, a
foreign policy analyst for the Center for Policy Studies, a
research institute in South Africa. ``In Congo, war is a guy under
a tree with an AK-47.''
</P>
<P>
   There has ben some bombing on the Ethiopia-Eritrea border, but
that war is fought the way World War I was: with human waves flung
against trenches. In the Congo, Zimbabwean jets have sunk ferries
said to be carrying rebels, but haven't been decisive in a battle.
</P>
<P>
   One war here might be ended with a precision strike: If a
missile tracked Jonas Savimbi's satellite phone signals into the
Angolan bush, it might behead the Unita rebel movement. But that
would require unpalatable choices: it would be a bald
assassination, it would hand victory to a government whose behavior
is only slightly better than Savimbi's, and some analysts say
Savimbi's generals might fight on without him.
</P>
<P>
   Helmoed-Romer Heitman, an analyst for Jane's Defense Weekly,
discerned two uses for air power in peacekeeping: AWACS planes and
fighters could impede, but probably not stop, the flow of men and
weapons around Congo and northern Angola, where roads are so bad
that decrepit ex-Soviet cargo planes ferry both.
</P>
<P>
   More important, if a force of African soldiers willing to go
into danger areas was mustered, transports for the troops and
helicopters for their commanders would be a very useful Western
contribution.
</P>
<P>
   Any mission for ground troops is more problematic.
</P>
<P>
   United Nations troops have poor reputations in Africa. Many are
small units from poor nations like Bangladesh, sent because the
United Nations pays their governments hundreds of dollars a day for
each soldier. A dozen units from a dozen countries whose only
mission is to look around and maybe get shot at are bound to fail,
as such a force did in Angola this year.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's well-trained and equipped troops are a different matter.
They could easily win battles. But that isn't peacekeeping. Congo
is 215 times the size of Kosovo, Angola 114 times. The terrain is
far more difficult, the fighting a patchwork of skirmishes without
front lines. If some 20,000 NATO troops have found it hard to
prevent murders of Serbs and Albanians in remote Balkan villages,
what could they do in Congo? The United Nations Department of
Peacekeeping Operations told one military analyst in Pretoria that
patrolling Congo would require 100,000 men.
</P>
<P>
   And for how long? And what would they do when they were shot at?
The Congo cease-fire document expects the peacekeepers to disarm
more than a dozen armed forces, including Unita, the Mayi-Mayi
guerrillas and the Hutu militias. Unita has been at war for 25
years. The Mayi-Mayi charge into battle naked, thinking they're
bulletproof. The Hutu militias, if disarmed, would be deported to
Rwanda to be executed for genocide, so it is unlikely that they
will disarm voluntarily.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, there's the ``stomach'' issue. Ugandan President Yoweri
Museveni, whose troops are fighting in Congo, was recently reported
to be mocking Western peacekeepers. ``Which U.N. troops will stay
in these mountains for six months?'' the Monitor newspaper quoted
him as saying. ``They will just run away like they did in Rwanda.
European soldiers go only to areas where there is no death.''
</P>
<P>
   Where the battle zone is contained, as in the Badme Triangle
between Ethiopia and Eritrea, peacekeepers could be a buffer
between the sides, as in Cyprus or the Golan Heights. But such
situations can be open-ended. Heitman put it this way: ``Cyprus?
The U.N.'s been there since the 60's. And if they left, the Turkish
and Greek Cypriots would go right back to war.''
</P>
<P>
   Strategists in Washington, London and Paris know this. They
haven't volunteered troops for Africa and thus far are reluctant to
pay for a United Nations effort.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, for a couple of years now, the United States and Europe
have been prodding African countries to form a joint force to calm
the continent's constant crises. Even France, whose Foreign Legion
once aggressively policed its ex-colonies, wants out, said Chris
Landsberg, deputy director of the Center for Policy Studies. Africa
is slowly warming to the idea of a regional joint force, but it's
still all theory.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the skittishness of the West infuriates Africans, who
often say it is racism to spend $1.50 per Kosovo refugee but only
11 cents per African refugee. Many African nations like Nigeria and
South Africa say they would be willing to provide the men to do
peace-keeping, but need help paying for them _ lots of help.
</P>
<P>
   ``Post-Somalia, post-Rwanda, the West is able but unwilling, and
Africa is willing but unable,'' said Landsberg. ``Somehow, we have
to convince the West that peace in this area is in their interest.
And then hundreds of millions of dollars has to come from somewhere
_ $20 million here and $20 million there isn't going to do it.''
</P>
