<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-24 13:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2626 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-REVIVAL-2TAKES-N     07-24 1264
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-REVIVAL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH, THE FORMER PRESIDENT, BASKS IN RENEWED RESPECT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After his galling defeat by the governor of
Arkansas in 1992, President George Bush became something of an
outcast in his own party. At Republican functions, speakers rattled
on longingly about Ronald Reagan, but never about Bush. It was as
if Republicans had collective amnesia about the man who led their
party and the nation from 1989 to 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Not anymore. The president who was belittled for breaking his
no-new-taxes pledge and ridiculed as a passive in-box president who
dealt only with matters in front of him, is now basking in the glow
of a surprisingly early, and positive, reassessment of his
stewardship.
</P>
<P>
   It is common for Americans to like their presidents better after
they leave office. But the resurgence of respect for Bush _ a view
demonstrated in polls and expressed in interviews with dozens of
Republicans at all levels, and even held by some Democrats _ has
occurred surprisingly quickly.
</P>
<P>
   History books aside, the shift carries more immediate political
implications. Worried that Bush's enhanced stature is helping his
son, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, stampede to the Republican
presidential nomination, the governor's foes are trying to tamp
down the reassessment of the Bush presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Just the week before last, President Clinton offered a
not-so-nostalgic recollection of the Bush years in a speech in
Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   And two of the younger Bush's rivals for the nomination _ Steve
Forbes, the multimillionaire publisher, and Lamar Alexander, a
former secretary of education _ have ridiculed the elder Bush's
slogan about a ``kinder and gentler'' country, in a not-so-subtle
effort to condemn the governor's similarly feel-good slogan of
``compassionate conservatism.''
</P>
<P>
   Sixty percent of Americans have a favorable view of the former
president and only 17 percent have an unfavorable view, according
to a CBS News Poll conducted last month.
</P>
<P>
   It is not the adulation Bush enjoyed after the Persian Gulf war,
when his job-approval rating catapulted as high as 90 percent. But
it is far better than the results of a CBS News/New York Times poll
the month before he was ousted by Clinton. Then, Bush was rated
favorably by 35 percent and unfavorably by 45 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have in retrospect a rosy nostalgic view and warm
feelings toward him,'' said Gary Orren, a professor of public
policy at Harvard's Kennedy School of Government.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difficulties that Bill Clinton has had have only amplified
the contrasts: In retrospect he looks even more virtuous. That
George W. is the moon getting a lot of bright light off his father
is something you might not have predicted in November of 1992, when
the economy was bad and there was all the hopefulness about
Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, many people, particularly Republicans, said that after
the Clinton scandals they have a new appreciation for Bush's
personal rectitude. Many also cited a greater appreciation for his
effort to end the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   Sounding a familiar refrain among active Republicans, Michael
McDaniel, chairman of the Indiana Republican Party, said, ``Believe
me, there's a big buyer's remorse out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who is 75, and his son, 53, appear to be drawing residual
benefit from each other. Governor Bush is so enormously popular in
his party that many Republicans look fondly upon the former
president for being part of his son's winning aura _ even as they
praise the son as a far more relaxed and more natural politician.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in a country that excessively loves winners and we tend
to be hard on presidents who were defeated in office after one
term,'' said Michael Beschloss, a presidential historian. ``But
when you have a son who seems the likely favorite to be a
Republican nominee and possibly the next president, it causes
people to look for good things about his father.''
</P>
<P>
   He said a similar dynamic was last in play with the Roosevelts;
people had a much more positive view of Theodore Roosevelt after he
left office, because of the popularity of his cousin, President
Franklin D. Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the dynamic works both ways: The younger Bush benefits from
his father's name and reputation; he draws instant credibility as
the son of someone who served in the Oval Office and left
Washington with his integrity intact. (The same factors affect
another Bush son, Jeb, the governor of Florida.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The romanticism of his being the son of a former president
just makes it that much more sexy,'' said Georgette Mosbacher, a
co-chairwoman of Sen. John McCain's presidential campaign whose
former husband, Robert, was Bush's secretary of commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Teeter, a pollster in Michigan who ran the 1992 Bush
campaign, said: ``People just automatically say, `If this guy is
George and Barbara Bush's son, we don't have any question about
those personal qualities that we were fooled on by Clinton.' hat's
where his family heritage really works for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Except for two high-profile parachute jumps, the last in June to
celebrate his 75th birthday, the elder Bush has done nothing to
aggressively reshape his image. Unlike most presidents, he has no
plans to write his memoirs, though he did write a book on foreign
policy with Brent Scowcroft, ``A World Transformed'' (Knopf, 1998).
</P>
<P>
   But if anything, Bush's decision not to speak out about the
transgressions of his successor has probably enhanced his
reputation as an elder statesman who is above politics.
</P>
<P>
   Characteristically, Bush went out of his way not to gloat when
asked to comment for this article. ``I am unfamiliar with the
polling numbers you talked about,'' Bush said in a typewritten note
faxed from his home in Kennebunkport, Maine. ``But if what you say
is true _ well, that is very nice. Since leaving the White House, I
have tried hard to stay out of the limelight. I also have not tried
to shape history. I will leave it up to the historians and
academics to figure all that out. What I hope they will say is that
we got some things right, made some mistakes, but served with
honor.''
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Kaufman, who was Bush's political director in the White
House and is still his political adviser, said there had been a
dramatic rise in requests for the former president to appear at
party functions.
</P>
<P>
   ``In '93, we'd get maybe two or three requests a month, max,
like `Can he do the Lincoln Day speech for the Harris County
Republican Party in Texas?''' Kaufman said. ``I'd get calls, `Do
you think the president would mind asking his son if he'd be the
speaker?' But this year, I probably get from 25 to 30 requests a
week for him to be the headliner at events like the Republican
National Committee's annual gala.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush is not as adored as Reagan in his party. There are still
lingering hard feelings from the 1992 campaign; a month before that
election Bush was faring so poorly that only two dozen of more than
400 Republican congressional candidates accepted Bush's offer to
appear in campaign videos with him.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, his improved popularity may come as much from moderates
as from hard-core conservatives who never quite trusted Bush as a
genuine conservative _ and still do not. ``I think he's a more
beloved figure in the country than in the party,'' Teeter said.
``It's the marginal, more independent Republicans who look back and
say, `Gee, compared to Clinton, he's wonderful.'''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A poll conducted in March for Fox television found that if the
1992 election were held now _ certainly a fanciful notion _ Bush
would draw 58 percent of the vote, and Clinton 37 percent. But it
is impossible to decipher the accuracy of a survey that asks people
to re-evaluate how they voted. For all anyone knows, respondents
were confusing Bush with his son, who has dominated the political
news for months.
</P>
<P>
   In his recent speech, Clinton did not mention his predecessor by
name, but clearly sought to dash any fond memories of the Bush era.
``We may have to remind our fellow citizens in times to come just
what it was like back then,'' Clinton said. ``How high the
unemployment was, how stagnant the wages were, how steeply growing
the inequality was, how fast the social conditions were
worsening.''
</P>
<P>
   The efforts to link the younger Bush with his father are
inevitable because of the similarities between the two men. They
both have sought to take any harsh edge off their Republican
principles. They both toiled in the Texas oil business. But while
the elder Bush had long expertise in foreign policy and federal
matters, the governor's has been limited to state government.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest difference, cited by many Republicans, is that
Governor Bush's hands-on, wade-into-the-crowd campaigning style
more resembles Clinton's than that of President Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``George W. has that Clintonesque, Reaganesque ability of
relating to people that was George Sr.'s major problem,'' said Mike
Kiedrowski, executive director of the Republican Party in Montana.
``He's much more like Ronald Reagan than his father. But in
retrospect President Bush has gained over the years. I may not
agree with every policy, certainly not the '90 tax increase. But he
was a good leader.''
</P>
<P>
   Billy Van Devender, a Republican national committeeman from
Mississippi, said of the younger Bush, ``He's got all the
attributes of his dad, but his son can do it a lot better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-99 1305EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990724.0122 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-24 13:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2630 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAXCUT-POLITICS-ART-9     07-24 1328
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAXCUT-POLITICS-ART-900&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEEKING COMMON GROUND ON FEDERAL TAX CUT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Del., Mo., Texas)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(jw) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the midst of the bitter debate last week over
the Republican tax bills moving through Congress, it was easy to
lose sight of the emerging consensus in both parties that there
should be a tax cut this year.
</P>
<P>
   The question now is where the middle ground on taxes might be _
and how the White House and Congress can get there.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a tax cut waiting to happen,'' said Rep. Michael
Castle, R-Del., who favors a compromise smaller than the $792
billion package passed by the House last week but bigger than the
$300 million or so that President Clinton has said he can support.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton insisted that a tax reduction would have to await
progress in shoring up Social Security and Medicare, and that it
could not be so big as to starve domestic spending programs or risk
a return to federal budget deficits. But he made clear that he was
open to a deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not debating whether to have tax cuts or not,'' Clinton
told a news conference on Wednesday. ``We should have tax cuts.''
</P>
<P>
   On the face of it, a compromise package of tax cuts totaling
$400 billion to $500 billion over the next decade would not seem
difficult to work out. From among the array of proposals contained
in the bill passed by the House on Thursday and a bill scheduled to
be taken up by the Senate _ as well as from ideas backed by
Democrats _ there are plenty of options for addressing both party's
priorities.
</P>
<P>
   But before they get to that point, both sides will have to
decide that they want a deal more than they want to use the issue
to campaign on in the 2000 elections. They will have to fit an
agreement on taxes into a broader compromise covering spending
levels and the future of Social Security and Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   And even if they decide to negotiate seriously, working out a
tax deal will be far more difficult than simply splitting the
difference, because their respective approaches reflect an
ideological clash as much as a dispute over the size of any tax
cut.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and most Democrats in Congress want any tax cuts to be
directed at low- and moderate-income households, and to be linked
to some specific purpose, like promoting more retirement savings or
helping to subsidize the purchase of health or long-term care
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans want the tax reductions to be spread more broadly.
In practice, their plans would give the biggest cuts to the people
who pay the most in taxes _ the affluent _ and reduce taxes not
just on income but on wealth, through reductions in capital gains
taxes and the inheritance tax levied on large estates.
</P>
<P>
   An analysis by the Treasury Department of the House tax bill
found that 79.6 percent of the benefits would go to taxpayers with
the highest 20 percent of income, above $81,967. A third would go
to the top 1 percent of taxpayers, those with income above
$346,555.
</P>
<P>
   The Treasury analysis looked at the effects of the House bill's
main provisions, including the 10 percent reduction in personal
income tax rates, the reduction in the top rate on capital gains to
15 percent from 20 percent, the repeal of the estate tax and the
increase in the standard deduction for married couples.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their tax cut is all over the lot, and most of it goes to the
top 10 percent of earners,'' said Rep. Richard Gephardt of
Missouri, the House Democratic leader.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans said the people who have been most overtaxed are
those who earn the most. They cited figures showing that taxpayers
earning $200,000 and over _ about 2 percent of the population _ pay
40 percent of income taxes. People earning over $75,000 a year,
they said, make up 15 percent of the population but pay 75 percent
of income taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republicans are determined to protect taxpayers who ultimately
get stuck with the bills,'' said Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, who is
chairman of the Ways and Means Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are some areas where the two sides can clearly
reach a deal. Democrats generally support proposals contained in
both the House and the Senate bills to reduce the so-called
marriage penalty, the quirk in the tax code that leaves many
two-income couples paying more in taxes than they would if they
were single.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats favor the approach in the House bill. It would
increase the standard deduction for married couples to twice that
for single people, thereby focusing the benefits on lower- and
middle-income couples rather than wealthier couples who would
almost invariably itemize their deductions. The provision would
cost about $45 billion over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both parties see the marriage penalty as something they have
to do,'' said Richard May, a former Republican staff director of
the House Budget Committee, who is now a lobbyist.
</P>
<P>
   There is also widespread bipartisan support for tax breaks for
buying health insurance. Both the House and the Senate bills have
health provisions, totaling around $50 billion over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Both parties favor extending a series of expiring tax
provisions, including one that provides a break for research and
development expenses. Both bills contain $20 billion for the
expiring provisions.
</P>
<P>
   But finding agreement on the biggest provisions in the
Republican proposals _ reducing income tax rates, capital gains
taxes, the estate tax and the alternative minimum tax _ would be
tricky at best.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Both the House and Senate bills have as their centerpieces
reductions in personal income taxes. The House bill would reduce by
10 percent the rates for all income tax brackets at a cost of about
$375 billion over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   After 2001, the tax-rate cuts in the House bill would take
effect only if interest payments on the national debt were not
rising.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate bill would cut the current bottom bracket of 15
percent to 14 percent and expand the bracket to higher income
levels. The provision, which would cost about $300 billion over 10
years, would focus much of the benefit on middle-income taxpayers,
making it far more palatable to Democrats than the House version.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, analysts said, if an income tax reduction is
included in any compromise it would almost certainly be closer to
the Senate version than the House version. The two sides could also
fall back on a more modest rate reduction proposed by a group of
Senate Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rate cuts tend to be very expensive,'' said Robert Reischauer,
a former director of the Congressional Budget Office who is now a
fellow at the Brookings Institution. ``If they have a life, it's
most certainly in the form the Senate is putting forward.''
</P>
<P>
   There is little support among Democrats for a cut in the capital
gains tax, but with the investor class growing ever larger and the
stock market heading ever higher, opposition from Democrats is far
more muted than it used to be. Democrats are likely to be
assertive, however, in attacking Republican proposals to repeal or
sharply scale back the tax on large estates, saying such a cut
would confer huge benefits on a tiny handful of heirs for decades
to come.
</P>
<P>
   The degree to which Republicans prevail on their tax-cutting
priorities may depend on how far they prove willing to go in giving
in to Clinton in other areas, particularly the administration's
call for a new prescription drug benefit for Medicare recipients
and its insistence on using part of the projected budget surplus
for spending on education, health and other domestic programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's going to be a grand compromise on taxes,'' May
said, ``there's going to have to be a bigger, grander compromise on
discretionary spending and on prescription drugs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-99 1314EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990724.0123 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-24 13:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2632 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAPE-COD-ICECREAM-ART     07-24 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAPE-COD-ICECREAM-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR BEST AND BRIGHTEST, THE BEST JOB ON THE CAPE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Fla.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(jw) 
 By SARA RIMER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CENTERVILLE, Mass. _ Cory Sinclair, 17, was scooping ice cream
at the Four Seas as fast as he could and talking about the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be president,'' he said. ``I'm serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly O'Neil, 18, had more prosaic concerns. ``I'm sorry, we
don't have jimmies,'' she informed a customer. (As any Four Seas
regular knows, jimmies don't belong on good ice cream.)
</P>
<P>
   Mixing up a batch of coconut, Bryan Schlegel, 22, was feeling
restless and wistful.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to move on,'' he said. ``I've been here six
summers.''
</P>
<P>
   The Four Seas, a white cottage with blue shutters and a white
formica counter with 12 blue stools, has been an institution on
South Main Street of this Cape Cod village for 65 summers.
</P>
<P>
   The owner, Richard Warren, 64, who has been on the job for 45
years, makes what is indisputably delicious ice cream. He uses
fresh peaches, strawberries, blueberries and ginger, expensive
chocolate and loads of butter cream, and he tastes every batch
himself. He does not add candy or try bizarre flavors.
</P>
<P>
   But what also distinguishes the Four Seas is the help.
</P>
<P>
   Summer after summer, the young men and women behind the counter
seem as unchanging as the decor, the ice cream and the oldies on
the radio. They are clean-cut and sport no visible tattoos or
strange piercing. They are alert and polite, even when the
customers are rude.
</P>
<P>
   They are the class presidents, newspaper editors and honor roll
regulars from Barnstable High School who have been handpicked by
Warren, a retired math teacher and guidance counselor there.
</P>
<P>
   They start serving up cones at 16, and they stay through
college, ending their careers _ and career is the word they use _
as ice cream makers and managers, like Schlegel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the best job you can get on the Cape,'' said Tava Ohlsen,
18, who graduated at the top of her class in June, plans to go to
medical school and moved up this summer from ice cream scooper to
sandwich maker. ``People say, `Oh, you work at the Four Seas.
You're a good student; you're good with people.'''
</P>
<P>
   From the week before Memorial Day until the week after Labor
Day, the staff races from the counter to the ice cream and back to
keep up with the crowds. There are higher paying summer jobs _ the
Four Seas is minimum wage, with tips bringing it to about $10 an
hour _ but Warren never has any trouble finding help.
</P>
<P>
   He solicits recommendations from the faculty at Barnstable High,
and summons those with the highest ratings for interviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's known that you can't apply,'' Sinclair said.
</P>
<P>
   To be called by Warren is to become a member of his extended
family.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's like a second dad,'' said Jahni Clarke, 19. ``I tell him
about everything, from school to money to my love life.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of every summer Warren throws a staff party, with
dinner and a live band. He organizes an all-expenses-paid ski
weekend in New Hampshire every winter. He writes his employees'
college recommendations, and when they get to college, he visits
them.
</P>
<P>
   He brings ice cream to their weddings (romance, predictably,
blooms behind the counter, and there have been seven Four Seas
marriages so far).
</P>
<P>
   He has periodic reunions; at the last one, in 1988, only four
Four Seas alums, out of more than 200, were not able to make it.
</P>
<P>
   Warren is married, with four grown children. Each season he
gives out scholarships totaling several thousand dollars in memory
of his son Randy, who was killed in 1983 when he was hit by a car
while crossing the street in Fort Lauderdale. He was 21.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was never close to my dad,'' said Warren, who was talking
the other day between greeting customers and making ice cream. ``He
was 46 when I was born. I longed for a relationship with my
children. Randy and I were so close. We won the state father-son
golf tournament. We'd ski all day, play tennis till we dropped. He
wanted to run this place someday.''
</P>
<P>
   Randy lives on, in a way, Warren said, in the young people who
work beside him each summer. ``Bryan is like a son,'' he said as he
and Schlegel poured frozen pudding ice cream into cartons. ``We
just played in the father-son golf tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   Schlegel graduated this spring from the University of
Massachusetts at Amherst. He was recently called for an interview
in the customer service department of a Boston investment banking
firm. By fall, he said, he hopes to have a permanent job.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Clarke, who is a junior at the University of
Massachusetts, just moved up to manager. ``I'm the first black
manager,'' said Clarke, who was freshman class president and editor
of the newspaper at Barnstable High, which is mostly white.
</P>
<P>
   Things do change at the Four Seas. As hard-working as his 25
employees are, Warren said that most do not want to put in the
hours that previous generations did.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't need the money as much,'' he said, adding that
whereas workers from summers past arrived on foot or by bicycle, or
were dropped off by their parents, almost all of the employees now
drive their own cars.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest change, the one everyone is talking about, is
that Warren's son Doug, 36, is back from Las Vegas, where he had
been running a restaurant and selling computer software. The plan
is for him to take over the ice cream parlor. The elder Warren is
talking about retiring in a couple of years.
</P>
<P>
   His staff is skeptical. ``The chief will never retire,'' Miss
O'Neil said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
