<DOCNO> NYT19990724.0124 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-24 13:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2634 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLACK-TERMS25-COX     07-24 1732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACK-TERMS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `African-american' entrenched in national lexicon, 10 years
later
 &HT;    By Lyle V. Harris
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For the descendants of American slaves, a name was
always more than just a name. The skin-deep aspects of their racial
identity can be traced like tree rings to the terms used to
describe them.
</P>
<P>
   The n-word was supposed to be an insult, first used like a lash
to demean and defeat. Colored seemed like an upgrade of sorts,
until it was replaced by ``Afro-American,'' which for many referred
to a hairstyle, not a heritage. And for those who were around in
the late 1960s and '70s, black was not only beautiful, it was
revolutionary as well.
</P>
<P>
   Then in 1988 the Rev. Jesse Jackson publicly urged blacks to
stop playing the name game, and to once and for all declare
themselves African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Some dismissed Jackson's suggestion as a linguistic fad. A 1991
poll by the Joint Center for Economic and Policy Studies, a
Washington-based think tank, found the term ``black'' was still
preferred over ``African-American'' by nearly 5 to 1.
</P>
<P>
   Not anymore.
</P>
<P>
   When 279 respondents of African descent were asked by The
Atlanta Journal-Constitution's Southern Focus Poll which term they
prefer, their opinions went beyond the shifting racial lexicon to
the very heart of their dual, if distant, birthright.
</P>
<P>
   In the South, about 33 percent of those who answered said they
would rather be called black while 44 percent said they favored
African-American.
</P>
<P>
   Their counterparts outside the South preferred African-American
(51 percent) to black (27 percent). Regardless of geography, about
one-fifth of respondents said they didn't know, or didn't care what
they were called.
</P>
<P>
   Age, however, seemed to play some role. Among the Southern
respondents, 52 percent of people ages 18 to 29 picked
African-American, while roughly the same percentage 65 and older
opted for black.
</P>
<P>
   Rocena Parker, a 19-year-old student at the University of
Memphis, was only 8 when Jackson made his pitch and doesn't
remember the tempest it created. Still, there's no question which
term is right for her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like African-American better because it tells me where I
come from, my origin and my ethnic background,'' said the poll
respondent. ``To me, African-American is just stronger than
black.''
</P>
<P>
   Parker said when filling out applications which inquire about
her race, she'll often write the letters ``A-f-A,'' her own
shorthand for African-American.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like they say: You don't know where you're going unless
you know where you've been,'' Parker said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Jackson gets most of the credit for coining the term
African-American, that distinction rightly belongs to people such
as Ramona Edelin. A scholar and activist, Edelin piped up with the
idea in the waning hours of a black leadership meeting Jackson
convened in Chicago more than a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of us in the group had already decided to refer to
ourselves as African-American because we wanted to establish the
correct geopolitical basis for our agenda,'' said the former
African-American studies professor, who now serves as director of
the Congressional Black Caucus Foundation Inc. in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't think we should still be hanging on to the polar
opposites of white and black. For me, African-American was a
compromise word that enabled us in the movement to embrace both of
our cultural realities.''
</P>
<P>
   Edelin recalled that everyone in the meeting agreed with the
change.
</P>
<P>
   But she was surprised by how easily the term actually caught on.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first people trivialized it, but 18 months later we looked
up and everyone was using it on the networks and in newspapers. I
was getting calls about it from London and Brussels and all over
the world about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Timing is everything
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, African-American was a term whose time had come.
</P>
<P>
   Flush from two credible presidential bids, Jackson was a
charismatic media darling to major print and broadcast outlets who
were often grappling with minority hiring issues in their own
newsrooms.
</P>
<P>
   In the streets of Washington and at college campuses around the
country, South African political prisoner Nelson Mandela had become
a cause celebre, and his struggle for freedom helped establish a
kinship between the two continents that never existed before.
</P>
<P>
   And on prime-time television ``The Cosby Show'' and ``In Living
Color'' _ two shows with predominantly black casts _ ruled the
ratings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if there was anything special about that period,
but the whole country came to value multiculturalism as a social
ideal in a way we clearly did not in the 1950s,'' said John
McWhorter, an associate professor of linguistics at the University
of California, Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   While African-American appears to have become more popular, it
is still used interchangeably with black, even though the words
don't always have the same meaning.
</P>
<P>
   Some consider African-American too unwieldy for everyday speech.
Others say it doesn't encompass the far-flung diversity of blacks
whose families immigrated to America from other places, such as the
West Indies. But there's little doubt that the term has been widely
embraced, and it's showing no signs of falling from favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was growing up it was an insult to call someone
black,'' said Bob Spinks, a 55-year-old high school teacher and
poll participant from Oklahoma City. ``When you use the terms black
and white, it sets up inferior and superior connotations in your
mind. But with African-American, you're associating your blackness
with something positive.''
</P>
<P>
   Professor Darren Rhym of Clark Atlanta University agrees that
the term black is no longer pejorative, but he's concerned that the
growing acceptance of the term African-American marks an
abandonment of hard-fought ideals forged during the '60s.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a time when you said 'black' you were making a
political statement, you were saying you were tied to the black
power movement. It had almost a militant tone,'' says Rhym. ``Now I
think blacks are less politicized. The students I see are more
concerned with wanting to integrate. They don't want to stand out
and could care less about the black community.''
</P>
<P>
   New generation, new realities
</P>
<P>
   Professor Sonja Lanehart, a professor of English Studies and
Linguistics at the University of Georgia, sees the change more as a
matter of pragmatism, not politics. She believes the term
African-American has become the standard for a generation that's
still proud of its racial heritage, but doesn't want to beat anyone
over the head with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``African-American is a less contentious term,'' says Lanehart.
``The term 'black' seemed very strong and forceful, it was a term
of strength that intimidated some people. African-Americans in
positions of power are often interacting with people they are not
in conflict with. They want a term that says, `I'm different, but
I'm somebody you can get along with.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Even as the term African-American has become commonplace in
everyday speech, it's had a harder time making the cut in
mainstream reference books.
</P>
<P>
   The Third Edition of Webster's New World Collegiate Dictionary
published in 1996 has no listing for African-American. Their
competitors, the Merriam-Webster Dictionary, last year listed
African-American as a sub-heading to Afro-American, a term which is
all but passe in everyday speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very careful about including words that pop in and out
of the language,'' said Deborah Burns, marketing director for
Merriam-Webster in Springfield, Mass. ``African-American was being
used widely, and often enough that we thought it met the
standard.''
</P>
<P>
   Many newspapers use both terms, usually depending on context.
The term African-American first appeared in The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution's stylebook in 1995 as an alternative to
black. The newspaper's 1998 stylebook lists black as ``acceptable,
but not preferred over African- American.''
</P>
<P>
   For those who are having trouble making up their minds, the U.S.
Census Bureau will for the first time include the term
African-American on questionnaires for the 2000 Census along with
``Black'' and ``Negro.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted something for everyone,'' says Nampeo McKenney, a
senior researcher for the Census Bureau. ``More people are using
African-American, but we know from our research that there are
still people, particularly older people, who still call themselves
Negro or colored.''
</P>
<P>
   For some, the choice over which term to use was never much in
dispute.
</P>
<P>
   J. Lowell Ware, the late publisher of the Atlanta Voice
newspaper, was considered a pioneer for adopting the term
African-American in the late 1970s. His daughter Janis Ware runs
the paper now, and says the policy is still intact.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my father's mind, black was only a color,'' Ware said.
``Black says nothing about us, and I don't use the term at all
unless I'm talking about black furniture or a black outfit. I don't
think we've ever used black in our newspaper to refer to a person,
and I don't think we will.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta author Pearl Cleage is trilingual when it comes to her
preferred term.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still even use Negro sometimes,'' says Cleage. ``In a way I
think what we call each other is less important than how we act. If
we love each other and treat each other with respect that's what
really matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleage admits that she occasionally uses ``nigger,'' a word so
dreaded and controversial that it has its own euphemism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like saying 'the n-word,' it sounds silly,'' Cleage
said. ``Within our own community, we use the word in its own
context and I'm all right with that. But I wouldn't say it with
other people outside of our community. When we say it, we know what
it means.''
</P>
<P>
   To Jackson the ability of a community to choose its own identity
is the first step in determining its destiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our psyche was so crushed at one time that we were ashamed of
Africa,'' Jackson said in a telephone interview. ``To call someone
African used to be demeaning. But I think the term African-American
is sticking because our psyche has been globalized. We are saying
our heritage did not originate in slavery. We are saying, 'We are
citizens of the world.'''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
