<HEADER>
A2641 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REM-GEORGIA-POLITICS-     07-24 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REM-GEORGIA-POLITICS-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCK GROUP TAKES ON A `GOOD OLD BOY NETWORK'
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga.)   (jw) 
 By TOM LASSETER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ A grass-roots campaign against a local hospital's
plan to expand into surrounding neighborhoods here has all the
hallmarks of civic activism that this college town is known for:
yard signs, petitions, meetings, protests and, of course, the
support of one of the world's most successful rock bands, R.E.M.
</P>
<P>
   R.E.M.'s involvement in local affairs has been a staple for so
long that when its lead singer and most politically active member,
Michael Stipe, showed up for a community meeting with officials
from the Athens Regional Medical Center in late April, there was no
murmur from the crowd and only a few heads turned.
</P>
<P>
   Stipe has referred to the hospital's growth plan as an example
of `` '80s era Reagan-style aggression.'' And so it came as no
surprise when this month the band gave a check for $2,500 to the
recently organized Citizens for Healthy Neighborhoods. The band's
lawyer and manager, Bertis Downs, had already told the group that
R.E.M. would pay the bill for the best lawyer it could find.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on who is talking, R.E.M. is either Athens' best
corporate citizen or one of the biggest bullies to hit town since
the Union army.
</P>
<P>
   Since coming together as four university undergraduates in 1981,
the band has never really left this community of 90,000, which
includes 30,000 students at the University of Georgia. Two of the
band's members, Stipe and Mike Mills, still live here, and it is
generally acknowledged as a serious social faux pas to make a scene
if one sights, say, Stipe walking his dog or talking with a friend
at a local bar.
</P>
<P>
   World headquarters for the band, which has sold more than 40
million records and is in the third year of an $80 million contract
with Warner Brothers Music, the biggest company in the industry,
are above a cookie shop downtown.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview from Bologna, Italy, one of the band's
stops on its summer tour, Stipe said he wanted Athens to remain, as
much as possible, the sort of place it was when he moved here.
``It's home. That's something that most Americans hold close,''
Stipe said.
</P>
<P>
   Through the weight of its wealth and reputation, Stipe said,
R.E.M. is able to act as a check to what he sees as the ``good old
boy network'' of conservative politicians and developers,
especially on issues involving historic preservation and the
environment. ``I think they're terrified of me because I'm
different,'' said Stipe, a multimillionaire who keeps his head
shaved, often dresses in clothes that might have come from a thrift
store and has been known to paint his fingernails.
</P>
<P>
   Some locals said that the band, led by Stipe, who describes
himself as ``an unashamed liberal,'' was too aggressive in setting
its agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``The average citizen does not realize how much funding R.E.M.
has put into political campaigns in Athens,'' said Marilyn Farmer,
one of two Republicans on the local commission. ``They have an
attitude of ultimately trying to control what happens in Athens
government.''
</P>
<P>
   The band was referred to as the R.E.M. mafia in some local
circles in 1989 when it stepped into a debate on how the civic
center would be designed. Stipe, along with many other critics,
said he thought the architect's draft was too obtrusive for the
rustic downtown district.
</P>
<P>
   When it seemed the city's leadership would not listen, R.E.M.
paid $5,000 for a consultant to review the plans. From that point
the tide began to turn and the center's plan soon became less
modern and ended up incorporating an existing fire hall.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   R.E.M.'s next big entry into local politics came in 1990, when
the residents of Athens and the surrounding county, Clarke, voted
to unify their governments. The ensuing mayoral election was
recognized as a pivotal moment in the region's history.
</P>
<P>
   The underdog, a liberal and a former City Council member, Gwen
O'Looney, was not thought to have much of a chance to win since the
local government was run largely by conservative Democrats. That
changed when the band put its support behind Mrs. O'Looney, who
said she wasn't sure if she wanted to run until R.E.M. promised to
raise at least $10,000 for her.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the race, which Mrs. O'Looney won, the band and
its management, giving as individuals, accounted for almost
one-third of Mrs. O'Looney's campaign fund, donating $14,285 of the
approximately $43,000 she collected, according to her financial
disclosure statements.
</P>
<P>
   That same year, the band's members and management contributed
$3,000 to a successful campaign by John Barrow for a seat on the
newly unified commission. The money constituted more than one-third
of the approximately $8,000 Barrow collected. Also, the group gave
$1,500 to the successful commission campaign of Cardee Kilpatrick.
</P>
<P>
   Barrow became the acknowledged gadfly of the unified
government's commission. He and Mrs. Kilpatrick would often align
themselves with Mrs. O'Looney, who lives on the same street as
Downs, the band manager, and only a few blocks from Stipe, to push
for historic preservation and environmentally friendly measures.
</P>
<P>
   In a county where the average per capita income is about
$21,000, Stipe today owns, including his home, $953,348 in property
in a three-block area, according to the Athens-Clarke County tax
assessor's records.
</P>
<P>
   The band members' money means they are not subject to local
influence, said Pete McCommons, publisher of Flagpole magazine, a
local alternative publication.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their money is independent of Athens,'' he said. ``Nobody can
touch them. Nobody can pick up the phone and say, `Fire them.' They
are untouchable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
