<HEADER>
A2644 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CZECH-GYPSY-STUDY-NYT     07-24 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CZECH-GYPSY-STUDY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO GYPSIES, CZECH SPECIAL SCHOOLS ARE A LESSON IN BIAS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRAGUE, Czech Republic _ Before he went to school, the
5-year-old Gypsy boy could read. In fact, he liked reading so much
that his teachers complained that he paid more attention to his
books than to what was going on in his classroom.
</P>
<P>
   Six months later, teachers decided that the boy, Lada Hejkrlik,
was ``mentally deficient,'' and recommended his transfer to a
school for children whose ability to learn is impaired.
</P>
<P>
   His mother, Jana Hejkrlikova, was outraged. To her, it was a
clear case of racial discrimination, part of a long pattern of
Czech bias against the Gypsies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The teacher told me, `Your child just cannot keep up, we'll
send him to a special school,''' said Mrs. Hejkrlikova. ``She told
me he was preconditioned for it.''
</P>
<P>
   It took her six months to persuade an army of psychologists and
education consultants that her son was perfectly capable of
studying at an ordinary school.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Lada is in his 20s, a senior at a technical college.
Without his mother's intervention, his career prospects could have
been minimal.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Hejkrlikova is now a member of the Czech Republic's state
commission for minority rights, a panel established after Communist
rule collapsed in 1989 and a growing number of racist incidents
led, gradually, to discussion of the situation of the 300,000
Gypsies estimated to live in the Czech Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout Central and Eastern Europe, the Gypsies were
persecuted, imprisoned and killed by the Nazis, then virtually
ignored under the Communists.
</P>
<P>
   In many countries, they are widely viewed as uneducated and
prone to crime, living in poor housing and inherently nomadic.
</P>
<P>
   In the Czech Republic, there are not even any statistics about
Gypsies. But by some estimates about half of their schoolchildren
attend schools intended to deal with retarded children, or special
schools intended primarily for pupils with an IQ below 50.
</P>
<P>
   According to a research study published by the European Roma
Rights Center, a human rights organization based in Budapest,
Hungary, the Czech educational system shows signs of widespread
segregation and discrimination against Gypsies.
</P>
<P>
   The study shows that a Gypsy child is at least 15 times more
likely to be labeled mentally retarded than a Czech pupil.
</P>
<P>
   Once transferred into the special schools, the students' chances
of further education are reduced to virtually zero. Special school
graduates are not eligible to enter high school, because of their
limited curriculum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gypsies sent to special school get the equivalent of an
educational death sentence,'' said James Goldston, the Budapest
Center's legal director.
</P>
<P>
   Some parents are beginning to speak up. On June 15, 12 Gypsy
families filed a complaint with the Czech Constitutional Court to
challenge their children's segregation in special schools.
</P>
<P>
   They also filed a lawsuit against the regional education board
in Ostrava, a drab industrial region in the north of the Czech
Republic that has become the site of frequent racist incidents.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Debbie Winterbourne, a lawyer for the
Budapest-based Roma center, said that her organization planned to
file a complaint at the European Court of Human Rights in
Strasbourg, France, later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Class action does not exist under Czech jurisdiction. But local
lawyers, activists and the Budapest-based center all hope that the
case might benefit all Gypsies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have other children and this can happen to any of them,''
said Berta Cervenakova, one of the 12 plaintiffs. ``And I am not
fighting just for my kids. I do this for everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Her daughter Nikol, 10, was transferred last year to a special
school despite a report card that shows her grades were sufficient
for normal education.
</P>
<P>
   Ninety-two percent of her current classmates in the special
school are Gypsy.
</P>
<P>
   The parents demand formal acknowledgment from the Czech
government that they were denied equal opportunity in education and
that they have been victims of racial discrimination and
segregation, which violates Czech as well as international law.
They also request compensatory education for their children.
</P>
<P>
   Days after the lawsuit was filed, representatives of the
regional education board invited Mrs. Cervenakova and the other
parents to take their children back to a regular elementary school.
</P>
<P>
   A written statement from the Education Ministry asserts that the
charges of segregation and racial discrimination are unfounded
since children can be transferred to special schools only with
parental consent.
</P>
<P>
   The report by the Budapest center suggests that parents are
often actively persuaded by teachers and psychologists into signing
the transfer to a special school without understanding the possible
consequences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parental consent is a red herring, an attempt to blame the
victims for their suffering,'' Goldston said.
</P>
<P>
   Gypsy parents who may have been through a special school say
they find it hard to resist the authorities. Some even welcome the
move, saying their children are less likely to be taunted by
non-Gypsy pupils.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what it's like when your child comes home crying
without a cap every single day, and it's freezing outside?'' Mrs.
Cervenakova said. ``The kids were calling Nikol `dirty Gypsy' and
the teacher was just putting more pressure on her. She was scared
to go there.''
</P>
<P>
   But special schools do not necessarily shield Gypsy children
from racist abuse. Mrs. Hejkrlikova described a recent incident.
</P>
<P>
   In March, a special school teacher ordered two 9-year-old Gypsy
boys to strip naked before their Czech classmates. She searched
them for 50 crowns, the equivalent of $1.40, she assumed they had
stolen, Mrs. Hejkrlikova said. Gypsies had to complain many times
before the education board investigated and finally gave her a
verbal reprimand.
</P>
<P>
   In a report on protection of national minorities, submitted to
the Council of Europe this year, the Czech government noted that
the public, as well as many police officers and other
law-enforcement officials, often play down racist incidents,
leaving offenders either unpunished or with light sentences.
</P>
<P>
   The level of violence against Gypsies in the Czech Republic, and
neighboring Slovakia, has already set off several waves of highly
publicized immigration to Canada, France, Britain and, most
recently, Finland, where 100 Czech Gypsies are awaiting word on
whether they will be granted asylum.
</P>
<P>
   The latest example of trouble came in the northern town of Most,
where the local Gypsy leadership this month said that its
population was ``seriously jeopardized by violent attacks by
skinheads'' who it said ``increasingly terrorize them and attack
their homes at night.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
