<DOCNO> NYT19990724.0127 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-24 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2651 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PATIENTS25-COX     07-24 1843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATIENTS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Patients set better treatment by HMOs as top priority
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ It took seven months of experimentation and
exasperation for Bob Montgomery to find the right combination of
medicines to control his Parkinson's disease. Which ones would
work? How much? When?
</P>
<P>
   ``And you've got no idea of the frustration,'' he said. ``Can
you imagine being out on a golf course with three of your friends,
and all of a sudden you medication wears off? I'd have my left hand
on the golf club, and when I tried to put my right hand on it, I
couldn't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery thinks the world of his local neurologist. That
doctor had helped him regulate his medication. But Parkinson's is a
complicated disease, and before he joined his HMO, Montgomery saw a
subspecialist at the Ohio State University Parkinson's center known
as one of the best in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Now he'd like to see them both, the Columbus doctor no more than
once or twice a year. But the Columbus doctor isn't part of his
HMO's local network, so Montgomery has to pay that bill himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying I shouldn't pay more to see someone who's out
of the network,'' said Montgomery, who's otherwise healthy at 67.
``But I shouldn't be denied access to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Like a majority of Americans, Montgomery thinks HMO members need
some government protection to keep their health plans from making
too many decisions that are more pleasing to accountants than to
physicians. But when the U.S. Senate passed its
Republican-sponsored ``Patients' Bill of Rights Plus'' 10 days ago,
consumer advocates and physicians' organizations harshly criticized
the bill for not living up to its title.
</P>
<P>
   House legislation on health plans is still in committees, and
President Clinton has promised to veto the Senate version.
</P>
<P>
   Access to disease-focused specialists, rarely granted by any
HMO, was one of several rights missing from the Senate bill. The
most publicized exclusion was the right to sue an HMO that doesn't
pay for services a doctor recommends, but also omitted were an
enforceable independent review process and prohibitions against
punishing a doctor for advocating on his patient's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, that happens, said a Montgomery County doctor who told an
HMO its member had too much pain and not enough blood pressure to
be sent home from the hospital. The HMO responded that the doctor's
standing in its network would have to be re-evaluated if the
patient were not sent home, which is why the doctor asked not to be
identified.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate bill included some provisions hardly anyone beefed
about. It protected most Americans from losing health coverage
because their genes signal future diseases. It also made health
plan premiums fully tax deductible for the self-employed, and
long-term care insurance tax deductible when an employer doesn't
subsidize.
</P>
<P>
   Americans want stronger protections from health plans than were
passed by the Senate, polls indicate. Kaiser Family Foundation
surveys have been steady for the past two years on their support
for the rights to file HMO malpractice suits, to have complaints
reviewed independently and to thorough coverage of specialists'
care. In April's survey, released last week, the results showed 70
percent in favor of the right to sue, 83 percent for reviews and 77
percent for specialists.
</P>
<P>
   The figures tend to drop at least 20 points when people are
asked how they'd feel if it made their annual premium $200 higher,
but civil liability was still favored by a 49 percent plurality,
and the review and specialist stipulations still had majorities
more than 55 percent.
</P>
<P>
   More generally, the Kaiser Foundation found that five out of
every eight managed care members are at least somewhat worried
their plans would care more about cost than quality if they were
sick, and the August issue of Consumer Reports suggests they're
right to worry. In its poll of 19,000 HMO members, CR found only
one-third of those who were ill were very or completely satisfied
with their plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the insurance companies are taking advantage of the
public,'' said Montgomery, a longtime insurance agent whose sons
now run Montgomery Insurance and Investment Agency. ``They do it by
making the rules and regulations so strict and not paying claims
when they're supposed to. It's the big insurance company and little
you, so a lot of people will give up.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you're not going to get any help from the government,
because the insurance companies have got the politicians in their
hip pockets.''
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocates were just slightly more diplomatic after the
Senate passed its bill, which executive director Ron Pollack of
Families USA called, ``insurance industry protections, not patient
protections.''
</P>
<P>
   Consumer Reports likened the status of health care information
to that of information on products 30 years ago, before labels
divulged the nutritional content of food, energy efficiency of
appliances and plain-English costs of everything from groceries to
credit.
</P>
<P>
   Even the health insurance industry's gloating after the Senate
vote was about its media blitz opposing extensive reforms, and not
about any business practices that made those reforms unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Chamber of Commerce, representing business people who
aligned with the insurance industry, called the limited reforms
``victories for business, the economy and the fight to reduce the
rising number of uninsured in America.'' An Ohio Republican
congressional aide said the broader Democratic-sponsored reforms
would have had a ``disastrous effect'' on working people by driving
up premiums and forcing employers to drop coverage.
</P>
<P>
   But the government watchdog organization Public Citizen said the
right to sue an HMO would have cost a typical health plan less than
60 percent of what at least one of them pays its top five
executives, based on Congressional Budget Office estimates. Public
Citizen said health plans spent $37.5 million lobbying Congress in
1997 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes me absolutely furious that this was defeated because
of politics,'' said Kathy Gerding of Centerville. ``We need to be
able to sue health plans. The way it is now, I can't even get them
to return a phone call about my 7-month-old baby.''
</P>
<P>
   Since she sent her first letter to Anthem Blue Cross and Blue
Shield on April 25, Gerding said she hasn't been able to get claim
denials in writing and had her phone calls returned only once. That
was the morning after she was on television celebrating the passage
in committee of Ohio House Bill 218, which would require health
plans to pay for any medically life-sustaining infant formula
prescribed by a doctor. Her daughter cannot tolerate milk, soy or
protein.
</P>
<P>
   Few health plans cover those special formulas, although Gerding
says welfare recipients on Medicaid have that coverage. The plans
are only carrying out limitations imposed by employers who pay most
of the premiums, say officials at both Anthem and United Health
Care, the other dominant local HMO. But Gerding and consumer
advocates at least want someone other than the HMOs, with their
incentive not to spend money, interpreting what is and is not
medically needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we sue too much in this country,'' Gerding said. ``But
if that possibility exists, it will make them say, `You are a
customer. We are going to take care of you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, HMOs are ``basically responsive only to their
stockholders,'' said Dr. Richard Reiling, a Kettering surgeon who
has withdrawn his longtime Republican support over the issue.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats' proposals probably would have been too
restrictive, said Dr. Norman Schneiderman, who directs Miami Valley
Hospital's emergency and trauma center. But he said patients need
more protection than the Senate passed ``because there are some
managed care plans that really are not going to do the right thing
unless you're forced to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   He called it typically Washingtonian that Senate Majority Leader
Trent Lott (R-Miss.) squelched a request to let a bipartisan group
of moderate senators come up with a compromise. ``I really feel the
leaders in this country are more interested in how they look to
their constituents than doing the right thing for the country,''
Schneiderman said.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting Senate bill was a collection of partial
concessions to consumer demand that will ``actually do more harm
than good,'' said Adrienne Hahn, Consumers Union's legislative
counsel. For example, according to consumer and medical groups:
</P>
<P>
   _ It provides for independent review of HMO coverage decisions,
but the review boards are paid and chosen by HMOs and an HMO risks
no more than a $10,000 fine by refusing to comply with the board's
decision _ which might be that the HMO must pay for a $30,000
surgery. Hahn said the provision undermines 18 states' laws that
require review by boards fully independent of HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   _ It covers the 48 million Americans in employer-funded health
plans exempt from state laws, but most other provisions don't apply
to the 113 million other Americans in health plans.
</P>
<P>
   _ It requires HMOs to cover all cases that reasonable people
would call an emergency, but it doesn't limit co-payments and
doesn't guarantee coverage after the patient's life is out of
danger.
</P>
<P>
   _ It guarantees access to experimental treatments for cancer
patients, but not for anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   _ It assures patients who are pregnant, institutionalized or in
the middle of a treatment of keeping their doctors even if they
leave the HMO's network, but only for 90 days.
</P>
<P>
   _ It sets minimum hospital stays for mastectomy patients, but
keeps most determinations of medical necessity in the hands of
HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   _ It doesn't allow HMOs to forbid doctors from discussing all
their health options with patients, but it doesn't keep HMOs from
punishing doctors and other professionals for sticking up for their
patients or going public with unsafe practices. Nor does it curb
financial incentives to doctors for seeing more patients,
prescribing fewer drugs and making fewer referrals.
</P>
<P>
   _ It requires access to specialists ``in a timely matter'' but
doesn't stipulate how specialized or convenient those doctors must
be.
</P>
<P>
   Even timely access would be an improvement for many, according
to research by the U.S. Agency for Health Care Policy and Research.
Nearly a quarter of patients in California HMOs ``had difficulty
getting referrals to specialty care,'' said the report last week in
the American Medical Association journal JAMA. And the Robert Wood
Johnson Foundation recently announced its finding that since 1992,
newly graduated specialists have been drifting away from areas
where HMOs are prevalent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure those politicians would feel differently if they had
somebody in their families who's affected by a life-threatening
disease,'' Gerding said. ``But until they do, they just don't get
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
