<HEADER>
A2652 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-USFRANCHISE25-COX     07-24 1576
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-USFRANCHISE25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CEO builds hotel franchiser into major player
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Mike Leven used to be unhappy during the day but slept
like a baby at night.
</P>
<P>
   That was when he was the No. 2 person at Holiday Inn Worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Today that's changed. As president of one of the nation's
fastest-growing hotel companies, Leven is much happier during the
day but often has restless nights.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew that no matter what I did, the company would survive
and go on. I was just a cog in the wheel,'' said Leven, who left
Holiday Inn in 1995 to co-found Atlanta-based US Franchise Systems,
a hotel franchise company. ``(Now) I'm personally responsible for
every person here. At the end of the day, you can't walk away from
this.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why Leven, USFS president and chief executive officer,
sometimes wakes up in the early morning hours musing over such
things as whether earnings will meet analysts' expectations or how
hotels are performing. His company has emerged from its first two
years of red ink and is rapidly expanding, with more than 1,006
properties open or in development.
</P>
<P>
   The company was recently ranked 10th among the nation's largest
hotel franchise companies with its Microtel Inn &AMP; Suites, Hawthorn
Suites and Best Inns &AMP; Suites brands. Revenue has more than doubled
since 1997, to $10.6 million in 1998. US Franchise went public at
$13.50 a share in October 1996 and reached a 52-week high of $23.25
last month. The company reported its first profit in the third
quarter of 1998, a quarter ahead of projections.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're ramping up the profit curve very rapidly,'' said John
Rohs, an analyst with Schroder Securities in New York.
Additionally, ``small-growth companies have come back into style.
They're no longer the scourge of the earth.''
</P>
<P>
   Accidental hotel executive
</P>
<P>
   The 61-year-old, silver-haired Leven is credited with much of
the company's success. Described as gregarious, witty and sometimes
``emotional,'' Leven has a laid-back style around the office. Most
employees refer to him by his first name, and he often forgoes a
tie. Two of his three sons work for the company.
</P>
<P>
   To get some idea of the atmosphere around USFS, visitors need go
no farther than the front office. There, in a waist-high cage, sits
Repete, a snow-white, 20-pound rabbit.
</P>
<P>
   Not your usual office furnishing, Repete was once used in an
advertising campaign when the company touted that it was
``rabbitly'' expanding and was an example of ``procreation at its
finest.''
</P>
<P>
   But there's another side to Leven. In his second-floor office in
13 Corporate Square off Buford Highway, one wall is heavily
decorated with golf memorabilia and plaques. Opposite his desk is
his ``philosophy wall,'' which includes a Norman Rockwell poster
depicting diverse people of the world. One of his prized
possessions is a framed selection of notes Leven once wrote to
employees when he was an executive at Days Inn. Examples include:
``I am very alarmed,'' ``Great way to lose a bonus'' and ``Please
change immediately and advise the customer, `Sorry, we're stupid.'
''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think one of Mike's stronger suits is clearly his sales
ability,'' said Mark Woodworth, a vice president at PKF Consulting
in Atlanta. ``My take is that he has always been very good at
understanding what people want and delivering the product.''
</P>
<P>
   Leven grew up in Boston's Mattapan section. He was an only
child, the son of a traveling salesman for a retail paint and
hardware company. His mother was a secretary.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't poor, but everything that came in went out,''
recalled Leven. Early on, he was encouraged to be a lawyer, and he
imagined himself as the next Clarence Darrow. After graduating from
Tufts University, he was awarded a scholarship to the University of
Chicago's law school, but he left after one semester ``unhappy,
lonely and disappointing my parents and grandparents.''
</P>
<P>
   He enrolled in Boston University, where he earned a degree in
public relations and communications. Unable to land a job, he
became a social worker. By then he was engaged to Andrea Aronson,
and social work just didn't bring in enough money for a young
family. Thus began his career in the lodging industry. Leven heard
about a sales job at the Roosevelt Hotel in New York for $98 a
week. At the time, Leven had stayed in a hotel only once in his
life and had never eaten in a hotel restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at myself as a businessman by default,'' said Leven.
``Still today, I don't think of myself as a great business guy. I
think I'm OK. I don't think I'm really tough enough, although I'm
pleased with what I have accomplished.''
</P>
<P>
   Later he took positions of increasing responsibility at Sonesta
Hotels and Dunfey Family Hotels. He made his greatest marks at Days
Inn of America and Holiday Inn Worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   He served as president of then Atlanta-based Days Inn from 1985
to 1990, leading the company through a reorganization that resulted
in its growth from a 225-unit regional chain into more than 1,000
hotels open and 400 more under franchise agreement.
</P>
<P>
   He also made a mark by initiating special efforts to hire older
workers, people with disabilities and the homeless.
</P>
<P>
   It was while he was at Days Inn that he started a diversity
program to attract Asian-American franchisees. In fact, Leven
wanted to know so much about the culture that he took his family to
India. He was instrumental in the formation of the Asian-American
Hotel Owners Association.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving Days Inn, Leven joined another hotel giant,
Holiday Inn Worldwide, which had been acquired by British-based
Bass PLC and later became Bass Hotels &AMP; Resorts. There he was
instrumental in the launch and growth of Holiday Inn Express, now
an industry success story. During his five-year reign, the new
brand grew to 330 properties, with a backlog of nearly 500 more.
</P>
<P>
   By his own admission, Leven found it difficult to work for his
new overseas employers. ``I was close enough to the top to see how
things worked,'' he said. ``I have a lot more empathy for the
Founding Fathers of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Becoming an entrepreneur
</P>
<P>
   He decided to leave the company in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found that in a big company, there's a tendency to
dehumanize the business,'' he said. ``Companies that are larger
lose their souls to become totally numbers-driven.''
</P>
<P>
   Leven was pondering his next move when his nephew, Neal Aronson,
then a principal at the New York investment firm Odyssey Partners
suggested that he strike out on his own. The idea was heartily
backed by a longtime friend and golf partner, Home Depot co-founder
and Chairman Bernie Marcus.
</P>
<P>
   Like Marcus, Leven is very active in community organizations. He
has worked with the Atlanta Jewish Federation and is a trustee of
the American Jewish Committee's Atlanta Chapter.
</P>
<P>
   Leven took the chance, and although he has stumbled at times, he
has never taken a fall. In 1995, he and Aronson formed USFS after
raising $17 million. They bought the exclusive worldwide
franchising rights to the Microtel chain.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of potential for new construction within the
economy-limited service segment of the lodging industry,'' said
PKF's Woodworth. While there were budget hotels that targeted the
same market, many were in poor condition and very old. The
company's new Microtel brand appealed to travelers on a budget.
Leven calls them ``the Wal-Mart customer.''
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, franchise owners of hotels _ his primary customers
_ liked the idea that every Microtel would be in a new building and
would be held to high maintenance standards. Uniform quality
standards are one of the most important factors in franchise
success.
</P>
<P>
   More expansion was on the way. In early 1996, USFS leased the
franchise rights to Hawthorn Suites, an extended-stay hotel chain.
It would later acquire full ownership.
</P>
<P>
   The first big test for the company came in October 1996 when
Leven and Aronson took the company public in an IPO of 2.3 million
shares at $13.50 a share, raising $22 million.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998 the company acquired the exclusive worldwide franchising
rights to Best Inns &AMP; Suites, a midlevel economy brand. A second
public offering followed, raising $40 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last year or so they have been able to build up a real
head of steam,'' said Schroder Securities' Rohs, who notes that
many hotel stocks have been out of favor.
</P>
<P>
   Leven is still focused on expanding the business. The company
recently announced agreements to build hotels in Honduras and
several other Latin American countries. Over the next few years,
Leven hopes to add 200 properties annually for all three brands.
More acquisitions may also be on the horizon, which would
``accelerate earnings.''
</P>
<P>
   While hotels remain his priority, Leven said the company might
consider branching into other businesses that typically do well at
franchising, such as restaurants and car rental agencies.
</P>
<P>
   The company is moving so quickly, Leven may find it hard to
concentrate on four other additions to his family _ his
grandchildren. A set of triplets and a granddaughter were all born
within the last few months.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal is to develop a company with $100 million of
free-and-clear cash flow and a billion in value,'' he said. ``And,
if I'm not too old, I may go for the second billion.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
