<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-24 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2656 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANDERSON-COLUMN-N     07-24 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: IS CLEMENS NOW OVERANALYZING CLEMENS? 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Yankees keep waiting for Roger Clemens to be the
real Roger Clemens _ the five-time Cy Young Award winner, the
American League's dominant pitcher, the barrel-chested right-hander
whose 20 strikeouts in a game share the major league record with
the Cubs' Kerry Wood, now recuperating from arm surgery. But it's
as if a stranger is impersonating Roger Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   In 17 starts, his won-lost record is a deceptive 9-4 and his
earned run average is a shaky 4.90. If it were at that altitude at
the end of the season, it would be the highest in his 16 years in
the big leagues.
</P>
<P>
   At his best, he often had three times as many strikeouts as
bases on balls (271 to 88 a year ago with Toronto, for example) but
this season his ratio is much weaker: only 97 strikeouts to 51
walks. He has invariably allowed fewer hits than innings worked
(only 169 hits in 234 2/3 innings a year ago), but this season his
ratio is wobbly: 113 hits in 101 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll keep grinding,'' he was saying now in the Yankee
clubhouse. ``If it came easy, it wouldn't be fun.''
</P>
<P>
   For most of Clemens' career with the Red Sox and the Blue Jays,
it always came easy, or he made it look easy. Before this season,
his 3,153 strikeouts ranked ninth on the career list, his 93 games
with 10 or more strikeouts were fourth, his six ERA titles were
second, his 233 victories were the most of any active pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe all that success is why, as he awaits Sunday's start
against the Indians at Yankee Stadium, he might be thinking too
much about his struggle to be the real Roger Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to see not so much analysis between games, analysis
by himself,'' said Joe Torre, the Yankee manager. ``He's trying so
hard to direct everything _ where this pitch has to go, where that
pitch has to go. He busts himself up. Just let it fly.''
</P>
<P>
   Paralysis by analysis. It can happen to any athlete in any sport
when too much thinking is involved. With a pitcher, it can lead to
his aiming the ball instead of just letting it fly, of letting the
batter worry about it instead of the pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``But all that analysis,'' Torre was quick to add, ``is what
made Roger so good. And there's a big pride factor.''
</P>
<P>
   That pride is why Clemens, understandably, would want to show
the Yankees why he has been the power pitcher of the '90s, why he
was worth being acquired in a trade for David Wells, the Yankees'
best pitcher a year ago in their winning 125 games and the World
Series, why he is expected to help them win another World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the tradition here,'' he said. ``I'm constantly
reminded of it, like the Yogi Berra Day last Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clemens doesn't buy Torre's big-pride theory that he's
trying too hard to justify his $8.1 million salary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't need to prove myself,'' he said. ``I pretty much had
my way the last two years in Toronto.''
</P>
<P>
   In his two Cy Young Award seasons with the Blue Jays, Clemens
was 21-7 and 2.05 ERA in 1997, 20-6 and 2.65 last year. But even
though the radar guns still clock his fastball in the low 90s,
he'll be 37 on Aug. 4. Maybe this is just the beginning of the end.
</P>
<P>
   He's got to prove that he hasn't reverted to his mediocre
numbers over his last four seasons with the Red Sox: an overall
40-39 with an overall 3.75 ERA, including a 10-13 record with a
3.63 ERA before bidding Boston adieu for free agency.
</P>
<P>
   In two of those last four Red Sox seasons he was on the disabled
list, in 1995 with a strained muscle behind his right shoulder, in
1993 with a strained groin muscle and a sore pitching elbow. And
maybe a damaged left hamstring contributed to his struggle this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``My hammy took a little longer to heal,'' he acknowledged,
``because I pitched with it.''
</P>
<P>
   And maybe Clemens' pitching with a damaged hamstring proves
Torre's big-pride theory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coney has that same big pride,'' Torre said, referring to the
right-hander David Cone, ``but he's understated about it. He's also
done it in more big games, playoff games, World Series games. And
he had to learn to do it without his fastball.''
</P>
<P>
   Cone also learned to do it under the New York microscope at an
early age, notably with his 20-3 record in his second of six
seasons with the Mets before moving on to Kansas City, to Toronto
and eventually to the Yankees late in the 1995 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``And if you can make it here,'' Joe Torre said, smiling, ``you
can make it anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his 9-4 won-lost record, Roger Clemens hasn't yet made
it in New York, but maybe he will if he stops analyzing why he
hasn't.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
