<HEADER>
A2658 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VENEZUELA-CONSTITUTIO     07-24 1330
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENEZUELA-CONSTITUTION-ART-930&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENEZUELAN LEADER'S PUSH FOR NEW CHARTER CALLED A POWER GRAB 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By LARRY ROHTER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela _ The fate of South America's
longest-running, if turbulent, democracy hangs in the balance in
the vote on Sunday to select delegates to write a new constitution
_ the 27th in Venezuela's history, although the first since 1961.
</P>
<P>
   But that may be the only point on which President Hugo Chavez
and his opponents agree.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez maintains that only a new charter will enable him to
carry out the ``peaceful social revolution'' he promised in his
successful presidential campaign last year.
</P>
<P>
   His critics contend that the election of the 131 members of the
National Constituent Assembly is their last chance to prevent
Venezuela, the largest foreign supplier of oil to the United States
in recent years, from slipping into what they see as a coming
one-man dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
   ``On paper, this is a laudable initiative, an effort to get
representatives of the people together to discuss where we have
failed and to rethink who we are,'' said Jorge Olavarria, a lawyer
and historian who was an early political adviser to Chavez but who
has now broken with the president and is running for an assembly
seat on an anti-Chavez slate. ``But in reality, it is a plan for
Chavez to carry out a coup under legal cover.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the changes that Chavez, a 45-year-old former army colonel
who organized an unsuccessful coup attempt in 1992, wants enshrined
in a new constitution is the right to succeed himself in office.
When sworn in early in February, he contemptuously described the
current 1961 constitution as ``moribund,'' and on repeated
occasions he has acted as if the charter had already been revoked
and his own powers expanded.
</P>
<P>
   This month, for instance, Chavez promoted 34 military officers
who had been part of his 1992 uprising, defying a warning by the
Senate that his action was unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   He has also made Gen. Lucas Rincon his chief of staff, a move
that opposition leaders said also violates a law prohibiting active
duty soldiers from holding such posts.
</P>
<P>
   And he tried to put military officers in charge of the police,
provoking threats of resignations there.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision is mine,'' Chavez said in brushing aside the
disapproval of the Senate, whose powers of advice and consent are
even more extensive than those of its American counterpart. ``I am
commander in chief of the armed forces.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Chavez has bypassed government ministries and put
some 70,000 soldiers to work on huge public works projects,
building schools and hospitals, providing free medical services and
selling food to the poor below market cost. Beginning in September,
the government also intends to send soldiers into the schools to
teach military doctrine to students.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chavez's ultimate goal is to remain in power, converting the
traditional political class into a scapegoat and making the armed
forces his political party,'' said Anibal Romero, author of
``Security, Defense and Democracy in Venezuela,'' and other books.
``Some of the things he is doing, such as his flirtation with Fidel
Castro, bother them, but they like the fact that he is
incorporating them into his government and giving them civilian
posts.''
</P>
<P>
   The election, which will take Venezuelans to the polls for the
fourth time in less than a year, is nominally nonpartisan. But the
campaign has turned into a bare-knuckles display of political
brinkmanship, with Chavez, who enjoys an 80 percent approval rating
in the latest polls, inevitably at the center of the fray.
</P>
<P>
   When the National Electoral Council, for instance, ruled that
Chavez could not actively campaign for candidates from his own
party, he was defiant.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they want to take me to jail, let them come for me,'' he
said. ``Here I am.''
</P>
<P>
   But when the same body recently barred his weekly radio and
television shows until after the vote, his response was to comply
with the letter of the verdict, though not the spirit.
</P>
<P>
   He sent aides to substitute for him at the radio program last
Sunday and then called in as a guest. The president then
circumvented the ban on his television show by using his powers as
head of state to convoke a national network for a speech that all
stations were obliged to carry.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can bind me with 1,000 chains, but Hugo Chavez will keep
on talking,'' he said during the telephone call to the radio
program. Fined the equivalent of $7,700 by the tribunal because of
the violations, Chavez has set up stands on the street to collect
donations from supporters to pay the penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must help Chavez root out the corruption that is eating
away at this country,'' Pedro Rafael Hernandez Ochoa, a supporter
of the president, said Thursday night at a ceremony at which money
was delivered to Chavez at the Presidential Palace to pay the fine.
``The rotten political elite is blocking his way, and only with a
new Magna Carta can he make the changes we need to make Venezuela a
true democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbidden by law from being a candidate himself, Chavez has
urged his wife, Marisabel, a radio broadcaster with no previous
political experience, to run as his standard-bearer. In addition,
five members of his Cabinet resigned to run for assembly seats,
joining former President Carlos Andres Perez, against whom the 1992
coup was directed, and lawyers, economists, athletes, journalists
and even an astrologer among the 1,059 candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The president is also facing an investigation into whether he
has misused state funds to promote his candidates. He has described
that effort as part of a politically motivated conspiracy to weaken
his fight ``against the tyranny of corruption and the elites that
destroyed this country.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Eduardo Roche, the nation's comptroller general, retorted: ``The
president can be certain that insults and falsehoods do not
frighten me. He must understand that this office will never be
subservient.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the passions aroused by the issues, and the country's
turbulent history of military strongmen and coups before the 1961
constitution, the campaign his been generally peaceful.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, though, four people in white hoods interrupted a
university forum featuring Alberto Franceschi, an outspoken
opposition leader who is expected to be the principal anti-Chavez
spokesman in the assembly, and detonated a series of bombs.
</P>
<P>
   No one was injured in the incident, which emptied the
auditorium. But Franceschi described the episode as ``a humiliating
display of Chavez-style democracy,'' intended to ``silence the
voice of the opposition.''
</P>
<P>
   There are persistent reports that Chavez's ruling coalition, the
Patriotic Pole, has agreed that the top vote-getter will be made
president of the assembly, with powers to control the agenda and
pace of work.
</P>
<P>
   In a television interview last week, Mrs. Chavez, who polls
indicate may win that distinction, said she was unaware of such an
arrangement, but added, ``I feel prepared and would accept the
challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the result, further conflict is expected. Despite
rulings by the Supreme Court to the contrary, Chavez has said the
assembly will have the power to dissolve Congress and the courts
and assume their powers until a new charter is approved, indicating
on several occasions that he wants it to do precisely that.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Constituent Assembly is going to be the moment of truth
for Chavez,'' said Anibal Romero, who is a professor of political
science at Simon Bolivar University here. ``It is going to force
him to define a path, and I believe that path is going to be one of
military populism and anti-imperialism.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
