<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, July 25, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   The air will become noticeably drier Sunday across the Northeast
as slightly cooler air arrives on breezes from the northwest. Low
pressure near Montreal will steer a cold front off the New England
coast by mid-afternoon. Showers and a few thunderstorms will dampen
the interior Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   As winds begin to blow from the northwest in the Middle Atlantic
region, the humidity will drop, the haze will lift, but the air
will remain quite hot. Readings will reach between 95 and 100
degrees in parts of Virginia and the eastern Carolinas. Isolated
thunder is expected along the shore and in the southern
Appalachians.
</P>
<P>
   Along the perimeter of very sultry air, strong thunderstorms
will develop from the Carolina coast across the Deep South and into
eastern Texas. There will be a concentration of storms at the Gulf
Coast due to active sea breezes.
</P>
<P>
   Small high pressure located near Chicago will sponsor sunshine
and rather hot but moderately humid air in the Middle West and Ohio
Valley. A torrid flow from the south will interact with an
approaching front to trigger a cluster of heavy thunderstorms in
eastern South Dakota. Moisture from the Southwest monsoon will
initiate more afternoon storms from southern Arizona to central
Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Pleasantly cool air will spread from the Pacific Northwest into
the northern Rockies. Clouds will dominate west of the Cascades in
Washington. Developing offshore breezes in northern California will
bring sunny skies to the Coast. The Southwest will be hot and a bit
more humid in the deserts.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: PAST THE PEAK
</P>
<P>
   The maximum average daily temperature for the year in New York,
78 degrees, occurs Sunday and Monday. Interestingly, this does not
coincide with the maximum amount of daylight, which was on June 21,
the first day of summer. The lag exists for two reasons. First, the
sun's energy takes a long time to completely remove winter's chill
throughout the atmosphere. Second, the oceans also take a long time
to warm, thus, any wind blowing off the water cools the coast until
the waters become warm. After Monday, the average temperature will
start its steady drop to winter's lowest point in January.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
