<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-24 14:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2667 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUDY-SOUTH25-COX     07-24 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUDY-SOUTH25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Symbolic politics: Giuliani set to visit Clinton hometown
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's a lunch in Little Rock, Ark., where the best
stuff being served up doesn't appear on the menu.
</P>
<P>
   When New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani sits down Tuesday with
big-name locals at a $500-a-head fund-raiser at the Capital Hotel,
it will be political chutzpah not rubber chicken that will be the
real bill of fare.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like it's more symbolic than anything,'' said Steven
Neuse, head of the University of Arkansas' political science
department.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you hadn't already heard about Giuliani's Southern swing
_ after Arkansas, he heads Wednesday to Alabama for three private
fund-raisers _ nearly everyone knows that he's the presumed likely
Republican candidate in the 2000 U.S. Senate race in New York. His
presumed Democratic opponent? First lady and former Little Rock
resident Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   By now, too, most Arkansans have figured out the real reason for
this brief visit by the tough-talking man known simply as ``Rudy''
to most New Yorkers. The election may be 16 months off, the
electorate 1,500 miles away. The $30,000 to $35,000 expected to be
raised by Tuesday's lunch may barely buy a steak dinner in
Giuliani's Manhattan, let alone significantly affect campaign
coffers.
</P>
<P>
   But it's never too early to pound away at the ``Hillary as
carpetbagger'' theme.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's hilarious!'' Travis Lawrence, 29, the manager of New
York Air Brake Co. in Little Rock, said when told about Giuliani's
impending visit. ``It's kind of rubbing it in her face by coming to
her hometown. It's kind of like he's saying `I ain't got no
business being here' and `You ain't got no business being there'!''
</P>
<P>
   Officially, Giuliani's Southern sojourn has nothing to do with
rubbing anybody's face in anything, and everything to do with
allies' mutual backslapping.
</P>
<P>
   ``Primarily, the reason for the trip is to do the fund-raisers
and, obviously, to meet with business and political leaders in
Arkansas and Alabama,'' said Bruce Teitelbaum, executive director
of the mayor's Senate exploratory committee. ``People who've heard
about what he's done with New York (City), who think he's done a
great job there and think he'd do a great job in the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the chairman of the Alabama GOP had hoped to lure
Giuliani there for a party fund-raiser in the fall, but says a
private citizen ``jumped ahead of us'' by organizing Wednesday's
events in Huntsville, Birmingham and Tuscaloosa, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   All this fuss over a pro-choice Yankee?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people see Giuliani as a very successful big city
mayor,'' said Alabama party Chairman Winton Blount, adding that
only out-of-town business is keeping him from Wednesday's
fund-raisers. ``You only have to go to New York to not only listen
to New Yorkers talk about it, but to sense it and feel it and see
it. So I think he'll do OK.''
</P>
<P>
   The $1,000-per-couple Alabama events should raise ``over six
figures,'' Teitelbaum said. Still, there's no free lunch, as the
mayor may discover in Little Rock, where he'll meet first with his
luncheon co-sponsors and fellow Republicans, Gov. Mike Huckabee and
Lt. Gov. Winthrop P. Rockefeller.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a chance to show off Arkansas to the mayor of the
nation's largest city,'' Huckabee spokesman Rex Nelson practically
crowed, adding that the group might also check out the Old
Statehouse's museum.
</P>
<P>
   If it seems odd to think of Rudy even temporarily transplanted
from his normal milieu of crowded subways, cranky reporters and
careening bike messengers, Blount says it's just politics as usual.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money doesn't have any state borders,'' said Blount, whose
organization recently sent out a fund-raising letter proclaiming
``We must rid ourselves of the Clintons'' and invoking the first
lady's possible candidacy. ``The Clinton Administration will be
raising money from Hollywood and all the places that they raise
money from.''
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe it's just politics as usual in this highly unusual
race. The first book deal has already been signed to cover the
Clinton-Giuliani race _ and neither has officially entered yet.
Meanwhile, Giuliani could face a bloody primary battle against a
candidate backed by arch-enemy New York Republican Gov. George
Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   Is it any wonder, then, that Rudy might welcome this brief
respite in the kinder, gentler South? Or that Arkansans might be of
mixed-emotions about this whole slightly surreal situation?
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people say, `Oh, Hillary will be sensitive to us, it will
be like having a third senator from Arkansas','' said Arkansas
Democrat-Gazette columnist John Brummett, adding that others see
Giuliani as a ``mean-spirited'' former federal prosecutor who'll
open up all the old Clinton wounds for a huge press corps. ``You
hear `Oh my God, it's going to another case of international focus
on Arkansas-bashing'.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence, the air brake company manager, was more succinct.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just as backwards as it can be.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
