   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   ANIMAL-ALLIES _ WASHINGTON _ Cockroaches wearing backpacks and
elite troops of trained honeybees are among the recruits the
Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency is considering for
possible use in detecting land mines and chemical or biological
warfare agents. DARPA's year-old Controlled Biological Systems
Program is working on ways to use natural creatures or copy some of
their techniques to detect environmental hazards on the
battlefield. (Nesmith, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Eds: MOVED Wednesday. With photos.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CAMPAIGN _ WASHINGTON _ Despite his impeachment baggage,
President Clinton is still one of the most powerful political
weapons available to Democrats in the 2000 elections. And he's
obviously champing at the bit to hit the campaign trail. A look at
what Clinton can do to raise money and rally support for Vice
President Al Gore and congressional candidates _ including his
wife. (Deans and Shepard, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Eds: MOVED Thursday in (W) Washington and (p) politics
categories.
</P>
<P>
   ENCRYPTION _ WASHINGTON _ The House is heading for a showdown
over the issue of encryption software for computer data. The
government enforces strict export limits on the software for
national security reasons, but U.S. technology companies are
worried about losing the market to foreign firms who face no such
restrictions. Five different House committees are under orders to
finish their bills by Friday, and so far their approaches differ
widely. (Glass, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   Eds: MOVED in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL
</P>
<P>
   RUDY-SOUTH _ The New York Senate race grows even stranger this
week when Rudy Giuliani heads South for fund-raising stops in
Little Rock and later in the fiercely anti-Clinton territory of
Alabama. Is the South ready to become a player in the New York
Senate contest? (Vejnoska, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   COXNET FOCUS _ (EDS: This is the CoxNet FOCUS page for the
current week. This layout is now available.)
</P>
<P>
   CARIBBEAN-TRADE-$ADV25 _ SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic _ At
first glance, the proposed Caribbean Basin Parity Trade Initiative
winding its way through Congress looks like small beans. But the
measure, being pushed by Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla., as well as
President Clinton, merits attention for several reasons. First, the
region is the United States' sixth-largest export market. Second,
the measure would eliminate tariffs on a variety of items including
clothes and watches, meaning the prices for those items in U.S.
stores should go down. And the measure could boost economies in the
Caribbean, which would hopefully stem immigration that has
skyrocketed since last year's hurricanes. We look at the impact of
CBI on the average Joe, and in particular on states such as
Florida, Georgia and Texas. Measure should come up for passage by
mid-July. (Emling, Cox News Service) Moving in international and
financial categories. WITH GRAPHIC. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-ELECT _ MEXICO CITY _ The world's longest ruling party,
Mexico's Revolutionary Institutional Party, or PRI, could be facing
the most competitive presidential election ever in July 2000.
Mexico is creeping toward democracy, and elections are hotter than
ever thanks to a more vigilant press, the use of polls and more
transparent election systems and rules. The PRI, which still
controls most of Mexican political life, will be tested in July by
opposition candidates who have mustered unprecedented strength,
especially the brash Vicente Fox of Mexico's conservative
opposition. Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, on the left, has fallen behind in
polls but is still a likely contender. But first, four candidates
within the ruling PRI will battle for their party's nomination in
the party's first-ever primary in November. (Ferriss, Cox News
Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   With ELECT-BOX _ Poll data. (Ferriss, Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CAMPAIGN _ WASHINGTON _ Despite his impeachment baggage,
President Clinton is still one of the most powerful political
weapons available to Democrats in the 2000 elections. And he's
obviously champing at the bit to hit the campaign trail. A look at
what Clinton can do to raise money and rally support for Vice
President Al Gore and congressional candidates _ including his
wife. (Deans and Shepard, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Eds: MOVED Thursday in (W) Washington and (p) politics
categories.
</P>
<P>
   BUSHED _ AUSTIN, Texas _ As Gov. George W. Bush begins to
educate Americans on who he is and what he would do as president,
education will be on the top of the list. Texas is being touted as
a shining example of improvement, no small feat in the country's
second largest state, which used to rank near the bottom in most
academic indicators. Bush has made education a top priority, from
ending social promotion to increasing accountability and testing to
increasing state funding of public schools. But he's been unable to
deliver on vouchers, and some critics say he cannot take credit for
the recent rise. The seeds of Texas' success were sown in the
mid-1980s, with laws to create smaller classes, give more money to
poor school districts and increase academic standards. (Brooks,
Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   PATIENTS _ How do patients feel about the need for protecting
them from health plans? Includes Kaiser Family Foundation survey
from April, released this week, showing continuing strong support
for protection legislation. Overview of the issue. (Lamb, Dayton
Daily News) WITH PHOTOS. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   PATIENTS-ADVOCATE _ United's poor customer service in fighting
over a $550 bill has turned local consultant Jane Arntz into a
professional patients' advocate. (Lamb, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   PATIENTS-UNITED _ HMOs help some people in ways that
fee-for-service medical plans never did. Anthem has helped a woman
whose children have asthma, and United has helped a young man with
diabetes. (Lamb, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
