<HEADER>
A2670 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-GULAG-VISIT-AR     07-24 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-GULAG-VISIT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-PRISONER OF CHINA SEEKS INSIGHTS AT OLD GULAG SITE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Map is being
sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(jw) 
 By RUSSELL WORKING    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MAGADAN, Russia _ On the outskirts of town, a former Stalinist
prison stands behind a row of concrete slabs. Undaunted by warnings
from local residents who wish to remember Stalin's horrors but are
acutely aware that this is still state property, the
Chinese-American guest scrambled up the wall.
</P>
<P>
   The guest, Harry Wu, a former Chinese dissident, spent 19 years
in Maoist prisons that were modeled on the Soviet gulag system and
set up with the help of Russians. Now that he was visiting the
Russian city that was once the center of a sprawling archipelago of
sub-Arctic prison camps, he wanted a better look.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't go in there,'' cried Miron Etlis, a former prisoner
who was guiding Wu on a trip to a nearby monument to Stalin's
victims. ``That's military property.''
</P>
<P>
   Wu, 61, jumped off the wall into the yard.
</P>
<P>
   Wu is a research fellow at the Hoover Institute at Stanford
University and is active on behalf of Chinese political prisoners.
He visited Magadan, a city of 134,000, as it was commemorating the
60th anniversary of its incorporation at the height of Stalin's
purges and seven years after the Kolyma labor camps opened here.
</P>
<P>
   The anniversary came complete with oompah bands in the square
and cheerful drunks lurching down Lenin Prospect in the midnight
sun, apparently heedless of the tens of thousands of former
prisoners buried in the tundra around here _ some of the 2 million
or so who mined gold, silver, tin and uranium in the Magadan and
nearby Chukotka regions from 1932 to 1957.
</P>
<P>
   Hu flew in at his own expense to speak to a crowd of just 15 at
a historical conference held as part of the 60th anniversary
events. He has repeatedly returned to China to document prison
labor and the harvesting of organs from executed inmates, and said
he wanted to urge Russians both to treasure their nascent democracy
and the memory of Soviet repression.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to remove all the Lenin and Stalin statues and put up
gulag monuments,'' Wu said at one point, jabbing his finger at his
hosts. ``That's the only way to keep it from coming back.''
</P>
<P>
   Magadan residents, like Russians in general, are ambivalent
about how best to commemorate the legacy of state terror. On a hill
outside town, a monument to gulag victims looms like a giant head
from Easter Island.
</P>
<P>
   Yet a street and a school are named for Edward Berzin, the
director of Dalstroi, the state company that built the camps and
ran the mining enterprises, and his muscular bust stands on a
pedestal in front of city hall. Because he was purged in 1937,
officials have recast him as a gulag victim.
</P>
<P>
   Lyudmila Vronchina, a city librarian who helps former inmates
garner the documents necessary to apply for federal aid for
ex-prisoners, said the Berzin monument ``sends chills down my
spine.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a murderer,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Biryukov, a Magadan lawyer whose father was a camp
prisoner, has compiled a list of every one of the 11,000 people
documented to have been shot in Kolyma camps by the state security
organ, the N.K.V.D.
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of others died from disease, cold and
overwork. Biryukov has also begun researching the location of
graves and said some bodies were still partly preserved in the
permafrost.
</P>
<P>
   Wu had another idea: using the old prison as a gulag museum. The
property is now owned by the Russian military but partly occupied
by a scrap metal dealership.
</P>
<P>
   After jumping from the wall, Wu charged into the old prison,
yanking open doors and testing locks, trying to calculate how many
prisoners occupied each cell.
</P>
<P>
   The cells, whose walls have been knocked down, measured about 10
feet by 11 feet and were unlighted and unheated. Prisoners
sometimes froze to death overnight. Surviving prisoners would stack
the dead in the corner and eat their bread rations until the guards
noticed.
</P>
<P>
   ``So each cell was designed for 20 people,'' said Wu, pacing
about. Etlis, 71, who had found his way in through a gate, arrived
to hear this. ``Ha! I was in a cell like this in Kazakhstan and
there were 50 people,'' he said. Wu eventually concluded that up to
3,500 prisoners had been crammed into the building.
</P>
<P>
   After Wu had filmed every corner, the group filed out. But he
hung back, apparently pondering the prison's history, then beckoned
to a reporter and pointed out a 1930s-era padlock bolted to a jail
door.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get it off,'' Wu said. ``I want it.'' After efforts to pick it
with a pen failed, he said: ``Just break it. Break it with your
hands.'' The lock held. Disappointed, Wu walked out. Just such a
lock had hung on his own Chinese prison door.
</P>
<P>
   ``This,'' he said, ``was the lock produced by Lenin.''
</P>
</TEXT>
