<HEADER>
A2671 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PATIENTS-ADVOCATE25-C     07-24 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATIENTS-ADVOCATE25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HMO's rejection stiffens crusader's resolve
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ It wasn't just United HealthCare's refusal to pay
a $555 medical bill that turned Jane Boucher Arntz into a crusader
for patients' rights. What really got under her skin was her
impression that United seemed bent on doing whatever it took to
avoid paying that bill.
</P>
<P>
   She has letters from United that gave her the wrong phone number
for appealing the coverage denial and contradicted themselves in
explaining it. She has the sour aftertaste of what she called rude
customer-service representatives who seemed annoyed at being
bothered with her contention that stabbing abdominal pain
constituted an emergency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have we gotten so inhuman that it's all about money and,
`Don't care about healing people?''' Arntz asked. ``The group of
people I met were so cold: 'Forget her pain. We're fighting about
$500 here.' You get the feeling these people never had anyone in
their families who were sick.''
</P>
<P>
   Arntz' secondary insurer paid the claim without a quibble, but
the experience ``completely changed'' the focus of her career as a
national public speaker and president of Boucher Consultants.
</P>
<P>
   She has conferred with the staff of Sen. Orrin Hatch (R-Utah),
who sits on the subcommittee that oversees health insurance. He
shared her concern about the health care system's ``lack of
compassion'' and failure to cover certain medical services, so she
was disappointed when he voted with Senate Republicans against the
right to sue an HMO this month.
</P>
<P>
   Like many people unhappy about patient protections left out of
the Senate bill, Arntz said her health plan's callousness was at
least as upsetting as its stinginess.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked with countless people who feel helpless, depressed
and resigned because they do not know how to make the system
respond to their needs as it ought to,'' she said, including some
doctors and hospitals other than HMOs. ``I want to contribute to
the kind of health-care reform where the patient comes first.''
</P>
<P>
   Arntz, now 49, was giving a seminar in Asheville, N.C., on Oct.
18, 1996, when she felt a stabbing pain in her abdomen unlike any
she'd had with previously treated endometriosis. She went to a
nearby clinic, which sent her to a lab for diagnostic tests.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute would center largely around whether she should have
gone to a different treatment facility.
</P>
<P>
   ``United HealthCare always has the best medical interests of its
members in mind, including making sure the member receives the most
appropriate treatment at the appropriate setting,'' the company
said in a prepared statement, citing its policy against violating
the confidentiality of any specific member.
</P>
<P>
   In a city she didn't know and in pain she couldn't stand, Arntz
said she drove her rental car to the only place she had seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of reasons you can have pain in the abdomen,''
she said. ``A tumor. An irritable bowel. I thought I was having an
appendicitis attack or something like that.''
</P>
<P>
   She knew United's rules. She called its number for
preauthorization but couldn't get through. She said she learned
later United was having phone problems that day.
</P>
<P>
   All the tests were negative, and the pain eventually subsided.
Her Dayton specialist, to whom United had earlier referred her,
wrote on her behalf that the tests appeared to be a reasonable
response to her complaint, but the claim was denied.
</P>
<P>
   She called the phone number on the denial letter to appeal. In
her next four phone conversations, United representatives told her
she couldn't, could, couldn't and then could have an appeal
hearing.
</P>
<P>
   The day after her hearing, United's customer service supervisor
sent Arntz a letter saying the appeal was denied but she could call
a particular number if she had other questions. That number was
wrong, and connected her with a recorded message at NCR.
</P>
<P>
   After several more calls, Arntz reached the customer service
supervisor, who Arntz said was sarcastic and demeaning in refusing
to explain specifics of the denial and couldn't understand why
Arntz was upset about a little typo in the phone number.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may not be happy about the committee's decision, but it does
not give (the supervisor) the right to be rude,'' Arntz wrote in a
letter to David Shafer, then United's CEO in the Dayton office. A
vice president wrote back three weeks later apologizing ``for the
apparent confusion and frustration you experienced with our
customer service staff, although I feel it was unintended.''
</P>
<P>
   By appealing to the Ohio Department of Insurance, or ODI, Arntz
was able to learn United based its denial on the clinic's use of
two different dates, evidence that the clinic was not an
urgent-care center, the lack of preauthorization, the
inappropriateness of the tests for her diagnosis of ``acute
abdominal or pelvic pain,'' and United's not learning the situation
was an emergency ``until the hearing.''
</P>
<P>
   United also told ODI that when Arntz explained she was ``forced
to go outside the network,'' it suggested the trip to the clinic in
North Carolina ``was a planned visit.'' And it said her doctor's
reference to Arntz's proactive role in maintaining her health
``does not support the contention that this was an emergency
visit.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Arntz wants to be a voice for people with similar
experiences who are unable to speak up for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``On top of being sick,'' she said, ``you have to deal with the
psychological fear that they're not going to pay. Then you have to
deal with the stress of fighting something that's much bigger than
you are as an individual. Most people don't have the resources _
financial or emotional _ and they give up. I took it as far as I
could with United and I still lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Insurance is only part of her new mission, Arntz said. She also
is working on a Ph.D. in naturopathy, which emphasizes the body's
natural ability to heal itself, and she wants to speak and write
about the role that well-informed people can play in protecting or
retrieving their own good health. She wants ``to wake people up to
what their options are and even though their situation may look
impossible, to keep on keeping on.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
