<SLUG> BC-PATIENTS-UNITED25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    United HealthCare stresses education
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Chris Anderson was 19 last summer when he came
home not feeling so good. Thin and athletic, he had never really
been sick, but now he kept drinking water and couldn't quench his
thirst.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden, he was a diabetic and he was in the
hospital,'' said his mother, Linda.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson's HMO, United HealthCare, normally wants patients in
Anderson's condition out of the hospital in 24 to 48 hours, his
mother said. But his blood sugar levels kept fluctuating wildly,
and 48 hours weren't enough for the Mercy Medical Center staff in
Springfield to stabilize those levels and teach him all the ins and
outs a diabetes patient needs to know to keep the disease from
flaring up.
</P>
<P>
   No one from the HMO objected when Anderson stayed in the
hospital more than 72 hours. The next person to contact him from
United was its diabetes coordinator, offering to help however she
could and urging him to make prompt appointments with an eye doctor
and dentist to help avert common diabetic complications.
</P>
<P>
   Managed care was originally set up to reduce costs by decreasing
the need for medical service. Anderson's experience has been a
happy example.
</P>
<P>
   ``United HealthCare encourages all that education because if
diabetics control their blood sugar, they can avoid or delay any of
those horrible complications,'' Linda Anderson said. ``They
actually get it, that if they encourage people to take care of
themselves now, they'll save money in the long run.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's neat that a health plan gets that, instead of saying,
'Oh, no, we can't pay the $35 it would cost to get that education
class,' even though it might keep you from getting your leg
amputated sometime down the line.''
</P>
<P>
   Both United and Anthem Blue Cross and Blue Shield, which
dominate the Dayton-area HMO market, have several programs to help
members control various diseases. Besides diabetes, United has
programs for members with asthma and other lung diseases, heart
disease and back problems, along with increased rates of childhood
vaccinations, babies with acceptable birth weights and such
preventive screenings as mammograms.
</P>
<P>
   United has paid for Anderson's glucose monitor insulin pen for
injecting measured cartridges. ``They're convenience things,'' said
his mother, ``but they make it easier for a person to take control
of diabetes.'' Now with his recently approved insulin pump
providing regular doses through a small catheter, Anderson no
longer has to give himself three or four shots a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just have to change the batteries and the catheters,'' said
Anderson, who lives in Springfield and works in Dayton. ``There's
some things United Health is covering that I'm sure would never
have been covered under regular insurance.''
</P>
<P>
   It's an intricate regimen, keeping close track of everything he
eats, interrupting any exertion to make sure his blood sugar is
stable. All it took last fall was some over-the-counter cold
medicine to throw him out of whack. Who knew some of those drugs
were loaded with sugar?
</P>
<P>
   United hooked Anderson up with diabetes educator Tanya Evans,
who has since moved from Mercy to Children's Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything I know about diabetes, I learned from her,'' he
said. ``It's nice to know in case something does go wrong, I can
always get a hold of her.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson has had a good attitude about the disease, his mother
said, at least partly because ``they taught him not to be afraid of
it.'' To him, diabetes is just another job he has to do.
</P>
<P>
   He's still active athletically. He runs, works out, water skis.
``Nothing stops him,'' Linda said. Nothing except for the sheer
normalcy he has maintained in a life disrupted so suddenly.
</P>
<P>
   With all the time he spends at work, he said, ``I really don't
have as much time for sports as I used to.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
