<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COWBOY-JUNKIES25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cowboy Junkies glad to be on the road; bemused by attempts to
label sound
 &HT;    By Carol Simmons
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The Canadian-born band happily known as the
Cowboy Junkies makes music that eludes corralling.
</P>
<P>
   You just can't fence in this gang _ consisting of siblings
Michael, Margo and Peter Timmins plus Michael's childhood friend
Alan Anton _ with easy labels. The encyclopedic ``All Music'' guide
on the Web lists the band under the genre of rock, but describes
its style as ``Alternative Pop/Rock, Alternative Country-Rock,
Adult Alternative Pop/Rock.''
</P>
<P>
   Which pretty much means you've got to listen for yourself.
</P>
<P>
   It also means a description that may be true for one particular
song or album gets applied over and over again, whether or not it
still holds.
</P>
<P>
   The band's breakthrough album, ``The Trinity Sessions,'' which
was recorded in a Toronto church with a single microphone,
identified the group's sound as haunting, mournful and ethereal.
But that was 11 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Timmins, the band's chief songwriter, guitarist and
guiding force, says that while he and his bandmates once felt some
frustration when reading or hearing seemingly automatic adjectives
applied to their music, they're mostly amused these days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think fans take more offense than we do,'' he said last week
from Santa Fe, N.M., where the band was performing as part of its
``Summer Waltz'' tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very difficult thing to define music,'' Timmins
acknowledged. ``You get hanged with certain adjectives and they
stick. Sometimes it's just funny. There's nothing you can do to
influence it.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the group has such a way with a slow, sad song _
especially given the hypnotic and often languorous (and yes,
ethereal) quality of lead singer Margo Timmins' voice _ it's not
surprising that the Cowboy Junkies often are portrayed as brooding
and even dark.
</P>
<P>
   Michael admits that their music does often touch on the darker
aspects of life, but it's a mood, not necessarily a world view.
Michael said he's most interested in capturing the full experience
life has to offer.
</P>
<P>
   Read the band's tour diary, updated almost daily on its recently
launched Web site, www.cowboyjunkies.com, and you soon see that
these are not unhappy people. Reflective and thoughtful, certainly,
but also joyful and adventuresome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you invest real emotion, sing about the true side of
relationships, there will be some dark,'' Timmins said. There's
also a lot of light.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing comes sugar-coated, though. ``There's not a lot of
saccharin in our songs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The main thing is to be real, to tell real stories.
</P>
<P>
   That's part of the reason the late singer-songwriter Townes Van
Zandt was such an influence on the band. Despite his personal
demons and shortcomings, Van Zandt told stories that rang with
truth while capturing a pure ``love of songs,'' Timmins said.
</P>
<P>
   In concert, Margo has been known to dedicate their early song
``Misguided Angel'' to Van Zandt, just as folk-rock songstress
Lucinda Williams has been known to dedicate her own ``Drunken
Angel'' to the late songwriter.
</P>
<P>
   The Junkies' summer tour is a two-month jaunt through Canada and
the United States, where the band (which includes backup from
Cincinnati-based Over The Rhine's own Karin Bergquist and Linford
Dettweiler) is primarily playing outdoor venues. Timmins said
they've been very lucky in terms of weather so far, hitting towns
just before or after major heat waves.
</P>
<P>
   Timmins said the tour is partly for the fun of it, and partly to
support the band's recently released album, ``Rarities, B-Sides and
Slow, Sad Waltzes,'' which is available only at the shows and on
the Internet through its official Web site and amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   Put out on its own newly revived Latent label, which the band
used to release its debut album, ``Whites Off Earth No!,'' as well
as ``The Trinity Sessions'' collection, ``Rarities'' is an
assortment of songs that were recorded over the years, but never
found a home on any of the band's previous releases.
</P>
<P>
   Resurrecting the label allows the group to pursue side projects
while still recording albums for the Arista label.
</P>
<P>
   Timmins, who produced the 10-song (plus a hidden track)
collection released in May, said the process of putting the album
together was enjoyable on several levels. ``We got to go through a
lot of old tapes we haven't gone through in a long time,'' he said.
The effect was something akin to going through an old photo album,
in that band members had the chance to reflect on the course of
their musical journey, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Expecting to be somewhat embarrassed by early recorded efforts,
``I was pleasantly surprised at how good we sounded,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The results are pure Cowboy Junkies, distinctive, yet not easily
defined.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing that all of these songs have in common,''
Timmins writes in the liner note, ``is that they are our stories
told in the best way we know how.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
