<SLUG> BC-PRIVATE-PLANE-SAFETY-830&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO PICK A PRIVATE PILOT, CHECK HOURS LOGGED, RECENT FLYING AND
PERSONALITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Each year, about 1 in 100 of the nation's private
planes have an accident, and 1 in 300 have an accident that kills
somebody. How can a traveler considering using something other than
a commercial airline spot the risky flights in advance?
</P>
<P>
   There are no hard-and-fast answers in the complex arena of
general aviation, which includes nearly 200,000 planes, everything
from individuals' private planes to corporate jets and air taxis.
But the questions come up from time to time, especially after a
highly publicized accident like the one that killed John F. Kennedy
Jr., his wife, Carolyn Bessette Kennedy, and her sister Lauren G.
Bessette.
</P>
<P>
   Government records show that flying on a major airline last year
was 225 times safer than on a private plane, with 1.35 fatal
accidents per 100,000 flight hours on the so-called general
aviation planes compared with .006 per 100,000 hours on big
airlines.
</P>
<P>
   While statistical comparisons of driving and flying are
imprecise, it appears that driving a car is six or eight times more
dangerous than flying commercially, but hundreds of times safer
than flying in private planes.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with those kind of odds, passengers might want to think
carefully about the plane, its pilot and the conditions in which
they will fly.
</P>
<P>
   Flight instructors, government officials and other experts say
that, as a general rule, whether the pilot has recent experience in
the precise model of plane to be flown can be just as important, or
more so, than the total number of hours the pilot has spent aloft.
</P>
<P>
   The experts also say that passengers might pay attention to the
pilot's physical and mental condition and temperament.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tendency is to work all day, and then you go out and
fly,'' said L. Nick Lacey Jr., a senior Federal Aviation
Administration official. ``He's climbing into this machine that
requires tremendous concentration.''
</P>
<P>
   Others add that a critical factor is personality, including the
willingness to delay a trip or turn around and go home if
conditions are deteriorating.
</P>
<P>
   A question to ask a pilot is how many hours he or she has
logged. It takes at least 40 hours to get a certificate as a
private pilot, which allows the holder to carry passengers, but not
for pay. In practice, many pilots have 75 or more hours before they
get a private certificate.
</P>
<P>
   (Carrying passengers who pay requires a commercial license,
which takes 250 hours, but many of those pilots have far more.)
</P>
<P>
   Experts differ when asked how much experience is enough. The
average general aviation pilot logs fewer than 100 hours a year;
some people consider a pilot a novice until 500 hours have been
logged.
</P>
<P>
   ``It varies tremendously with the kind of training he gets,''
said a captain at a major airline, who is a former accident
investigator.
</P>
<P>
   A military pilot with 200 hours of intense training could be
landing a jet on an aircraft carrier at night, he said. But after
200 hours in a small Cessna, a civilian would be little more than a
novice.
</P>
<P>
   Another question is how many hours the pilot has logged in the
plane in which the trip will be made.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's a multiengine airplane,'' said Thomas Bradshaw, an
aviation insurance broker at Halpin Hall &AMP; Associates, in Fort
Worth, ``how much time does he have in a multiengine? If it's got
retractable landing gear, how much time does he have in
retractable?''
</P>
<P>
   The FAA does not require training when ``transitioning'' from
one general aviation airplane to another, he said, but some
insurance companies require it before providing insurance.
</P>
<P>
   If a pilot invited him for a first flight on a new type of
airplane, Bradshaw said, ``I'd run the other way; I'd be watching
from the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Another question is currency. To be legal, a pilot must have
completed three takeoffs and three landings in the preceding 90
days; otherwise, the pilot must fly with an instructor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of accidents in spring, because people drag
their airplanes out, and try to remember how to fly,'' Bradshaw
said.
</P>
<P>
   As for the plane, one with twin engines is not necessarily safer
than one with a single engine, to judge by the statistics. Among
single-engine planes, those with refinements like a pressurized
cabin, retractable landing gear and more powerful engines may not
be any safer than smaller, more basic models, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   A pilot with a twin-engine plane may be tempted to fly into
riskier situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Human nature being what it is, sometimes pilots will try to
fly in conditions in twins they wouldn't fly in single,'' said
Richard L. Collins, an editor of Flying magazine, which is written
for private pilots. He has logged 18,500 hours since 1951, more
than many airline pilots.
</P>
<P>
   Bad weather can bring down a two-engine plane as easily as one
with one engine, Collins said. ``The conditions don't know the
difference; they don't know how many engines you have.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A pilot with an instrument rating allowing flight in poor
visibility is generally reassuring. But the most important sign is
someone who stays within his limits, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you really want to think about, how much do you trust
this person's judgment,'' said Patrick E. Bradley, an aviation
lawyer who defends pilots and manufacturers in post-crash civil
lawsuits. ``If he has an incredibly type-A personality, and he's
going to get there no matter what, perhaps he takes risks you might
not be comfortable with,'' Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, who has a commercial pilot's license, said that many
flights would be safe if conducted in good weather, but that if he
agrees to a flight many days in the future, ``I don't know what the
weather conditions are going to be, and it's awkward for me to back
out.'' His solution, he said, is ``I'll just beg off at the
outset.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said that the day after he got his license, he took his
mother for a ride; now, he said, he is appalled that he did that.
</P>
<P>
   There are 618,400 people with pilot's certificates, according to
the FAA, of whom about half have instrument ratings, which means
they have been trained to fly straight and level when they have no
visual cues. Of the 618,400, there are 247,200 private pilots.
</P>
<P>
   Among pilots involved in fatal crashes, about half have
instrument ratings, but those with such ratings may also fly more
than those without, so their accident rate may be lower; the
aviation agency does not keep statistics to determine this.
</P>
<P>
   Among pilots involved in fatal accidents between 1989 and 1998,
those with instrument ratings for airplanes had an average of 4,617
hours of experience, according to the aviation agency; those
without such ratings had an average experience of 1,271 hours. The
statistics are somewhat uncertain because for about 5 percent of
the pilots, the records do not show if they had instrument ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Flying only in daylight and in good weather, when an instrument
rating is less important and there is no chance of a thunderstorm
or a cloud that obscures a mountain, will eliminate a great deal of
risk, experts say.
</P>
</TEXT>
