<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-CHASS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAYS WANT TO MAKE PLAYOFFS, AND NOT JUST AS WILD CARD 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No sooner did the Toronto Blue Jays overtake the Boston Red Sox
for the best second-place record in the American League than they
proclaimed that the wild-card spot in the playoffs would not be
good enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, no, no, no, no,'' Gord Ash, their general manager, said
emphatically. ``The Yankees are a very strong club, but that's
where our sights are set. It's unfortunately not very realistic
when I think they've beaten us six straight times, but we're only
eight back in the loss column and anything can happen. The way
we're playing now we can beat anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays are one of the surprising teams that have added
spice to the division and wild-card races in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   In the AL West the Oakland Athletics didn't seem to want to
disappear from contention until their No. 1 starting pitcher, Kenny
Rogers, asked to be traded. In the National League, the Cincinnati
Reds have created a race in the Central Division, the San Diego
Padres have catapulted themselves into the West race and the
Philadelphia Phillies can still see the Mets in the wild-card race
_ while the Mets are suddenly crowding the Atlanta Braves in the
East.
</P>
<P>
   Those developments figure to have an impact on trade talks this
week leading to the nonwaiver trading deadline Saturday at
midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Teams that might otherwise have been willing to trade someone
_pitching is the commodity most in demand, of course _ could now
hold back because of their contending status. Some of those same
teams, now thinking they have a chance, could be in the market for
an acquisition themselves.
</P>
<P>
   David Wells, whom the Blue Jays acquired from the Yankees for
Roger Clemens, is one playoff-experienced pitcher who has been
coveted by contenders. But Ash has said all season and reiterated
last week that the club is not trading him.
</P>
<P>
   ``For whatever reason, people keep writing that we are, but we
aren't,'' he said. ``When we signed him to the extension, it was
intimated that we did it because that made him more attractive on
the trade market, but that wasn't our purpose. You need players who
have been through that September situation. He certainly falls into
that category.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays were in position to supplant the Red Sox in second
place in the East and in first place in the wild-card division
Friday night because they had compiled the best record in the major
leagues since June 13, winning 27 of 36 games,
</P>
<P>
   The Padres, at 25-11, and the Mets, at 25-12, had the next best
six-week records. The Yankees had a 23-13 record, which is why the
Blue Jays were able to gain four games in the standing, and the Red
Sox had an 18-19 record, enabling the Toronto upstarts to make up
9{ games on them.
</P>
<P>
   Now it may only be a coincidence, but the Blue Jays began their
charge at the Red Sox and the Yankees the day that Tony Batista
became their shortstop after his acquisition from Arizona. In 35
games, Batista has driven in 27 runs and hit 11 home runs, placing
him third in homers behind Shawn Green (28) and Carlos Delgado
(25).
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew he had power,'' Ash said. ``He hit 15 after the break
last year. But we really didn't get him for that purpose. It's a
side benefit. We were looking for defense and he's been
sensational. There was a knock on him for his range and his range
has been fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Batista has replaced Alex Gonzalez, whose services the team lost
for the year in mid-May when he went down with a shoulder injury.
Batista has teamed well with second baseman Homer Bush, whose
average has hovered around .290 and who has had a team-leading 21
stolen bases in 23 tries.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays have also improved because their injured players
got healthy. ``We don't have the depth to our roster to have the
kinds of injuries we had,'' Ash said.
</P>
<P>
   Joey Hamilton has been a more effective starting pitcher since
his return from the disabled list, and Paul Quantrill's return has
bolstered the bullpen. So has John Frascatore, who came with
Batista in the trade for Dan Plesac, a left-handed reliever the
Diamondbacks hoped would solve their closing problems (he didn't).
</P>
<P>
   Jim Fregosi, who replaced Tim Johnson as manager in spring
training, has also been a major factor in the team's rise toward
the top.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not that the players wouldn't have played to the same level,''
said the general manager, who made the move because of the fallout
from Johnson's fanciful tales of combat in Vietnam, ``but the
attitude and the atmosphere are tremendously positive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
