u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-U.N.-CRIMINAL-COURT-4     07-24 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.N.-CRIMINAL-COURT-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.C.)  
 U.S. SEEKS CHANGES IN TRIBUNAL ON WAR CRIMES 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By PAUL LEWIS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The United States is expected to continue its
campaign against politically inspired war-crimes prosecutions at a
conference about the proposed International Criminal Court that
begins here Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The three-week meeting for representatives of about 120
countries that have approved forming such a court has been called
to discuss outstanding technical issues. Those include the court's
rules of evidence and procedure and the precise definition of the
crimes it may try under a mandate covering crimes against humanity,
war crimes, genocide and aggression.
</P>
<P>
   But legal experts say they believe the United States will use
these discussions to explore ways of shielding American soldiers
and officials involved in peacekeeping or enforcement operations _
like the recent bombing of Yugoslavia _ from prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Fear that its citizens might suffer frivolous or politically
inspired prosecution even if the United States never accepts the
court's jurisdiction led the United States to vote against the
treaty setting up the new tribunal, to which 120 countries agreed
in Rome last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Washington sees the talks as a way to get a foot in the door
for changing the court's statutes to protect American nationals,''
said William Pace, leader of the Coalition for the International
Criminal Court, a group of 800 organizations around the world that
support the court. ``But the statutes are agreed. The others won't
change them.''
</P>
<P>
   Reed Brody, advocacy director of Human Rights Watch, a watchdog
organization that supports the court, said: ``The bottom line is
that the United States wants to immunize its soldiers and
policymakers against prosecutions it does not like. The rest of the
world is not going to accept this.''
</P>
<P>
   Only six other countries voted against the treaty, leaving the
United States in the company of China, Israel, Iraq, Qatar, Sri
Lanka and Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   So far just three countries _ Senegal, San Marino and Trinidad
and Tobago _ have ratified this treaty, which needs 60
ratifications to go into effect. But 83 countries have signed it _
including all other NATO members except Turkey _ and many are
moving swiftly toward ratification.
</P>
<P>
   As a result the court could well be functioning in The Hague
within three or four years.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The United States has suggested several ways its concerns might
be met but so far they have proved unacceptable to the countries
that agreed to support the court.
</P>
<P>
   Under one proposal, citizens of countries that reject the
court's jurisdiction could only be prosecuted with the consent of
their governments. But that means that rogue states could escape
justice for their crimes by never signing the treaty.
</P>
<P>
   Another proposal is to require approval for prosecutions by the
U.N. Security Council, where the United States has a veto. But so
do the other four permanent members _ China, Russia, Britain and
France _ which means such a rule would greatly widen the potential
for political interference in cases brought before the court.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of the court argue that American citizens are already
well protected against unjustified prosecution by a number of
safeguards in the court statutes approved at Rome.
</P>
<P>
   ``The risk of politically motivated prosecutions is almost nil
because of elaborate, overlapping safeguards, many proposed by the
United States,'' said Michael Posner, executive director of the
Lawyers Committee for Human Rights, another watchdog group. ``It is
outweighed by the real benefits of having a permanent court
available to deal with future Saddam Husseins.''
</P>
<P>
   The most important of those safeguards is that the primary
responsibility for judging war crime accusations would rest with
the national courts of the accused person's home country. The court
could only try a case when the suspect's home courts were unable or
unwilling to hear it.
</P>
<P>
   ``So long as the United States has a credible judicial system,
Americans are protected,'' Posner said.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the administration eventually gets enough assurances to
be able to sign the treaty drawn up in Rome, the court will face
formidable opponents in the Senate, to which any agreement will be
sent for approval.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., has already warned that the treaty
would be ``dead on arrival'' at the Senate Foreign Affairs
Committee, of which he is chairman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-99 1458EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
