<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL NOTEBOOK: PADRES AREN'T MARLINS; BOSOX ROOKIES;
MILESTONES 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By MURRAY CHASS  
 &HT;     
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   No Big Dip for the Padres
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 San Diego Padres are doing a poor imitation of the 1998
Florida Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres were supposed to be an exact copy, were they not?
Didn't they dismantle their team soon after their World Series loss
to the New York Yankees, just as the Marlins had decimated theirs
after winning the World Series in 1997?
</P>
<P>
   That's what some people thought, but there was one major
difference, as Padres president Larry Lucchino pointed out. The
Marlins, he noted, slashed their payroll by $32 million; the Padres
have actually increased their payroll by a few million, to just
under $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 Marlins finished with a 54-108 record, a whopping 52
games out of first. The 1999 Padres were only two games from first
with a 49-45 record when the weekend began. A 24-7 burst that was
built on a major league-best 14-game winning streak was
responsible.
</P>
<P>
   Lucchino credited general manager Kevin Towers with creatively
putting the team together and manager Bruce Bochy with using the
players wisely. The Padres have one of the least potent offenses in
the league, but they are one of the best at stealing bases and
runs. ``With the changes we made this winter,'' Bochy said, ``we
knew we lost a lot of power and experience. We're more of a
run-and-shoot-type offense. We have to create runs. Speed is one of
our strengths and we try to utilize it.''
</P>
<P>
   Damian Jackson and Reggie Sanders each have 24 stolen bases, and
Eric Owens has 22. Jackson and Sanders were the payment from
Cincinnati in the controversial Greg Vaughn trade. Owens was signed
as a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say enough about what Owens has done for this club,''
Bochy said of the surprising .300-hitting outfielder. ``In spring
training I didn't think I had a spot on the team for him. But every
time he played he hit and fielded well.''
</P>
<P>
   The 28-year-old Owens, who has never played a full season in the
majors, began the season on the bench, but injuries opened outfield
spots for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has taken full advantage of it,'' Bochy said. ``He's a
throwback, a Charlie Hustle-type player who will go all out.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanders, an outfielder, and Jackson, at shortstop, have helped
defuse the furor that arose when the Padres traded Vaughn after
having lost Kevin Brown, Ken Caminiti and Steve Finley as free
agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We consulted seven people in the organization, and all seven
of them wanted to make the trade,'' Lucchino said. ``The press
played it up as a salary move. Had we not made that deal, it would
have been for public relations reasons and not baseball reasons. It
was the right decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Among other players, center fielder Ruben Rivera, whom the
Padres obtained from the Yankees for Hideki Irabu, has become a
productive hitter after struggling to get his average over .200,
and catcher Ben Davis, the second player picked in the 1995 draft,
has spent a productive first month in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   Explaining Rivera's ultra-slow start, Bochy said: ``Not playing
winter ball set him back. We wanted him to play, but he wanted to
take time off. He got off to a rough start and his confidence was
shaken, but we kept throwing him out there and he kept getting
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis, the manager said, already plays like a veteran and will
do most of the catching even after Jim Leyritz and Greg Myers
return from the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   Among the team's other injured players has been Tony Gwynn, who
twice has been on the disabled list and continues to be plagued by
a strained left calf. He has played in only half of the Padres'
games.
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox Rookies Slumping
</P>
<P>
   As the Red Sox sink slowly in the East, here's one element in
their change in fortune:
</P>
<P>
   From May 8 through June 25, three rookie pitchers, Juan Pena,
Brian Rose and Jin Ho Cho, right-handers in their early 20s,
started 12 games and gained eight victories against no defeats as
the team compiled an 11-1 record. In that seven-week span, the Red
Sox, on the strength of a 29-16 record, went from five games out in
fourth place to one game out in second, spending 23 days in first
place along the way.
</P>
<P>
   From June 27 through Friday night, Rose, Cho and another young
right-handed rookie, Tomokazu Ohka, made 11 starts, earning two
victories against five losses as the team compiled a 2-9 record. In
that four-week period, the Red Sox, on the weakness of an 8-16
record, plummeted from one game out to seven games out and lost a
place in the standing.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the Red Sox should call in a corps of diplomats to
straighten out their United Nations pitching staff. Ohka is
Japanese, Cho Korean, Rose American and Pena, now in the minor
leagues, Dominican.
</P>
<P>
   Closing In on Milestones
</P>
<P>
   Entering Saturday's games, Mark McGwire had 491 career home
runs, Wade Boggs had 2,987 hits and Tony Gwynn had 2,985 hits. Will
McGwire become the 16th player to hit 500 home runs before Boggs
and Gwynn become Nos. 22 and 23 to hit the 3,000 plateau?
</P>
<P>
   The Anaheim Angels suffered their eighth consecutive loss Friday
night. With each of seven of those losses, they lost a game in the
standing, plunging from 6{ games behind Texas to 13{.
</P>
<P>
   In the Baltimore Orioles' 5-3 victory over Boston on June 20,
Mike Timlin gained his ninth save. Twenty-six games later, in a 5-2
victory over Boston, Timlin picked up his 10th save. In between,
the Orioles had only one save.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Mays, a member of the Minnesota Twins' rookie regiment,
started against Chicago's teams in the space of six days. Against
the Cubs on July 17, he pitched a three-hit shutout. Showing no
favoritism, the 23-year-old right-hander pitched against the White
Sox last Thursday and allowed no runs and five hits in eight and
one-third innings. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
