<SLUG> BC-EDIT-GRIEVING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A WEEK OF GRIEVING 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Sunday, July 25:
</P>
<P>
   In the long week of public mourning for John F. Kennedy Jr.,
Americans found an almost pastoral comfort in their technological
solitude. From separate rooms around the country, we learned about
the crash that took the lives of President Kennedy's son, his wife,
Carolyn Bessette Kennedy, and her sister Lauren Bessette. Only a
few found a public place to express their sorrow _ on the beach at
Martha's Vineyard or the sidewalk outside the Kennedys' Manhattan
apartment. Most Americans mourned into a television set and grieved
into a computer.
</P>
<P>
   As television news cycled endlessly last week, media-savvy
psychologists and telegenic priests tried to soothe and explain our
collective sadness. Commentators whispered their lamentations over
the footage of some 350 mourners entering and leaving a private
service Friday at an uptown Manhattan church. Meanwhile, for those
who wanted to talk, not listen, there were the computer chat rooms.
Some were so clogged with electronic keening and heartfelt
panegyrics that one writer in The Washington Post described the Web
last week as ``a giant Hallmark card.''
</P>
<P>
   If the television coverage was repetitive and sometimes mawkish,
people watched for hours, as the viewing statistics now show, and
the intensity of this public grief carried several messages. Partly
it stemmed from a nation's collective memory of the child who
softened his elegant parents in the White House and played under
his father's desk. That little boy became a man who, for all his
ease, was also a link to deep scars on the American political
psyche. Indeed, that somber linkage made more striking the sunny
and mannerly way he bore his celebrity when the cameras were
tracking the days of his life rather than the way of his death.
</P>
<P>
   The public will slowly flag in its ability to be vicariously
sad, but the families must follow the stages of a grief more direct
and normal. Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., hovering like an old lion
over the younger mourners, endured his duties with strength and
eloquence. His eulogy, with its poignant humor about his own lost
political ambitions, summed up the pain that another foreshortened
life represents for this particular family. ``Like his father,''
the senator concluded piercingly, ``he had every gift but length of
years.''
</P>
<P>
   The news cycle will turn more directly now to questions about
why a high-powered, private airplane fell from the night sky, a
moment that feels, suddenly, like a long time ago. After federal
investigators have examined every bend in this broken airplane and
asked about John Kennedy Jr., not as a mythic prince but as an
inexperienced pilot, this crash could find its place not so much in
aviation history as in basic aviation instruction theory. The late
hour, the disappearing horizon, the frailty of a newly unbound
ankle _ all these unspectacular parts of the John F. Kennedy Jr.
story may offer cautionary lessons to future pilots. The
conclusions about what caused this crash and started this
extraordinary week of public distress are months away. Until then,
we have been connected to these deaths in the way we share our
public passions now _ by electronic proxy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-99 1508EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
