<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-GREENSPAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE ORACLE OF THE FED 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Sunday, July 25:
</P>
<P>
   Alan Greenspan, who has been chairman of the Federal Reserve
Board for a dozen years, is a past master of the art of Delphic
congressional testimony. So perhaps it is understandable that many
congressmen take for granted that he is always that way, and seem
to have trouble understanding him when he decides to make himself
perfectly clear.
</P>
<P>
   That is what happened last week, when Greenspan testified before
a House committee on the very day the House was voting for a
massive tax cut. It was, he said, not a good idea. He got to say it
over and over again because Republicans kept seeking Greenspanian
ambiguity where it did not exist.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan is not a fan of big government, but he is an economist
concerned about a sizzling economy that could rekindle inflation
and that may _ he concedes he is not at all sure _ have produced a
stock-market bubble. Last month the Federal Reserve pushed up
interest rates a bit, and, in one of the more oracular parts of his
testimony, Greenspan seemed to hint that more tightening was
likely. In that atmosphere, the last thing he needs is a tax cut
that would provide more economic stimulus. ``I'm saying, hold off
for a while,'' he testified.
</P>
<P>
   But while there is no economic need for a tax cut now, there
might be one in a few years. As Greenspan noted, the business cycle
should not be presumed dead just because we are in the midst of the
longest peacetime expansion in American history. ``At some point,''
he warned, ``this economy is going to slow down and perhaps slow
down quite significantly.''
</P>
<P>
   That is when a tax cut would be needed. Unfortunately, the bill
passed by the House could provide just the opposite. It calls for a
series of cuts in individual income tax rates, but would delay the
cuts if the interest expense on the federal debt rose. But that is
just what happens as a result of recessions, which cause tax
receipts to fall and welfare costs to rise. The bill would cut
taxes, in other words, unless a tax cut was actually a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   That provision to delay the cuts was put in to pacify Republican
moderates worried about deficits. They bought it, not worrying
about the perverse economic effects or about the fact that it would
delay only the reductions in individual income tax rates, which
happen to be the only parts of the bill that benefit lower- and
middle-income taxpayers. The other parts of the tax bill, including
a reduction in capital-gains tax rates, a phase-out of the estate
tax and a variety of special-interest breaks for corporations,
would not be affected. The campaign contributors seeking those
breaks will be pleased.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan is treated reverently on Capitol Hill, but it appears
that the Republicans do not want to heed his advice to run a
surplus and pay down the national debt, while saving a tax cut for
when it is needed. It may be up to President Clinton to use his
veto pen to prevent this folly from becoming law.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-99 1510EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990724.0148 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-24 15:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2688 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-BASEBALL-NYT &LR;      07-24 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-BASEBALL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: BASEBALL'S MADDENING LIST 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Sunday, July 25:
</P>
<P>
   Major League Baseball has decided to join the millennium ratings
madness with its own best-of-the-century list. Between now and
September, fans will be asked to examine a list of 100 players and
choose two for each infield position, two catchers, nine
outfielders and six pitchers. In order to correct obvious
oversights, a special panel will be authorized to add up to five
players to the team.
</P>
<P>
   One of the good things about this exercise is that baseball
offers reams of statistics _ hard facts on which to base
comparisons. Thus there is no excuse for wildly improbable choices.
On the other hand, the numbers also tend to skew things in favor of
the great players of yesteryear, obscuring the fact that the
overall quality of play has improved. The variations from the norm
were much greater before, say, 1929, with more 30-game winners
among the pitchers and more .400 hitters. Judgment calls that take
account of the evolutionary nature of the game are therefore
inevitable. Here are ours.
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher: Based on the numbers alone, the available six slots
could be filled almost entirely with legends: Cy Young, Walter
Johnson, Christy Mathewson, Grover Cleveland Alexander and Lefty
Grove. Young won 511 games, Johnson 417, the others 300 or well
over _ astounding by today's standards. We'll take Young, Johnson
and Alexander. From the modern era, we'll select Bob Feller, Sandy
Koufax and Tom Seaver. Cardinal fans can substitute Bob Gibson, and
Giants fans Juan Marichal, for Seaver, and we won't complain. There
was little to separate the three.
</P>
<P>
   First Base: Lou Gehrig and Mark McGwire. Gehrig is Gehrig. We
almost chose the great Jimmie Foxx, but how does one not include
McGwire and his 70 home runs in one year?
</P>
<P>
   Second Base: Rogers Hornsby and Jackie Robinson. Hornsby was
simply the best-hitting second baseman of all time. Robinson, the
first black man in the major leagues, began his career relatively
late, but he lit up the National League when he got there. Nobody
could win games like Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop: From the old days, Honus Wagner, who some think is
the best player of all time, an unprovable proposition. From the
modern era, Cal Ripken Jr. The power of Ernie Banks made us pause
here. But Ripken was (and still is) a more complete player.
</P>
<P>
   Third Base. Mike Schmidt and Brooks Robinson. Schmidt struck out
a lot, but he also hit more than 500 homers and fielded well. We
rated Robinson's exceptional grace in the field over George Brett's
and Eddie Mathews' prowess at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Catcher. Johnny Bench, superb at and behind the plate, and Yogi
Berra, an exceptional clutch hitter and student of the game who
wins by a nod over an earlier Yankee, Bill Dickey.
</P>
<P>
   Outfield. There are 34 to choose from, but only nine slots.
Eight are automatic _ Ty Cobb, Babe Ruth, Joe DiMaggio, Ted
Williams, Stan Musial, Willie Mays, Mickey Mantle and Hank Aaron.
The ninth is almost impossible. Tris Speaker, a superb fielder with
a .344 average? Pete Rose, the all-time leader in hits? Or Tony
Gwynn, the most consistent hitter of the '80s and '90s?
</P>
<P>
   We'll take Rose, for his longevity and hustle, and put Gwynn on
our bonus list of five players. That list includes two players from
the old Negro leagues, Josh Gibson, a catcher, and Satchel Paige,
who actually made it to the major leagues at the age of 42, when he
went 6-1 for the Cleveland Indians in 1948. The final two
supplementals are left-handed pitchers, Grove and Warren Spahn.
</P>
<P>
   What's missing here? Relief pitchers, for one thing, like Dennis
Eckersley and Rollie Fingers, both on the best-100 ballot. But no
list is perfect. Baseball fans can be endlessly disputatious, and
the task of making this new list will inspire further argument. But
therein lies the fun of it. As Berra once advised, ``take it with a
grin of salt.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-99 1512EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
