<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-24 15:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2689 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-HOSTETLER-NYT &LR;      07-24 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-HOSTETLER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOSTETLER RETIRES TO CARE FOR PARALYZED SON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., N.J., Calif., W.Va.)  (mk) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Everything was going right for Jeff Hostetler. An ankle injury
from a 1998 preseason game had completely healed and he had spent
the last year getting into top shape. Last month, four teams showed
serious interest in signing him as a backup quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   It looked as though one of the National Football League's most
resilient players and classiest citizens was on his way back to the
playing field at age 38.
</P>
<P>
   Then something happened that dramatically changed Hostetler's
plans. Last month, his 8-year-old son, Tyler, the youngest of his
three boys, was paralyzed from the neck down after an accident on a
sports recreation vehicle he was riding with a 9-year-old friend at
the friend's house near the Hostetler home in Morgantown, W.Va. The
vehicle suddenly tumbled over, flipping Tyler, and leaving him with
several broken vertebrae.
</P>
<P>
   Football suddenly became insignificant for Hostetler. He told
teams that his career was on hold. After 15 seasons, nine of them
with the Giants, Hostetler has in effect retired from the NFL to
care for his son.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm concentrating only on him right now,'' Hostetler said in a
telephone interview the other day. ``I have my priorities in the
right spot. The focus is not on football. It's on my son. That is
all that matters and nothing else.''
</P>
<P>
   Hostetler, always an intensely private person, has talked to
only a handful of people about the accident. The Giants' co-owner,
Wellington Mara, called Hostetler to express his concern and offer
whatever help he could. A close friend of Hostetler's arranged a
call to Tyler, a baseball fan, from Barry Larkin, the Cincinnati
Reds' All-Star shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time Hostetler has had to watch one of his
three children endure physical trauma. His son Jason was
hospitalized as an infant in 1984, during Hostetler's rookie year
with the Giants, because of heart problems from which he recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Hostetler stayed by Jason's side then, and said he planned to
devote all of his attention now to Tyler. ``I will not leave him,''
Hostetler said, ``until he walks again.''
</P>
<P>
   Hostetler declined to discuss details about his son's injuries.
But he did say that Tyler has improved somewhat since the accident
and can now move his toes and has some feeling in his arms.
Hostetler is optimistic that Tyler will regain his ability to walk.
</P>
<P>
   Hostetler said he hoped to establish a foundation to help people
who suffer from paralysis, and he talked about dedicating his life
to raising money for a cure.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, a number of NFL quarterbacks have experienced
hardships involving family members, their children in particular.
The son of the Buffalo Bills' Doug Flutie was born autistic. The
former Bills quarterback Jim Kelly started a foundation to help
provide money for research on Krabbe's disease, a rare degenerative
disorder that attacks the nervous system of infants; his son is
afflicted with the ailment. The son of former NFL quarterback
Boomer Esiason has cystic fibrosis.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, quarterback Mark Rypien, a free agent, announced
that he planned to skip training camp this summer because of recent
family adversities. Rypien sat out last season after his 3-year-old
son died of cancer. That year, cancer was also diagnosed in his
wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``My heart and mind are not there,'' said Rypien, who has not
ruled out signing with San Diego, Seattle or Washington once the
season begins.
</P>
<P>
   Hostetler, a third-round draft pick out of West Virginia,
remains one of the best-known athletes in New York because of his
outstanding play for the Giants and the number of charities he was
involved in. His best year with the Giants was 1990, when he
replaced the injured Phil Simms with two games left in the regular
season. He won both those contests and the Giants clinched the East
Division title.
</P>
<P>
   Hostetler remained on top of his game throughout the postseason,
leading the Giants to an undefeated playoff record and a 1-point
victory over the Bills in Super Bowl XXV. He completed 20 of 32
passes for 222 yards and a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Hostetler, who is 6 feet 3 inches and 220 pounds, was a powerful
player, as fast as many defensive backs and just as athletic. In
the locker room he was highly respected for being a candid and a
kind person.
</P>
<P>
   Hostetler played for the Raiders both in Los Angeles and
Oakland, where he had two 3,000-yard passing seasons. He threw for
23 touchdowns in 1996, a career high, and then signed with the
Washington Redskins.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-99 1516EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
