</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE SELF-IMPORTANCE OF BEING AN UMPIRE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also BBO-UMPIRES) 
(mk) 
 By ROBERT LIPSYTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you've ever spent any private time with major league umpires,
at their homes or out with their families and friends (they have
groupies, too), you might mistakenly think that their egos are even
bigger than their bellies. The self-importance of umpires is
astonishing; they pretend to see themselves as somewhere between
the thin red line that protected the British Empire from its own
barbarism and the U.S. Supreme Court. When more than five umpires
appear together, you expect them to start singing, ``We Are the
Game.''
</P>
<P>
   It is no wonder that most of them have offered up their
resignations, as of Sept. 2, as part of a convoluted plan that may
be a bluff, may be a mistake, may be a brilliant tactic to return
to their jobs as independent contractors rather than unionized
employees. Whatever the plan, these people are desperate for
respect. Umpire righteousness dwarfs the righteousness of doctors
who leave managed-care organizations in a huff, then organize their
own HMOs. It's no joke that God has a stethoscope in one pocket, a
ball-and-strike counter in the other.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, I find all this rather endearing. There are fewer and
fewer professionals out there who take themselves and their work so
seriously. There is too much ESPN defensive irony in the world;
half-educated smarties who think that what they do is somewhat
beneath them (their mothers had dreams) and the best way to show it
is by coolly mocking their work.
</P>
<P>
   Umpires do not mock their work. Umpires need to believe that not
only are they the glue and the spine of the only true game, they
are also universal symbols of order, justice and the possibility of
fair play. They are dedicated to eternal vigilance, and they have
taken oaths; this is why obese umpires faint or even die on the
field rather than quit. And it is why they are justifiably angry at
how they have been treated by the pencil-necked accountants who
manage sports, people who have never played the game or, more
important, never policed and judged it.
</P>
<P>
   The umpires have a case. Baseball bureaucracy has long treated
them as necessary but accessory, like traffic cops or waiters.
There is a sense that when machines can do the job, everyone will
be better off. Umpires rarely receive full-hearted league support
in disputes with players and managers, and the continuing trend
toward verbally abusing and even physically attacking amateur
umpires signifies a cultural animosity that organized baseball has
done nothing to counteract.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, changing the strike zone is a betrayal of the
umpirical imperative: There must be standards and they must be
maintained. The strike zone has become the hemline of baseball. It
is despicable enough that more or less of a woman is shown for
marketing reasons, but raising and lowering, widening and narrowing
the strike zone is close to sacrilege.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, umpires have too much dignity to demonstrate against these
outrages. Imagine if every umpiring team just plopped down in the
middle of the infield at the start of a game. Let the ground crews
carry them off in tarps or earth movers. But also alas, umpires
have so little pride in their physical appearance that it is often
hard to take them seriously. Ballplayers detest fat umpires because
it desecrates their game.
</P>
<P>
   So, I say, let them strike or resign, or whatever they call it.
But let them use their time off the field to improve themselves, to
actually become those magisterial arbiters of their fantasies, at
the Umpire Re-education and Fitness Camp, which will be held at an
undisclosed location in the desert.
</P>
<P>
   For as long as it takes or until after the World Series
(whichever is later), umpires will attend the following four
workshops, naked except for protective cups, shinguards, masks and
chest pads:
</P>
<P>
   DIET: Cutting down on postgame steaks and booze is not enough.
There's no point in losing 50 pounds if it makes you feel
vulnerable. As the fat is suctioned off, umpires must learn that
butt- and belly-bumping degrade their dignity, and that surrounding
their beleaguered souls with protective flesh is no solution to
their true lack of self-esteem.
</P>
<P>
   THERAPY: In short-term counseling, each umpire will explore the
reasons he became an umpire. Was it to get back at the boys who
never chose him into their games, or was it to have some sense of
control, however false, over a chaotic life? Was it the salary and
benefits, the ladies in the lobby?
</P>
<P>
   FITNESS: In courses run by the astoundingly fit National
Basketball Association referees and the theatrical World Wrestling
Federation referees, our umpires will learn to position themselves
not only to view plays but also to obscure the views of players who
disrespect them, shifting just in time to allow a high spike or an
errant throw to mete out justice.
</P>
<P>
   SUPPORT: Motivational speakers will remind them that they are
the reason there is a season, uh-huh, that without umpires players
would kick dirt and spit on each other, and that there would be no
alibis for being caught stealing or watching a third strike. It
will be encouraging for them to hear that managers who pick on
umpires, like Billy Martin and Earl Weaver, tend to be small men
and maybe mentally ill.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, umpires should feel free to ignore all this,
negotiate with baseball and stay on the job. No one would much care
either way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
