<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-24 15:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2691 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGO-POLITICS-NYT &LR;      07-24 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGO-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERB OPPOSITION AIDES SAY TIME ISN'T RIGHT TO OUST MILOSEVIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NIS, Yugoslavia _ A leading Serbian opposition politician, Vuk
Draskovic, believes that the moment is not yet ripe for ousting
President Slobodan Milosevic. He intended to make a rally here
Saturday night his last for some time, his aides said.
</P>
<P>
   Senior aides to Draskovic said they believed that the opposition
was wasting energy by holding an endless series of summertime
rallies that are not attracting enough people to put any real
pressure on Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic believes that Milosevic must be induced to leave power
in a way that avoids civil conflict and significant bloodshed.
</P>
<P>
   His aides said Saturday's meeting in Nis would be Draskovic's
last for at least several weeks, although the other main opposition
grouping, the Alliance for Change, has scheduled further rallies
and says it hopes to lead a grand march on Belgrade sometime in
September.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone says Milosevic must go,'' a senior Draskovic aide
said. ``But how? He doesn't even contemplate going. You can ask him
to go for 1,000 days, but asking him isn't serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic will resume mass meetings as an important part of the
strategy to get Milosevic to resign, ``but we want to pick the
right moment, when we can create momentum and there is something
important to say,'' the aide said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Draskovic is concentrating on trying to choose a
transitional government of experts that all the opposition can
agree upon, and then trying to push Milosevic to empower that
government and finally to step aside after new elections.
</P>
<P>
   The Alliance for Change demands Milosevic's resignation first,
before any transitional government, but pressed by the United
States, Draskovic and alliance leaders are working on a joint
platform as a way to bridge their differences, if not to solve them
all. That platform will include the idea of Milosevic's ouster and
new elections.
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic and Democratic Party leader Zoran Djindjic, who were
allies in the 1996-97 marches against Milosevic, are now bitter
rivals, which has undermined both their reputations and the
credibility of the opposition generally.
</P>
<P>
   Washington and the Serbian opposition are also hoping that
Milosevic's government will begin to crumble from within,
especially with the prospect of new indictments on war crimes from
the International Tribunal in the Hague. Indictments may come soon
of Mirjana Markovic, Milosevic's wife and the leader of the
influential Yugoslav United Left Party, and of Vojislav Seselj, the
ultranationalist leader of the Radical Party and a Serbian deputy
prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   They are hopeful that the former army chief of staff, Momcilo
Perisic, who came out last week in sharp opposition to Milosevic
and his government, will attract more army and police support to
the idea of the President's ouster. But Perisic is likely to form
his own party, given his lack of respect for Draskovic, Djindjic or
another former general, Vuk Obradovic, who heads the Social
Democracy Party.
</P>
<P>
   Washington and its European partners will also resume aid to
independent media and opposition parties here, supporting the
argument that there will be no ouster of Milosevic otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans are pushing a respected economist, Dragoslav
Avramovic, who helped end Yugoslav hyperinflation in January 1994,
as prime minister of a transitional government. Avramovic is
affiliated with the Alliance for Change, but Draskovic is now more
willing to consider the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Draskovic believes that the timing is not yet right for
the naming of such a government, his aides said. He also considers
that the opposition is dissipating anger at Milosevic with rallies
now that have no idea behind them except Milosevic's ouster and
that offer no serious alternative program behind which citizens
could unite.
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic also believes that the West is harming the cause of
the opposition by allowing the majority Albanians to sweep most of
the Serbian minority from Kosovo through intimidation and killings.
</P>
<P>
   That case will be made stronger by the news overnight of the
killing of 14 Serbian farmers in the Kosovo village of Gracko,
despite earlier calls by the farmers for protection from British
troops policing the sector since NATO and the United Nations took
over the province.
</P>
<P>
   There are growing feelings in Serbia that NATO and the West are
not serious about protecting the rights of all the citizens of
Kosovo, including the Serbs. NATO and the United Nations have been
slow to start policing the province in earnest, the Serbs feel, and
government officials have started to suggest that Yugoslav police
and even army troops should return to Kosovo if such killings
continue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
