<DOCNO> NYT19990724.0152 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-24 15:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2693 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-GAMBLE25-COX     07-24 3820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GAMBLE25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The lost Gamble
 &HT;    By Mike Tierney
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ He stood before the judge in federal court, ears
pricked to absorb the magic words: probation, no jail time. Oh, he
knew that pleading guilty to two counts of perjury could bring as
many as five years behind bars. And Lord knows, in today's sports
climate, athletes who wager against their own teams must perform
saintly acts to rise to the level of coach chokers and steroid
users.
</P>
<P>
   But he reminded himself that he had stopped lying about details
of his involvement in a campus football gambling ring and helped
expose a betting virus inflicting the basketball team. That
prominent politicians from Max Cleland to Lewis Massey, many of
them his mother's onetime co-workers, had offered character
references. That he met his degree requirements within four years
in the acclaimed Medlin School of Journalism at lofty Northwestern
University. And that the president of the United States remained a
free man despite having perhaps perjured himself.
</P>
<P>
   So when the Hon. Judge George M. Marovich cleared his throat to
pronounce sentencing on May 7, the self-assured, well-rounded
grown-up kid from an upscale Atlanta neighborhood and the
prestigious Lovett School, the Big Ten wide receiver with an
Olympic sprinter's speed, an orator's diction and a favorite
cousin's charm, expected to skate. He would walk out of the
courtroom and drive off, watching this sordid chapter of his young
life fade to nothing in the rearview mirror.
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe no tackler has ever jarred him harder than the
judge's words: two months in prison.
</P>
<P>
   After the sentencing
</P>
<P>
   How foretelling was this: The birth certificate of the man whose
testimony paved the way to a record number of criminal indictments
in a sports gambling scandal at one university reads Christopher
Gamble. The irony can be found in his first name, St. Christopher
being the designated guardian on life's journeys.
</P>
<P>
   But his first significant journey _ off to college in 1990 _ was
rerouted to hell in the guise of a Chicago courtroom. It ended with
Gamble, now 27, peering over one shoulder to see his mother begin a
crying jag that would last for days. The shame he heaped upon
Vernetta, a devoted employee to some of Georgia's leaders in
government, and his father Rich, a Morehouse man and onetime
Atlanta police officer of the year, was almost too much to bear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hurt, I was mad,'' he said six weeks later in an
interview at his townhouse in Marietta, a day before entering the
prison camp section of the Atlanta Federal Penitentiary. ``But I
was also somewhat relieved. I thought about a Bible verse, `This
too shall pass.' It's been my theme ever since.''
</P>
<P>
   As far back as he remembers, Vernetta and Rich stressed God and
faith above all else, with education a close second, even after
they split up when Chris was 8. One grandfather was a Baptist
minister, the other a deacon.
</P>
<P>
   Home was the Peachtree Hills neighborhood, where Gamble recalls
being the lone black youngster. Living with his mother, he dabbled
in numerous sports until breaking an ankle in a pee-wee league
football game. ``That's it,'' Mom said, and he gravitated toward
soccer.
</P>
<P>
   Gamble was fast-tracked toward a top-level youth team run by
Bill Holleman, also soccer coach and athletics director at Lovett.
The Gambles, of modest means, were granted financial aid, and Chris
thrived at the costly, challenging school. His report cards were
all A's and B's, his Lions soccer team's ledger nearly all W's.
``He could walk the walk as well as talk the talk,'' Holleman said.
</P>
<P>
   Not until the soccer club team disbanded before his junior year
did Gamble, faced with free time in the fall, resume football.
``And to get the coach to stop bugging me.''
</P>
<P>
   But, said Bill Railey, it was with the purest of intentions. ``I
was worried for him because there weren't a lot of college
scholarships for soccer, and I knew he'd need a scholarship to
go,'' Railey said.
</P>
<P>
   Gamble's renewal with a full-contact sport scared him. ``I had
to get accustomed to getting hit,'' he said. ``I found out I
enjoyed it.''
</P>
<P>
   College coaches enjoyed watching him run down passes, few more
so than Steve Spurrier. On his way from Duke to Florida, Spurrier
was searching far and wide for receivers for his whirlwind offense,
but he came in on Gamble too late. Chris' parents were smitten by
Northwestern's academic demands, which surely he could handle with
his 1,200 score on the entrance exam. And Vernetta was won over by
head coach Francis Peay, an African-American and Christian. ``There
was no choice in the matter,'' Gamble said, meaning his parents
made the choice.
</P>
<P>
   Rich steered him toward a journalism major. As he told Chris,
``You can communicate orally. If you can create on paper, you can
do anything in life.''
</P>
<P>
   After two football seasons, one of them inactive as a redshirt,
he wanted out. ``I couldn't stand it,'' Gamble said. He sassed a
coach who mocked him in practice after a dropped pass (``Do you
need glasses?'' ``No, my eyes are fine.'') and developed a sour
attitude. He plunged into academic probation. Worse, he felt
engulfed by despair on his horrid team.
</P>
<P>
   ``People didn't care,'' he said. ``Nobody had faith.'' He quoted
a coach, before one game: ``We don't have a snowball's chance in
hell of winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Gamble said, ``You have to have a mind-set to overcome that
negativity. I wanted to transfer. My parents wouldn't let me.''
</P>
<P>
   Socially, Gamble adapted. As a freshman, he dated a senior on
the basketball team. She graduated and moved home to California. He
visited her during spring break, and they swung by Las Vegas. Never
before a gambler, he was exposed to a fascinating new world.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was such a rush,'' he said, ``a quick way to make a buck.''
</P>
<P>
   Gamble approached these games of chance as he would games of
football or soccer _ a contest that you win by outworking or
outsmarting your opponent, whether it be a defensive back or a
dealer. ``That's where I got in trouble,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   They cashed in enough chips to pay for the Vegas trip, with $400
left over. Right off the bat, Gamble had a distorted perception of
gaming. Sometimes, when you win, you really lose.
</P>
<P>
   Gambling escalates
</P>
<P>
   Before Gamble's sophomore season, in 1992, Francis Peay was
replaced by the inspirational Gary Barnett. In his introductory
team address, Barnett enthused about guiding the Purple to Pasadena
_ the Rose Bowl _ a path last traveled in '49. Many players thought
Barnett was wack but Gamble welcomed him. ``He gave me a fresh
start.'' He also gave Gamble, no shrinking violet for the Purple,
jersey No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   If Gamble wasn't a team leader in the locker room, he was in the
living quarters. He helped organize poker games on Tuesdays and
Thursdays. The stakes would start at a nickel, dime or quarter, but
inevitably would escalate to a dollar. The luckiest player might
walk away from the table with a $200 profit.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Gamble found a slice of Las Vegas in the Midwest. Maybe
twice a month as a senior, now living off campus, he would take
what was left over from his $700 monthly scholarship stipend checks
after paying the bills and head to riverboat casinos on the
Desplaines River in nearby Joliet, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   More often than not, he won. But as the gambling gods giveth at
the blackjack and craps tables, they taketh away at the sports
bookmaker.
</P>
<P>
   At first, the wagers were small, five or 10 bucks per football
game. For a gambler, that's dipping a toe in the water before
diving in. Gamble had no trouble finding a bookie. Brian Ballarini
arrived at Northwestern on a football scholarship but an injury
ended his college career before it began. He maintained a rapport
with former teammates by accepting bets from them.
</P>
<P>
   Gamble became a regular, and a semi-regular loser. He remembers
plunking down $300 one Sunday in 1993 on Pittsburgh, a 1 1/2-point
favorite at home against the Browns, after hearing Cleveland return
specialist Eric Metcalf was hurt. He turned on the TV for the
kickoff. ``And who do I see warming up?'' he said. ``Eric
Metcalf.''
</P>
<P>
   Metcalf dragged his sore knee to punt returns of 91 and 75 yards
for touchdowns as the Browns won 28-23. ``Soon as I lost that
$300,'' Gamble said, ``I thought, `I'm gonna get it back.'''
</P>
<P>
   How? Increase the next bet.
</P>
<P>
   The wagers were not placed blindly. He would analyze matchups
and conclude, say, that a Big Ten member he had faced lacked
sufficient speed against a team from another conference. Yet, his
debt to Ballarini skied to about $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Then Gamble went from dumb to dumber. He bet against his own
team.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 1, 1994, Ohio State was favored by 15 points. ``To me,
it was almost a no-brainer,'' he said, to assume that his team
would fall by far worse. ``Our quarterback was hurt. They'd beat us
51-3 the year before. We were 1-1-1. I thought we were going to get
killed.''
</P>
<P>
   Gamble wanted to erase his entire tab with a single bet, but
Ballarini limited him to $500 on the Ohio State game.
</P>
<P>
   You'd have to be double-jointed to bend over backward far enough
to justify such a desperate act. But Gamble tries: ``I knew going
in that what I was doing was wrong, but I didn't see the harm in
it. I was betting with a kid at school, not a (professional)
bookie.''
</P>
<P>
   Gamble insists that he played hard that day. ``I was trying to
get to the NFL. I still had a job to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Alas, so did his teammates. Northwestern led 9-0 at halftime.
For a moment, the money was forgotten. ``Wow,'' Gamble said to
himself, ``we're going to a bowl. We've turned it around.''
</P>
<P>
   When it was clear the Wildcats would cover the spread, meaning
they would not lose by more than 15 points, Gamble remembered the
bet. He told fellow receiver and co-captain Michael Senters,
another suspected gambler, ``I just bought myself a $500 bowl
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Turns out, he only bought himself more trouble. The worst
possible scenario unfolded. Northwestern lost 17-15 when a
potentially game-tying two-point conversion carry by the dazzling
running back Dennis Lundy fell short. Gamble was a double loser,
game and bet. He was $1,600 in the red, so the senior who had
started college with a $100 bank account opened by his mother and
now was risking five times that amount on games and got cut off by
his bookie.
</P>
<P>
   Ballarini was not, however, lacking for business. In a plea
agreement, he confirmed that 12 to 15 players were customers.
</P>
<P>
   One was Lundy, who also invested $500 on the Ohio State game.
His ballooning debt dated to the season opener, when he risked $200
on Northwestern against Notre Dame. The Wildcats, underdogs by 26
points, closed to within 27 on a late touchdown. Lundy sprinted
onto the field so he, instead of some backup, could run in the
two-point conversion and ensure his team would cover the spread.
</P>
<P>
   Innocently, the coaches summoned him back. As Lundy agonized on
the bench, the conversion failed and Notre Dame rewarded its fans _
and bettors _ with a 42-15 win.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Gamble, who rarely touched the ball most games, Lundy
could affect an outcome. His was the most frequently called number
in the huddle. And it was called during the season's penultimate
game at Iowa after the Hawkeyes had handed over a fumble at their
1-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   The next play went to Lundy, whose team was a 5 1/2-point
underdog and trailed 35-14. Lundy fumbled it right back _ unhit.
</P>
<P>
   On the sideline, a defensive player getting his ankle taped
muttered that Lundy must have bet on a game again. The trainer
tipped off a graduate assistant, and up the chain of command went
the hot-potato remark, all the way to Barnett. By Monday, a school
investigation was under way.
</P>
<P>
   Gamble dismissed the rumors about Lundy. ``You'd gotta be
crazy'' to fumble intentionally, he thought. ``No one would do
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Lundy did, to relieve a debt. When Iowa won 49-13, his tab with
Ballarini shrunk by $400.
</P>
<P>
   Scandal unravels
</P>
<P>
   One more game, one final loss, and Gamble was gone, having
relished only 11 victories in college after his two Lovett teams
went 25-2. He yearned to play on a winner again and, undrafted by
the NFL, signed a free-agent contract with the Minnesota Vikings.
</P>
<P>
   In training camp, he disappeared amid a crowd of veteran
receivers and ultimately was waived, but that was the least of his
troubles. The agents calling him now were not sports agents.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI had entered the Northwestern case. Gamble was
interviewed twice, then appeared before a grand jury. Some
excerpts:
</P>
<P>
   _ On whether he ever owed Ballarini $1,600: ``I don't recall
ever being in debt to him that much.''
</P>
<P>
   _ On how frequently he bet: ``Maybe once a month, maybe twice a
month.''
</P>
<P>
   _ On whether he had to pay an interest charge, known as
``juice,'' on losing bets: ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   Authorities eventually totaled up three lies. They claim he did
owe $1,600, that he bet several times a week for a total of $10,000
to $15,000 and that he paid juice _ a bookmaker's profit.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing for his future in pro football, Gamble says he tried to
make it sound like innocent fun.
</P>
<P>
   He was summoned back by the FBI two years later, confessed to
lying and returned to the grand jury. He told the truth but not
nothing-but-the-truth. One response came back to haunt him.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Any betting with respect to Northwestern University games?
</P>
<P>
   A. No, not on football.
</P>
<P>
   He explains now: ``There was nothing I was ashamed of except
that. So I lied.''
</P>
<P>
   After the second grand jury appearance, Gamble figured his legal
business was done. He still had no lawyer, a potentially grievous
lapse in judgment because one might have advised him to plead the
Fifth Amendment and decline to answer questions about his betting.
Gamble says he was confused by his interrogators' instructions on
that option, but assistant district attorney and prosecutor Patrick
Collins says his rights were ``exhaustively'' made clear to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had I gotten an attorney from Day One,'' he said in the
interview at his townhouse, ``I would not be here talking to you
about this.''
</P>
<P>
   With his latest lie, the investigators' gloves came off. They
pursued him to Atlanta for more questioning. ``This time,'' he
said, ``they weren't playing around.''
</P>
<P>
   They blamed him for dragging out the inquiry. They stressed the
gravity of perjury. Gamble, the journalism grad, followed the news.
He knew what Bill Clinton was going through in the Monica Lewinsky
scandal. He got scared.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, he came clean. And he continued to unfurl a tale about
which investigators knew next to nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is the guy that turned us on to the whole basketball
thing,'' Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   Gamble detailed how he and a pal had put guard Dion Lee in
contact with Kevin Pendergast, a former high school soccer
All-American and Notre Dame kicker turned bookie. How Gamble drove
Lee, who owed him money, to Buffalo Joe's restaurant. How Lee went
in, returned to the car clutching an envelope filled with cash and
gave some to Gamble. The money apparently was Lee's payoff for
throwing a game.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with those leads, investigators discovered evidence of
three basketball games fixed by Lee and two teammates in the
1994-95 season.
</P>
<P>
   Family last to know
</P>
<P>
   Last Dec. 4, Gamble was indicted on two counts of perjury. He
had kept his father Rich, now a Naval Investigative Service special
agent in St. Marys on the southeast Georgia coast, in the dark.
Rich was out, on his daily swim, and missed Chris' call on the eve
of the announcement.
</P>
<P>
   When he turned on ESPN, Rich heard that four players from
Northwestern's 1994 team had been indicted. He thought, ``Hmm, must
be some of Chris' friends.'' The first name reported was his son's.
</P>
<P>
   (Chris said he also hid the matter from his mother. She declined
to be interviewed for this story.)
</P>
<P>
   Gamble eventually pleaded guilty. The sentence, which includes
three years' probation, requires him to share his ordeal on behalf
of the NCAA with athletes at other universities.
</P>
<P>
   His only speech so far was directed to a rapt audience of about
100 at Georgia State. Gamble felt nervous but not from stage
fright; at Northwestern he often addressed high school groups.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting on the edge of a stage, declining a microphone, Gamble
made the painfully public confession that he had humiliated his
parents, disgraced the family name, threatened his career
ambitions. ``For the rest of my life,'' he said, ``when I fill out
a job application, I need to check the `convicted felon' box.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Saum, the NCAA director of agent and gambling activities,
and Cathy Jones, GSU assistant athletics director for compliance,
described the scene in identical words: ``You could hear a pin
drop.''
</P>
<P>
   Saum: ``He's a very eloquent young man. He has a gift _ relating
to athletes.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones: ``It was much more effective than us saying to
student-athletes, `Just don't do it.' I'm hoping to invite him
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Gamble was not connected to game-fixing and because he
lifted the veil on basketball gambling, a sentence shorter than the
6-to 12-month guidelines was recommended. But if Gamble hoped to
get off scot-free, he was deluding himself. The judge also had to
weigh a more recent run-in with the law.
</P>
<P>
   Gamble had taken work at the Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch clothing store
in Cumberland Mall. Last year, he pleaded guilty to theft by taking
and shoplifting, which resulted in five years' probation. Cobb
County prosecutors say he issued 48 fraudulent cash refunds to
friends totaling $6,885.61. They say he ``removed'' $232.50 worth
of merchandise from the store and helped three friends ``remove''
$406 in goods.
</P>
<P>
   Gamble says the refund scam _ taking liberties with employee
discounts _ was commonly practiced by the store's sales staff.
Asked for comment, a spokesman at Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch corporate
offices said he would look into Gamble's sweeping accusation but
did not respond.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why he so often exercised poor judgment, Gamble thought
long and hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``My friends,'' he said, ``tell me that I'm someone who doesn't
always see the big picture.''
</P>
<P>
   Vernetta Gamble was in Chicago for the perjury sentencing. Rich
Gamble was not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think what he did was that grave _ more of an immature
thing than criminal,'' he said. ``But what Chris did could easily
have been avoided if he'd only to come me first.'' Because he did
not, Rich reasoned, Chris was on his own.
</P>
<P>
   Chris portrays his father as a proud, image-conscious man
``24/7.'' As a cop whose beat was the downtown Atlanta Zone 5, Rich
would go to work each morning with a goal of catching five felons.
``And pretty much for one year,'' he said, ``I did.'' His scrapbook
documents five awards for outstanding police work.
</P>
<P>
   On the mornings before his shift began, Rich would haul young
Chris out of bed. Dad would strap on his bulletproof vest to
simulate chasing criminals, and they would run wind sprints up the
steep Peachtree Hills streets. ``That's why Chris is so fast,''
Rich said. ``And I was the second-fastest cop in the department.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, he admits to being one resentful father. ``Of course, I
am,'' he said. ``Look at what it's cost him.''
</P>
<P>
   Avoid mistakes in life, he preached to Chris almost daily when
they lived together, ``because society makes you pay if you're a
minority. Now he has this anchor to drag around the rest of his
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris feels an occasional tug on that anchor. A letter arrived
shortly before he was off to prison advising him that, as a felon,
he could no longer vote. In contrast to most young adults, he had
never missed an election since turning 18. The letter provoked
thoughts of African-Americans throughout history who had been
turned away at the ballot box, and now he was one of them _ by his
own hand.
</P>
<P>
   Chris believes his father is finally coming to grips with his
missteps. Not long ago, they fly-fished together, a tradition that
dates back to when Chris was 8 and the kid fell into freezing
waters after insisting he tag along. Dad made him shiver, soaking
wet, until the fishing was done. Tough love always was Rich's
style.
</P>
<P>
   Rich received a letter the other day _ return address, Atlanta
Federal Pen. Chris depicted life there as ``football camp without
the football.''
</P>
<P>
   `Chris was a con'
</P>
<P>
   Gamble's legacy at Northwestern is muddled. There were his three
seasons as a starter. His 10-catch, 146-yard gem against Illinois,
a 27-26 win after his team trailed by three touchdowns, that earned
him Big Ten Player of the Week. A six-catch game against Michigan.
Consistently high grades for performance by coaches. Effective
recruiting pitches to young prospects, which helped fulfill that
crazy Gary Barnett's Rose Bowl promise _ just one year after Gamble
left.
</P>
<P>
   But there is also Gamble's bitterness toward the university for
``abandoning us.'' And there is Barnett's lasting impression of
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chris was a con,'' said Barnett, newly named coach at
Colorado. ``When I talked to him about the gambling, he lied to me.
I found him likable at first, but I got burned by Chris, and I
don't trust him. We were constantly having to get Chris to do the
right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   And as a player?
</P>
<P>
   ``Chris was fast. Decent in practice,'' he said. ``He just never
made the big catches'' in games.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven persons connected to Northwestern gambling, including
four football and three basketball players, were indicted. Nine
have pleaded guilty _ four to sports bribery, four to perjury, one
to interstate gambling. (Among the perjurers was Dennis Lundy, who
left Northwestern as its career rushing leader despite the yards he
sacrificed on plays to win his bet.) Michael Senters was sent to
pre-trial diversion.
</P>
<P>
   The only case left hanging involves Dwight Brown, a football
player, who has pleaded innocent to perjury. His trial is scheduled
for Oct. 5.
</P>
<P>
   By then, Gamble hopes to be back on the job as a buyer for an
unidentified large corporation that promised to hold the position
open, playing golf, worshipping in church, warning college athletes
about the perils of gambling and avoiding all manner of betting
except the occasional Super Bowl or March Madness pool. He no
longer peeks at point spreads in the newspaper and tells friends
who ask for advice on a game that he cannot help them.
</P>
<P>
   The closest he has gotten lately to full-scale wagering was at
the movies. He paraphrases the Matt Damon character in
``Rounders,'' a poker player, reciting the gambler's lament: ``Not
many true gamblers can tell you about the pots they've won, only
pots they've lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Gamble's biggest bet was not at the card table, nor at the
casino, nor at the bookmaker's. It was at the grand jury, when he
bet that he could lie and get away with it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
