<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-NOTES25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FSU's Bowden counters son's pitches perfectly
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Some leftovers from last week's ACC football meetings:
</P>
<P>
   _ Florida State coach Bobby Bowden turns 70 on Nov. 8 but don't
think for a minute he's any less competitive. Son Tommy, now the
head coach at Clemson, tells the story about brother Terry who,
during his early days at Auburn, used age against his father in the
recruiting process. Terry Bowden started telling recruits that his
father probably wouldn't be coaching much longer in an effort to
lure them away from Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Bowden had the perfect, but chilling, response.
</P>
<P>
   ``Daddy let it go for about two weeks before he decided to
respond,'' said Tommy Bowden. ``Then he started telling recruits:
`I'll be at Florida State longer than Terry will be at Auburn.'
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't mess with Daddy. He's still pretty sharp.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The ACC missed a chance to lock in a fifth bowl agreement when
the Music City Bowl in Nashville signed a deal with the Big East.
The ACC currently has teams guaranteed to the Bowl Championship
Series, the Gator, Peach, and Micron PC Bowls.
</P>
<P>
   The ACC coaches can't understand why the league can't get half
its teams locked into bowls, while the SEC has seven slots
reserved. Several coaches admitted that SEC schools use it against
them in recruiting.
</P>
<P>
   Expect the ACC to pursue a slot in the new Mobile Alabama Bowl
being run by ESPN analyst Mike Gottfried. This year's game will
match the WAC No. 2 against Conference USA No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Atlanta Sport Council is talking to the conference about
bringing the ACC men's basketball tournament to the Georgia Dome in
2005 and 2006. League officials first want to see how the event
fares at the Dome in 2001, its first trip back to Atlanta since
1989. But if the ACC waits that long, the SEC will probably come in
and lock up the Dome with a multiyear deal. The SEC Tournament is
here in 2000 and 2002, in Nashville in 2001, and in New Orleans in
2003.
</P>
<P>
   _ N.C. State coach Mike O'Cain suddenly has a lot of friends who
wear North Carolina blue. O'Cain's team opens the season on Aug. 28
at Texas, coached by Mack Brown. The Tar Heels are not happy with
Brown, who left Chapel Hill suddenly in March of 1998. ``I had one
guy tell me that it hurt him to pull for N.C. State, but that he
hoped we beat their butts,'' said O'Cain.
</P>
<P>
   _ Virginia has lost its best linebacker, Donny Green, to
academics. ``Yeah, I saw it coming,'' said coach George Welsh.
</P>
<P>
   _ Florida State wide receiver Peter Warrick, who will likely be
taken near the top of next year's NFL draft, has a $3 million
insurance policy against a career-ending injury. The policy is
sponsored by the NCAA.
</P>
<P>
   One man's opinion
</P>
<P>
   Keith Dunnavant has an interesting feature in his newest Paydirt
Illustrated magazine. He lists 10 ``Plays of the Century'' in SEC
football. Among them are Alabama's goal-line stand against Penn
State in the 1979 Sugar Bowl and the 93-yard Buck Belue-to-Lindsay
Scott pass that lifted Georgia over Florida in 1980. It's good
reading.
</P>
<P>
   _ Another reason to be frustrated with the NCAA. A 27-member
panel charged with improving academic performance in college
basketball, where only 41 percent of the players graduate, tries to
tie scholarships to graduation rate. Graduate all the players, get
14 scholarships. Graduate none, get 12. That's incentive?
</P>
<P>
   _ A recommendation that will improve the academic standing of
all athletes: Mandatory attendance at summer school before the fall
of the freshman year. Athletes should learn where the library is
located before attending their first practice. The cost would be
part of the scholarship. In some cases we have college football
players who participate in a game before they attend their first
class. Wrong, wrong, wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Worth noting
</P>
<P>
   Arkansas defensive end Carlos Hall has been arrested on a
forgery complaint. Police say he stole three checks made out to the
school and cashed them at a bank.
</P>
<P>
   _ Former athletics director Tom Butters will be among five new
members enshrined into the Duke Sports Hall of Fame on Sept. 24.
Butters' ability as an administator and fund-raiser made him one of
the most powerful athletics directors in the country. He also hired
a little-known guy named Mike Krzyzewski as the school's basketball
coach.
</P>
<P>
   _ Former Vanderbilt football coach George MacIntyre is battling
multiple sclerosis. MacIntyre, 58, first felt the symptoms of MS
two years ago. He was the last Vandy coach to beat Tennessee and
Alabama and take the Commodores to a bowl game. He lives in
Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Knoxville News-Sentinel reported this week that John
Rattay, the brother of Louisiana Tech quarterback Tim Rattay,
visited Tennessee last week. John Rattay, from Tempe, Ariz., is
also a quarterback prospect.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
