</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990724.0154 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-24 15:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2695 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS-FEELING25     07-24 1270
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-FEELING25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Respect finally is Falcons'
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Like just about everyone else who knew anything of the
Falcons, Dan Reeves drew a quick first impression. It wasn't good.
After interviewing to become head coach, he embraced the majority
opinion.
</P>
<P>
   This was a hopeless franchise, and it wasn't just the sight of a
weight room without a floor, of weights resting on dirt under the
stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves, a native of Americus, Ga., was picking up all kinds of
bad vibes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to come in the worst way because this was coming back
home,'' he said. ``But it just wasn't the right time.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, 1977 was 20 years too early. Reeves, then 32, had just
finished his first season as offensive coordinator of the Dallas
Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons, on the other hand, had two winning seasons in their
first 11. The '76 season was a mess, as Marion Campbell was
replaced after going 1-4 by Pat Peppler, who went 3-6.
</P>
<P>
   But as defending NFC champions, the Falcons' image has changed.
With their training camp opening days away, most of the improvement
seems to have happened since Reeves arrived in '97.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons began 1-7, but closed 6-2.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, not even Reeves' open-heart surgery in December
could derail a train than went 16-3, and wasn't derailed until
falling to Denver in Super Bowl XXXIII.
</P>
<P>
   It almost made president Taylor Smith and the family that has
owned the team since '66 forget the worst of the past.
</P>
<P>
   It's impossible, though, not to remember all the ugly
comparisons made by media and fans of the family of late owner
Rankin Smith, and the Clampetts, the hillbilly clan of TV fame that
struck it rich in oil and moved to Beverly Hills.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hell, it was (late Journal-Constitution columnist) Lewis
Grizzard (who coined the comparison),'' Smith said, ``and then...
Sports Illustrated wrote an article about how (Atlanta was)
Losersville, that we were the two worst pro franchises in one city,
the Braves and Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to get those... tags. The name fit, though, in
tough times.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons' track record for bungling things was immense, and
not just on the field. Rankin Sr., who was born into a wealthy
family that founded the Life Insurance Co. of Georgia, bought the
team for $8.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   He had no clue how to run a football team. And differences
between the team's scouting and coaching staffs exacerbated the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Rankin Sr. often made the final decisions anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, at times folks were as interested in his private
life, which was marked by occasional legal scandals, battles with
alcohol and occasional buffoonery.
</P>
<P>
   There was the time he and friend and their dates put a yacht on
automatic pilot, and, while drinking scotch, rammed the boat into a
reef off Bimini.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taking trips with him was like one of those National Lampoon
Vacation movies, with Chevy Chase,'' his first wife, Meme Smith,
told the Wall Street Journal. ``He'd make all these plans and
everything would go wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   It got better for a while when Rankin Jr. was made club
president in '77, although his interview with Reeves didn't work
out.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did Reeves cringe at the spartan weight room under team
offices in Atlanta-Fulton County Stadium, but he didn't much like
the fact that when the Braves were playing, the Falcons had to bus
to a park just to practice.
</P>
<P>
   There was more.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were talking about hiring Eddie LeBaron, a former Cowboys
quarterback, as general manager at the same time,'' Reeves
recalled. ``I respect LeBaron, but he wasn't even involved in
football at the time. He was an attorney in Las Vegas.''
</P>
<P>
   So the team hired Leeman Bennett, who engineered the best
stretch in franchise history, going 7-7, 9-7, 6-10, 12-4, 7-9 and
5-4. He was fired, he was told, because he couldn't take the team
to the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   By the late '80s, Rankin Jr. was embroiled in a messy paternity
suit, and stepped down as president. To this day, although he
remains on the board of directors, he's virtually invisible.
</P>
<P>
   Fast-forwarding through the mostly ill-fated tenures of coaches
Dan Henning, Marion Campbell (again), Jim Hanifan (briefly), Jerry
Glanville and June Jones, an important decision was made.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves was hired.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had dug a big hole,'' Taylor Smith said. ``I don't want to
get into it, but it was just a fact that we operated that way (with
coaching and scouting staffs with separate agendas) for a long
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we always said, if we ever had a chance to hire somebody
like Dan, we wanted to do it. The change began as soon as Dan got
here. It was all about leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   And power.
</P>
<P>
   ``My major concern was that if I'm going to be given the
responsibility,'' he said, ``I wanted the authority.''
</P>
<P>
   And so he does. Reeves signs off on virtually every move.
Scouting department reports are reviewed by the coaches. But Reeves
makes the final calls there, too.
</P>
<P>
   Just as important is a new mind-set.
</P>
<P>
   He remembered from his first interview being surprised to learn
that the Falcons didn't factor character or intelligence into draft
strategy.
</P>
<P>
   His team, however, is based as much on that as X's and O's.
</P>
<P>
   The team fell to 1-7 in `97 the day after Rankin Sr. died, only
to go 22-5 since then.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely, it's a coincidence'' Reeves said. ``They made a
commitment to change, and they were going to have somebody run the
football operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a special kind of person (to be a player). If you've
got to use the whip every day, you're not going to be successful.
You've got to have people who are self-motivated.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the biggest ingredients in last year's success _ and
perhaps the most unstable _ was chemistry on a roster assembled
largely by Reeves and his staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``You definitely get a feel that there's more discipline,'' said
defensive end Lester Archambeau, who was acquired in trade from the
Green Bay Packers in `93. ``Guys seem more committed to the sport.
With that, you get a better character of person on and off the
field.''
</P>
<P>
   The effect can be found at the ticket office, at cash registers
from coast to coast and publicity for the players.
</P>
<P>
   Season ticket sales are up about 10,500, about 35 percent. At
this time last year the Falcons were 29th in merchandise sold
nationally, trailing even the nonexistent Cleveland Browns.
</P>
<P>
   This year, they're 20th.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons were valued last year at $233 million.
</P>
<P>
   Last week in Aspen, Colo., Falcons running back Jamal Anderson
appeared in a fund-raiser to fight breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing the reach the Falcons have all of the sudden,''
said Brian McCarthy, the NFL's corporate communications manager.
``Jamal couldn't go four or five feet without somebody stopping him
and asking him to do the `Dirty Bird' (dance).''
</P>
<P>
   But success can be fleeting.
</P>
<P>
   Several personnel moves could catch up with the Falcons, or the
injury bug they largely avoided last season could bite hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had one year of success,'' Reeves said. ``To me, it's
only going to change if we do it on a consistent basis, and compete
to where fans can be proud of us year in and year out.''
</P>
<P>
   Archambeau is enjoying it while he can.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I know is that (before) I was walking around town, and
nobody cared that I played for the Falcons,'' he said. ``I probably
get stopped about 10 times more than before. It's like a
caterpillar that goes into a cocoon and comes out a beautiful
butterfly.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
