<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-24 15:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2696 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOELESS25-COX     07-24 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOELESS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Shoeless made mark in Americus
 &HT;    By Guy Curtright
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMERICUS, Ga. _ The real ``Shoeless Joe'' didn't vanish when he
was banned from organized baseball, not to reappear on a diamond
again until an Iowa farmer plowed under part of his cornfield.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Jackson played and managed anywhere and everywhere he could,
finding his ``Field of Dreams,'' if not redemption, in dusty
ballparks throughout his native South and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson didn't really play in Dyersville, Iowa. But he did swing
his famous ``Black Betsy'' bat in Americus and other towns in
southwest Georgia, where fans flocked to see the former
major-league star.
</P>
<P>
   A marker outside Thomas Bell Stadium tells part of the rest of
the story, but it is misleading. Although seemingly ancient, the
wooden stadium wasn't built until 1938. The summer that Jackson
briefly put Americus in the nation's sports headlines was 15 years
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   It was 1923, just two years after Jackson and seven Chicago
White Sox teammates were banned for life by commissioner Kenesaw
Mountain Landis, even though they were acquitted in court of
throwing the 1919 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Ignoring the Landis edict, the Americus team of the independent
South Georgia League signed Jackson for $75 a week on July 16 _ and
touched off a firestorm.
</P>
<P>
   Although technically not under his domain, other teams in the
unofficial minor league were fearful of Landis, who threatened to
ban anyone who played with or against any of the Black Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Several newspaper writers came out strongly against Jackson,
with sports editor Morgan Blake of The Atlanta Journal likening him
to Benedict Arnold and claiming that some crimes can never be
forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   But Jackson said his foes ``were making a tempest out of a
teapot'' and said opposing teams were afraid of ``that long bat I
swing.'' He took the field at Americus on July 20 against
Bainbridge and hit a triple in his first at-bat, then a double in
his second. Despite rain, 600 fans turned out on a Friday afternoon
at the old Barlow ballpark, next to the Americus swimming pool.
</P>
<P>
   As Jackson, managing as well as batting cleanup and playing
right field, continued to hit, the crowds grew bigger and the
protests fewer. Everyone wanted to see Jackson, who had just turned
34 and feasted on South Georgia League pitching after hitting .356
during a 13-year major league career.
</P>
<P>
   The Americus team, formed by Bell, was in last place in the
six-team league when Jackson arrived. But it won the second half of
the split season and played Albany for the title in what was
advertised as Georgia's Little World Series.
</P>
<P>
   With Jackson going 11-for-22 and hitting two homers in the
second game, Americus won the series in six games. The opener in
Americus drew more than 2,000. Capacity crowds had become the norm
everywhere Jackson played.
</P>
<P>
   Fans came to see Jackson hit, but he also thrilled them in the
field. An over-the-shoulder catch he made in the playoffs was
called by an Americus sportswriter ``the most sensational and
spectacular play ever seen on a minor-league diamond.''
</P>
<P>
   But an appearance by the infamous ``Shoeless Joe'' was treated
as more than just a game. It was an event. Band concerts and
barbecues frequently preceded the games. One poster told the fans,
``This is the day that you young married people can tell your
children about in the afteryears.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson had played in the North and Southwest under assumed
names before coming to Americus, but he clearly enjoyed displaying
his talents again in his native South. He owned a cleaning business
in Savannah and called the coastal Georgia city home for most of
the 1920s before moving back to Greenville, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the 1923 season, Jackson took out a lease on the
poolroom at the Windsor Hotel, and Americus fans hoped he would be
back to play the next season.
</P>
<P>
   But on Sept. 6, Jackson and pitcher Lefty Wingard signed with a
team in Waycross. Jackson played with several teams in the next few
years, with Waycross being one of his common stops.
</P>
<P>
   The South Georgia League _ which had been made up of Americus,
Albany, Bainbridge, Blakely, Dawson and Arlington _ wasn't around
in 1924, anyway. Dawson and Arlington disbanded a week before the
end of the 1923 season, and Bainbridge didn't show up for a final
regular-season series at Americus.
</P>
<P>
   Hard feelings remained about the use of Jackson and other
questionable players, many of whom had been blacklisted from
oraganized baseball. Thomas Bell had resigned from his duties with
the Americus team before the first game of the Albany championship
series because of a dispute over players and umpires.
</P>
<P>
   In 1935, Americus joined official minor-league baseball and
played in the Georgia-Florida League until the early 1950s. Bell
became mayor and led the push for a new stadium, which opened on
July 12, 1938. The Barlow ballpark, where Jackson had played, was
torn down in 1942.
</P>
<P>
   Despite continued talk that Jackson should be in the Hall of
Fame, his days in Americus are all but forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people who would have seen him play are long since
dead,'' said Gilly Pervis, 92. ``That was a long time ago.''
</P>
<P>
   JOE JACKSON FILE
</P>
<P>
   Born: July 16, 1889, in Pickens County, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   Died: Dec. 5, 1951, in Greenville, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   Nickname: ``Shoeless Joe'' was bestowed on him in 1908 after he
played in a minor-league game for Greenville at Anderson, S.C.,
without his spikes because of blisters on his feet.
</P>
<P>
   Family: Married Katie Wynn in 1908. No children.
</P>
<P>
   Position: Outfield.
</P>
<P>
   Major-league teams: Played with Philadelphia A's (1908-09),
Cleveland Indians (1910-15) and Chicago White Sox (1916-20).
</P>
<P>
   Career stats: Hit .356, with a high of .408 in 1911. Hit .382 in
his final season.
</P>
<P>
   Postseason stats: Hit .304 in the 1918 World Series and .375 in
1919.
</P>
<P>
   Downfall: Accused of collaborating with seven other White Sox
players to throw the 1919 World Series to the Cincinnati Reds. All
players were acquitted by a Chicago jury in 1921. But commissioner
Kenesaw Mountain Landis still banned them for life for associating
with gamblers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
