<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HOUSECLEANING AT REDSKIN PARK 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The shuffling of the Washington Redskins' front office has
telephone lines burning in the National Football League.
</P>
<P>
   Charley Casserly, one of the most respected general managers in
football, was removed from his old position and is now an adviser
to the Redskins' new owner, Daniel Snyder. He will not be there for
long, league insiders say. Look for him to leave Washington soon
for a position with another team.
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins' new public-relations director, John Konoza,
resigned after only a few days on the job. Snyder dismissed some 25
employees, including secretaries and much of the public-relations
staff. Konoza, perhaps seeing that he was not in the most stable of
situations, left the team.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Vinny Cerrato, the newly hired director of player
personnel. If there is anyone who can help clean up the mess, it's
he.
</P>
<P>
   Cerrato's is not a highly publicized name, but he was the secret
weapon of the San Francisco 49ers' front office for the past eight
years, running both the college and pro personnel departments.
</P>
<P>
   During his tenure, the 49ers, always picking near the bottom of
every round because they were regularly in the playoffs, still
managed to draft excellent players. They included wide receivers
Terrell Owens and J.J. Stokes and safety Merton Hanks.
</P>
<P>
   From 1991 until this year, Cerrato was involved in one way or
another with bringing every player to the 49ers except wide
receiver Jerry Rice and quarterback Steve Young. It was that track
record that attracted the Redskins to him.
</P>
<P>
   Now he is responsible for turning around the Redskins, who have
not made the playoffs for six years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we can win immediately without mortgaging the
future,'' he said. ``It's about changing the attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Redskins coach Norv Turner has not been the answer since
replacing Richie Petitbon in 1994. But Turner won a power struggle
that ended with the jettison of Casserly and must know that if he
does not win this season, he will in all probability be unemployed
at the end of it.
</P>
<P>
   Future Brightens for Lett  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dallas Cowboys defensive lineman Leon Lett should breathe a sigh
of relief. He will most likely be playing football after all at
some point this season.
</P>
<P>
   Reports surfaced last week that Lett had applied for
reinstatement to the NFL after being suspended last month for the
third time in four years because of violation of the league's
substance-abuse policy. The reports suggested that commissioner
Paul Tagliabue may be relatively lenient.
</P>
<P>
   Lett faces up to a one-year suspension but Tagliabue has wide
latitude when it comes to punishing violators of the policy. He
apparently feels that since Lett has been tested up to 10 times a
month for the past two years and has not missed any after-care
meetings, he deserves some consideration.
</P>
<P>
   The length of the suspension has not yet been set, though four
games seems most likely. A 10-game suspension, however, remains a
possibility.
</P>
<P>
   Rams Face Problem in Faulk
</P>
<P>
   If the St. Louis Rams are not careful, they could have a
disaster on their hands. Their star running back, Marshall Faulk,
the best all-round back in pro football last year with 1,316 yards
rushing and 86 catches, may be on the verge of a long holdout.
</P>
<P>
   Faulk has failed to report to training camp because he wants a
new deal. He has two years remaining on a contract that pays him
$2.2 million a season, but wants $5 million a year and a signing
bonus of more than $8 million.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis cannot afford to have Faulk in a long holdout. While
Faulk is out of camp, the No. 1 back is Greg Hill. If Coach Dick
Vermeil wants to finally turn the Rams around, Faulk needs to be in
camp soon.
</P>
<P>
   Around the League
</P>
<P>
   _ A common assumption is that Giants quarterback Kent Graham
will be replaced at some point in the season by the backup Kerry
Collins. One thing is certain: Graham is already making it
difficult for Collins to supplant him. Graham is in great shape and
seems mentally prepared for a long battle.
</P>
<P>
   _ The new Green Bay coach, Ray Rhodes, has made believers of his
players. His legendary intensity is considered a positive. Rhodes
simply needs to make sure his intensity does not eventually wear on
the franchise.
</P>
<P>
   _ Denver linebacker Bill Romanowski recently signed a seven-year
deal that will pay him $32.2 million. The chances of his completing
that contract are slim because he will be 39 when it expires in
2005. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
