<SLUG> BC-BBO-HALL-FAME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRETT, YOUNT AND RYAN BRING BIG NUMBERS TO COOPERSTOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Kan., Wis., Texas)  (mk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the meter rolls from 2,999 to 3,000, it's a ``magic
change,'' said a man who has experienced it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like walking on the moon,'' George Brett said. ``It's the
most monumental hit you'll ever get in your career.''
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks apart in September 1992, Brett and Robin Yount
joined the magic circle, becoming the 17th and 18th players to
reach 3,000 hits, and on Sunday they will take another joint step,
going into the Hall of Fame in Cooperstown, N.Y., as players
elected in their first year of eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   Brett and Yount played one more season, retiring after the 1993
season, Brett with 3,154 hits, Yount with 3,142. Nolan Ryan retired
with them. He had given up 3,923 hits. But he also had amassed
5,714 strikeouts, one of his 48 major league records.
</P>
<P>
   Not since 1936, the first year that elections for the Hall were
held, had three players gained entrance in their first year on the
ballot. These three are not strangers to each other. Ryan, in fact,
struck out Brett 18 times and Yount 16. But they were never victims
of any of his record seven no-hitters.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan played so long, retiring when he was 46, that he struck out
seven sets of fathers and sons, including the Griffeys, the
Bondses, the McRaes, the Franconas and the Alomars, all three of
them. He also struck out 12 sets of brothers, including the Bretts,
the Ripkens, the Niekros and all three Alous.
</P>
<P>
   Brett and Yount were only two of 12 players Ryan struck out who
went on to get their 3,000th hit. That means he missed only nine of
the players who reached 3,000 career hits. Cap Anson was just a
little before his time. But Ryan will soon have struck out 15,
because as Brett and Yount enter the Hall, Wade Boggs and Tony
Gwynn approach 3,000 and Cal Ripken is not far behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's by far the greatest achievement I ever had,'' Brett said.
``It's just a mystical, magical moment that happens in someone's
life. It's hard to explain why one hit means so much. The 3,001st
hit is not nearly as exciting as the 3,000th.''
</P>
<P>
   His playoff home run against Rich Gossage that sent the Kansas
City Royals to the 1980 World Series was exciting, Brett said,
``but that doesn't put you in an elite club with some of the
greatest players who played the game.''
</P>
<P>
   During the winter following their entry into that club, Brett
recalled, he and Yount were invited to a dinner with other members
of the 3,000-hit club during a lavish memorabilia show in Atlantic
City.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way they welcomed Robin and me was far greater than I
could have expected,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Hall of Fame isn't as exclusive, but it is the pinnacle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one common factor besides their talent was they both
played the game hard. They played it the right way,'' Mike
Hargrove, the Cleveland Indians' manager, said of Brett and Yount.
``I think you need something other than your talent to make the
Hall of Fame, and Robin and George had it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hargrove was a rookie with Texas in 1974, when Brett was a
rookie with the Royals and Yount was a rookie with the Milwaukee
Brewers. He remembers noticing Brett sooner than Yount, but it was
Ryan, a veteran by then, who made the most indelible impression on
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``My rookie year,'' Hargrove said, ``I tried to bunt against
Nolan and the next two pitches were right at my chest. I thought I
was dead. That convinced me never to try to bunt off Nolan Ryan
again, and I didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Hargrove, whom Ryan struck out nine times, also recalled that
Ryan did not have time for nonsense when he pitched.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nolan was the ultimate competitor,'' the former first baseman
said. ``He really focused in on what he was doing. Nothing was ever
funny to Nolan when he pitched.''
</P>
<P>
   Hargrove recalled that Ryan had a habit of checking the grass
and dirt in front of the mound before throwing his warm-up pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our guys on the Rangers knew he did that,'' Hargrove said,
``and one day in Texas, Clyde Wright took a bunch of plastic
spiders and snakes and salted the area around the mound with them.
Nolan came out and looked around and saw these things. I thought it
was funny. So did Clyde. Nolan didn't think it was funny at all. He
looked over at our bench and looked at Clyde, and Clyde was dying
laughing.''
</P>
<P>
   Ryan was serious enough to gain 324 victories, tying him for
12th on the career list. But his 292 losses are third most and his
2,795 walks are the most in history.
</P>
<P>
   Brett finished with a .305 batting average, and Yount .285.
Yount, who began his major league career at age 18, was the
third-youngest player to reach 3,000 hits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
