<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA: COAST DEMOCRATS CLASH  
 QUAYLE HUMOR  
 CAMPAIGN 2000  
 MISSISSIPPI: L'AFFAIRE FORDICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   California Democrats Duel With Democrats
</P>
<P>
   California Democrats came out of last fall's elections in the
best political shape in decades, capturing the governor's office
for the first time in 16 years and winning the race for lieutenant
governor, as well as winning solid control of both houses of the
state Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Hopes rose for speedy action on the party's governing agenda,
much of it in legislative limbo for years because of standoffs
between Republican governors and Democratic legislative leaders.
</P>
<P>
   But except for passage of a tough assault weapons ban and a few
education reforms and environmental measures, there is little
action. Instead, Democrats are squabbling with Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders of the Democratic majorities in the legislature,
Assembly Speaker Antonio Villaraigosa of Los Angeles and Senate
President Pro Tem John Burton of San Francisco, are liberal,
aggressive, outspoken legislators. They are pressing hard for speed
on such high-cost items as health care changes and workers'
compensation.
</P>
<P>
   But the new governor, Gray Davis, is a cautious, almost dour
centrist with strong ties to California's business community. He
wants to move slowly and, by all means, husband the state's money
and avoid new taxes.
</P>
<P>
   In June he vetoed sections of several health and education
measures that Democrats had pushed to passage, saying they were too
costly and the product of undisciplined legislating.
</P>
<P>
   Then 10 days ago, without taking the usual precaution of
notifying Villaraigosa and Burton, Davis began contacting committee
chairmen and legislation authors directly to discuss action he
wanted or did not want.
</P>
<P>
   Burton, infuriated, called the end run ``a totally improper
intrusion in the legislative process.''
</P>
<P>
   Villaraigosa declared, ``We are not going to allow the
legislative process to be dictated by executive department heads.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor, who is already out raising money for a re-election
bid, says voters gave him a clear mandate to govern last fall when
he won by 20 points. He vows not to back down.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a totally different view of the world than I do,''
he said of Burton and Villaraigosa in an interview on Tuesday with
The San Francisco Chronicle. ``It was my vision that commanded a
20-point victory, the largest victory in 40 years. Their job is to
implement my vision.''
</P>
<P>
   To which Burton countered:
</P>
<P>
   ``I do have an absolutely different view. I believe in checks
and balances.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Quayle Deploys His Sense of Humor
</P>
<P>
   It's a more laid-back Dan Quayle chasing the Republican
nomination this time around. The eyes that once had a startled glow
that resembled, as it was often said, those of a deer caught in
headlights, now have a soft twinkle.
</P>
<P>
   Consider:
</P>
<P>
   Last Thursday, in an appearance on ``The Tonight Show,'' Quayle
held up a name card that he said had come from the door of his
studio dressing room. His name was spelled QUAYL.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no E,'' the former vice president told the show's
host, Jay Leno. ``There's always an E on Quayle. There's an E on
every word. Right?'
</P>
<P>
   As in potatoe.
</P>
<P>
   And self-depreciatione.
</P>
<P>
   Will it help?
</P>
<P>
   Bobbie Gobel, the director of the Christian Coalition in Iowa,
has her doubts. She says that there are far too many Republicans
running and that some should drop out, especially some of the
hard-right conservatives who are competing for the Christian right
vote. If more than one or two of the ``godly'' candidates stay in,
she argues, the rather sizable and influential Christian vote could
be splintered into a meaningless mess.
</P>
<P>
   So the other day, said The Arizona Republic, Ms. Gobel raised
the issue with Quayle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him,'' she told the paper, ``that we had too many
candidates. With the buffoon thing, did he think he could wiggle
out of it?''
</P>
<P>
   His reply, as relayed by Ms. Gobel:
</P>
<P>
   ``If God is in this, I will be the next president of the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   No Issue Dominates The 2000 Campaign
</P>
<P>
   In the 1992 presidential election, a struggling national economy
was the big issue, as summed up by that year's Democratic catch
phrase, ``It's the economy, stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the big issue was still the economy _ an economy
rolling along so well that President Clinton was able to coast to
re-election.
</P>
<P>
   So what's the big issue for Election 2000?
</P>
<P>
   Not the economy, says the Pew Research Center for the People and
the Press. According to a new poll conducted by the nonpartisan
study group, based in Washington, the economy is now rolling along
so merrily that it ranks No. 11 with voters as a pressing political
issue.
</P>
<P>
   The current most worrisome issue is health care, the poll found,
followed, in order, by Social Security, Medicare, education, taxes,
the national debt, crime, gun control, foreign policy, national
morality, the economy and, finally, welfare reform.
</P>
<P>
   But as Pew Center director Andrew Kohut sees it, none of those
issues is likely to dominate the 2000 campaign as the economy
dominated the 1992 and 1996 campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``None are so overriding,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Road Signs Figure In L'Affaire Fordice
</P>
<P>
   In our last installment of the Fordice Saga, Kirk, the governor
of Mississippi, and Pat, his wife of 44 years, were at a marital
impasse.
</P>
<P>
   After a weeklong liaison in France with an old high school
sweetheart, the Republican governor was back home in Jackson,
pressing for a divorce, threatening to thrash nosy reporters and
insisting there was no parallel between his extramarital behavior
and that of President Clinton, whose resignation he repeatedly
demanded during the impeachment inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Fordice, for her part, was hanging tough, refusing to decamp
from the Executive Mansion and saying that while the governor might
want her gone, she did not view their marriage as ``some sort of
romantic comedy'' and would fight to salvage it.
</P>
<P>
   Then she apologized ``for being a partner in a marriage that has
become a source of embarrassment for Mississippi.''
</P>
<P>
   Now today's installment, in which we learn just how deep that
embarrassment runs for some Mississippians. . .
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, at a cost of $1,200, Republican leaders in
Vicksburg erected two signs at the city's limits that proudly
informed drivers they were entering the ``home of Governor Kirk
Fordice.'' But a few days ago, the city ordered the signs removed,
with several officials explaining that in light of the governor's
marital problems, the proud message the signs once sent had become
garbled.
</P>
<P>
   One sign had been spray-painted with the word ``hypocrite.'' The
other had been bashed to pieces.
</P>
<P>
   A city alderman, Sam Habeeb, a Republican, said that while he
belonged to the same political party as the governor, he
nevertheless favored removal of the signs ``to remove the mixed or
ambiguous messages that are out there about marital loyalty.''
</P>
<P>
   An alderwoman, Gertrude Young, a Democrat, said City Hall had
received a number of complaints about the signs after word got out
about the Governor's trip to France. Anyway, she noted, the
governor no longer owns a home in Vicksburg.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's spokesman, Robbie Wilbur, urged Mississippians to
consider ``the big picture.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The city of Vicksburg and the state of Mississippi,'' he said,
``are better off since the Fordice administration took office.''
</P>
<P>
   Stay tuned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
