<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-24 15:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2706 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-SARATOGA-NYT &LR;      07-24 1183
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-SARATOGA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MONEY MACHINE LIKE SARATOGA CAN RUN ON GOOD, AGED WOOD 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
Tom Durkin is the track announcer for the New York Racing
Association. 
 By TOM DURKIN  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With 25,000 people expected to show up for
Wednesday's opening of America's most popular, most successful and
arguably most beautiful race track, it's hard to believe that
Saratoga's viability was ever questioned.
</P>
<P>
   But in the 1950s, when newness and bigness reigned and plastic
was king, Saratoga Race Course, with its intimate wood-beamed
grandstand and authentic Victorian ambience, did not enjoy the
overwhelming success it has today.
</P>
<P>
   Eisenhower-era Saratoga did not hold the widespread democratic
appeal that it now relishes in the retro-starved '90s.
Society-minded Saratoga has always attracted the ``right'' people,
but in the '50s it did not attract a lot of people.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, downstate in Queens they were building a brand new
race track of glass and steel. Aqueduct was going to be a big track
for big crowds just a short ride away on the A train. Promotional
material would boast of 35,000 cubic yards of concrete work and
8,500 tons of structural steel framing. The Big A was the
architectural antithesis of Saratoga. It would have elevators,
escalators, air-conditioning and no trees in the infield to block
your view. You wouldn't even have to leave your seat to watch the
horses in the new state-of-the-art paddock. The Big A would mean
king-size comfort. So very '50s.
</P>
<P>
   The Big A would also mean big bucks.
</P>
<P>
   In its inaugural season in 1959, Aqueduct averaged 28,006 fans a
day. That same year at Saratoga, the crowds averaged 13,729. And
the folks in Queens were players, punching $96 per capita through
the machines. The upstate crowd managed $77 a person.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue collectors in Albany would cast covetous eyes on the
receipts from Aqueduct. At the same time, $50 million annually
realized in taxes from racing was a palpable part of state income.
For some, the temptation was surely there to race those prime
Saratoga dates in Queens County. That was, in fact, what the
operators of Saratoga did.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1950s it was the custom of the Saratoga Association
to run several weeks of their state-allocated dates at the Jamaica
Race Track on Baisley Boulevard in Queens. It was a far more
profitable site and the money made at Jamaica helped to subsidize
the purses and operating expenses of the exclusive Saratoga
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   In 1954, the 18 days of ``Saratoga at Jamaica'' averaged 23,000
fans with $1.8 million in handle. The 24 days of ``Saratoga at
Saratoga'' averaged 14,600 fans and $960,000 in handle.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Gilcoyne, the historian of the National Museum of Racing,
recalls the popular old Jamaica. ``Foot-Sore Downs is what many New
Yorkers called it because it drew big crowds and most people had to
stand,'' Gilcoyne said. ``It was a functional track with no attempt
at grandeur and niceties. It's an overused term, but Jamaica was a
blue-collar track. It was not Ascot.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't Saratoga either, where in August you would find more
blue bloods than blue collars.
</P>
<P>
   In 1955, Jamaica was purchased by a newly formed nonprofit
corporation that would become the New York Racing Association. The
NYRA would eventually sell Jamaica (it is now a housing project)
and rebuild the decaying Aqueduct and Belmont facilities. Saratoga
would remain in its fairly-well-kept Victorian state.
</P>
<P>
   Saratoga was a treasured asset to all racing enthusiasts because
of its history and tradition, high-class racing, grand social
atmosphere and ambience. But the accountants and revenue collectors
probably didn't care much about quaintness. Gilcoyne recalls the
situation: ``Saratoga couldn't compete financially with the New
York City tracks. There was an undercurrent of feeling at the time
that it would not last. The place was a little stale and there was
a foreboding that Saratoga was a terminal case.''
</P>
<P>
   So, a racing enthusiast, the owner of Log Cabin Stud, Gov. W.
Averell Harriman, led a pre-emptive attack before any meaningful
aggression on Saratoga could be mounted. The so-called Harriman Act
of 1957 was unprecedented. It mandated that a minimum of 24 racing
dates be run every year at Saratoga. A 100-year tradition of August
racing at the Spa would remain. It was the law.
</P>
<P>
   Harriman may have never envisioned the overflow crowds that are
drawn to the old course on Union Avenue now. Last year there was an
average of 24,660 a day. And with simulcasting the mutuel handle is
going through the slate roof: $13,348,310, a North American record.
</P>
<P>
   The only fear Saratoga lovers have now is that it will weaken
under the weight of its own success. Over the last 10 years, the
season has grown from 24 to 36 days. In a role reversal of the
1950s, it is taking dates away from the downstate tracks. The
36-day meeting has caused worries about diluting the quality of the
product. But business is better than ever; in fact, the financial
numbers are so impressive that NYRA officials will spend a good
deal of their time there this August squelching rumors about a
48-day meeting. How times have changed.
</P>
<P>
   Most observers attribute Saratoga's unbridled prosperity in
recent times to a combination of factors: easier interstate access
via the Northway, an energetic promotional campaign, tasteful and
appropriate physical improvements and the continuity of quality
racing.
</P>
<P>
   But the downstate tracks, Belmont and Aqueduct, are also
accessible, promoted and improved, and the racing itself remains
some of the best in the country even though the product has never
been quite as elite as Saratoga's.
</P>
<P>
   The primary reason for Saratoga's current success seems to be a
change in the esthetic zeitgeist of the sports crowd. Saratoga
survived the '50s when places like Ebbets Field and the Polo
Grounds didn't. Two of baseball's '50s survivors and among its most
successful stadiums are the genuine, cozy and quirky Fenway Park
and Wrigley Field. And when genuine, cozy and quirky wasn't
available in Baltimore and Cleveland, they just manufactured it.
They play to big crowds in all four cities no matter how poor the
team's record is.
</P>
<P>
   Saratoga is the real 19th-century item. Its grandstand of creaky
wood beams with its multisteepled slate roof dates to 1892. The
horses still inefficiently make their way from stables across Union
Avenue, stopping traffic, then cautiously wind through the backyard
crowds to be saddled under the trees, much as they did when Ulysses
S. Grant lived nearby.
</P>
<P>
   View obstruction was never an obsession at Saratoga. Large,
leafy maples continue to flourish in the infield, making for a
sylvan scene, but careful observation of the races is a challenge.
Just ask the track announcer.
</P>
<P>
   Odds are good that more people will pass through the turnstiles
this year than any other year since it opened in 1864. The place,
no doubt, feels much the same as it did when the Harriman Act was
signed back in the '50s. But in the '90s, we just feel it
differently. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
