<HEADER>
A2709 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOODSTOCK'99-MERCHANT     07-24 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOODSTOCK'99-MERCHANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOCAL MERCHANTS' HOPES FOR WOODSTOCK '99 WINDFALL ARE DASHED 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By ANDY NEWMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME, N.Y. _ More than 100 miles east of the exit leading to the
Woodstock '99 festival, concert-bound travelers crowded the
Starbucks counter at a rest stop on the New York State Thruway on
Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   But on James Street in Rome, a commercial strip only two blocks
away from a major entrance to the festival, the impact on business
was barely apparent.
</P>
<P>
   George Manley's decision to keep his store open around the clock
for the duration of the concert had yielded little more than a
chance to sit out front with friends and drink beer.
</P>
<P>
   Manley, who owns a pawn and junk store called the Bargain Shop,
had stocked up on the things every concertgoer needs, and it was
priced to sell _ mini-grills for $2, serviceable bicycles for $35,
flip-flops for a couple of bucks. But apart from a few bikes and a
fair amount of candy, the merchandise was not moving.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been slow,'' he said. ``I think we all expected to do a
lot better.''
</P>
<P>
   Some stores are doing well. At the Mohawk Acres Shopping Center,
which is practically on top of the main entrance, the Price Chopper
supermarket was packing them in, as were the Family Dollar store
and the Burger King. But for most shopkeepers in Rome, the dream of
a festival windfall seems to be fading.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of the problem is that most of the potential customers are
fenced in at the former Air Force base where the concert is going
on.
</P>
<P>
   And many of the attendees, after shelling out $5 for a beer or a
bottle of water, or $17 for a 25-pound bag of ice, do not even have
enough money to get home, let alone go shopping. Manley has been
doing as much buying as selling.
</P>
<P>
   ``These kids have to survive,'' he said. ``I bought some gold
chains. One girl sold her mother's gold ring just so she could get
back to Michigan.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday morning at Manley's store, the cashier, Diana DeMorrow,
said a couple of girls from Ohio came by hoping to sell a
television, some inline skates and a car stereo in order to buy an
extra ticket, which costs $150, and to get gas money to go home.
She turned them away, she said, because she did not know if the
merchandise was stolen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think tomorrow and Monday it's going to be the worst,'' she
said. ``Some of these people are starving already. They're eating
raw hot dogs because they can't afford the food up there.''
</P>
<P>
   Up the street, at the New Yorker restaurant, the owner, Carol
Morrill, was having similar problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said the city would do better, but I really don't see any
difference,'' she said. ``The kids who come by here, they have no
money. They're looking for deals.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, she said the festival had scared business away.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurt a little bit,'' she said. ``A lot of the Romans who
normally come out, my regular customers, came by last week and said
`I'll see you in two weeks, I'm going to spend the next two weeks
indoors.' They're staying close to home because they're afraid of
looters. They figure there's a lot of kids out there with no money
and no way to go home.'' Many of Ms. Morrill's other regulars have
simply left town for the duration, she said, rather than deal with
the chaos.
</P>
<P>
   Rome's fear of marauding tribes of tie-dyed Visigoths has proved
unfounded. Police reported Saturday morning that they had made 15
arrests so far, most of them for minor offenses, such as disorderly
conduct. Violent crime had amounted to one robbery.
</P>
<P>
   Manley remained hopeful that business would pick up. ``After
midnight,'' he said Friday night, ``people are going to come. After
the music ends they're not going to want to be cooped up in
there.''
</P>
<P>
   But midnight came and went, and while some concertgoers trickled
out and down the street, most didn't stop at his store.
</P>
<P>
   A little after midnight, two men pulled up in a car. The
longer-haired one went over to look at a bike and accidentally
knocked it over onto an aquarium tank, which shattered.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's OK '' Manley said.
</P>
<P>
   After browsing guiltily for about 15 minutes, the long-haired
man, Bob Rising of Mansfield, Ohio, bought a tube of
bug-repellent-cum-sunblock for $2.
</P>
<P>
   ``How about some Tylenol?'' Manley pitched hopefully. ``You here
for the weekend? You'll get some headaches. Tylenol, the big box,
three bucks a how-de-do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No thanks,'' Rising said. ``We don't do drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   The only thing people seemed willing to spend money on was
Woodstock-related merchandise. Across the street from the New
Yorker, a sports apparel store, Erin's Way, had given its floor
space over to Woodstock caps, Woodstock dog tags and most of all,
T-shirts, including a popular one that read ``All Roads Lead to
Rome'' and showed four horses pulling a coach containing a bird
playing a guitar.
</P>
<P>
   ``The owner drove down to Saugerties,'' more than two hours
away, to get them, said the cashier, Roxanne May, adding that when
she told customers he might not be back for another half hour, they
waited. ``Just for a T-shirt. It's crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Further down James Street, a ``Welcome Woodstock Fans'' banner
hung outside Midnight Mikey's tavern, but at 1 a.m., an hour after
Bush closed out the first night's music, the only Woodstock fans in
evidence were on the TV behind the bar.
</P>
<P>
   There were about 10 customers. Behind the bar, the proprietor,
Mike Vescio, said that all in all, it had been a pretty slow Friday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they didn't have that thing it would have been a lot
busier,'' he said. ``Some of my regulars are up at the concert.''
</P>
<P>
   Vescio said that he had been surprised by the low turnout at his
place.
</P>
<P>
   ``A guy from Oneonta came in here a couple of days ago, he goes
to these kinds of shows, and he said `Man, you're gonna be
jammed,''' Vescio said. ``Everybody thought with all these cars
coming through that people would jump out of the cars and buy
stuff.'' But the cars just keep going.
</P>
<P>
   Up the road, Vescio's daughter, Michele Vescio, had temporarily
changed the name of her bar, the Stockyard Inn, to the Woodstock
Inn. But not even that seemed to help. Nor did being across the
street from a Denny's that was jammed at 2 a.m. Saturday morning.
After three straight dead nights, Ms. Vescio decided to throw in
the towel.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, she said, rather than run a bar, she and her staff
were going to the show. ``If it's not worth our while to stay
open,'' she said, ``we might as well go up there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
