<HEADER>
A2710 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-UMPIRES-ART-NYT &LR;      07-24 0344
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-UMPIRES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE UMPIRES MAY HOLD ONTO JOBS 
</HEADLINE>
  (also see BBO-LIPSYTE-COLUMN) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the jobs of 26 of the 68 umpires already safe, a baseball
official held out the possibility Saturday that more umpires could
salvage their jobs in coming days if they rescind their
resignations.
</P>
<P>
   Major League Baseball has taken no public stance on the umpires'
job action, in which about 80 percent of them signed letters of
resignation, and Saturday it continued to maintain official
silence. However, league officials Friday notified umpires who had
revoked their letters that they would be able to continue to work.
</P>
<P>
   One official indicated at that time that the 42 umpires who had
not acted to rescind would have their resignations accepted.
However, when another official was asked Saturday what might happen
if umpires rescinded in coming days, he said, ``It's open to
judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't say, but it was possible the judgment would be based
on the umpire's record. If is an umpire his league believes to be
one of the better ones, he could be retained. If, on the other
hand, he is one who has received a low rating and the league had
been thinking of replacing him anyway, his withdrawal could be
denied and his resignation accepted.
</P>
<P>
   The official, who spoke on the condition he not be identified,
said word has circulated that more umpires are expected to revoke
their resignations, but he had no indication of how many might take
that step.
</P>
<P>
   The umpires' support of the resignation plan, devised by union
leader Richie Phillips, has been mixed along league lines. Thirty
of the American League's 32 umpires are union members, and 21 have
either not signed letters or have rescinded them. In the National
League, only one of the 36 umpires has not signed, and two have
rescinded, leaving 33 whose jobs are in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-99 1622EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
