<HEADLINE>
PACERS AND HAWKS WANT TO BE KNICKISH  
 REUNION IN L.A.?  
 SPURS EYE BURRELL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Latrell Sprewell and Marcus Camby, the explosive and
fleet-footed Knicks, are still on the minds of the Indiana Pacers
and the Atlanta Hawks. Having been victimized by the new-look
Knicks in the Eastern Conference playoffs, two of the league's more
renowned plodders are looking to become more athletic, more
versatile, more Knickish.
</P>
<P>
   After watching Camby fly as if he had wings in stripping
Indiana's frontline of its brutish reputation, Donnie Walsh, the
Pacers' president, is focused on adding youth and gracefulness to
his lineup. And after Sprewell turned the Knicks' four-game sweep
of Atlanta into a track meet highlighted by fierce dunks and
scowls, Pete Babcock, the Hawks' general manager, is set to revamp
his entire starting group _ save center Dikembe Mutombo _ if
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the season progressed, we became aware that our team speed
and quickness wasn't what we would like it to be,'' Babcock said.
``Then, to run into the Knicks, who had terrific athletic ability
and team speed, just accentuated what we already knew and drove the
point further home. So we want to try to restructure our team so
that we have better athletic ability top to bottom, and anything we
can do along those lines, we are committed to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks took their initial step in that direction by trading
Mookie Blaylock, the aging point guard at 32, to Golden State for
Bimbo Coles and the 10th pick of the draft, which they used to
select the Arizona point guard Jason Terry. In his first appearance
as a Hawk, Terry, incredibly quick and a solid outside shooter,
scorched Charlotte's Baron Davis, the third pick in the draft, for
30 points in a summer league game.
</P>
<P>
   More significantly, in what would be one of the biggest trades
of the off- season, Atlanta is looking into sending Steve Smith to
Portland for Isaiah Rider and Jim Jackson. That Babcock, who in the
past has insisted on his players displaying character on and off
the court, is considering the acquisition of Rider, a noted
malcontent whose tardiness and goofiness has worn thin in Portland,
shows how serious the Hawks are about escaping their pattern of
mediocrity.
</P>
<P>
   If Atlanta chooses to overlook Rider's past, it will be at least
partly because he has just one year remaining on his contract. The
Hawks are looking to free room beneath the salary cap, and Smith is
under contract through the 2002-2003 season.
</P>
<P>
   While some believe that a makeover is also in order in Indiana,
Walsh said his team has at least one more run at the conference
title left in it. ``I would love for you guys to write us off,''
Walsh said. ``We still have a lot of good basketball players. I
wouldn't just automatically say that since we lost to the Knicks,
we're out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Walsh is trying to build a youthful second unit
that could match strides with the Knicks. He believes he has five
athletic and multidimensional substitutes in Jalen Rose, who may
displace Chris Mullin as the starting small forward; Travis Best;
Al Harrington; and the first-round draft picks Jeff Foster and
Jonathon Bender, this year's prep-to-pros phenom.
</P>
<P>
   With his slower, more cerebral veterans still dominating the
starting five, Walsh envisions a two-headed club that could thrive
in a halfcourt battle or fullcourt sprint. There is, however, one
scenario that could quicken the process and make the Pacers' first
unit more blazing. Rik Smits, the 7-foot-4-inch center with chronic
foot problems, indicated at the end of the conference finals that
he would retire this summer, even though it would mean forfeiting
the $12 million he is due to receive next season. It is believed
that Smits will give an answer by early next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure he'll be back,'' Walsh said. ``I think it was
overstated that he was definitely retiring. I met with him the day
that the story came out and he told me that it was incorrect. He
said he'd see how he felt and that if his feet felt OK, he'd play.
If they didn't, he'd let me know.
</P>
<P>
   ``In his case, it would kind of be like Patrick Ewing is with
the Knicks. There is no way we're going to go out and replace him
in the short term, and if he isn't able to play, we'll play a much
faster style. But we're headed in that direction already.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, in what would seem to be a bizarre move since they already
have Reggie Miller, the Pacers are rumored to be interested in
signing the shooting guard Mitch Richmond through free agency.
Walsh said the theory should not be discounted and brought up the
Knicks as the reason why. ``Who would have thought that Latrell
Sprewell would make sense for the Knicks when they already had
Allan Houston?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hardaway to the Lakers?
</P>
<P>
   According to a report in The Los Angeles Times last week, the
Lakers are exploring the possibility of reuniting the former
Orlando Magic teammates Shaquille O'Neal and Penny Hardaway.
Hardaway, who along with O'Neal led the Magic to the National
Basketball Association finals in 1995, is supposedly the driving
force behind the idea. According to the report, the Lakers would
send Glen Rice and Derek Fisher to Orlando in a sign-and-trade
deal.
</P>
<P>
   But while Hardaway and O'Neal are said to have put their
much-publicized problems of the past behind them, a person with
knowledge of the situation said the Lakers are leery of bringing in
Hardaway, who has become known as a prima donna because of run-ins
with the coaches Brian Hill and Chuck Daly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Penny would love to be there,'' said the person, an agent who
spoke on the condition of anonymity. ``The Lakers are looking at
it, but I'm not certain that that's their No. 1 choice. It would
give them an interesting combination of talent, but there's a real
concern about Penny's attitude. The feeling is that he may be more
of a destructive than a constructive personality to be around.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the Lakers would probably rather deal with Hardaway
than with Rice, who has been unhappy for most of his brief stint
with the club. The situation recently surpassed the point of
toleration when the Lakers decided to pick up Rice's $7 million
option for next season. Rice, who wanted to renegotiate to the tune
of roughly $14 million per year, was incensed. For that reason, it
is almost a certainty that Rice will be traded, whether it is for
Hardaway or someone else.
</P>
<P>
   The talk of a West Coast reunion between Scottie Pippen and Phil
Jackson will probably amount to nothing more because the Lakers
have concerns about Pippen's back. Pippen, a veteran of 12 seasons,
is worn down for his age (33), having played in 182 career playoff
games, which amounts to nearly three full seasons. The Lakers think
his struggles last season in Houston were partly caused by his back
problems.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs' Plan B
</P>
<P>
   With its starting small forward, Sean Elliott, in need of a
kidney transplant, the NBA champion San Antonio Spurs are looking
for possible replacements, one of whom is the Nets' free agent
Scott Burrell. The Spurs have been in contact with Burrell for the
last week and are believed to be willing to pay him the $2 million
midlevel exception.
</P>
<P>
   Burrell, a member of the Chicago Bulls' 1998 title team, is
coming off a disappointing season with the Nets. Admittedly out of
shape for much of the year, he averaged just 6.6 points and 3.7
rebounds on 36 percent shooting. He missed 18 games and underwent
minor surgery on his right knee in April.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets were so displeased with Burrell's play that they have
offered him only a one-year, $1 million contract to return.
Burrell, who says that the former coach John Calipari promised him
he would receive $2 million this season, wants to return to the
Nets, but not for such a small sum.
</P>
</TEXT>
