<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-24 16:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2723 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-APPRAISE-REAL-3TAKES-     07-24 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPRAISE-REAL-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPRAISERS: THE ART OF GETTING TO THE BOTTOM LINE 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By DENNIS HEVESI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is an innocuous-looking packet of papers, or, these days, an
e-mail _ several pages evaluating the ``subject residence,'' floor
plans, photos of ``comparables'' and a dollar figure _ that can
make or break a deal: the appraisal.
</P>
<P>
   Clark Halstead, founder of the Manhattan brokerage that bears
his name and himself a former appraiser, likens the appraisal to
the Oracle at Delphi, ``where kings and commoners sat around a hole
in the stone until black or white smoke came out _ black smoke
means the deal's in trouble, white smoke means clean and green
straight ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   For the appraisal industry itself, however, the road has been
rough in recent years _ buffeted as it was by regulatory reform
following the savings-and-loan crisis of the late '80s and then
radically reshaped by computer technology.
</P>
<P>
   The residential transaction can be stressful for all the
parties: buyers, sellers, brokers, even the lenders. ``And the
appraiser only adds to the stress,'' Halstead said.
``Unfortunately, the Oracle doesn't speak in this case until late
in the deal,'' often not much before the closing.
</P>
<P>
   The buyer always worries whether the price is too high. ``And if
the appraisal is below the contract price,'' Halstead said, ``he is
consumed by buyer's remorse and tries to renegotiate, or walks
away.''
</P>
<P>
   The seller thinks the deal is done, and envisions closing on
that next dream house. ``So when the appraisal comes in low, he is
traumatized, not prepared to renegotiate,'' Halstead said, ``and
feels badly served by that fickle buyer.''
</P>
<P>
   The broker, having already mentally deposited the commission,
has to scramble. ``The broker has two courses,'' Halstead said,
``get the old appraiser to consider new comparables or convince the
parties to use another appraiser.''
</P>
<P>
   And another player in the drama, the mortgage broker, under
pressure to meet quarterly lending goals, has visions of bonuses
dancing out of his head. ``Lenders actually refer to mortgage loans
as sales: `How are your sales going?' the boss wants to know,''
Halstead said. ``Everybody's hanging on this. That's why it's like
the Oracle. If you get white smoke, it's party time.''
</P>
<P>
   A white puff rose over 18 Bertha Lane in Massapequa Park, N.Y.,
on Long Island, in April when Richard Meyer, president of Meyer
Associates, an appraisal company in nearby Bellmore, submitted his
valuation for the four-bedroom expanded Cape.
</P>
<P>
   The agreed-upon price for the house, with its new kitchen,
finished basement and a rear deck, was $238,000. The appraisal
price: a nearly on-the-money $242,500.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was the 1,000-square-foot one-bedroom in downtown
Manhattan that, because of an architectural quirk, opened onto a
2,000-square-foot terrace. ``People get emotional about outdoor
space,'' said Jeffrey Jackson Satkiewicz, chairman of the appraisal
firm Mitchell, Maxwell &AMP; Jackson. ``And when a property is unique,
like that, there's nothing to compare it to.''
</P>
<P>
   Black smoke rising.
</P>
<P>
   ``The contract price was $1 million,'' Satkiewicz said. ``We
appraised it at $750,000. The buyer tried to renegotiate. The
seller wouldn't budge. So the buyer walked away. This was six weeks
ago.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Two weeks ago,'' Satkiewicz said, ``the same buyer came
through purchasing another property; about the same size inside,
but the terrace was 1,000 feet rather than 2,000, and they were
paying $600,000. They were happy to have $400,000 more in their
pocket than to have the extra space.''
</P>
<P>
   The process is sometimes no picnic for the appraiser: tramping
through and nosing into other people's property, clipboard and tape
measure in hand; toting up square footage, noting the gas station
behind the back fence, the ancient oil heater; deducting for
defects and factoring in upgrades and amenities, like the finished
basement, the new kitchen, the fireplace, and, in more rarefied
environs, the racquetball court, the sumptuous landscaping, the
reflecting pool.
</P>
<P>
   There are hazards to the trade, Meyer said: ``Measuring houses
in the snow and falling into a basement window well. Being pulled
over by the police in exclusive neighborhoods _ we're taking
pictures and it looks like we're casing out a burglary.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The other day,'' Meyer said, ``one of my appraisers was doing
a two-family in Brooklyn and he was attacked by the tenant. She was
being evicted because she hadn't paid rent and took it out on the
appraiser.''
</P>
<P>
   The '90s have been a tumultuous time for the industry. And in
the estimate of Bert Thornton, president of the 19,000-member
Appraisal Institute, a trade association, ``the profession has
changed more in the last five years than in the previous 30.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps as nothing else, computers have streamlined and
standardized the process, rendering an array of data _ from
economic overviews and regional residential trends to specific
information on the most recent sale of ``comparables'' down the
block _ available, literally, at the push of a button. So, too, can
the final appraisal, complete with digital photographs, be e-mailed
to the client (usually, though not always, the lender) almost
instantaneously.
</P>
<P>
   Hand in hand with the computer revolution has been the ripple
effect on appraisers stirred by the globalization of money markets,
particularly given the allure of an enduringly vibrant U.S.
economy. ``There are no boundaries today,'' Thornton said, ``so you
have a lot of capital flowing in and out of the United States'' _
with investors from all over the world wanting a slice of the
American home-loan pie through what Wall Street calls
securitization. ``The loans are pooled,'' Thornton explained,
``rating agencies rate those pools of loans and they are
securitized, sold as shares.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, in a market where capital for lending is
plentiful and mortgage rates have been low and steady, the computer
has made it possible for so-called subprime borrowers _ those with
less than exemplary credit histories _ to be granted mortgages
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``The lender requires an appraisal on a property, and these days
that is probably the biggest condition for granting a mortgage,''
said Keith Gumbinger, vice president of HSH Associates, a mortgage
research company in Butler, N.J. ``In recent years, even folks with
poor credit have been able to obtain mortgages, albeit at higher
interest rates.''
</P>
<P>
   Computers have taken much of the subjectivity, and bias, out of
mortgage origination through what is called credit scoring _ the
strictly numerical calculation of a borrower's credit history and
capacity. That, in turn, expeditiously tells the lender what type
of mortgage it can offer. ``And that has lent itself to faster
pooling and easier securitization of the mortgages themselves,''
Gumbinger said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that virtually any borrower can get a mortgage,'' he said,
``the lender still needs to be reassured that the property has
value, and whether it is fairly valued against similar properties.
And, of course, that is the need for your appraisal.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the late '80s, forces other than the computer have
reshaped the appraisal process. In a kind of tectonic convulsion,
the industry was rocked by the nation's savings-and-loan debacle,
with government regulators laying part of the blame for that tidal
wave of irrational S&AMP;L lending on the ill-considered and sometimes
unethical performance of some appraisers. ``There are, as in any
profession, some unscrupulous appraisers,'' Thornton said.
</P>
<P>
   Dominick Pompeo is president of Diversified Valuation Group in
South Ozone Park, Queens, as well as a former chairman and current
member of the New York State Appraisal Board, the agency that
licenses appraisers. Congressional investigators found, Pompeo
said, ``that 50 percent of all losses by S&AMP;Ls were due to faulty or
fraudulent appraisals.''
</P>
<P>
   Either the appraised value was so high that it had no basis in
reality, Pompeo said, or the appraiser was simply unqualified.
Pompeo recalled how his office analyzed a lending institution's
portfolio and found that it had lent $2 million on a Manhattan
property it believed to be worth $4 million, ``based on an
appraisal by someone who was unqualified.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What the bank didn't know,'' Pompeo said, ``was that it was a
loft building, subject to the Loft Law, which restricts rents and
requires that the building be brought into residential code
compliance.'' The appraiser had forecast rents that were not
allowable and disregarded the cost of bringing the building into
compliance. The true value, he said, was $600,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of improprieties leading to the S&AMP;L crisis, a
lot of shady characters inflating values,'' said Jonathan Miller,
president of Miller Samuel, the company that produces the Douglas
Elliman Manhattan Market Report. ``Until then, it was an
unregulated profession that was not held accountable.''
</P>
<P>
   But in 1989, in response to the S&AMP;L collapse, the government
enacted Title 11 of the Financial Institutions Reform, Recovery and
Enforcement Act, requiring that anyone appraising federally insured
properties be state licensed, and establishing minimum requirements
_ 2,000 hours of field experience (now 2,500), 120 hours of
classroom training and passage of a written test.
</P>
<P>
   The law also allowed states to choose mandatory or voluntary
licensing status: mandatory meaning all appraisers had to meet the
minimum requirements to perform federally related appraisals;
voluntary meaning only those doing Federal work need be licensed.
New York is a voluntary state _ a choice that has caused some
consternation.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, the Federal Housing Administration shook up the
industry again. It discarded its list of 8,000 designated
appraisers, chosen by rotation to perform federally related
appraisals, and adopted a program called ``Lender-Select'' _
meaning the lender of any mortgage to be insured by the government
could choose any state-licensed appraiser. Problems arose.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lender has a fiduciary responsibility to FHA,'' said James
Park, a member of the Appraisal Institute's client services
committee and president of the JP Appraisal Service in Alexandria,
Va. But a General Accounting Office study, Park said, reported that
under Lender-Select the FHA insured many homes that did not meet
its requirements and, ``maybe more importantly, put people in the
unfortunate position of buying homes that had significant
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, the buyers defaulted. ``FHA ends up holding the
property and has to pay insurance to the lender,'' Park said.
``They then have to sell the foreclosed property, many times at a
loss. And, ultimately, the American taxpayer bears the burden.''
</P>
<P>
   Pompeo of the New York State Appraisal Board is troubled by some
shifts in the industry. In the past, he said, banks hired
appraisers directly. Now, increasingly, they rely on mortgage
brokers to provide clients, so the broker selects the appraiser.
</P>
<P>
   ``No longer is the lender a disinterested party because his
remuneration depends on the mortgage being completed,'' Pompeo
said. ``If the broker is unscrupulous, and the property has
attributes that the bank and the buyer should be aware of,'' an
unethical broker ``would wish the appraiser to ignore it. And
people who are not adhering to appraisal standards are being
rewarded by work from brokers who want a predetermined result in
their appraisals.''
</P>
<P>
   One trend that pleases cost-conscious lenders, but troubles some
appraisers, is the ``drive-by appraisal'' _ usually employed in
suburban settings _ in which the appraiser assumes that the
interior of the house is typical of the market.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   To address some of the problems, the Department of Housing and
Urban Development in June announced a Home Buyer Protection
Initiative, a program that, among other things, creates an
appraisal education program for consumers, mandates greater
specificity in identifying building deficiencies and requires that
the buyer receive a copy of the appraisal no less than five days
before closing.
</P>
<P>
   Although lenders constitute, by far, the majority of appraisal
clients, the buyer is entitled to a copy of the appraisal. And it
is usually the buyer who pays the appraiser's fee, as part of the
closing costs. Fees vary according to the complexity of the
property. So, for example, a half-hour perusal by Meyer of that
Cape in Massapequa Park might cost $250, while Satkiewicz's more
extensive inspection of a luxury Manhattan co-op could cost $1,000
or far more.
</P>
<P>
   Upon arriving at the property, the appraiser starts by
calculating dimensions _ using a tape measure or, perhaps, a sonar
device that, like a bat, bounces a signal from wall to wall, then
emits a disembodied voice intoning: ``Sixteen feet, four inches.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, Miller said: ``We sketch a floor plan, assess the
condition of the floors, walls, ceilings, anything visible; and
take note of upgrades,'' like a new kitchen, ``and amenities,''
like the pool.
</P>
<P>
   Through multiple listing services, official records or, wherever
possible, actual visits, the appraiser collects information on
comparables. ``In the case of co-ops,'' Miller said, ``we get hold
of the current co-op financial statement; or, for houses, we're
going to town hall or the local MLS to look at recent transfers in
the neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   Then begins the actual valuation work _ a complicated and not
entirely scientific process depending largely on the appraiser's
knowledge of the community. ``Let's say you have two properties
that are identical in every respect except for one amenity, such as
the view,'' Miller said. ``In the case of an apartment, the subject
residence could have a direct view of Central Park above the tree
line, while the same apartment below the tree line might have sold
for 15 percent less.''
</P>
<P>
   In a typical suburban community, Meyer said, ``upgrades such as
new kitchens, a pool, the rear deck could increase values,
cumulatively, by 10 to 20 percent of the total value.''
</P>
<P>
   Upgrade by upgrade, amenity by amenity, the home under
examination and its comparables are factored in to arrive at an
estimate of market value. ``It's a mix of the appraiser's objective
and subjective experiences,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   One morning in June, Satkiewicz walked through a four-bedroom
condominium on the 31st floor of the Grand Millennium at Broadway
and 66th Street and was immediately struck by the terrace and its
wraparound view of Central Park, the spires of midtown Manhattan
and the Hudson River. ``It curves around, almost juts out,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   His sonar measuring device in hand, Satkiewicz calculated the
terrace at 197 square feet _ just one of a panoply of amenities he
would account for during his 90-minute tour of the apartment, but
one that, he said, ``gives it star quality.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Satkiewicz returned to his office to crunch numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are five comparables on this appraisal,'' he said, ``and
they sold for between $976 and $1,129 per square foot.'' Using that
range, he chose $1,000 per square foot as his base for further
calculation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We adjust for exterior space by comparing sales of identical
apartments that have exterior space to those without,'' he said,
``and isolate the value of the terrace.''
</P>
<P>
   Saying that research and experience ``tell me that terraces are
worth half the square-foot price for inside the apartment,''
Satkiewicz valued the terrace at $500 per foot. He multiplied the
197 square feet of terrace by $500, for a preliminary figure of
$98,500 in added value to the apartment.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's just the scientific part,'' Satkiewicz said.
``There are things that are not quantifiable but need to be
factored in: one is what you see from the terrace; the second is
any improvement that enhances its utility, in this case, the terra
cotta tiles and the wiring for surround-sound stereo. In my
judgment, those add 50 percent to our base figure of $98,500,'' or
$147,750 in added value.
</P>
<P>
   That, however, is just one factor in the equation. ``We go
through the process for each of the major upgrades and amenities,''
he said, ``and get an adjusted range of sales prices for all the
comparables.'' With the comparables taken into account, Satkiewicz
said, ``we select a value within the range that we think best
represents the subject's position in the marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   His appraisal of the apartment, which the current owner bought
for $2.3 million in January 1997: $3.51 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
