<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-24 16:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2726 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SENATE-LAZIO-290&AMP;A     07-24 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-LAZIO-290&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFYING GOP PRESSURE, LAZIO PUSHES AHEAD WITH SENATE RACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Showing no signs of backing off in his maverick bid for the
Republican nomination for the U.S. Senate, Rep. Rick Lazio of Long
Island has sent a letter to Republican and Conservative Party
leaders across New York state, confirming that he will officially
declare his candidacy with a statewide tour in mid-August.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's decision to set a date for his announcement seemed
intended as a response to pressure from some Republican leaders
that he step aside and allow New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani
to take his party's nomination. The Republican candidate is likely
to face Hillary Rodham Clinton on the Democratic line in the
November 2000 election, and Republican leaders _ including
Giuliani's advisers _ have expressed concern about a primary. State
Senate Majority Leader Joseph Bruno called on Lazio to drop his
campaign last week.
</P>
<P>
   Although Giuliani is a better-known and presumably
better-financed candidate, Lazio is more conservative on some
issues _ like abortion rights _ that could be decisive in a
Republican primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want you to be one of the first to know that I have made my
decision _ I will be a candidate for U.S. Senate,'' Lazio wrote in
the letter to Republican and Conservative party leaders. ``I'm
going to make an official announcement on August 17th.'' The letter
was first reported Saturday in The New York Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   In the letter, Lazio said he had encountered signs of support
during his travels in New York. He also noted that he had raised
$3.2 million so far. An adviser said Saturday that Lazio was likely
to hire Mike Murphy, a prominent national Republican strategist who
worked for Bob Dole's presidential campaign in 1996, to help direct
his effort.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Lazio did not mention Giuliani by name, though he made a clear
and unflattering reference to the mayor's long-term political
ambitions and commitment to the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clear to me that New Yorkers want a senator who cares
about them and their problems, not someone who is interested in a
stepping stone to higher office,'' Lazio said. Mrs. Clinton has
pledged to serve out her term if elected; Giuliani, whose aides
have floated his name as a possible candidate for vice president,
has refused to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Teitelbaum, the chairman of Giuliani's political
committee, declined to comment on Lazio's letter.
</P>
<P>
   The letter was the latest indication that Lazio and Giuliani
seem to be engaged in a game of political chicken. Notwithstanding
Lazio's statements, several Republican leaders believe that in the
end, he may come under so much pressure from party leaders that he
will clear the field for Giuliani, rather than risk long-term
damage to his career.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side, some of Giuliani's advisers have said that
the mayor may not proceed with the Senate race if Lazio continues
with his primary challenge. Under that scenario, one associate
said, the mayor would serve out his term and then run for governor,
even if that meant a primary against George Pataki, the Republican
incumbent. Pataki and Giuliani are not on the best of terms; the
mayor's advisers believe that Pataki has been encouraging Lazio to
make this race.
</P>
<P>
   A withdrawal by Giuliani would risk making it appear that he was
shying away from a fight, which would not be in character. Thus,
many Republicans see those remarks as an attempt to force national
Republican leaders to turn up the pressure on Lazio to drop out.
</P>
<P>
   Although Lazio is viewed as a potentially strong candidate
against Giuliani, many Republican leaders believe that the mayor
would be a far stronger challenger to Mrs. Clinton.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-99 1654EDT &QL; 
