<DOCNO> NYT19990724.0173 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-24 17:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2732 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-TOURDEFRANCE-ARMSTR     07-24 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-TOURDEFRANCE-ARMSTRONG-ART-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMSTRONG WINS TIME TRIAL AND LOOKS FOR INSPIRATIONAL VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING to add photo note)  
 (ATTN: Texas)  (ART ADV:  Photo  is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jw) 
 By SAMUEL ABT    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FUTUROSCOPE, France _ Good thing Lance Armstrong didn't put his
money where his mouth is.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were a betting man,'' he said before the Tour de France's
19th of 20 daily stages Saturday, a long time trial, ``I'd put my
money on Zuelle. He needs to beat Escartin.''
</P>
<P>
   The race leader referred to the two men immediately behind him,
Alex Zuelle, a Swiss with the Banesto racing team who was in third
place, and Fernando Escartin, a Spaniard with Kelme who was in
second.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong's reasoning was sound and even accurate up to a point.
Zuelle did easily beat Escartin, making up a gap of 1 minute 13
seconds, and move up to second a day before the Tour ends in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   But Armstrong beat Zuelle and everybody else, registering his
fourth stage victory and the third in three time trials, which are
solitary races against the clock.
</P>
<P>
   The first was in the prologue July 3, just 4 miles, which he won
by 7 seconds over the second-placed Zuelle. The second was a
35-mile ride around Metz on July 11, which he won by 58 seconds
over the second-placed Zuelle.
</P>
<P>
   Over the 35 miles Saturday, he won by nine seconds over _ who
else? _ the second-placed Zuelle. Armstrong's teammate Tyler
Hamilton was third, 1:35 behind the winner in a gutsy showing by a
rider who gave his all for his U.S. Postal Service team leader in
the Alps and Pyrenees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really wanted this victory,'' Armstrong said later Saturday.
``I didn't start with the same fire I had in Metz but I wanted to
show the yellow jersey today.''
</P>
<P>
   He showed the emblem of leadership to vast crowds that stood in
the sun and a strong wind in and around Futuroscope, a theme park
devoted to technology. Armstrong rode like a machine himself,
finishing in 1 hour 8 minutes 17 seconds, a speed of 31 mph _ the
legal top speed for a car _ despite the wind.
</P>
<P>
   That performance increased his overall lead to 7:37 over Zuelle
and 10:26 over Escartin, now in third place. Hamilton jumped three
notches to 13th over all.
</P>
<P>
   Beforehand, relaxed and excited at the same time, Armstrong
lounged in a team trailer and talked about everything that came to
mind _ except for the fact that Sunday he will win the Tour de
France. Until the moment that he pulls the final yellow jersey of
the winner over his head, he refuses to refer to more than ``my
potential victory.''
</P>
<P>
   Not even the prospect of hundreds of fans who are coming from
back home in Texas to cheer him in Paris could budge Armstrong from
his refusal to claim victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``You will be surprised at all the people there on the
Champs-Elysees that at the last minute jumped on a plane to Paris
from Texas,'' he said. ``Neighbors, friends. To ride the Tour is
one thing, to ride well is another, to potentially win is another,
but to be there on the Champs-Elysees with family and friends and
neighbors, that's fantastic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited,'' he continued in an interview Friday night.
``I'm ready to get this over with, I'm ready to celebrate with
family and friends, I'm ready to have a good time. I've lived like
a monk for six months,'' since the racing season began.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In his white team T-shirt and blue sweat pants, Armstrong looked
remarkably fresh for somebody who was on the verge of completing a
three-week, 2,290-mile trek, often through rain, sometimes through
heavy heat.
</P>
<P>
   If he looks rested, though, he isn't. ``I don't feel fresh,'' he
said. ``I started to feel really tired after Piau-Engaly,'' the
first stage in the Pyrenees last Tuesday. ``That was two weeks into
the race, a rough period for anybody. It was a very hot day and I
had the stress after the race of more doping innuendos and I'd worn
the jersey for a week _ all that was hard for me.''
</P>
<P>
   He was referring to reports in the French press that an illegal
substance had been detected in his body after a urinalysis. The
charge surfaced after he won the Tour's prologue on July 3, was
revived after he won the first Alpine stage on July 13 and then
flowered in the Pyrenees, where he again rode strongly.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong then said that he had used a cortisone-based salve to
treat a skin rash and had produced a medical certificate to justify
its use, although he admitted that he had made ``a mistake'' not to
make this public earlier.
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, Armstrong said some people refused to believe
that he could be fit enough to win the demanding Tour de France 2
and a half years after he was diagnosed with testicular cancer that
had spread to his lungs and brain. Three months of what he
describes as ``very toxic chemotherapy'' checked the disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are journalists in France and there are doctors on
French teams who think I've been given something special by my
oncologist,'' he said. ``They think I was given drugs that boost
performance. It's the exact opposite: I was given things that can
kill you.
</P>
<P>
   ``That kind of talk, it makes me sick. But when the race is
over, that stuff doesn't live. The victory and the people that I
touch and the story that I can tell _ that lives.''
</P>
<P>
   His story is extremely important to him as an example to other
victims of cancer and their families, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud to be a cancer survivor and I'm proud to do this, I
really am,'' he said. ``This race and my performance here are going
to affect a lot of people in a positive way, in a wonderful,
fantastic way. I think I've told my story. That's what I always
wanted to do. I've shared my story with the world.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-99 1723EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
