<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-FORBES-REACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG ISLAND DISTRICT REACTS TO CONGRESSMAN'S MOVE TO DEMOCRATS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOHN T. McQUISTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIVERHEAD, N.Y. _ As Rep. Michael Forbes prepared for another
day trying to persuade Democrats that he was no longer a
Republican, the gathering crowds at the Tanger Outlet Center here
were searching for bargains, with little thought about politics.
</P>
<P>
   Some shoppers said they did not even know that their
congressman, Forbes, had switched parties. Others said they had no
interest in politicians, Republican or Democrat. Those who did
appeared evenly divided over Forbes' future as a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't think there's that much difference between
Republicans and Democrats,'' said Janet Marshack, 48, of Mastic
Beach, who described herself as an independent voter. ``They all
say and do whatever they believe will get them elected.''
</P>
<P>
   Others were more charitable. ``Maybe he's just having a midlife
crisis,'' said William Schmidt, 54, of Shoreham, a computer
technician who recently changed jobs. ``I didn't agree with my
boss, so I quit. It was a matter of principle, so I can identify
with what Forbes did.'' Schmidt said he was a Republican, but often
voted for Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Despite attacks from some former Republican supporters who
insist he has sown the seeds of his political destruction, Forbes
remains upbeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been a really wonderful week,'' he said Friday
afternoon as he left the Suffolk County Board of Elections in
Yaphank after enrolling as a Democrat. ``I'm making a lot of new
friends, and a lot of my old friends are calling me and reassuring
me that it's not about whether I have a D or R after my name.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The calls are running six to one in favor of the move, and
that's among Republicans who say they are fed up, like I am, with
the extremists who are running the House of Representatives.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes said that when he announced last Saturday that he was
switching parties, he did not know where the move would take him,
personally or politically. ``But this past week has been a pleasant
surprise,'' he said. ``The support has been overwhelming.''
</P>
<P>
   While the majority of voters in the 1st Congressional District
are more apt to vote Republican than Democrat, they are known for
an independent streak. They speak and act more like New Englanders
than New Yorkers, and often ignore party lines in the voting booth.
The district covers the eastern end of Long Island and includes the
communities of Brookhaven, Southampton, East Hampton, Shelter
Island, Riverhead, Southold, the eastern half of Smithtown and a
portion of Kings Park.
</P>
<P>
   At a strip mall on Route 58 at the eastern end of the Long
Island Expressway in Riverhead on Thursday, William Jordan, 68, a
retired teacher who lives in Mattituck, said party designation
meant little to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I agree with your policies, I'll vote for you,'' he said.
``If you're against what I believe, I vote against you. It's that
simple with me. So far, I have no quarrel with Forbes, even though
I'm a Republican. Actually, I didn't even known he'd changed
parties.''
</P>
<P>
   Carol Monahan, a 30-year-old mother with two young children who
was searching for a shopping cart in a supermarket parking lot,
said she did not know who her congressman was. ``Are you talking
about Forbes, that magazine guy who's always running for
president?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes, who won 65 percent of the vote when he last ran for
office as a Republican, said he hoped to win another sizable margin
as the Democratic candidate this fall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-99 1730EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
