<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-CUBS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME RUNS BY ALFONZO AND VENTURA OUTDO SOSA 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Some home runs are more equal than others.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Mets needed two homers Saturday to overcome the one
massive, generously applauded drive Sammy Sosa had launched earlier
at Shea Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   But at the end, the Mets _ baseball's hottest team over the last
seven weeks _ defeated the Chicago Cubs, 2-1, and continued their
drive to unseat the division-leading Atlanta Braves. The pair of
homers by Edgardo Alfonzo and Robin Ventura gave the Mets their
eighth victory in 10 games.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' rookie starter, Octavio Dotel, lost that third-inning
confrontation with Sosa, but he came back to send Sosa down on
strikes in his next two at-bats. That included a theatrical
eighth-inning battle with a runner on second and the Mets nursing
their one-run lead. Sosa chased a 92-mph fastball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I rolled the dice there,'' manager Bobby Valentine said about
leaving Dotel in to face Sosa. ``But this will be something he can
build on for the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Dotel had his second straight strong appearance, going seven and
one-third innings, striking out nine and giving up only five hits
before being relieved by Dennis Cook. Armando Benitez worked the
ninth inning for his 10th save. Dotel's clutch performance came
with his own future uncertain because of the imminent arrival of
Kenny Rogers, who the club hopes is a down-the-stretch winner.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers is scheduled to join the club Sunday, throw a bit on the
sideline, and then join the rotation by starting his first game for
the Mets against the Pirates here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Mets already have a five-man rotation in Dotel, Orel
Hershiser, Al Leiter, Masato Yoshii and Rick Reed, Dotel's
performance was a virtual screen test. It will come down to Yoshii
or Dotel as the odd man out. Valentine, tongue in cheek, suggested:
``Who knows? Maybe I'll go with all six guys if it works.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine added, ``If he's getting outs on breaking balls, he's
a pretty good pitcher.''
</P>
<P>
   Dotel was under enough pressure, and he had to face Sosa as
well. At least it wasn't merengue night, as it was on Friday when
Shea Stadium was full of Sosa fans.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it was Mets' Family Day, players bringing their
youngsters into the clubhouse and onto the field for a pregame
game.
</P>
<P>
   So who was doing that cheering in the third inning when Sosa
clubbed a home run over the 396-foot sign in right center in the
third? It was everyone, mostly.
</P>
<P>
   The stadium erupted into applause, and Valentine and his players
could not blame the promotion of the night before _ when many
Dominican countrymen of Sosa's attended and wildly cheered his home
run.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Saturday's was a spontaneous cheer for the man leading
the major leagues with 36 home runs _ as if New York was big enough
to encompass the Mets and Sosa, a visitor. Perhaps some of those
applauding in the crowd of 47,995 were the children of Mets'
players.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, when Sosa led off the fifth and went down swinging for the
95th time this season, the cheers resounded even louder than for
his home run.
</P>
<P>
   Alfonzo, less famous but a Met, got an even bigger hand in the
fifth, when he smacked a two-out home run to tie the score. The
420-foot shot came off Steve Trachsel, who came in with a 3-13
record and an earned run average of 6.73, but who had held the Mets
to only a pair of hits before Alfonzo's homer.
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth, it was time for another Mets blast, this one by
Ventura on a 3-2 pitch that put the Mets ahead by 2-1. They were
the only runs the hapless Trachsel permitted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
