<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-24 17:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2768 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SET-SLAVS-FREE-ECONOM     07-24 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SET-SLAVS-FREE-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO SAYS SLAVS CAN'T BE DEMOCRATS?  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This excellent 675-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 24 July 1999) ECONOMIST magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, she can be
reached via her e-mail address:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Are Slavs and democracy destined not to mix?
</P>
<P>
   From the harsh plains of northern Europe down to the bloody
Balkans, from the Black Sea across ten time zones to Siberia's
Pacific coast, Slavs have had but feeble and fleeting experiences
of gentle or just government, let alone democracy.
</P>
<P>
   With the fall of communism a decade ago, hopes of freedom rose,
then faded. Two chunks of Slavdom, in particular, have most
patently disappointed: the Slavic core of Russia, Ukraine and
Belarus; and the southern Slavs, centered on Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it is wrong to presume that Slavs can never be democrats.
Corrupt, incompetent and brutal as many of Europe's post-communist
governments have been, political and economic freedoms, albeit
often of the roughest kind, have burst forth in many places that
had seen none before.
</P>
<P>
   Russian elections at various levels have been a remarkable and
cheering novelty. The young, tough, clever and energetic have
unleashed their creative energies.
</P>
<P>
   And those Slavs who have had stronger and longer historic links
with the West _ Poles and Czechs, to name just some _ are indeed
creating juster, as well as richer, societies.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, while Serbs have been making mayhem in the Balkans,
other southern Slavs (Macedonians, Bulgars and Slovenes, among
them) have been striving valiantly to nurture their new
democracies.
</P>
<P>
   It is understandable that many Belarussians and Ukrainians, as
well as Russians, should hanker after the undemocratic but
comforting order of the past. The change has been traumatic and,
for millions of the poor and weak, for the worse.
</P>
<P>
   Russia is still deeply confused. Belarus, a small country of
questionable identity, has fallen under the thrall of a demagogue,
Alexander Lukashenka. Ukraine, with a population of 51 million and
vast economic potential, is a mess.
</P>
<P>
   If the people of those three countries, resenting the West's
seeming arrogance, wish to bond together again and turn their faces
inwards, that is their right.
</P>
<P>
   Though he may be thinking anew, Lukashenka has long sought to
link Belarus to Russia again. With an election for Ukraine's
presidency due in October, several leading candidates want their
country to join up with Russia too. If that happens, the West
cannot object.
</P>
<P>
   But it would be a wrong turn _ for the Slavs as much as for the
West. A bigger, yet still unreformed, Russia would be tempted to be
just that much more mischievous and menacing to its small neighbors
than it is already.
</P>
<P>
   Malign as Lukashenka is to his own people, Belarus on its own
would scarcely frighten Poles or Lithuanians in the way an expanded
Russia, with Belarus as its western flank, inevitably would.
</P>
<P>
   The West must keep its doors open to all those Slavs who may
aspire to join its economic and political clubs, especially the
European Union, so long as the prospective members meet the entry
requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Ukraine, strategically, is the key. Despite the failure of its
economy and the sourness of its politics, it has done well to
persuade the Russians that they should, by treaty, accept its
statehood.
</P>
<P>
   And Russia, it should be said, has done well to recognize that
the disputed Crimean peninsula is sovereign Ukrainian territory,
Russian pride having been salved with special rights for its Black
Sea fleet.
</P>
<P>
   Belarus, though less important geopolitically than Ukraine,
should have the same chance to reach out to the West, especially if
its leader's mooted change of heart is genuine.
</P>
<P>
   The West should do what it can to help and encourage the muzzled
Belarussian opposition. It should lift as many obstacles as
possible to free trade for both Ukraine and Belarus.
</P>
<P>
   Nor should Russia be cold-shouldered. Throwing money at it is
not the answer. But the idea that Russians, any more than other
Slavs, are allergic to democracy is as absurd as the myth of their
special soulfulness.
</P>
<P>
   Europe will never be truly free until settled democracy extends
all the way to the Urals. The West must prod, persuade and
persevere. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
