Alexander Lukashenka. Ukraine, with a population of 51 million and
vast economic potential, is a mess.
</P>
<P>
   If the people of those three countries, resenting the West's
seeming arrogance, wish to bond together again and turn their faces
inwards, that is their right.
</P>
<P>
   Though he may be thinking anew, Lukashenka has long sought to
link Belarus to Russia again. With an election for Ukraine's
presidency due in October, several leading candidates want their
country to join up with Russia too. If that happens, the West
cannot object.
</P>
<P>
   But it would be a wrong turn _ for the Slavs as much as for the
West. A bigger, yet still unreformed, Russia would be tempted to be
just that much more mischievous and menacing to its small neighbors
than it is already.
</P>
<P>
   Malign as Lukashenka is to his own people, Belarus on its own
would scarcely frighten Poles or Lithuanians in the way an expanded
