<DOCNO> NYT19990724.0183 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-24 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2770 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CYC-ARMSTRONG-PROFILE     07-24 2358
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYC-ARMSTRONG-PROFILE25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Armstrong the `Indy car' of cycling
 &HT;    By John Maher
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ When the 86th Tour de France concludes today,
the man who will ride in triumph down the storied Champs-Elysees is
almost certain to be Lance Armstrong. Saturday he won his third
straight time trial on the Tour and will carry a substantial 7
minute 37 second lead into today's final, 89 1/2-mile stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a great cyclist, one who is driven by huge motivation
and determination,'' conceded second-place Alex Zulle of
Switzerland, one of the prerace favorites who have been unable to
match Armstrong in the arduous 2,292-mile odyssey over the Alps and
Pyrenees and through the French countryside.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a pedal stroke apart,'' explained Davis Phinney, a former
U.S. Olympian and current cycling commentator. ``In cycling
everyone has a governor. You reach a point where your lungs are on
fire and your legs seize up. Lance doesn't have that limiter. Most
of us are Jeep Cherokees. He's an Indy car.''
</P>
<P>
   Barring disaster, Armstrong will probably sip champagne today,
but he's just as comfortable pulling on a Shiner Bock. He's an
Austinite, a Texan, an American. He's also a husband, a mother's
son and a survivor who has had a long and sometimes lonely ride to
the top.
</P>
<P>
   He's estranged from both his biological father and the
stepfather that leant him his All-American last name. He'd be Plano
East's most famous graduate, except that school gave him the boot.
He staged a remarkable fight with cancer, only to find that the
professional cycling teams that once courted him, shunned him.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was at the worst time in my life they wanted to forget
about me,'' Armstrong said.
</P>
<P>
   And, during this ride of his life, he's not only had to battle
exhaustion and his rivals, but the constant sniping of the French
sporting media, skeptical that anyone could accomplish such a feat
without the aid of performance-enhancing drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more out of envy and jealousy than anything else,'' said
Chann McRae, an Austin resident and world-class cyclist who has
known Armstrong since they both were boys. ``Lance is the cleanest
rider in the world. What sets him apart is that he is so strong in
the head. If you make him more angry he only gets better. He rides
on rage.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong was born to a teen-age mother and high school dropout.
Linda Walling, whose maiden name is Mooneyham, married another
17-year-old when she turned 17.
</P>
<P>
   Lance's birth that September in 1971 did little to stabilize the
marriage. It quickly foundered and by the time she was 20, Walling
was married again, to Terry Armstrong, a union that lasted until
Lance was 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a long time, there was just the two of us,'' said Walling,
who married her current husband, John Walling, in 1992. ``All I
did, my life, was going to work and raising my son, and I was happy
to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lance grew up in Plano, a football-worshipping suburb of Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were outcasts,'' McRae said only half jokingly. ``Our high
school did not support us at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong once said that he felt like it was him and his mother
against Plano.
</P>
<P>
   The pack mentality and team sports didn't suit Armstrong or
McRae. They soon gravitated toward individual endurance sports.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong wasn't afraid of taking on anyone, racing 10Ks against
adults when he was just a fifth-grader.
</P>
<P>
   McRae remembered, ``You haven't even reached puberty and you're
beating men 10 years older. You think, hey, I've found my gig.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, as teen-agers, they both tried swimming, as Armstrong was
a distance freestyler with City of Plano Swimming, a club team. The
pool was seven miles from his house and Armstrong biked there and
back. On weekends he and McRae would set off on longer jaunts. With
just a pocketful of quarters for drinks and emergency phone calls,
the teen-agers would point their bikes toward Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normally we'd head north,'' McRae said. ``Oklahoma is 60 miles
out, 60 miles back. We used to be out in the Texas heat melting
together. I think we ran out of water and almost died of
dehydration about 100 times.''
</P>
<P>
   When they hit the wall or had a flat, they'd phone one of their
moms to pick them up on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong had much the same bop-till-you-drop style in racing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd bonk sometimes,'' McRae said. ``He'd go all out and he'd
either win or physically explode. He wouldn't go from running to
jogging. He'd go from running to a real slow walk.''
</P>
<P>
   With their riding, running and swimming, the triathlon was a
great fit for both Armstrong and McRae. At the age of 16, Armstrong
was one of the best short-course triathletes in the country. As a
17-year-old, he was that tour's Rookie of the Year, and his prowess
was being noticed outside that sport's small circle. U.S. Cycling
got word that there was a pair of teen-agers in Plano that had some
phenomenal cycling times in the triathlon. Both were invited to
train with the U.S. Junior National Cycling Team. But, there was a
hitch, a big one. School officials at Plano East told them they
couldn't graduate if they took off six weeks during their senior
year.
</P>
<P>
   No is not a word that either Armstrong or his mother liked to
hear.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the most driven person I've ever met,'' McRae said.
``When he puts his mind to something, he won't let anyone get in
the way of his goal. He has always been that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong transferred to a private school, from which he later
graduated. He also did well enough in training that he made the
1989 Junior Worlds squad, which competed in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife was coach of the junior women's team,'' recalled
Phinney, who is married to 1984 Olympic gold medalist Connie
Carpenter Phinney. ``She talked about this guy who would go out
running before he went bike riding. She said he was impressive,
that if he learned technique he'd be unbeatable.''
</P>
<P>
   Phinney encountered Armstrong a little later. ``In 1992 he was
on the U.S. national team,'' Phinney recalled. ``We were in a race
and Lance goes by like an F-14. He left us all behind. At that
point the writing was on the road and it didn't say Phinney, it
said Armstrong. He was born on Mars, and I say that with
admiration. There's not many of them. Michael Jordan. Terrell
Davis.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing Armstrong couldn't distance himself from, however, was
huge expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``No question he is another Greg LeMond. Look at his body. He
has the potential to be a world champion,'' Eddie Borysewicz said
back then. Borysewicz wasn't some gushing fan; he'd been the U.S.
national coach for the 1980 and 1984 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lance was so good so soon and had so many people flocking to
him,'' Phinney said. ``That can be a very heady feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong also was getting known for his attitude. He could
literally work himself into a rage when he road.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gets so mad at his competitors,'' said McRae. ``It could be
about something someone said or just some guy trying to beat him.''
</P>
<P>
   When a win uncorked some of that emotion, Armstrong sometimes
responded by pumping his fist defiantly in the air or with other
gestures that some deemed showboating.
</P>
<P>
   ``People either loved him or hated him,'' Phinney said. ``I
liked his bravado, his take-no-prisoners attitude. You don't want
to be the NBA, but I think our sport needs more of that.''
</P>
<P>
   But in 1992 Armstrong suddenly had little to cheer about.
Instead, he had the wind knocked out of him. He entered the 1992
Olympics as the favorite and the hottest name in the 115-mile road
race in Barcelona. He finished a disappointing 14th. A little
later, in a professional race at San Sebastien in northern Spain,
Armstrong finished 111th in a field of 111. Fans jeered him as a
false phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   He called his mom from the airport in Madrid and told her that
was it, he was done with cycling.
</P>
<P>
   In his new hometown, Austin, where he moved to train on the
nearby hills, Armstrong faced for the first time an uncertain
future. He went in for testing at the Human Performance Laboratory
at the University of Texas to see if there was a scientific reason
for his recent disappointments. It didn't help his mood any that he
was in pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a sprained ankle, he could hardly walk. I think it was
the first time he was ever injured,'' said Eddie Coyle, head of the
lab. Tests, however, indicated that Armstrong was indeed in the
right sport. His levels of lactic acid, the substance that creates
the burning sensation in muscles and overwhelming fatigue, were low
even when compared to those of world-class cyclists. And his motor
could run hotter. While other cyclists may have a heart that can
beat a maximum 180 times a minutes, Armstrong can hit that and keep
working. He tops out at around 200 beats per minute. Coyle and
others noted that Armstrong could make some adjustments in his
technique and improve his efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came back full of piss and vinegar,'' Coyle said.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1993 season Armstrong finished second, behind Mexican
Raul Alcala, in America's biggest stage race, the 11-day Tour
DuPont. He then won three straight races in the U.S. to claim a $1
million prize, posing for cameras with an oversized version of the
prize and his mom. The 21-year-old Armstrong then headed for France
and some seasoning on the granddaddy of all cycling events, the
Tour de France. He won a stage there in a mad sprint in the last 50
yards before withdrawing to prepare for the World Championships in
Norway.
</P>
<P>
   There, he fulfilled his tantalizing potential. In a downpour, on
a slick course where he twice had to recover after crashing,
against Miguel Indurain and many of the world's other great
cyclists, Armstrong staged another one of his F-14 bursts. He won
with such ease that he had time to celebrate harder than any NBA
star after a monster dunk. He ripped the air with bunches, blew
kisses to the crowd and bowed.
</P>
<P>
   King Harald V of Norway summoned him for an audience. But when
messengers told him the invitation was for him alone, they received
a response they hadn't anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong later recalled, ``I don't check my mom at the door. I
don't care who it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Harald V met with the new world champion and the new world
champion's mom.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola, the sponsor of the team, had planned to drop its
sponsorship after the 1993 season, but changed its mind because of
Armstrong's success. In 1995 and 1996, Armstrong won the Tour
DuPont, but success on the longer Tour de France proved elusive.
Perhaps that was because Armstrong looked too All-American.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of the gaunt look of an endurance cyclist, the
broad-shouldered Armstrong had the appearance of an athlete who
could play any sport or a regular guy who could enjoy an occasional
Mexican dinner washed down with a cold beer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if it's muscle it's a gravity sport. You've got to go
uphill,'' Phinney explained.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in 1996, Armstrong's world was turned upside down. At the
Atlanta Olympics, where he was favored to go gold, he finished well
out of the medals.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong hadn't given much thought to a swollen testicle. But
while he was at his Austin home one fall day he began spitting up
blood.
</P>
<P>
   ``This wasn't drops, it was buckets,'' Armstrong said.
</P>
<P>
   In October, Armstrong was diagnosed with testicular cancer. Just
as he steeled himself for that fight, he got another jolt. The
cancer had spread to his lungs and abdomen and even to his brain.
In his lung there were tumors the size of golf balls.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very far advanced. It was about as severe as you can
get,'' said Dr. Lawrence Inhering, one of the doctors who treated
Armstrong at Indiana University Medical Center in Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Given only a 50-50 chance of living, Armstrong endured surgery
and chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's never pleasant to go through,'' Einhorn said. ``Everybody
gets hair loss. Loss of appetite and nausea. But he was always very
positive.''
</P>
<P>
   He vowed not merely to live, but to resume his demanding life as
a professional cyclist. In 1997, a year after he had stood at
death's door, he was declared cancer free. He began working to
resume his old career and started a new one as a crusader against
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall of 1997, Armstrong created the nonprofit Lance
Armstrong Foundation. It's premiere event is the Ride for the Roses
here. In 1998 the event raised more than $300,000 for medical
research. The foundation also sponsors a conference and supports
various scientific and research efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most surprising thing was not that he survived,'' said Dr.
Craig Nichols, one of the doctors who treated Armstrong. ``The most
surprising thing, and it was very pleasant and gratifying, was what
he did afterwards, how much he gave back. He's trying to make sure
this doesn't happen to other men.''
</P>
<P>
   If cycling teams appreciated Armstrong's charitable work, they
didn't show it. Cofidis, which had signed him to a lucrative
contract in 1995, dropped him. Others didn't return his calls. He
finally signed with the U.S. Postal Service team with a contract
full of incentives, but not the kind of salary he once commanded.
</P>
<P>
   The cancer treatments, however, had one effect on him that would
make him a cyclist better suited for the Tour de France. He lost
about 15 pounds. Most of it was muscle, but it was that upper body
muscle that just weighs down endurance cyclists.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong married Kristin Richard last year and she and his
mother will be there to share in the celebration if a leaner, far
wiser Armstrong becomes only the second American to win France's
greatest sporting event.
</P>
<P>
   While the French media continue to snipe at Armstrong, those
who've worked with him have no doubts that his performance is real,
and not drug aided.
</P>
<P>
   Coyle has tested Armstrong and his blood over a period of seven
years. He said, ``In all my testing I've seen no evidence of any
drugs. He's totally clean.''
</P>
<P>
   And now he's only one day away from completing perhaps the
greatest comeback in the history of sport.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
