<P>
   CARIBBEAN-TRADE-$ADV25 _ SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic _ At
first glance, the proposed Caribbean Basin Parity Trade Initiative
winding its way through Congress looks like small beans. But the
measure, being pushed by Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla., as well as
President Clinton, merits attention for several reasons. First, the
region is the United States' sixth-largest export market. Second,
the measure would eliminate tariffs on a variety of items including
clothes and watches, meaning the prices for those items in U.S.
stores should go down. And the measure could boost economies in the
Caribbean, which would hopefully stem immigration that has
skyrocketed since last year's hurricanes. We look at the impact of
CBI on the average Joe, and in particular on states such as
Florida, Georgia and Texas. Measure should come up for passage by
mid-July. (Emling, Cox News Service) Moving in international and
financial categories. WITH GRAPHIC. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-ELECT _ MEXICO CITY _ The world's longest ruling party,
Mexico's Revolutionary Institutional Party, or PRI, could be facing
the most competitive presidential election ever in July 2000.
Mexico is creeping toward democracy, and elections are hotter than
ever thanks to a more vigilant press, the use of polls and more
transparent election systems and rules. The PRI, which still
controls most of Mexican political life, will be tested in July by
opposition candidates who have mustered unprecedented strength,
especially the brash Vicente Fox of Mexico's conservative
opposition. Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, on the left, has fallen behind in
polls but is still a likely contender. But first, four candidates
within the ruling PRI will battle for their party's nomination in
the party's first-ever primary in November. (Ferriss, Cox News
Service) MOVED.
</P>
