<HEADER>
A2782 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLD-GEEZER-POLITICS-E     07-24 1350
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLD-GEEZER-POLITICS-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED, WHITE 'N' GREY: OLD IS GOLD TO VOTE SEEKERS  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This excellent 1,100-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 24 July 1999) ECONOMIST magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, she can be
reached via her e-mail address:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   They waddle slowly through the shopping malls; drive with
exaggerated care on the freeways; fumble with their change at the
checkout tills.
</P>
<P>
   In America's impatient culture, where competition is everything
and the richest man (counting his Microsoft billions just east of
Seattle) is only 43, it is easy to deride the elderly as
preordained losers, to be lectured at rather than listened to.
</P>
<P>
   As Oscar Wilde pointed out more than a century ago, ``In
America, the young are always ready to give to those who are older
than themselves the full benefit of their inexperience.''
</P>
<P>
   So why is it that the concerns of the old are the obsessions of
the political establishment?
</P>
<P>
   For the past two years the policy debate has been dominated not
by education, or race, or the environment, or gun control _ all of
them worthy enough topics for most Americans _ but by the future of
Medicare and Social Security, the two entitlement programs for the
elderly.
</P>
<P>
   Is this because American politicians have charitable feelings
that other Americans lack? Or because, pace Wilde, they respect the
aged even as they themselves strive so hard to appear unchangingly
young?
</P>
<P>
   Unhappily, the reason lies elsewhere: in the simple fact that
the old vote more readily than the young.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1996 federal elections, for example, just under half of
the electorate aged 25-44 voted, accounting for 39 percent of the
turnout. By contrast, 64 percent of voters aged 45-64 voted and 67
percent of those aged 65 or over; together they accounted for 53
percent of the turnout.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, if you win the votes of the old and those who
can see old age fast approaching, you win the election _ a formula
that becomes ever more convincing as Americans live longer and as
the baby-boomers move past the menopause.
</P>
<P>
   One youngish Democratic strategist bluntly explains: ``If
they're going to pander to me by coming out to vote, I'm going to
pander to them.'' Translate that into policy, and it means
emphasizing things like Social Security and downplaying tax cuts
(after all, the retired don't pay much tax).
</P>
<P>
   In short, the Democrats can present themselves as the party of
the New Deal, when Franklin Roosevelt introduced Social Security
specifically to abolish poverty among the old.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the Republicans are ready to jeopardize the
retirement safety net with wild schemes of privatization.
</P>
<P>
   How well this Democratic plan will work in next year's elections
remains to be seen. After all, in last year's midterm elections
elderly whites _ though not blacks _ tended to vote Republican,
apparently in protest at President Bill Clinton's antics with
Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   And in any case it must surely be a mistake (typical of the
young) to characterize the old as being all alike. Democrats like
to describe as typical the 70-year-old widow, able to get by for
the moment but terrified by the prospect of unaffordable nursing
care and prescription drugs (which are the fastest growing area of
spending by the old).
</P>
<P>
   The Republican riposte usually features the retired shopkeeper,
made wealthy by the stock market boom and hoping not to be
clobbered by capital-gains tax, or the arthritic farmer, anxious
that his descendants will not be impoverished by inheritance taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Both Democratic and Republican images are selective snapshots of
a reality in which the median net worth of households headed by
Americans aged 65 or over is around double the national average _
but in which a tenth of such households are also living in poverty.
</P>
<P>
   No matter. It is surely pleasant for all the old, so often
ignored by their children (32 million Americans aged 65 and over
live alone), to feel wanted, even if only by politicians and
pharmaceutical companies.
</P>
<P>
   The puzzle, however, is their reluctance to enjoy being old, to
admit to being ``grey warriors'' even as the politicians pay homage
to grey power.
</P>
<P>
   The old are not ``old,'' they are ``senior citizens''; their
persuasive lobby group, the AARP, calls itself an association of
``retired persons'' (which may be reasonable enough since its
membership begins at the age of 50); their retirement ghettos in
Florida and Arizona are ``gated communities,'' some of which offer
``assisted living'' for those who have become physically or
mentally ``challenged.''
</P>
<P>
   In one sense this reluctance is doubtless universal. It seems
unlikely, for example, that the Japanese, even as they preach that
age, wisdom and power all go together, actually appreciate seeing
the effects of gravity on their aging bodies. And no one,
regardless of race or culture, can be happy as muscles and memory
begin to fade.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Americans are surely unique in their determination not
to grow old gracefully. Last year, for example, they paid for
almost 2.8 million cosmetic procedures, from ``tummy tucks'' to
hair transplants, which were designed either to adjust reality or
to stave off the inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   Of these, almost a quarter were done to the bodies of baby
boomers and their siblings in their 50s and 60s.
</P>
<P>
   Is such suffering endured in a good cause? In the sense that the
more competition the better, maybe so. Let the old, if they feel so
inclined, strive against the young for everyone's economic benefit.
But let them not feel they have to be so inclined.
</P>
<P>
   When Americans are asked to define the age at which ``old''
begins, those who are aged 18-24 answer 58 _ but those aged 65 or
over answer 75.
</P>
<P>
   With luck that shift of definition is positive, evidence that
today's new ``seniors'' are enjoying the rejuvenating effects of
Viagra, HRT and the rest of the pharmacopoeia pressed on them at
every commercial break in the TV programming.
</P>
<P>
   There is, however, a less happy explanation. Even though the
advance of medicine is slowing the aging process and extending
life-expectancy, some 63 percent of American adults would,
according to an AARP survey, prefer not to live to 100.
</P>
<P>
   The leading reason for their reluctance is a fear of being in
poor health, but the second reason _ cited by 38 percent of the
poll _ is the fear of not having enough money.
</P>
<P>
   Add those feelings of insecurity to the demographic arithmetic
(the number of 65-and-overs will almost double in the next 30
years), and no wonder Democrats and Republicans alike have decided
to use the budget surplus to ``save Social Security first.''
</P>
<P>
   Why not, if in electoral terms age comes so clearly before
beauty? If the young object, they can always go and vote. &QL; 
