<HEADER>
A2787 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-WHALEN-PROFILE-AR     07-24 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WHALEN-PROFILE-ART-665&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG PICTURE IN FOCUS, WHALEN PLAYS SMALL TIME 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two weeks ago, Sara Whalen played in the biggest game
of her life in front of 90,000 fans at the Rose Bowl. On Saturday,
she played on a much smaller stage, in front of fewer than 2,000
fans at North Hempstead Park.
</P>
<P>
   But Whalen doesn't see the shift from playing in the Women's
World Cup final in Pasadena, Calif., to playing in a
semiprofessional game in New Hyde Park, as a letdown. As one of the
younger members of the U.S. women's national team, she views
playing in the United Soccer League's W-League as a way to
strengthen her skills while earning some extra income.
</P>
<P>
   ``The number of people watching the game has never been an issue
for me,'' said Whalen, 23, who was a reserve defender on the
national team. ``The W-League is less stressful, but it's important
to the players. Whether I'm playing in front of 90,000 people or
I'm playing in front of 10 people, the soccer part never changes. I
play because I love to play.''
</P>
<P>
   In the World Cup final against China, Whalen replaced the
injured Michelle Akers at the start of overtime and played solidly.
In the tournament, she played 165 minutes in the three matches, and
was a starter in a victory against North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a lot of playing time for a reserve in the World Cup,
but I'm probably not as tired as the starters,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday night she made her season debut with the Long Island
Lady Riders, who are 9-4 over all and in first place in the North
Division. The Lady Riders, who won the league title in 1995 and
1997, played the Rochester Ravens at North Hempstead Park.
</P>
<P>
   Whalen, who is a native of Greenlawn, was an all-America player
at the University of Connecticut in 1995, 1996 and 1997. She first
joined the Lady Riders in 1997 and helped them to win their second
W-League title. She also played for the Lady Riders in 1998, but
because of her commitment to the national team this year, was
available to return to the Long Island team only after the World
Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, 17 former or current national team players were in
the 5-year-old W-League _ the only national soccer league for
women. But during World Cup years, the majority of the team _ in
particular the star players like Akers, Mia Hamm, Julie Foudy,
Brandi Chastain and Briana Scurry _ take time off to recharge.
</P>
<P>
   This season, only a handful of national team players are in the
W-League: Whalen, Tracy Ducar and Cindy Parlow, both with the
Raleigh Wings, and Christie Pearce, with the New Jersey Lady
Stallions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of Sara's teammates, I'm sure, want to take some time
off, and that's understandable,'' said Chuck Jacob, owner of the
Lady Riders. ``But some players just like to play. In Sara's case,
she probably would have liked to play more during the World Cup. So
she's in shape and ready to play.''
</P>
<P>
   As for watching one of his players celebrate the World Cup
championship, Jacob said: ``It was fantastic. What a thrill it was
to pick up Time Magazine last week and see Sara smack in the middle
of the cover. Though she might not have been the most pivotal
player, it was great. The whole Women's World Cup was a tremendous
boost for the sport.''
</P>
<P>
   Whalen agreed. ``I think the one thing I've noticed the most is
that we're drawing a bigger scope of people,'' she said. ``We're
seeing 40-year-old men, crying with joy, with their two sons. I
think our team has done a lot for women's sports in general, not
just soccer. Look at all of the positive role models on the team.
Growing up, I couldn't have imagined this.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been a chaotic month for Whalen. But it has also been one
that she says she will not forget. Since winning the cup, she and
her teammates have been given the VIP treatment, making stops in
Disney Land, New York City, the White House, Cape Canaveral, Fla.,
and back to New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a great ride,'' said Whalen. ``We got to fly on
Hillary Clinton's jet, go to the White House and hang out with
Bill. I mean, what more can I say?''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But now it's back to business. Whalen hopes to make the U.S.
Olympic team that will go to Sydney, Australia, for the 2000 Summer
Games. But being the last of the 20 players selected for the World
Cup team, and knowing that there are only 18 roster spots for the
Olympic squad, Whalen believes she has to work even harder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel positive because I was playing first or second off the
bench against China, so I feel good about myself,'' Whalen said.
``I definitely feel that way. I was going through a tough time with
where my position was on the team, barely made the World Cup team.
I gained a lot of experience.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
