<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKE-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE EVERLY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   and dynamite production resumed.
</P>
<P>
   But explosives, which once employed thousands in Carthage, are a
dwindling part of the town's economy. The biggest employer is
Leggett &AMP; Platt, a furniture maker. The area's economy also is
increasingly dependent on visitors. And the two _ explosives and
tourism _ don't always get along.
</P>
<P>
   Carthage is probably best known for being home to the company
that sells those teardrop-eyed Precious Moments characters, which
are reproduced in porcelain figurines and on other products.
</P>
<P>
   The company draws 750,000 visitors a year to its chapel, which
it says was inspired by the Sistine Chapel. But at this chapel, the
biblical characters are replaced by Precious Moments characters.
</P>
<P>
   Precious Moments built the chapel on property that adjoins ICI,
the other explosives plant in Carthage. When ICI a few years ago
planned to build an incinerator to burn surplus explosives and
ammunition, Precious Moments sued and got an agreement on how the
incinerator would operate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have every reason to believe that the incinerator is
running in a perfectly proper fashion,'' said Ted Easley, a senior
project manager for Precious Moments.
</P>
<P>
   VanGilder, who has also written a history of the Carthage area,
says tourism will become even more important in the future. And
rather than being hidden, he said, the area's explosives industry
and the last dynamite plant in North America deserve to be part of
that heritage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shouldn't be forgotten,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
