<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-24 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2791 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DYNO--TWOTAKES-KAN &LR;      07-24 1192
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DYNO--TWO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DYNAMITE PRODUCTION A SOLID PART OF TOWN'S ECONOMY 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE EVERLY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARTHAGE, Mo. _ From its Victorian mansions to a Civil War
battlefield, this southwest Missouri town is steeped in history.
Even a chunk of Route 66 still gives off some kicks.
</P>
<P>
   Carthage's visitors bureau offers dozens of brochures about the
town's history and its attractions, including the nearby Precious
Moments chapel. But you'll find no mention of a group of buildings
on the city's outskirts.
</P>
<P>
   The buildings are home to the last plant in North America that
makes dynamite _ the explosive that played such a crucial role in
this country's development that it has been called the single most
important engineering tool from the Civil War to the end of World
War II.
</P>
<P>
   Now dynamite is in the twilight of its career. The workhorse has
been displaced with cheaper and safer explosives. Dynamite
accounted for far less than 1 percent of the explosives used in the
United States last year.
</P>
<P>
   And as dynamite wanes, the circle is closing with a nod to the
explosive's heritage. The Carthage plant, in operation since early
in the century, is now owned by a company that traces its roots to
dynamite's inventor, Alfred Nobel. The company's name: Dyno Nobel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The legacy continues,'' said Paul Worsey, director of the
University of Missouri-Rolla's Explosive Research Center.
Dynamite's story began in the mid-1800s, when a new explosive was
needed to make coal and mineral mining and improvements such as
railroad tunnels economical and speedy.
</P>
<P>
   Black powder lacked the needed punch, and liquid nitroglycerin
was so unstable that hundreds of lives were lost in accidental
explosions.
</P>
<P>
   In Sweden, Nobel came up with a solution: mix nitroglycerin with
an absorbent material to create a paste that could be shaped into
sticks of dynamite. The new explosive was far more stable than
nitroglycerin and packed the necessary wallop to cut through hard
rock. Nobel, whose explosives fortune would eventually finance the
Nobel Prizes, took out a patent in 1867.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did dynamite allow mining to flourish, it was at the
center of the country's most notable construction projects. Hoover
Dam, for instance, was completed in the 1930s after using 8 million
pounds of dynamite. The project wouldn't have happened without the
explosive, the dam's officials say.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, dynamite blew away rock to make way for the
system of interstate highways. The Alaska Pipeline used 36 million
pounds of the explosive in one of the last big projects in which
dynamite played a large role.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the going got tough, the tough used dynamite,'' said S.S.
Jenkins Jr., a Kansas City area resident with a 40-year career in
explosives and the author of a book about the explosives industry,
(begin ital.)Short Fuses(end ital.).
</P>
<P>
   Dynamite's popularity peaked in the 1950s. Since then it has
lost customers to newer explosives that are cheaper and safer. Out
of 6 billion pounds of explosives sold last year in the United
States, only 20 million pounds were dynamite, according to the
Institute of Makers of Explosives.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't use dynamite for sentimental reasons,'' said Bob
Pilshaw, an Overland Park blasting consultant and a former
distributor of explosives.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the fading of dynamite isn't without some regrets.
Pilshaw's son, Russell, is a blasting contractor in Lawrence, Kan.,
and uses other explosives for most his work. He sees the day when
he won't have to use dynamite at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of sad,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When that day is coming, no one will say for certain. Dyno
already makes other explosives at the Carthage plant. A Dyno
spokesman said that there was still a small market for dynamite and
that the company would supply it.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this time we're committed to fill the niche,'' said Brad
Larson, a Dyno spokesman in Oslo, Norway, the company's
headquarters. The company, which is the second-largest seller of
explosives in the world, operates one other dynamite plant, outside
Oslo. Dyno Nobel was established in 1865 by Alfred Nobel's
associate Carl Wennerstrom, who bought the Norwegian patent rights
for Nobel's methods for producing nitroglycerin. Later the company
began producing dynamite.
</P>
<P>
   The company squared its historical circle with Nobel in 1986
when it bought Nitro Nobel AB, the Swedish company Nobel founded in
1864 under the name Nitroglycerin Aktiebolag.
</P>
<P>
   ``We make quite a bit of it. ...There's a huge debt owed to
Alfred Nobel,'' Larson said.
</P>
<P>
   Dyno came to Missouri in the mid-1980s, when it bought the
Carthage plant from another explosives manufacturer, continuing a
tradition from the early 1900s of making explosives in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Originally the Carthage explosives factory supplied the region's
lead and zinc mines and marble quarries. By the early 1900s, the
area had four explosives plants. The mines and quarries have all
but disappeared, but the Nobel plant and one other explosives
factory remain.
</P>
<P>
   Today about 270 people work at the Dyno plant, which is known
for good wages and benefits. To get there they travel down a road
on the far outskirts of town, past Cloud's Meat Processing and the
company that makes Ott's salad dressing.
</P>
<P>
   The dynamite plant is surrounded by a chain-link fence to keep
unwanted visitors out. At a guardhouse, people are screened before
a gate is opened. Signs at the entrance warn that no smoking,
lighters, matches or other flame producing devices are permitted on
the grounds. ``No Hunting'' signs are planted around the property.
</P>
<P>
   Plant executives keep a low profile and rarely comment publicly
about operations. Area residents seem to take the plant in stride.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're glad it's here; it's accepted,'' said Marjorie Bull, a
Carthage resident.
</P>
<P>
   But the coexistence isn't always peaceful.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago the plant was deemed one of the 50 worst water
polluters in the country. Company officials agreed to improve
wastewater treatment at the plant, which must use some powerful
chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   In April a fire at the plant caused the evacuation of some
nearby homes. The fire was put out with no injuries or explosions.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was the explosion on a July day in 1966.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told someone, `Listen to the thunder,' but I looked up and
there were no clouds,'' said Doris Wardlow, who was about 30 miles
away when the first explosion occurred.
</P>
<P>
   A truck had driven onto the dynamite plant's grounds with one of
its wheels on fire. The fire spread to some brush and then to the
plant and the bunkers where dynamite was stored.
</P>
<P>
   After the first explosion, Marvin VanGilder, then editor of
(begin ital.)The Carthage Press(end ital.), ran outside and saw a
mushroom cloud rising above the plant. Many in Carthage thought it
was a nuclear attack by the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   In the next 13 hours, six explosions leveled the plant and
caused damage to many parts of Carthage. Only one person was
killed, however, and three dozen residents suffered only minor
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a miracle,'' said VanGilder.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
