<HEADER>
A2792 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOROCCO-HASSAN-BOS &LR;      07-24 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOROCCO-HASSAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMAN DESCRIBES MOROCCAN KING AS BENEVOLENT AND CRUEL
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS W. HAINES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Heads of state from Washington to the Middle East are
mourning the passing of Morocco's King Hassan II, praising him as a
broker of peace, a stabilizing force in a turbulent region.
</P>
<P>
   But few people have reacted to the news of Hassan's death as
personally as Malika Oufkir, a striking woman who has lived a
catalog of lives _ childhood palace harem member, 20-year prisoner,
expatriate in Paris _ at Hassan's whim.
</P>
<P>
   Oufkir, 46, recounted her travails earlier this year in ``La
Prisonniere,'' a memoir that hit Paris bestseller lists and shed
light on the darker side of life within Morocco's royal circle. Her
story details two nightmarish decades of imprisonment, many in
Morocco's southern desert, locked alongside her mother and five
siblings because her father, once a powerful Hassan ally, tried to
assassinate the king.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, sitting on the edge of a bed in the bright loft
designed by her husband, a Paris architect, Oufkir described the
emotional conflicts she still feels toward Hassan, a man criticized
for violating human rights to retain his power.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time I heard he was dead, it was sadness, because he
was my father, because I cannot forget my childhood. With him, he
took a part of my life,'' Oufkir said, speaking in English. ``Now,
it's la serenite, it's peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Oufkir's story has resounded so strongly here because it is has
universal elements of lost youth, of helplessness in the face of
power. Also, in a nation closely linked to Morocco _ France
colonized the country and controlled it until after World War II _
Oufkir's memoirs have given rare insight into the fantasy of life
inside Hassan's circle and the horror of life outside it.
</P>
<P>
   But Oufkir does not use her history as a political weapon,
railing against Hassan and his policies. As she speaks in calm,
measured tones, it is clear that to her, the journey is one of
personal understanding, of deciphering the intersections of her
life with Hassan's.
</P>
<P>
   When Oufkir was born, in 1954, her birth father, Mohammed
Oufkir, was becoming a powerful player within the monarchy. When
she was 5, Hassan's father adopted her into the palace, making her
a member of Hassan's personal harem.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a decade, she lived a pampered life, sheltered
within the palace walls. Hassan, who succeeded to the throne in
1961, became the dominant man in her life, gentle and attentive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only man I used to speak with and have a relationship with
was the king,'' she said. ``He was my father, and he was also the
king.''
</P>
<P>
   As a teenager, Oufkir wanted out, to return to her natural
family. Hassan granted her wish in 1970. For more than two years,
she reveled in a wealthy, fast-paced life, jetting to Hollywood to
pursue acting dreams, meeting Steve McQueen and other stars of the
day.
</P>
<P>
   Her birth father had become one of Hassan's most powerful
lieutenants, rising to minister of defense. But privately, he was
one of Hassan's most potent opponents. In August 1972, Oufkir led
an attempt to assassinate Hassan as the king's personal jet
returned from Paris to Rabat, one of several attempts on the
monarch's life early in his reign.
</P>
<P>
   Oufkir's body was discovered later. The palace described the
death as a suicide, but multiple bullet wounds pierced the body.
</P>
<P>
   Several months later, Malika Oufkir, her mother, five siblings,
and a cousin were imprisoned in the south Moroccan desert.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was when the nightmare began,'' Oufkir said.
</P>
<P>
   For a few years, the family was kept together. Eventually, they
were separated in another prison: damp cells, scarce food,
scorpions. No doctor. No books.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eight years inside jail, without sun, without going outside,''
Oufkir said. In 1987, Oufkir, a sister, and two brothers tunneled
their way to freedom, only to be recaptured after weeks on the run.
International attention pressured Hassan to lighten their sentence
to house arrest. In 1991, the family, which had held together for
years, was released. In 1996, after more outside pressure, the
family was allowed to leave Morocco.
</P>
<P>
   With Hassan's son, King Mohamed VI, enthroned Saturday, Oufkir
seemed optimistic, hoping that he will bring better things to her
native country.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you forgive, without forgetting, you can better
understand the future,'' she said. ``That's why I am looking
forward, and hope the Morocco of the future is a Morocco of
democracy and equality.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, on what turned out to be his final trip to
Paris, Hassan told a French interviewer he regretted the way Oufkir
and her family had been treated.
</P>
<P>
   That brought Oufkir some peace, but left one lingering question:
Why did Hassan, who showered affection on her when she was young,
take away her freedom for acts she did not commit?
</P>
<P>
   ``For me,'' she said, ``it is forever the only question without
answer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
