A2793 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUMMER-BEACH-CLUB-895     07-24 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUMMER-BEACH-CLUB-895(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGING SHORE ENCLAVE IS STILL A FAVORITE PLACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JODI WILGOREN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTIC BEACH, N.Y. _ Under a color caricature of 10 fat old
men playing cards, 10 mostly fat, fairly old men sit playing cards,
as another summer day dwindles at the Old Westbury Beach Club.
</P>
<P>
   They have been here forever, it seems. Maybe not Philly Hutter
in his seersucker shorts and shirt, or Mel Bessen, with the
gold-and-diamond pendant of a king playing card that he won in a
poker game, or Big Jerry with his hairy back. Maybe it was their
fathers.
</P>
<P>
   The game is seven-card stud, high-low, white chips a quarter,
red and black a buck. Eight, nine, 10 balding and graying heads
crowd around the table every afternoon, here by the pool if it's
breezy or, when it gets sweaty hot, upstairs under an awning, with
an ocean view nobody bothers to look at.
</P>
<P>
   Cabana boys call it ``Grumpier Old Men, Part 3,'' and, like
actors on cue, the men argue about everything from how to deal the
cards to how to split the pot to how often to take ``latrine
calls.'' They grumble over what they've lost and what the others
have won, wondering, perhaps, what they are doing there, but never
thinking about not showing up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come here in the summertime; in the winter, I go to
Florida,'' says Bessen, 64, a retired jeweler. ``I don't golf. I
don't play tennis. I enjoy playing cards.''
</P>
<P>
   The Old Westbury is one of a dozen beach clubs that form a
Borscht Belt by the sea on a mile-long strip of sand just. Unlike
the dying resorts in the Catskills, the beach clubs, most built in
the 1930s, are thriving, filled with a new generation of toddlers
and their toys, even as old-timers like Dr. Murray Bookbinder, 94,
struggle to maneuver along the boards with their walkers.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to summer communities in the Hamptons or on Martha's
Vineyard, Atlantic Beach on the South Shore is a day-tripper's
domain: They come after lunch and leave before dinner, or start
with a swim at sunup and stay for sunset cocktails.
</P>
<P>
   They stream over Long Island's only toll bridge ($1.25 each way)
mostly from the neighboring Five Towns region, but also from
elsewhere in Nassau and Suffolk counties, and New York City.
(Residents of Atlantic Beach have a small patch of sand set aside,
but otherwise, access to the ocean is limited to club members.)
</P>
<P>
   Alyssa Mack Kuhn has moved to Springfield, Ill., but she and her
children stay with her parents all summer so they can be at the
corner cabana in the Catalina, where three generations of her
family have camped for three decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are things we did as children, and these are things we
do with our children,'' says Mrs. Kuhn, 38, who has spent 33
summers kibitzing at the Catalina. ``I always knew I wanted to give
them what I had.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the clubs are as Jewish as Jerusalem, the Long Island
accents as thick as the humidity. They are places where everybody
knows your name (and, probably, your mother's), but members might
not recognize one another in street clothes rather than swimsuits.
</P>
<P>
   It is a family scene, with a startling number of stay-at-home
moms and only a handful of bankers on cellular phones. There are
lots of teachers on summer break and people who work in the garment
industry; the parking lot has as many sport utility vehicles as
Cadillacs. The younger women wear matching wrap miniskirts on top
of their swimsuits and carry Kate Spade bags; the older ones have
tissues sticking out of their tops.
</P>
<P>
   Every summer, someone spreads a fresh coat of paint _ peach at
Sunny Atlantic, sea-foam green at the Catalina _ over everything in
sight. The rest is the same as it ever was.
</P>
<P>
   Women with fresh lipstick play mah-jongg, as their mothers did.
Men with clunky gold Stars of David around their necks play cards,
like their dads. And children play and play, splashing in kiddie
pools, safe in the sand courts surrounded by cul-de-sacs of
cabanas.
</P>
<P>
   Some stroll along the shore, some take a steam, some just sit
and schmooze.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like camp for adults,'' says Ilene Pachtman, 45, sunning
herself at the Catalina. ``We're all really close. Which came
first, I don't know. We've always had the cabana.''
</P>
<P>
   Cabanas, small wooden cabins connected to one another, cost
$3,000 to $10,000 for the season, depending on the club and the
location, and most people split them among two or three families. A
cheaper choice is a locker, which has space to store things and to
change, but nowhere to hang out. Locker people usually stay by the
ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Not quite a beach house, a cabana falls somewhere between a
large walk-in closet and a tiny Manhattan living room, but
nonetheless has touches of home. People display color-coordinated
plastic plates on shelves, and decorate the swinging wooden doors
to the two changing rooms with matching shelf paper. Most have
showers in the back, very few a toilet. Some clubs have cabanas
with electricity, and thus toasters, microwaves, refrigerators and
telephone lines. Once, someone put up a satellite dish to catch
MTV.
</P>
<P>
   There is a Martha Stewart-inspired cabana with wicker
wastebaskets, plastic flowers and country touches, and a nostalgic
one where a framed print of Frank Sinatra hangs above the full bar
with blender.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever you want to do,'' Paul Malkin, the 75-year-old owner
of the Sunny Atlantic, says as he shows off a locker festooned with
yellow-and-white wallpaper and a framed print. ``This is your home
away from home.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Like any community, the clubs, which range in size from the
intimate Sunny Atlantic, with 100 cabanas, to the sprawling Silver
Point, with 800, have their cliques.
</P>
<P>
   Old folks tend to gather by the pool, shaded by the awnings in
front of their cabanas, rarely stepping on sand. The bustling
neighborhood is the sand court, where cabana shelves are filled
with peanut butter and animal crackers rather than vodka and tonic,
and a mountain of plastic beach toys collects in the middle.
Upstairs, on what some clubs call the crow's nest, are the adults
who have older children, who are off at camps or summer jobs.
(There is virtually no one 10 to 18 at the clubs, and there are few
people in their 20s.)
</P>
<P>
   Along the beach, the colors of the umbrellas change from club to
club. Inside, each clapboard compound has a distinct character. The
Sun and Surf does not provide furniture but lets members remodel,
so the cabanas have built-in sinks and even bunk beds. The
brass-and-mirrors Sands offers a flea market of jewelry and gifts
on Wednesdays, and has a kosher caterer and three party rooms.
Silver Point is the largest and the cheapest.
</P>
<P>
   At the kitschy Catalina, members are sure the 1984 Matt Dillon
movie, ``The Flamingo Kid,'' was shot there. (Actually, it was at
the Silver Gull Beach Club on Breezy Point.) It may as well have
been.
</P>
<P>
   Water aerobics have replaced the movie's poolside dance classes,
and there is a cafeteria-style restaurant rather than the El
Flamingo's overflowing smorgasbord. But the cabana boys are every
bit as tan, and just as likely to have flirtatious middle-aged
women tucking dollars in their pockets.
</P>
<P>
   The cabana boy _ there seem to be only boys, though the rare
young woman gets a job as a parking valet _ is the essence of
beach-club culture. This is what makes members who cannot afford a
house in the Hamptons feel rich. When you're thirsty, just holler
his name.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get a second, can I get iced tea the way I like it?''
Stephanie Schandler asks Asher Friend, 22, a cabana boy at the
Westbury.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know exactly what that means,'' Friend says, rushing for the
tea, with two lemons squeezed and four packets of Sweet 'n Low.
``There's a million little things that you kind of just have to
know. Let's say someone's allergic to pickles _ and I have that _
everything they have here comes with pickles. So I have to
remember, even though he doesn't tell me every time.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Spiegel, 22, started on the strip six years ago as a chair
boy, lugging 100 lounge chairs a day in hope of $1 tips. Now he is
head cabana boy at the Old Westbury, in charge of tending to the
Game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Larry, I think I'm ready for a brew,'' says Skip Sturza, a
stack of chips in front of his ample belly. ``Give me a Chinese
brew.''
</P>
<P>
   The club does not keep cards on hand, which is why Spiegel once
spent a night running to five drugstores in search of the
jumbo-size Bicycle cards the Game requires.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys are pretty demanding,'' Spiegel says. ``They're
harder than kids to take care of. They have to have their way.'' He
stops for a second. ``They're going to read that and kill me.''
</P>
<P>
   The women are a few cabanas away, deep in their own game at the
mah-jongg table. Most mah-jongg players are somebody's grandmother,
but four women in their late 30s, best friends who live in the Five
Towns, decided two years ago that it was time to learn the game
their mothers used to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a rite of passage,'' says Debbie Zelvin of Woodmere,
getting ready to leave the club in time to meet the day-camp bus.
</P>
<P>
   At another mah-jongg game by the pool, where the most you can
lose in a day is $10, Charlotte Brust and her daughter, Ronnie
Soled, sit at the same table.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are we going to do in the city, sit on a bench?'' asks
Mrs. Brust, 76, who lives in Manhattan with her husband, Frank, a
staple of the poker game. ``We get here early, like 10 o'clock. We
stay here until 6, 7 o'clock. We find something to eat. By the time
we get home, it's time to go to bed already. We wake up and come
back the next day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
