<SLUG> BC-CAR-NOTES25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Course favors Gordon
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG POND, Pa. _ After a week off, NASCAR shifts into gear today
with the Pennsylvania 500.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Skinner is at the pole position for the 1:05 p.m. race. He
will share the front row with No. 2 qualifier Mark Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Pocono is the site of a circuit race for the second time in five
weeks, with Bobby Labonte winning the Pocono 500 June 20. The track
is considered one of NASCAR's toughest because of its shape
(tri-oval) and distance (2.5 miles).
</P>
<P>
   ``This track is definitely unique,'' said Jeff Gordon, defending
Pennsylvania 500 champion.
</P>
<P>
   No one may know the tricky course better than Gordon, who starts
seventh. He has finished first or second in seven of the past eight
races at Pocono. His worst performance was a No. 7 finish in July
1996.
</P>
<P>
   Back on track
</P>
<P>
   The return to racing could not arrive any sooner for Winston Cup
points leader Dale Jarrett, who is ahead of Jeff Burton by 240
points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hated to sit out last weekend, even though I enjoyed the
time off,'' Jarrett said. ``When things are going well, you want to
race again as soon as you possibly can.''
</P>
<P>
   For Martin, the bye was a blessing as he continues to heal from
a crash at Daytona July 2. Martin tore up his left knee, fractured
his left wrist and broke a rib.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in a whole lot better shape now,'' Martin said. ``I don't
anticipate me having any physical problems for this race. But New
Hampshire (two weeks ago) was a challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Rookie problems
</P>
<P>
   Elliott Sadler may be wondering if there is a curse following
him at Pocono. The rookie blew two engines during practice Friday.
Sadler lost a third engine Saturday when he crashed into a wall
during second-round qualifying. He damaged his left foot in the
wreck, but an examination revealed no break.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has probably been the worst weekend of racing I've ever
had,'' Sadler said. ``I don't know why, but everything seems to be
going wrong so far.''
</P>
<P>
   Sadler was forced to use a provisional for today's race.
However, Morgan Shephard is hanging around in case Sadler opts to
pull out. Shephard missed the cut during both rounds of qualifying.
</P>
<P>
   In the field
</P>
<P>
   Former Hollywood stuntman Stanton Barrett had the fastest time
(167.532 mph) during the final round of qualifying. Barrett will be
making his second NASCAR start after finishing 30th in the Las
Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
