<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-24 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2796 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-PENN500-25COX     07-24 0432
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-PENN500-25COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    All's not Wells with NASCAR
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG POND, Pa. _ Cal Wells has never fielded a car in a NASCAR
race, but the California businessman already has secured two of the
sport's top sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   Wells, 43, and his company, Precision Preparation Inc., have
shaken NASCAR's good ol' boy network the past two months, securing
the deep pockets of fast-food giant McDonald's and Procter &AMP;
Gamble's Tide brand for a future NASCAR operation.
</P>
<P>
   After the corporations announced they wouldn't renew their
sponsorships with veterans Bill Elliott and Ricky Rudd, Wells
became perhaps the most hated man in the garage. And he can expect
a cold shoulder when his team debuts at Daytona International
Speedway next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got some guy that's come in here and back-doored them
on their sponsors,'' Terry Labonte said. ``I wouldn't know the guy
if he walked through the door. The guy's got to be one hell of a
salesman to sell a team that he doesn't even have.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As an owner, you put your heart and soul into it,'' said Read
Morten of Columbus, one of three owners of Ernie Irvan's No. 36
Pontiac. ``But this guy makes an offer these sponsors can't refuse.
If he thinks he's going to be welcomed here, he's mistaken. He's
sure not welcome here.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells, who owns a two-car CART team, a two-car Formula Atlantic
operation and an off-road team, signed a five-year contract with
McDonald's and is expected to get a similar deal from Tide.
</P>
<P>
   Wells says he isn't surprised by the reaction of other owners
and drivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe I've got to earn my way in, like any other new guy
on the block,'' Wells said. ``I know it's going to be tough. There
certainly seems to be a perception that we've disrupted the
constant in the pack.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there's a lot of guys that have come in from other
disciplines of racing. They weren't all born in North Carolina. I
think once people get to know me, that perception will change.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells is expected to field a Busch Grand National team with
McDonald's next season, and jump to Winston Cup in 2001. However,
he could go straight into Winston Cup racing with Tide next year.
</P>
<P>
   Wells insists he didn't steal the sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're involved in a number of motorsports disciplines,'' he
said. ``You meet a lot of people. ... Often one conversation can
lead to another. We were approached by both groups and we were able
to provide the operations both groups were looking for.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
