by his mother, Linda after winning the Time-Trial in Stage 19 held
at Futuroscope in the 1999 Tour De France. Armstrong cemented his
lead with a victory in Saturday's penultimate stage - a time trial,
paving the way for his coronation on the Champs Elysees in Paris on
Sunday. (Ralph Barrera/Austin American-Statesman Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) YELLOWSTONE NATIONAL PARK, Wyo. -- July 24, 1999 --
NATIONAL-PARKS-OVERUSE-3, 7-24 -- Spectacular sights like geysers
and thermal pools easily distract the average visitor from the
problems arising from the deterioration of Yellowstone National
Park. Many things tourists may not see on a typical trip through
Yellowstone's 2.2 million acres spread across parts of Idaho,
Montana and Wyoming are having a great impact on the park's future.
Hordes of summer tourists and the increasing numbers now visiting
in the spring, fall and winter are overwhelming the park's ability
to accommodate them properly. (Monica Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) YELLOWSTONE NATIONAL PARK, Wyo. -- July 24, 1999 --
NATIONAL-PARKS-OVERUSE-2, 7-24 -- Although this bull elk is being
shot on film, the killing of wildlife in Yellowstone Park has more
than tripled in the last 10 years. Many things tourists may not see
on a typical trip through Yellowstone's 2.2 million acres spread
across parts of Idaho, Montana and Wyoming are having a great
impact on the park's future. Hordes of summer tourists and the
increasing numbers now visiting in the spring, fall and winter are
overwhelming the park's ability to accommodate them properly.
(Monica Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) CENTERVILLE, Mass. -- July 24, 1999 --
CAPE-COD-ICECREAM-2, 7-24 -- Sarah Reid, Jahni Clarke and Sarah
Paddock, are among Richard Warren's current employees at the Four
Seas. Clarke says that his employer, who hires only the most
accomplished students, is like ``a second dad'' to him. The Four
Seas and its delicious ice cream have been an institution of this
Cape Cod village for 65 summers. But what also distinguishes the
Four Seas is the help. They start serving up cones at 16, and they
stay through college, ending their careers as ice cream makers and
managers. (Jared Leeds/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) CENTERVILLE, Mass. -- July 24, 1999 --
CAPE-COD-ICECREAM-1, 7-24 -- Richard Warren, 64, front, who has
been on the job at the Four Seas for 45 years, and his son Doug,
fill a container with some delicious ice cream. The Four Seas has
been an institution of this Cape Cod village for 65 summers. But
what also distinguishes the Four Seas is the help. Summer after
summer, the young men and women behind the counter seem as
unchanging as the decor and the ice cream. They start serving up
cones at 16, and they stay through college, ending their careers as
ice cream makers and managers. (Jared Leeds/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) MAGADAN, Russia -- July 24, 1999 -- RUSSIA-GULAG-VISIT,
7-24 -- Harry Wu, 61, a former Chinese dissident who spent 19 years
in Maoist prisons that were modeled on the Soviet gulag system,
explores an old Stalinist prison in Magadan. Wu is a research
fellow at the Hoover Institute at Stanford University and is active
on behalf of Chinese political prisoners. ``You have to remove all
the Lenin and Stalin statues and put up gulag monuments,'' says Wu.
``That's the only way to keep it from coming back.'' (Russell
Working/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) YELLOWSTONE NATIONAL PARK, Wyo. -- July 24, 1999 --
NATIONAL-PARKS-OVERUSE-1, 7-24 -- In the Wyoming wilds, visitors
wait for the eruption of the Old Faithful geyser at Yellowstone
National Park. Many things tourists may not see on a typical trip
through Yellowstone's 2.2 million acres spread across parts of
Idaho, Montana and Wyoming are having a great impact on the park's
future. Hordes of summer tourists and the increasing numbers now
visiting in the spring, fall and winter are overwhelming the park's
ability to accommodate them properly. (Monica Almeida/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) GRACKO, Yugoslavia -- July 24, 1999 --
KOSOVO-SERB-DEATHS, 7-24 -- Dostana Stojanovic, the widow of one of
the victims in the worst single attack against the few Serbian
civilians left in Kosovo since NATO troops arrived last month,
being comforted by family members at her home in Gracko. Officals
say that 14 Serbian farmers were killed, some disfigured with blunt
instruments. More than 80,000 of the 200,000 Serbs in Kosovo when
the NATO bombing ended have left since alliance troops arrived in
mid-June. (Tyler Hicks/New York Times Photo)
</P>
