<SLUG> BC-R-N.Y.-GORE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN BRONX, GORE HAILS HOSPITAL FOR ITS WORK ON ASTHMA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING to DELETE photo note)  (js) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Vice President Al Gore made a campaign stop Saturday
in the Bronx, where he broke ground for a new children's hospital
being built at Montefiore Medical Center and called attention to
the links between poverty, pollution and the health of young
people.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, the leading contender for the Democratic presidential
nomination next year, cemented his ties with local Democratic
officials and hailed the new hospital as a model for children's
hospitals across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The new hospital will have a comprehensive program to treat
children with asthma. Gore said that the asthma hospitalization
rate for children in the Bronx is five times the normal rate.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Irwin Redlener, president of the Children's Hospital at
Montefiore, said that ``38 percent of children in New York City
homeless shelters have asthma, the highest percentage in the
world.'' Among the causes, he said, are stress, overcrowding and
``environmental factors that we do not fully understand.''
</P>
<P>
   While Gore was in the city, the presumptive front-runner for the
Republican presidential nomination, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas,
appeared upstate in Cooperstown, accompanying the former Texas
Ranger pitcher Nolan Ryan, who is being inducted into the Baseball
Hall of Fame. Bush used to own an interest in the team.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the White House has emphasized childhood asthma as an
example of the effect of poverty and pollution on public health,
and New York City has been used before to make a political point of
the issue.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1997, long before she became a contender for the New
York Senate seat, Hillary Rodham Clinton visited the South Bronx to
help start a childhood asthma initiative in the city. This January,
she introduced the administration's $68 million national program to
fight childhood asthma, the largest federal program ever to address
the problem, which affects about 6 million children.
</P>
<P>
   According to the administration, more than 100,000 children are
hospitalized each year because of asthma, making it the leading
cause of hospitalization due to chronic illness for children, at a
cost of $1.9 billion in medical expenses annually.
</P>
<P>
   The administration has cited asthma, which is aggravated by
inhaling smog, as a reason to tighten air quality standards under
rules that industry groups have successfully challenged in court.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Gore announced that the federal government was
adopting a new air quality index to be used by local weather
forecasters across the country. The new index is based on levels of
smog, soot, carbon monoxide and other pollutants, he said, and it
will, for the first time, recommend specific precautions for people
with respiratory ailments like asthma.
</P>
<P>
   The original air quality index was introduced in 1976 and has
not been updated in more than 20 years.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The vice president became interested in Montefiore through his
friendship with Carl Sagan, the astronomer and successful
popularizer of science, who died in 1996. Friends of Sagan are
working with Montefiore to establish a rooftop planetarium and
observatory for children at the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will allow children of the Bronx to receive unparalleled
care in an inspirational environment,'' Gore said. ``Every child
can chase the stars, feel loved and connected and be able to live
out his or her dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   Redlener, touching on another of the administration's favorite
themes, estimated that there were 300,000 uninsured children in New
York City, including 80,000 to 100,000 in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   The new hospital, on Bainbridge Avenue in the Norwood section,
will be affiliated with Albert Einstein College of Medicine.
</P>
</TEXT>
