<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFORM-PARTY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFORM PARTY CONVENTIONEERS CONSIDER FUTURE WITHOUT PEROT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEARBORN, Mich. _ With disarray in their ranks, leaders of the
Reform Party Saturday struggled at their annual convention to
restore power and relevance to their maverick movement, as they
pondered a possible future without H. Ross Perot at the helm.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the fiercest challenge yet to Perot's leadership, the Texas
billionaire's top aide, Russell E. Verney, said Perot is ready to
relinquish his grip on the party if the delegates want change at
the top.
</P>
<P>
   Verney himself is stepping aside after running the party for
Perot since he founded it in 1995. ``I think they are at the point
where they are ready to blossom,'' Verney said of a new wave of
Reform Party leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The move comes amid pressure from the party's new star, Jesse
Ventura, the former professional wrestler who shocked the political
establishment last year by winning the Minnesota governorship as a
Reform candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura's forces, deployed en masse at the 332-delegate
conclave, were maneuvering on several fronts to block Perot from
heading the Reform Party's presidential ticket in 2000. Although
the nominee will not be chosen until next year, delegates approved
rule changes Saturday to loosen Perot's lock on the party
apparatus, and Perot's clout could be further diminished when
national officers are elected Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Perot, who has pumped $72 million of his fortune into the
third-party movement, stunned both major parties by winning nearly
20 percent of the presidential vote in 1992. But he garned only 8.5
percent in 1996, and many of his longtime supporters believe his
time has passed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We owe him an enormous debt for getting us this far,'' said
Jack Gargan, Ventura's choice to replace Verney as national
chairman. ``Now it's time for him to turn the party over to us, to
let the birdie out of the nest and watch us fly.''
</P>
<P>
   The push for Perot to step aside came amid a virtual
free-for-all in the early race for the party's presidential
nomination _ and the $12.6 million in federal matching funds that
accompanies the prize.
</P>
<P>
   With the two major parties watching warily, fearful that a
Reform candidate could sway the outcome of next year's presidential
race, there were booths, buttons, billboards, bumper stickers, and
bands of delegates promoting nearly every conceivable nominee in
2000.
</P>
<P>
   Draft efforts were underway for, among others, Colin Powell,
Patrick Buchanan, Donald Trump, Ralph Nader, Ted Turner, and three
former senators: Lowell Weicker of Connecticut, Sam Nunn of
Georgia, and David Boren of Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   Although some delegates wore ``Ross is Right for President in
2000'' buttons, Beverly Kidder of Princeton, N.J., expressed the
sentiments of many Reform Party members.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Ross is more comfortable in business,'' Kidder said.
</P>
<P>
   Both the leadership battle and the frenzy to draft new faces for
2000 reflected the restlessness within much of the movement for
change. And Ventura recently raised the stakes by saying a Perot
candidacy in 2000 would be ``borderline ridiculous'' and by
suggesting he would quit the party if Gargan was not elected.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the battle between Gargan and candidates loyal to
Perot was growing increasingly nasty, as both sides accused each
other of jeopardizing the party's future. There were
unsubstantiated charges of irregularities in the election process
and infighting that was uncharacteristic of the movement's
grass-roots activists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Democracy is not always pretty, and this is one of those times
when it isn't,'' said Patricia Benjamin, Gargan's leading opponent,
who is seen as a Perot ally. ``Everybody is going in a different
direction. But hopefully we'll all end up in the same place at the
end.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid the acrimony, many delegates said they think the party
could be dangerously riven if the skirmish is not resolved before
the convention ends Sunday. ``This is a critical time for us,''
said Donna Donovan of Glastonbury, Conn. ``We absolutely have to
look like we have our act together when we come out of this
convention.''
</P>
<P>
   The challenge is formidable since Perot and Ventura aren't
talking to each other and had no plans to appear together during
the event. Perot was scheduled to address the delegates Saturday
night.
</P>
<P>
   The Reform Party's Massachusetts chairman, Andy Lizotte of
Milford, said he wished ``everybody would take a step back'' from
the ``grudge match'' for the good of the party.
</P>
<P>
   Lizotte said party members ``are realistic enough to see the
numbers and recognize that Ross Perot would have a very difficult
time winning'' in 2000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
