<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sports-crazy Lee drops by convention
 &HT;    By Michael Lee
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Spike Lee didn't have a table set up, but he signed
his share of autographs walking station-to-station Saturday
afternoon at the National Sports Collectors Convention at the
Georgia World Congress Center.
</P>
<P>
   The director of ``Summer of Sam,'' was here to visit his
grandmother, Zimmi Shelton, who lives in southwest Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's not doing well,'' Lee said. ``I had to come see her.''
</P>
<P>
   The Morehouse alum was also at the convention, which runs
through today, to add to his own sports momentos, which include
items from Michael Jordan and jerseys worn by Jackie Robinson and
Satchel Paige.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson attracts
</P>
<P>
   Pamela Anderson really has no connection to sports, that is,
unless you count swimming, which she did in the series,
``Baywatch.'' But there was no doubt that with sports heavyweights
like Joe Montana, Carl Yastrzemski and Joe Frazier here for the
convention, she was the biggest draw Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Gibson and Eric Stace were among about 60 who paid $150
for a photograph with Anderson. The UPS co-workers drove from
Virginia Beach, Va. ``We came just for Pam,'' Stace, 28, said. ``It
was worth every penny of it.'' Russell reflection
</P>
<P>
   Much was made about Bill Russell signing autographs this
weekend, when for so long he didn't. But after chatting with fans
willing to pay $200-$500 for his signature, Russell wondered why
there was any fuss.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was mostly a nonevent,'' Russell said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
