u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-SERBS-BOS &LR;      07-24 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-SERBS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEACEKEEPERS STRUGGLE TO PROTECT REMAINING SERBS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUDAPEST _ A brutal massacre of 14 Serb farmers in Kosovo
prompted the region's chief war crimes investigator to launch a
probe Saturday _ the only known inquiry into an attack on Serbs in
Kosovo in the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   International leaders charged with keeping the fragile peace in
Kosovo condemned the attack on the farmers, who were apparently
ambushed and gunned down at close range as they were harvesting
crops.
</P>
<P>
   Louise Arbour, who has presided over numerous other Kosovo war
crimes inquiries into violence against ethnic Albanians, said she
was alarmed at the scale of Friday night's attack on the Serbs _
the deadliest retaliatory violence since the war ended. ``The
strongest deterrent message must be sent to those who are inclined
to perpetuate the cycle of violence that has shattered Kosovo in
the last year,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But aside from a vague plan to step up protection in some areas,
there is little NATO troops can do to stop the series of revenge
killings and expulsions against Serbs by embittered Albanians, the
officials conceded.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a reality that KFOR,'' the peacekeeping force assigned
to patrol Kosovo since mid-June, ``cannot be everywhere all the
time,'' Lieutenant General Michael Jackson told reporters Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we will leave no stone unturned to get hold of the
murderers . . . and bring security to all the people of Kosovo,''
Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's massacre was the worst single episode of violence since
the war ended. British troops who sped to the scene in Gracko, a
village near the provincial capital of Pristina, said they found 13
men lying dead in a corn and wheat field, with a 14th Serbian
farmer slumped dead on a tractor.
</P>
<P>
   The troops had been in Gracko, a mainly Serb village, just hours
before the assault, said Colonel Robin Hodges, a spokesman for the
British peacekeeping contingent.
</P>
<P>
   The episode upsets what peacekeeping officials maintained had
been a gradually improving environment in Kosovo. It also angered
Serb officials and residents who fear the Western military forces _
which bombed the Serbs for nearly three months _ are not committed
to protecting Serb civilians.
</P>
<P>
   The ``serious crime questions the seriousness of the cooperation
between the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia and KFOR,'' Nebojsa
Vujovic, the chief liaison with KFOR and NATO, told the state-run
Tanjug news agency. Vujovic called the murders ``the heaviest crime
against humanity by blind and bloodthirsty killers who are trying
to deprive Kosovo Serbs of their right to live and survive.''
</P>
<P>
   KFOR has no suspects yet, but the Kosovo Liberation Army has
denied responsibility. ``We do not know who did it, and I sincerely
believe these people have nothing to do with the KLA,'' said KLA
General Agim Ceku.
</P>
<P>
   KFOR is increasing its presence in Gracko and ``certain other
areas,'' said spokesman Roger Atkinson. The British troops have
``reassessed'' the level of threat for the area of Gracko, Hodges
said.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, Gracko was evaluated as an area that needed troops
to cruise by every two or three days to remind locals that they are
there, Hodges said. Now, Gracko needs the more frequent presence of
``deterrence'' forces, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the peacekeepers' verbal commitment to evenhanded
patrolling of the region, both Albanians and Serbs in Kosovo
complain that KFOR _ the only internationally recognized authority
to keep order in the province _ has done little to prevent or
punish episodes of violence and looting.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of a local police force and courts has left a vacuum of
power and of order in Kosovo, creating a free-for-all atmosphere
for both Albanians and Serbs bent on revenge, residents say.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are burning Serb houses. Sometimes, there are Albanian
houses in the row, and they get burned, too,'' said a 30-year-old
ethnic Albanian man who asked not to be named.
</P>
<P>
   Ethnic Albanians who had learned to live with Serbs under
political repression now say they cannot stomach sharing land with
people whose government orchestrated the deaths of an estimated
10,000 Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is just with the Serbs. Not the Serbian
government, but the Serbian people,'' said Asim Kasmi, 23, of the
western city of Pec.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nearly every Serb did something, even just a little,'' added
Mantor Kassapolli, 23. ``We didn't look at it this way before,'' he
said. ``But they gave us a reason now.''
</P>
<P>
   Serbs who have not fled the area have found themselves an
endangered minority _ facing the same threat of assault, murder,
and forced eviction their Albanian neighbors did just months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Belgrade's government estimates that at least 100,000 Serbs _
more than half the ethnic Serb population in Kosovo _ have been
intimidated into leaving Kosovo for upper Serbia. The UN High
Commissioner for Refugees does not dispute that estimate.
</P>
<P>
   But KFOR appears as helpless to prevent the crimes against Serbs
as international forces were to protect Albanians a year ago, when
the ethnic cleansing of Albanians in Kosovo began escalating.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were just lined up and gunned down,'' a devastated Zivane
Nderkovic said of the 14 murdered Friday, two of whom were his
sons. ``They were just bringing in the grain. It's a shame that the
world helps only Albanians, not Serbs,'' Nderkovic told Reuters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
