<HEADER>
A2825 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGO-POLITICS-1STLEAD     07-24 1283
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGO-POLITICS-1STLEAD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERB OPPOSITION LEADER CRITICIZES NATO FORCES IN KOSOVO  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS for rally having taken place; refinements)   By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NIS, Yugoslavia _ A leading Serbian opposition leader, Vuk
Draskovic, made an emotional attack on NATO forces on Saturday,
saying they had allowed the ethnic purging of Serbs from Kosovo and
the creation of an Albanian state in the province.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a rally of some 25,000 supporters here, he condemned
the killing of 14 Serbian farmers in the Kosovo village of Gracko.
He said the incident would promote anti-Western feelings in Serbia
and hurt the political opposition to President Slobodan Milosevic
of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Breaking into English, Draskovic appealed to the American people
``to stop, please, with the collective punishment of the Serbian
people and to stop supporting the project of a Greater Albania in
the Balkans.'' He said a Kosovo that was deprived of its ethnic mix
under NATO control would undermine the fundamentals of the American
commitment to a ``multi-ethnic, multi-racial'' state that protects
the rights of all citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm indicting KFOR and the United Nations mission in Kosovo
for the massacre that has happened,'' he said after the rally,
using the initials for the Kosovo peacekeeping force and echoing a
similar statement made by Milosevic. ``Gangs and bandits committed
crimes against Albanians in the name of the Serbian people. And
now, when Albanians commit crimes against Serbs, no one is against
them.''
</P>
<P>
   But in his speech, Draskovic blamed Milosevic for the tragedy of
Kosovo, which has a strong emotional and religious pull on Serbs,
and for everything else that has gone wrong in Yugoslavia for the
last 10 years, as his supporters shouted, ``Slobo, resign!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Guilty or not,'' Draskovic shouted, ``the interests of the
nation require you to give up your armchair and resign!''
</P>
<P>
   But this will be Draskovic's last mass rally for some time,
senior aides said Saturday, because they believe that the moment is
not yet ripe for ousting Milosevic. Such a conclusion could fuel
speculation among Draskovic's rivals in the Serbian opposition that
all he actually wants is to replace Milosevic, rather than really
change Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   The aides said they believed that the opposition was wasting
energy by holding an endless series of summertime rallies that were
not attracting enough people to put any real pressure on Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic must go, Draskovic believes, but he must be induced to
go in a way that avoids civil conflict and significant bloodshed.
</P>
<P>
   His aides say he will hold no more meetings for at least several
weeks, although the other main opposition grouping, the Alliance
for Change, has scheduled further rallies and hopes to lead a grand
march on Belgrade in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every one says Milosevic must go,'' a senior Draskovic aide
said. ``But how? He doesn't even contemplate going. You can ask him
to go for 1,000 days, but asking him isn't serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic will resume mass meetings as an important part of the
strategy to get Milosevic to resign, ``but we want to pick the
right moment, when we can create momentum and there is something
important to say,'' the aide said.
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic is concentrating instead on trying to choose a
transitional government of experts agreed on by most or all
opposition parties, and then trying to push Milosevic to empower
that government and finally to step aside after new elections.
</P>
<P>
   That too has prompted other opposition leaders to suspect that
Draskovic wants only to replace Milosevic with himself.
</P>
<P>
   The Alliance for Change demands Milosevic's resignation first,
before any transitional government. Under pressure from American
and European diplomats, however, Draskovic and alliance leaders are
working on a joint platform as a way to bridge their differences,
if not to solve them all. That platform will include the idea of
Milosevic's ouster and of new elections.
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic and the Democratic Party leader Zoran Djindjic, who
were allies in the 1996-97 marches against Milosevic, are now
bitter rivals, which has undermined both of their reputations and
the credibility of the opposition generally.
</P>
<P>
   Washington and the Serbian opposition are also hoping that
Milosevic's government will begin to crumble from within,
particularly if there are new indictments of those close to
Milosevic from the international tribunal on war crimes in The
Hague. Milosevic and four of his closest aides were indicted in
late May on charges of war crimes for their role as commanders of
Serbian forces that killed Kosovo Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Indictments may come soon of Mirjana Markovic, Milosevic's wife
and the leader of the party that partners his in government, and of
Vojislav Seselj, the ultranationalist leader of the Radical Party
and a Serbian deputy prime minister, American officials say.
</P>
<P>
   The officials and the opposition are hopeful that the former
army chief of staff, Momcilo Perisic, who came out this past week
in sharp opposition to Milosevic and the government, will attract
more army and police support to the idea of the president's ouster.
But Perisic is likely to form his own party, given his lack of
respect for Draskovic, Djindjic or another former general, Vuk
Obradovic, who heads the Social Democracy Party.
</P>
<P>
   Washington and its European partners will also resume aid to
independent media and opposition parties here, buying the argument
that there will be no ouster of Milosevic otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans are pushing a revered economist, Dragoslav
Avramovic, who helped end Yugoslav hyperinflation in January 1994,
as a uniting figure for the opposition and even as prime minister
of a transitional Serbian government. Draskovic said Saturday night
that the transitional government of experts should be nonpartisan
and nonpolitical, and that its members should vow not to seek
elected office.
</P>
<P>
   But Draskovic believes that it is not yet the right time to name
such a government, his aides said. And he believes that the
opposition is dissipating anger at Milosevic by rallies now that
have no idea except Milosevic's ouster and that offer no serious
alternative program for citizens to unite behind.
</P>
<P>
   The main tasks of the transitional federal and Serbian
governments would be to restore diplomatic and economic ties with
the West, to prepare for free and fair elections monitored by
outsiders and ``to stop the genocide of the Serbian people,''
Draskovic said at the rally.
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic, a nationalist, believes that the West is harming the
opposition cause by allowing the majority Albanians to sweep most
of the Serbian minority from Kosovo through intimidation and
killings.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is now no border with Albania, but they make only a
Serbian-Kosovo border,'' he said of NATO. ``Albanian criminal gangs
go over to burn Serbian churches and the roots of our religion,
raping Serbs and kidnapping them and burning their houses. If KFOR
came to protect innocent Albanians, who will now help the Serbs?''
</P>
<P>
   After his speech, Draskovic said, ``Our friends in the U.S. and
European Union, through their support to Albanian terrorists, are
supporting Milosevic.''
</P>
<P>
   There are growing feelings in Serbia that NATO and the West are
not serious about protecting the rights of all the citizens of
Kosovo, including the Serbs. NATO and the United Nations have been
slow to start policing the province in earnest, the Serbs feel, and
government officials have started to suggest that the Yugoslav
police and even army troops should return to Kosovo if such
killings continue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
