<SLUG> BC-WOODSTOCK-ANNIVERSARY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
30TH ANNIVERSARY CELEBRATED WITH NEW MUSIC, YOUNGER CROWD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME, N.Y. _ As the crowd grew to an estimated 220,000 people,
Woodstock '99 endured the ups and downs of any city Saturday. The
festival's first birth was recorded, but so was its first death _
suffered by a 44-year-old Massachusetts man.
</P>
<P>
   ``He died of a heart attack, and we understand that he had a
preexisting condition,'' said New York State Police Major James
Parmley. The man's name was withheld pending notification of his
family.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, Woodstock '99 functioned without the serious traffic
problems and rainstorms that plagued Woodstock '69 and Woodstock
'94.
</P>
<P>
   The police contingent of 550 officers have made what Parmley
admits are remarkably few arrests (15 since the festival began
Thursday, five of those on drug-related charges).
</P>
<P>
   The most serious problem has been the intense summer heat
(temperatures hit the high 80s Saturday), which has resulted in
about 1,000 revelers being treated for heat exhaustion.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, this 30th anniversary of Woodstock, which cost $35
million to stage at the decommissioned Griffiss Air Force base,
continues to impress authorities and fans alike at how well it's
going.
</P>
<P>
   When producers Michael Lang and John Scher held a press
conference Saturday, the biggest question was the amount of nudity
on site. That nudity has been particularly prevalent on the
three-day pay-per-view broadcast emanating from these hot, dusty
airport runways, with three stages and hundreds of food vendors
(and three beer gardens) in between.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is going so well that you guys are really digging
for something,'' Lang said to the reporters who asked about nudity.
``The body is a beautiful thing,'' added Scher. ``And anyone
watching the pay-per-view has been warned that it would be
uncensored. All the promotions said that.''
</P>
<P>
   The nudity was still restricted to a minority of the
concertgoers _ and some defended it as perfectly appropriate,
especially given the history of Woodstock events.
</P>
<P>
   ``This festival is for people who need to get away from the
stress of their daily life and just go for it,'' said Kiri Jewell,
18, who drove here with a group of friends from Michigan State
University. ``It's OK to dance and get naked. It's all about being
comfortable with yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite some links to the past, this Woodstock resembled the
original mainly in name. None of the performers at the first
Woodstock were invited, and this year's event was clearly aimed at
an audience that wasn't even born in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   It was also aimed at reviving the economy of this desolate
upstate New York area, hard-hit by the closing of the air base,
which had employed 5,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Woodstock is worth $30 million to this region,'' said Rome
Mayor Joseph Griffo, who is often referred to as ``the Rock 'n'
Roll Mayor.'' He then excused himself to go hear the Dave Matthews
Band, which drew the largest crowd of the day, with fans spread out
as far as the eye could see from the towering, nine-story-high East
Stage, as sound boomed across the tarmac, carried by numerous
stacks of speakers stationed at various points well into the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Many fans were still recovering from a high-energy Friday night,
when the band Korn played an industrial-strength, metal-rap set,
followed by Britain's Bush, which didn't finish until after
midnight. And then came an all-night ``rave'' in one of the
abandoned airplane hangars, as techno DJ Moby fired up the crowd in
the wee hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``The DJ is the global youth ambassador _ and this is the techno
generation,'' said Matt E. Silver, who produced the ``rave,'' which
he preferred to call a ``DJ Culture'' night.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's music had the afternoon highlights of Kid Rock (whose
assistant wore a Jimi Hendrix wig in a nod to the original
Woodstock), punk-rockers Everclear, hippie icon Bruce Hornsby (who
offered new, bluegrass reworkings of some of his songs), and
Matthews. Due to come were Alanis Morissette, Rage Against the
Machine, and Metallica. Woodstock concludes Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
