<HEADLINE>
HIGH MARKS FOR ECONOMY AT MIDTERM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The U.S. economy at midyear seems poised to continue growing
well into next year, which would make it the longest economic
expansion in history.
</P>
<P>
   All the keys to continued growth are in place. Meanwhile, few
analysts foresee anything on the horizon with the potential to
seriously undermine America's prosperity in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   Even developments considered by some as bad news have a
good-news aspect. The recently reported May trade deficit, for
instance, was a record $21.3 billion, which topped the previous
high by well over $2 billion. As bad as this shortfall may have
seemed, however, it was a dramatic indicator of how much stronger
the U.S. economy is relative to the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Some economists estimate the rising trade deficits will tamp
second-quarter growth, and they are revising their forecasts of
gross domestic product to an annual rate of 3 percent or less for
the April-June period. Nevertheless, this also is good news because
slower growth means the Federal Reserve will be less inclined to
further tighten monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Fed recently nudged one of its key rates up
slightly, it has maintained generous monetary growth, which has
been the booster fuel for the economy and stock market.
</P>
<P>
   The steady rise of the Index of Leading Economic Indicators,
which is a predictor of economic activity three to nine months
hence, makes it likely the expansion will set a record early next
year by surpassing the duration of the 1960s boom. Since the stock
market is not only a key leading indicator but also a prime source
of consumer confidence, Wall Street's fortunes probably will
determine how much longer prosperity will continue after the record
is set.
</P>
<P>
   Slightly more than two-thirds of the investment advisory crowd
is bullish, which is a modestly bearish sign. It's not, however, a
number reflective of mindless euphoria. An example of market
restraint would be its reaction to a gangbusters second-quarter
earnings report by General Motors. GM stock fell nearly 2 points on
the news, which some analysts attributed to expectations of a
softer domestic market next year.
</P>
<P>
   The mood thus would seem cautiously optimistic, which is
justified, given what's in place. The Fed shows no sign of turning
off the money spigot, and consumer spending remains strong, which
is vital because two-thirds of economic growth is the result of
personal consumption. There are even signs that the economies of
key overseas trading partners are beginning to recover from the
global downturn that began two years ago in Asia. Even Japan is
apparently perking up after spending most of the '90s in the
doldrums.
</P>
<P>
   If the foreign resurgence is for real, it would probably mean a
badly needed boost for the manufacturing sector in the
not-too-distant future. Foreign economic problems have hit U.S.
manufacturers particularly hard as troubled countries have curbed
imports while stepping up exports to America to rejuvenate their
ailing economies.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. economy is locked in a virtual circle: A rising stock
market feeds the consumer confidence that boosts consumption, which
fuels the expanding economy that encourages optimistic investors to
continue to bid up stock prices.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
