A2830 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOODSTOCK'99-NYT &LR;      07-24 0592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOODSTOCK'99-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAN DIES OF HEART ATTACK AS HEAT HITS WOODSTOCK  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By PAUL ZIELBAUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME, N.Y. _ Unrelenting heat claimed a victim at Woodstock '99
when a 44-year-old Massachusetts man suffered a heart attack at the
concert Friday night and died, New York State Police officials said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The man, whose name was being withheld by the police Saturday
afternoon, had undergone a heart operation just 11 days ago and
chose to attend the three-day concert against the advice of
doctors, said Maj. James Parmley of the State Police.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Friday night, a female fan went into labor on the
grounds of the former Griffiss Air Force Base, where the concert is
being staged, and was taken to a city hospital. But concert
officials said they did not know Saturday if the woman had given
birth.
</P>
<P>
   As some of the most popular acts took the stage Saturday,
including the Dave Matthews Band and Limp Bizkit, the mood inside
the 1,100-acre concert site _ a sprawling and increasingly
garbage-caked theme park of food and shopping booths, cash machines
and nonstop music _ remained peaceful. In such heat, getting rowdy
is tough going.
</P>
<P>
   The mercury in thermometers appeared to be stuck in the high
80s, reducing all but the most energetic of the 200,000 fans to
laconic shade-seekers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not observed that many offenses,'' Parmley said. ``The
attitude of the concertgoers is excellent.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the concert weekend began on Friday, the police have made
15 arrests, 5 for drug possession and 10 for driving offenses,
Parmley said. The police have stayed out of the concert site
itself, though, leaving clusters of young people free to sit and
smoke marijuana. One fan was sent on his way Friday night when he
climbed into the back of a State Police cruiser, apparently
mistaking it for a taxi, and asked the trooper behind the wheel to
rush him to a concert stage for a show.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was just confused,'' said Parmley.
</P>
<P>
   As the festival matured Saturday into the outsized music event
promoters had promised, a few Woodstock eccentricities also
emerged. Namely, trash and nudity.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been naked all morning,'' shrugged Mark Puma, 28, of
Brockport, N.Y., after watching one of a series of nude female
beauty contests, held on the top of a trailer. ``It's cool.''
Friday night, as the British rock band Bush played on Woodstock's
east stage, nude men were engaged in a mountain-bike race around a
cordoned dirt track.
</P>
<P>
   By Saturday, the ground-level view of the concert, the 30-year
anniversary of the 1969 original in Bethel, N.Y., was a rather
filthy one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at all the pizza boxes,'' said Marie Costello, 48, after
snapping a photo of two friends standing amid an ever-deepening sea
of the boxes, pizza slices, flattened french fries, melon rinds,
corn cobs, soda bottles, paper cups and discarded clothing. ``It's
getting thicker and thicker. You have to watch where you step.''
</P>
<P>
   The Woodstock e-mail tent, usually the site of long lines of
young Internet enthusiasts, closed for several hours Saturday to
allow frantic staffers to see some of the music being played. But
fans, seeking money to buy more of what even the concession clerks
say is overpriced food and water, are enduring long lines to access
Fleet Bank's cash machines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've gone through $150 on drinks and food already,'' said
Puma, as he lay spread-eagled with two friends on a patch of
stomped-down grass. ``And I haven't had a beer yet. It's too hot to
drink.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
