u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-INDIANS-NYT     07-24 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-INDIANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKS BEAT INDIANS, 21-1  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There will be a Yankees staff meeting in late
September to prepare for the American League playoffs, with Manager
Joe Torre and others circled around a table. General Manager Brian
Cashman will be there, as well as the principal owner, George
Steinbrenner, and in that meeting they will remember what Hideki
Irabu did Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   They will discuss the Yankees' pitching rotation for the
playoffs, and somebody will recall how on a miserably hot day in
July, Irabu dominated the Cleveland Indians. Remember how he threw
strikes, someone might say. Remember how he confidently he pitched,
throwing his curveball and his fastball for strikes and prompting
the Indians to chase his split-fingered fastball out of the strike
zone, while his teammates feasted on Cleveland's meaty pitching in
a 21-1 wipeout at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Chili Davis had five hits, matching his career high; Jorge
Posada established a career high with four hits, and nine other
Yankees had at least one hit, among the team's 21. The Yankees
scored 14 runs over the middle three innings, beginning their
onslaught against the veteran left-hander Mark Langston.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians had been forced to go deep into their bullpen in
Friday night's 10-inning loss to the Yankees, and as Cleveland was
pounded Saturday, Manager Mike Hargrove turned to Tom Candiotti for
relief _ less than 24 hours after the knuckleballer started
Friday's game. The Yankees will try to complete a sweep of the
series against their A.L. rival Sunday afternoon, when Roger
Clemens (9-4) faces Cleveland's Bartolo Colon (9-3).
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are 59-37, the best record in the major leagues, six
and a half games ahead of Toronto in the East Division before the
completion of the Blue Jays' game Saturday night, and the Yankees
probably will not play many more meaningful regular-season games.
Sure, Toronto will play in New York soon and the remaining games
with Boston will contain the usual intensity. But the Yankees are
destined for the playoffs, and the primary focus over the last two
months of the regular season will be preparing for the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   If David Cone, Roger Clemens and Orlando Hernandez are healthy,
they will be part of the pitching rotation, especially if the
Yankees play Texas in the first round and have the home-field
advantage, a strong possibility; the Rangers are loaded with
right-handed hitters. Unless Andy Pettitte is traded before
Saturday's deadline, the decision facing Torre, the pitching coach
Mel Stottlemyre and the rest of the Yankees' staff will be whether
to employ Irabu or Pettitte as the No. 4 starter in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Irabu faded badly in the last three and a half months
of the season and spent the entire post-season tucked away in a
corner of the bullpen, waiting for a disaster that never occurred;
Irabu would have pitched only if a starter either was injured or
knocked out in the first couple of innings.
</P>
<P>
   But Irabu is making a strong bid for a more integral role this
season. His record since May 25 is 6-0, and he has done well in
games against good teams, games that are important to the Yankees.
He beat the Blue Jays on May 30, allowed two runs in seven innings
against the Rangers on June 14 and earlier this month fought and
scrapped in a tough game against the Mets in the third game of a
series in Shea Stadium and prevented the Yankees from getting
swept.
</P>
<P>
   His outing against the Indians Saturday, however, was among his
best against a contender, and he was throwing well even before the
Yankees turned this game into a laugher with seven runs in the
fifth inning and six more in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Irabu began throwing his curveball at the beginning of last year
almost as a novelty, something to show off every so often, like
gaudy dice hanging off the rear-view mirror of a sports car. But
Irabu's seemingly inert curveball _ it ambles along at 63-67 miles
an hour _ has become a significant part of what propels him.
</P>
<P>
   Hitters rarely swing at it, and he has become adept at throwing
it for strikes; for Irabu, it's like getting two free numbers in
the batter versus pitcher lottery. Irabu fired a first-pitch strike
to 10 consecutive hitters in one stretch, and in the first five
innings he reached a two-ball, no-strike count only twice. Irabu
allowed seven hits, one walk and a run in seven innings. In his
last 10 outings, he has allowed more than three runs only once,
with an earned run average of 3.05.
</P>
<P>
   He was in complete command, no doubt aided by the late-afternoon
shadows that stretched across home plate and then the pitcher's
mound, obscuring the hitters' vision in a game that began at 4:35
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   But dimmed sight lines hardly bothered the Yankees, who scored
four runs against Langston in the first inning, with Davis dumping
a two-run single off the glove of a diving Kenny Lofton. The
Yankees added a run in the fourth before their offensive dam broke
on the Indians in the fifth. The rally began with Davis smacking a
double off Langston and continued until 12 Yankees had batted, with
seven runs scoring.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Brosius led off the sixth with a home run, and Davis
capped the explosion with a three-run home run, off Candiotti. The
Yankees led, 18-0, and they wouldn't stop there.
</P>
<P>
   Chad Curtis singled home a run in the seventh, Ricky Ledee added
a two-run single, giving them a 20-run lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
