<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALAXY'S MATHIS RETURNS TO STARTING ROLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA -- This has been a humbling season for the Galaxy's
utility striker and playmaker, Clint Mathis.
</P>
<P>
   He hopes his return to a starting role against Kansas City this
afternoon at the Rose Bowl is because he earned it -- not because
Cobi Jones and Robin Fraser are with the U.S. National Team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not always the best thing to say `you're starting just
because Cobi's gone or this and that,''' said Mathis. ``I've been
working hard and this is a big opportunity for me to get in and
show myself and the rest of the league that maybe I can start and
become an impact player.''
</P>
<P>
   Entering his second MLS season, Mathis' confidence was soaring
at the beginning of the season. The 22-year-old had spent time with
the U.S. National team and when the Galaxy carelessly sold
midfielder Martin Machon to Santos of the Mexican first division at
the end of last season -- Mathis figured to be the natural
replacement.
</P>
<P>
   That all changed when Mathis, a rookie-of-the-year candidate in
1998, struggled with fellow playmaker Mauricio Cienfuegos, mostly
because Cienfuegos arrived to the team late after a contract
dispute with Major League Soccer.
</P>
<P>
   That prompted new coach Sigi Schmid to move Mathis to the
front-line, replacing Welton as the Galaxy's scoring problems
became a headache.
</P>
<P>
   As Schmid settled, he acquired foreign midfielders Roy Myers and
Simon Elliott. The new duo made an immediate impact, leaving Mathis
paired up front with Jones.
</P>
<P>
   But when when Mexican striker Carlos Hermosillo arrived June 12,
there was no place for Mathis to go. He returned to the place he
began as a rookie -- on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody likes coming off the bench when you're at this level,''
said Mathis. ``I tried to look at it in a positive way. Everyone
likes to play the whole game but you have to look at reality
sometimes. We're a team, not just 11 players. That means your bench
has to do its job when they're called upon.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that's all I've been doing. I've been fortunate to put
some goals away when they've called on me. I figure if I keep
working and scoring it only makes the coaches decision tougher to
keep you off the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Mathis has shown his potential of late.
</P>
<P>
   In the Galaxy's last match against New England, Mathis returned
as a midfielder starter (replacing Elliott, injury) and scored his
team-leading sixth goal in a 5-2 victory.
</P>
<P>
   And in a U.S. Cup game earlier this week, Mathis -- a striker
while Jones is with the U.S. National team -- scored twice in a 3-2
victory over the San Diego Flash.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's responded in such a professional way,'' said assistant
coach Ralph Perez. ``Clint has been asked to play a variety of
roles for us this season and that's not always fair. When you're
versatile it hurts you a little bit because then you're put into a
lot of positions where you can't hone in on any particular
position.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he's done a wonderful job coming off the bench for us.
He's been the big spark we've needed at times. I know it's tough
going for playing to not playing, but it isn't because he hasn't
done his job. We just felt it was a good role for him and this team
at this particular time.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether he's starting or coming off the bench, Schmid couldn't
be happier with Mathis' work rate and willingness to move around.
Schmid also says Mathis is more of a complete player than he was a
few months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's doing a much better job using his turn of speed,'' said
Schmid. ``He's also a very explosive player with a good first step.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clint's on his way. He's dynamic and willing to take risks in
the final third (of the field) and his running off the ball is
better than it was. He also has a willingness to go at people
quickly and as a result he's scoring goals.''
</P>
<P>
   With Western Conference leaders Colorado and Chicago to follow
the Kansas City game this week, Mathis realizes he's needed more
than ever, especially with Jones and Fraser not around.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team has a lot of depth, one player isn't going to make a
difference,'' said Mathis. ``But if I can go out and score some
goals then good things will happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of the things I've learned. If you don't go out
there and work hard to get it done, there is always someone coming
off the bench who can do it for you.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have an opportunity this week to help my team win. That's
the only thing I'm thinking about. All the other (personal) stuff
happens happens when your team wins games.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
GALAXY-WIZARDS INFO BOX
</P>
<P>
   TODAY'S GAME: Galaxy (10-7, 24 points) vs. Kansas City (5-13, 13
points), Rose Bowl, 12:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   TELEVISION: ESPN
</P>
<P>
   RADIO: KTNQ 1020-AM (Spanish); KCTD 1540-AM (English)
</P>
<P>
   SERIES: Tied 7-7, 1-1 this season.
</P>
<P>
   GALAXY UPDATE: Los Angeles has won five of its last six,
including a 5-2 victory over New England before the All-Star break.
They are starting to show signs of the team that scored 85 goals in
32 games last season, but remain in fourth place in the Western
Conference standings behind Colorado (12-4, 32 points), Chicago
(10-7, 28 points) and Dallas (10-9, 28 points) as the second half
of the season begins this afternoon. Defender Robin Fraser and
striker Cobi Jones are both with the U.S. National team in Mexico.
They will also miss crucial road games against Colorado and Chicago
later this week. And with defender Paul Caligiuri questionable with
a strained left groin, Clint Mathis, Ezra Hendrickson and Daniel
Hernandez will likely get starting nods. All three were starters at
the beginning of the season before losing their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   WIZARDS UPDATE: Kansas City started the second half of the
season with a 4-3 victory over Tampa Bay, Thursday. They started to
show signs of life by winning three of four games earlier in the
season, but dropped their last two games prior to the All-Star
break, including a 5-0 drubbing to Dallas. Kansas City has
traditionally fared better in the second half of the season (19-17)
and they have beaten the Galaxy once this year.
</P>
<P>
   By Fred J. Robledo
</P>
</TEXT>
