<SLUG> BC-GEN-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR A TIME, THEY WERE VAPOR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scott Atwood was in a 25-foot sailboat called Vapor with his
partner, Bill Boyd, for 18 days out in the middle of the Pacific
Ocean, battling the elements and enduring the fates like a
modern-day Sir Francis Drake.
</P>
<P>
   He admits there was a cloying monotony to the 2,225 mile
Transpacific Yacht Race adventure he recently completed from Pt.
Fermin in San Pedro to Diamond Head near Honolulu sleep three
hours, steer three hours day after rainy day surrounded by nothing
more illuminating than ocean water.
</P>
<P>
   ``You become like a robot out there after a while,'' says
Atwood, a 1973 Millikan High graduate and 43-year-old younger
brother of two-time Olympic swimmer Susie Atwood. ``You know
eventually you'll reach your destination. You know eventually it'll
all come to an end. But the sheer boredom of it all can become a
struggle. You just have to keep reminding yourself to enjoy the
moments because those moments will become great memories one day.''
</P>
<P>
   Atwood relates there was an interesting, if not slightly
troubling group of whales Atwood estimates there were at least 40
who shadowed the boat for a couple of hours one afternoon and even
blew foul-smelling water from their snouts on him and Boyd.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were the huge hump back whales, and we kept a wary eye on
them,'' says Atwood. ``I don't know what we could have done had
they decided to become aggressive. The only weapon we had on board
was a flare gun. Still, it was bad enough they sprayed us with
water. There was a terrible odor, and it was the worst shower I've
ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   But what made the trip so unique for Atwood and Boyd and gained
them widespread media attention was a broken rudder that
dramatically impeded the progress of the Vapor and a malfunctioning
radio that prevented the two men from having daily communications
with race officials.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, for 15 harrowing days harrowing, that is, for their
families Atwood and Boyd lost contact with civilization.
</P>
<P>
   No one knew their whereabouts, but Scott Atwood insisted the
mood on the Vapor never reached a panic state.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never once feared for our lives,'' he says. ``We were
always in control of the situation, despite the broken rudder. It
broke after we got out about 1,000 miles, but we tried to go with
it as long as we could. We wrapped a bunch of lines around the
rudder like a tourniquet, and kept it together for about 500 more
miles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then we finally had to go to the backup rudder, which is not
built as strongly as the primary one. It's much like one of those
small spare tires they use on cars. I believe we were in first
place in our class when the rudder first broke, but after that we
couldn't go much faster than five or six knots a hour. I think we
went around 90 miles a day instead of the 170 we would have had the
rudder not broken. We were reduced to going to a crawl.''
</P>
<P>
   The Vapor, the smallest sailboat in the history of the Transpac
race that began in 1906, finally reached its destination on July 17
at 6 p.m after departing on June 29.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt good to hit land,'' admits Atwood. ``I love sailing.
It's my great passion in life. But this trip was a little
frustrating. Scary? Never. Oh, we touched the mast out there a few
times during the rain storms and we were besieged with them for the
final 1,000 miles but it never got dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Atwood has been a boating enthusiast as long as he can
remember one of his uncles, Al Frost, introduced him to the pastime
when he was a kid and he was a member of the crew on the winning
sailboat in the Transpac two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go from being first in the big boat class to last in the
small boat class in two years,'' says Atwood, son of Wright and
Marian Atwood of Long Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Why did he choose to go in something only slightly larger than a
dinghy?
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the challenge of it all,'' he says. ``I already knew
how it felt to win in a big boat. I wanted to see if I could do it
in a small one.''
</P>
<P>
   Atwood's gallantly supportive wife, Kathie, presented him with a
book to read on the journey by Dr. Laura Schlessinger called ``Ten
Things Men Do To Mess Up Their Lives.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she just was trying to tell me something,'' laughs
Atwood, who was both a water polo and swimming star at Millikan.
</P>
<P>
   Atwood got rid of his foreign car repair business, Los Alamitos
Motors, in January to concentrate on his sailing interests and also
to obtain his teaching degree.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to get into teaching so I can have the summers off for
my boating,'' he says. ``Right now I'm looking for a job.
</P>
<P>
   The father of three children, Christopher, 11, Sean, 6 and
Kimberley, 2, Atwood and his family reside in Huntington Beach.
</P>
<P>
   For those who find it difficult to lose weight, Scott Atwood
recommends an 18-day odyssey at sea eating only one meal a day, as
he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a small gas-powered stove on board, and we ate a lot
pre-prepared dinners,'' he says. ``I figure I lost 10 to 15 pounds.
We also went through a case of Gatorade, a case of soft drinks and
11 of the 14 two and a half gallon Arrowhead water containers we
had on board. We also had a bottle of rum and bottle of wine, but
never touched either.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Atwood plans to participate in the Transpac again, but not
in a boat he could fit into his dining room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather go with a full crew if for no other reason I'd like
more people to talk to,'' says Atwood. ``After 18 days in such a
confined area, Bill and I didn't have much to talk about after a
while. It can get a little lonely out there, but it was an
experience I wouldn't trade for anything ... ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
