<HEADER>
A2874 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-HOWARD-LADN     07-24 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-HOWARD-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUNTER CHASES HIS DREAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK C. GIRARDOT  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The painter climbed the ladder and began to work.
</P>
<P>
   It was a Thursday and he had a lot of catching up to do. It is
no easy task supporting a wife and small child.
</P>
<P>
   He slapped some paint on the roller and applied it carefully to
the blank wall in front of him. His mind began to drift.
</P>
<P>
   Just three days earlier, the painter had a different job. He was
the starting punter for the San Francisco 49ers. Years of kicking
around on the fringes of the National Football League had seemingly
paid off.
</P>
<P>
   The painter's dream had finally come true. Then came the phone
call. ESPN was reporting that the 49ers had decided to cut their
punter after just the second game of the 1998 season.
</P>
<P>
   &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Nothing will stop punter Eddie Howard, 26, a 1991 graduate of
Covina, from pursuing his dream. Nothing. Even if it means he has
to paint houses between kicking jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always told myself I want to be able to look in the mirror
and say, `I gave it all I had,' '' Howard said. ``I don't want to
look back and think, `If only I would have done this or that.' As
long as I continue to try, I won't have to say `if.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Howard has been working out with the Tampa Bay Buccaneers this
year and has been asked to attend their training camp, which begins
Aug. 1. After years of preparation, Howard -- by all accounts --
finally has a shot at achieving his goal.
</P>
<P>
   No one is more proud than Howard's wife, Monique, who is
pregnant with their second child and living with her parents in
Arcadia. She understands her husband's dream, even as their lives
become more complicated.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line boils down to, I will never be the one to
squash it as long as it's realistic,'' Monique Howard said. ``He
genuinely has a better chance every year. So who am I to say,`It's
time to stop?' It's getting harder, I'll tell you that.''
</P>
<P>
   More than anyone, Monique, a second-grade teacher at Workman
Elementary in Covina, knows that when the 49ers cut Eddie it wasn't
the first indignity he had suffered in pursuit of his dream.
</P>
<P>
   After graduation in 1995 from the University of Idaho, Howard
was signed and cut by the Green Bay Packers. He was cut by the
Detroit Lions after minicamp in 1996; cut in the preseason by the
Chicago Bears in 1997; and cut on the final day of training camp in
1998 by the Washington Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   That was almost the roller coaster's last stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was flying home debating what I was going to do,'' Howard
recalled. ``I thought, `I got to get back to work -- put food on
the table. I wasn't too sure what was going to happen. It's tough
when you get released.''
</P>
<P>
   As soon as he got off the plane, Monique had some news.
</P>
<P>
   ```You are trying out for San Francisco,' she told me,'' Howard
said. ``It was a crazy, crazy experience. Here you prepare yourself
for the worst. Your emotions are up and down. You get released and
you are not in the best of moods. Then I'm trying out with San
Francisco, the 49ers, a team I had looked up to all my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Once he made the team, Eddie was signed to a contract for
$10,000 a week. He called Monique and told her to quit her job. On
the Wednesday before the opening game of the season, Howard
attended his first practice. It was brutal. Howard felt powerless
and alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough,'' he recalled. ``I'm getting yelled at, it's
windy and I don't know anybody other then the guys I'd seen on
TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Then came Sunday. In front of a national television audience and
a sellout crowd of partisan 49er fans at 3Com Park, Howard shanked
a punt.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I remember is walking off the field and I'm getting
booed,'' he said. ``The next day I was reading in the newspaper,
`If Howard doesn't have a good game, this could be it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Game two was a Monday nighter against the Redskins. Howard
turned in a so-so performance. After the game he remembers hearing
San Francisco head coach Steve Mariucci tell someone, ``We're going
to have patience (with Howard).''
</P>
<P>
   After a long flight home, Howard was planning on a day off and
an opportunity to redeem himself in the third week of the season.
It never came.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a message form Monique that said, `I think they
released you,''' Howard recalled. ``That's the whole thing. There
was no humanity factor.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard's family learned his fate from an early morning report on
ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just like that,'' he said. ``Two days later I'm in
Orange Country on the job and with every step up that ladder I was
thinking I could be playing somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Although frustrated, Howard continued to paint. Every afternoon
he put down the brushes and rollers, took off the coveralls, and
picked up his football to go practice punting at Arcadia High
School.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what you have to do,'' he said. ``I know I can play.''
</P>
<P>
   &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The call from Tampa Bay came during Easter week. Howard was on a
flight for Tampa right after Easter dinner, Monique recalled.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't the first time a family occasion clashed with Eddie's
football career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year he wasn't here and I had my daughter,'' Monique
said. ``He was on a cell phone listening in when I was giving
birth. We got married July 5, 1997, then he left a week later for
camp in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just understood that every year he's going to camp.''
</P>
<P>
   Things are settling down though. Although the Bucaneers are
paying Howard only $280 a week, he plans to fly home from Tampa to
attend the birth of the couple's second child, due any day now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody wants to miss the birth of their child,'' he said. ``I
don't want to ever feel like I put football in front of family or
kids.''
</P>
<P>
   And if all goes according to plan, Eddie may survive the
preseason to find a spot on the Buccaneers' roster, according to
Joel Buschbaum, an expert on player development for the magazine
``Pro Football Weekly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a decent college punter and he's got an outside shot
with Tampa Bay because they don't have a punter right now,''
Buschbaum said. ``He's going to have to do better than he did last
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard thinks 1999 might be his year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't going to sign unless I had a serious shot,'' he said.
``I'd like to make Tampa Bay home and get a chance to play against
all the other teams that didn't give me a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   But Howard is not a sure thing. And if Tampa Bay gives him the
brush-off, the punter will trade in his NFL uniform for coveralls
and become the painter once again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
