<SLUG> BC-DADS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROSECUTORS REACH ACROSS INTERNATIONAL BOUNDRIES TO HAUL IN
DEADBEAT DADS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By OSCAR AVILA  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. CHARLES, Mo. _ David Goldberg, a St. Charles chiropractor,
avoided paying $74,000 in child support by living in Israel for
months.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg returned to the United States this month, but not
because of detectives or diplomats.
</P>
<P>
   Credit the photocopied papers on Benicia Baker-Livorsi's desk.
</P>
<P>
   Baker-Livorsi, an assistant prosecutor in St. Charles County.
knew she had her man when she came across a 1963 treaty requiring
Israel to return parents accused of putting their children's
welfare at risk.
</P>
<P>
   Because of that treaty, authorities say, Goldberg almost became
the first American extradited for allegedly not paying child
support. Instead, he voluntarily returned July 13.
</P>
<P>
   More and more the enforcement of child support is moving
overseas as immigration and international commerce increase. That
means prosecutors are sifting through arcane treaties and pacts to
enforce the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``These cases are finally getting the attention they deserve,''
Baker-Livorsi said. ``A child's suffering knows no international
borders.''
</P>
<P>
   In Goldberg's case, prosecutors did not have to rely on
international pacts, because he turned himself in. Now he faces 11
felony counts of failure to pay child support. A preliminary
hearing is Aug. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg's case earned him notoriety in St. Louis. Photos of him
exiting a plane, in handcuffs, were displayed prominently in the
newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Melissia Goldberg, Goldberg's fifth wife, has
evoked sympathy for her story. She said she lost the family's
five-bedroom home and was forced to move to a campground. She sold
jewelry and other assets to provide food. Residents have responded
by donating thousands of dollars and an offer for lodging.
</P>
<P>
   David Goldberg's attorney, Art Margulis, acknowledged that
Goldberg owed money to his fourth wife. Goldberg returned to St.
Louis to straighten out the situation, Margulis said.
</P>
<P>
   Margulis called Melissia Goldberg's claims a sham. He said
Goldberg provided her with several $1,000 payments and assets to
sell. Margulis contends Melissia Goldberg misspent the money.
</P>
<P>
   Margulis also complained that David Goldberg faced a $310,000
bond _ payable only in cash. Margulis said the children would be
better- served if Goldberg would be released so he could earn a
living.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope we can resolve this,'' Margulis said. ``But the
prosecutor seems bent on jail time as part of any solution. If
that's their attitude, we would have a real problem in settling
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors, however, argue that Goldberg is a risk to flee.
</P>
<P>
   The case already has altered Goldberg's once-tranquil life.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg, 41, had chiropractor offices in Kansas City and St.
Charles, about 20 miles northwest of St. Louis. He and Melissia
adopted five children from Latin America. But he owed child support
to Lisa Burns, his fourth wife.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow _ Margulis has no explanation _ Goldberg fell behind on
the payments. Melissia Goldberg said her husband told her last
October: ``I'm in trouble. We need to leave right away.''
</P>
<P>
   She didn't want to go to Israel, so he left without her.
</P>
<P>
   At that point Melissia Goldberg didn't know where to turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in a state of shock,'' she said. ``But I got my
self-worth back and took over trying to look out for my children.
No matter what, we were going to make it.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg was charged by St. Charles County prosecutors with not
paying $74,000 to Burns and an unspecified amount to Melissia
Goldberg. He remains jailed and declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Melissia Goldberg has filed for divorce.
</P>
<P>
   When it came to tracking down Goldberg, Baker-Livorsi and her
staff sought help from the Department of Justice and state
authorities. They looked for legal and diplomatic alternatives and
found the 1963 treaty. Prosecutors said they had attempted in the
past to make overseas contact with parents in arrears on child
support, but they knew of no other extradition attempts.
</P>
<P>
   One of the challenges in international child-support cases is
that global laws are a patchwork. Even then, each country will
enforce existing agreements with different levels of urgency.
</P>
<P>
   ``You run into so many roadblocks,'' said Anna Giorgio of
Pittsburgh, who said her husband moved to Europe and was not paying
child support. ``You don't even know where to start. You really
feel helpless.''
</P>
<P>
   Some parents turn to private collectors, who boast that they can
track down deadbeats all over the world. Prosecutors warn, however,
that those collectors have no legal authority and can charge hefty
commissions.
</P>
<P>
   Even when the deadbeat parents are found, spouses and lawyers
face other hurdles.
</P>
<P>
   Bonnie White, senior collections officer in the district
attorney's office in Contra Costa County, Calif., recalls her
pursuit of a parent to Germany. Correspondence with German
authorities had to be translated and phone calls exchanged at odd
hours because of the time difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have enough trouble tracking down all our parents in our
own country. Now take that times a hundred when you're talking
about a foreign country,'' said White, co-author of (begin
ital.)The Child Support Survival Guide(end ital.).
</P>
<P>
   Individual U.S. states also can sign agreements with other
countries, but Missouri has no such agreements, Baker-Livorsi said.
She hopes Missouri lawmakers will move more aggressively to work
with other nations.
</P>
<P>
   California maintains agreements with almost 20 nations _ from
Bermuda to the Czech Republic. Not all countries want to cooperate,
however. White said Mexico did not sign an agreement until last
year.
</P>
<P>
   State and federal authorities also can take such actions as
revoking business licenses, suspending passports and garnisheeing
wages, if the parent works overseas for an American firm.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Melissia Goldberg's attorneys said they would be
satisfied to reach a settlement with Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   The children, whose financial care prompted the case, are
holding up well, she said.
</P>
<P>
   In the next few weeks, Melissia Goldberg plans to move into a
home and continue her studies for a bachelor's degree in
communications.
</P>
<P>
   She said the pursuit of her husband across the globe was worth
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want justice to be served,'' she said. ``I want him to
take responsibility for these children. We're willing to do
whatever it takes to have him own up to what he needs to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
