<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFORM-PARTY--1ST-LEDE-WRITETHROUGH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFORM PARTY CONVENTIONEERS CONSIDER FUTURE WITHOUT PEROT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: Updates with Perot comments)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEARBORN, Mich. - With disarray in their ranks, leaders of the
Reform Party Saturday struggled at their annual convention to
restore power and relevance to their maverick movement, as they
pondered a possible future without H. Ross Perot at the helm.
</P>
<P>
   In the fiercest challenge yet to Perot's leadership, the party's
new star, Minnesota Governor Jesse Ventura, called before the
convention for the Texas billionaire to relinquish his grip on the
organization and renounce a possible bid for the presidency in
2000.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura's forces then pushed on the first two days of the
three-day conclave for a rules change that would loosen Perot's
lock on the party apparatus. And Ventura campaigned for a new party
chairman who wants Perot to step aside for the movement's sake.
</P>
<P>
   Perot, in his first public comments on the showdown, gave no
clear indication in a speech Saturday night to nearly 350 delegates
about whether he intends to make a third run for the White House.
The Texas billionaire said: ``As long as I am helpful to the
organization I'm certainly happy to help and participate in any
constructive way.''
</P>
<P>
   Perot made no direct reference to Ventura, the former
professional wrestler who shocked the political establishment last
year by seizing the Minnesota governorship and becoming the only
party member to have won a significant elected office.
</P>
<P>
   But Perot was clearly rankled by the controversy swirling around
the party he founded. ``The last thing I want is all of these
things I see in the paper day in and day out about catfights that
have nothing to do with fact but make great fiction,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just remember,'' he exhorted the crowd, ``united teams win and
divided teams lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Perot's top adviser, Russell J. Verney, said earlier Perot is
ready to step aside if the delegates so desire. Verney himself is
giving up his post after running the party for Perot since he
founded it in 1995. ``I think they are at the point where they are
ready to blossom,'' Verney said of a new wave of Reform Party
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Perot, who has pumped $72 million of his fortune into the
third-party movement, stunned both major parties by winning nearly
20 percent of the presidential vote in 1992. But he garnered only
8.5 percent in a dismal outing in 1996, and many of his longtime
supporters believe his time has passed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We owe him an enormous debt for getting us this far,'' said
Jack Gargan, Ventura's choice to replace Verney as national
chairman in Sunday's election. ``Now it's time for him to turn the
party over to us, to let the birdie out of the nest and watch us
fly.''
</P>
<P>
   The push for Perot to step aside came amid a virtual
free-for-all in the early race for the party's presidential
nomination _ and the $12.6 million in federal matching funds that
accompanies the prize.
</P>
<P>
   With the two major parties watching warily, fearful that a
Reform candidate could sway the outcome of next year's presidential
race, there were booths, buttons, billboards, bumper stickers and
bands of delegates promoting nearly every conceivable nominee in
2000.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Ventura refused to reschedule his weekend
activities and attend the convention after his flight from
Minnesota to Detroit for the opening session on Friday was canceled
due to thunderstorms.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Ventura spoke to the delegates that night by speaker
phone. He praised Perot's contributions to the movement, insisted
he has no designs on the presidency in 2000, and gave a final boost
to Gargan's candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the battle between Gargan and candidates loyal to
Perot grew increasingly nasty, as both sides accused each other of
jeopardizing the party's future for their short-term political
expedience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Democracy is not always pretty and this is one of those times
when it isn't,'' said Patricia Benjamin, Gargan's leading opponent,
who is seen as a Perot ally. ``Everybody is going in a different
direction. But hopefully we'll all end up in the same place at the
end.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid the acrimony, many delegates said they feared the party
could be dangerously riven if the skirmish is not resolved before
the convention ends Sunday. ``This is a critical time for us,''
said Donna Donovan of Glastonbury, Conn. ``We absolutely have to
look like we have our act together when we come out of this
convention.''
</P>
<P>
   The Reform Party's Massachusetts chairman, Andy Lizotte of
Milford, said he wished ``everybody would take a step back'' from
the ``grudge match'' for the good of the party.
</P>
<P>
   Lizotte said party members ``are realistic enough to see the
numbers and recognize that Ross Perot would have a very difficult
time winning'' in 2000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
