<SLUG> BC-TEN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMPRAS STILL SIMPLY THE BEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If you never saw a George Mikan hook shot or a Don
Budge backhand, if you missed Sandy Koufax's fastball and Roman
Gabriel's bombs, you had best not pass on the chance to study Pete
Sampras this week at the Mercedes-Benz Cup at UCLA's Tennis Center.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras is a local treasure on loan to the world, as much a sign
of the progression of tennis as the La Brea Tar Pits are of
evolution.
</P>
<P>
   His tennis talent, dug up from concrete courts in Torrance some
21 years ago, has been polished to an incandescent sheen. Sampras'
brilliance is the benchmark upon which future generations of tennis
stars will be compared.
</P>
<P>
   He is, quite simply, the best.
</P>
<P>
   We say this even though Roland Garros is one opponent Sampras
has yet to conquer. We know full well how Bill Tilden helped put
the roaring into the Twenties with his temperamental genius and
Davis Cup dramatics. We haven't forgotten Budge's Grand Slam in
1938 or Rod Laver's two Grand Slams, in 1962 and 1969.
</P>
<P>
   We're quite cognizant Sampras isn't bringing a global No. 1
ranking into his backyard tournament, his first competition since
capturing his 12th Grand Slam title at Wimbledon earlier this
month.
</P>
<P>
   That Sampras is ranked No. 3 reflects not on his game but the
lameness of the soon-to-be-shucked ratings system. (Sampras himself
took a shot at the status quo in a recent conference call with
reporters, quoting a friend who quipped, ``You could be dead and be
ranked No. 1.'')
</P>
<P>
   The 27-year-old Sampras could be the second coming of Tilden.
His game is that complete. Because the Nineties have been replete
with challengers to Sampras' throne, he deserves history's nod.
</P>
<P>
   From Andre to Yevgeny, ``there's 60 players, maybe even more
than that, who are capable of winning'' a Grand Slam. So said
Laver, whose road to Grand Slam glory every year tended to have the
same speed bumps. Their names: Roy Emerson, Ken Rosewall and Tony
Roche.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras' defeat of Andre Agassi at Wimbledon moved him into a
tie with Emerson for the all-time lead in Grand Slam titles, one
ahead of Laver.
</P>
<P>
   When Laver was going for his second Grand Slam, in 1969, he got
so nervous he chewed his fingernails until they bled. Last year
Sampras, in an effort to retain his No. 1 ranking for a record
sixth consecutive year, entered seven of the final eight
tournaments and saw his hair fall out from the stress.
</P>
<P>
   He retained his top ranking and felt more relief than joy. That
told him something. If he has to go to such lengths to extend his
top ranking one more year, there likely will be a new No. 1 to
shoot for in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure how much I enjoyed getting it,'' Sampras said.
``People ask me if it was worth it and I say `kind of.' When it was
over I was as drained as I've ever been, physically and mentally.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirty years ago, the pressures were decidedly different. A
player in Laver's day had to be among the best in the world to make
a comfortable living. If he didn't win, his mortgage might not get
paid.
</P>
<P>
   A player today can live like a prince without making much of a
run at No. 1. Lacking any financial incentives to plant their flag
on the summit, some players seem more inclined to linger at the
ledge just below the peak where it's easier to breathe and
maneuver.
</P>
<P>
   They're the ones you hear grousing when the rankings computer
spits them out at the top. They're the ones who tank matches and
horde appearance fees and make you appreciate Sampras all the more.
He set out to be No. 1 at the age of 7 and, once there, has never
wavered in his desire or diligence.
</P>
<P>
   There are certain people, Sampras conceded, who need to be the
best to feel good about themselves. He mentioned Ivan Lendl and
Jimmy Connors and then he dropped his guard for just a second,
perhaps just to see if we were paying attention.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras couldn't have bared more of himself if he had dropped
his drawers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might also fall into that category,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So it turns out winning is a drug for Sampras, his own personal
Prozac. Goodness knows we've heard of athletes with far worse
addictions.
</P>
<P>
   It's fitting that Sampras' return to the L.A. Tennis Center
after a few years' absence coincides with the tournament's lauding
of Laver, who will be honored in a ceremony on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   As a youngster, Sampras watched 16-millimeter films of Laver's
matches as raptly as today's kids do ``The Lion King.'' From his
serve-and-volley game to his shy demeanor to his French Open
failures (Laver had a 6-5 record at Roland Garros before his
breakthrough victory in 1962), Sampras' resemblance to Laver is
uncanny.
</P>
<P>
   They are as alike as a lanky, tanned, dark-haired bachelor and a
compact, fair-skinned, red-headed husband and father of two could
be.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you asked him what charisma was, he'd think you were
referring to the Romanian junior champion,'' a writer once whined
of Laver.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras is painted in the same drab tones today by people who
cannot be dazzled by simple elegance. Too often what the eye is
drawn to are the accessories _ the tattoos, the temper tantrums and
titillating private lives turned inside-out for the sake of the
spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   A silken one-handed backhand and 125-mph serves? They don't
impress some people much.
</P>
<P>
   If Sampras were a plumber fixing a broken pipe or an accountant
preparing a tax return, his ethereal efficiency and good manners
would be endearing. Of course, game, set and match points are never
to be confused with rupture points or decimal points.
</P>
<P>
   We like our sports figures to be compelling and not just
competent. And if that means setting an example of boorishness or
brutishness for our children, well, then, we'll just tell the kids
to do as we say and not as their idols do.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras is different. He'd be worth impersonating if he weren't
so inimitable. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
