<SLUG> BC-BBN-McHALE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEHIND THE SCENES, SUTTON MAKES A DIFFERENCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Don Sutton knows something about big moments.
</P>
<P>
   He pitched in four World Series and won 324 games. His career
was just beginning when Sandy Koufax and Don Drysdale were winding
down with the Dodgers. By the time he was through, Sutton was
headed to the Hall of Fame, where he was inducted one year ago
today.
</P>
<P>
   The focus now has shifted to two of Sutton's other former
teammates, Nolan Ryan and Robin Yount, who along with George Brett
and Orlando Cepeda are going into Cooperstown today.
</P>
<P>
   After 24 big-league seasons, Sutton has a lot of former
teammates. But Ryan and Yount were special; Ryan for the sheer
electricity his fastball brought to every game, Yount for the
competitive spirit that made winners of the Milwaukee Brewers even
if they only appeared in one World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Sutton's favorite moment during his short time with the Brewers
came on the final day of the 1982 season. He was pitching against
Baltimore's Jim Palmer, another Hall of Famer, and trying to hold
off the Orioles' late-season charge for just one more day.
</P>
<P>
   But what he remembers best was the pregame clubhouse. The
Brewers had nearly been caught by the Orioles and had every reason
to panic. But when Sutton walked in he remembers nothing but calm.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the most relaxed clubhouse for a big game I had ever
been in,'' Sutton said. ``Robin made it that way. That was his
season and this was his moment. No shouting, no yelling. You just
knew we were going to win.''
</P>
<P>
   When Yount hit two homers off Palmer in that game, the Brewers
had their title. They came back from a 0-2 deficit to beat the
Angels in the league championship series but lost in seven games to
St. Louis in the World Series. Yount was chosen American League
MVP.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an honor to be a part of something that great,'' said
Sutton, who came over from Ryan's Houston Astros as a late-season
addition. ``And an honor to play with Robin Yount.''
</P>
<P>
   Sutton is now a candid and respected broadcaster for the Atlanta
Braves, but he has always made a point of remaining distant from
the lives of modern players. There was no shagging flies before
games, no batting-practice sessions just to see if he could still
bring it.
</P>
<P>
   But quietly, Sutton has been offering advice to any pitcher who
approaches him and there are about a half-dozen Braves who have
sought his counsel. He has a particular interest in All-Star
right-hander Kevin Millwood, whom he compares to Drysdale.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like his makeup, his personality,'' Sutton said. ``He wants
to be good and he wants to be good because it's the right thing to
do, not because he wants to be well-known for doing it. His
personality is almost identical to Don Drysdale. He plays a lot
older than his birthday.''
</P>
<P>
   After Millwood got off to a poor start this season, Sutton dug
through some old files to show the young right-hander pictures of
Drysdale to illustrate a flaw in his delivery. It's no coincidence
Millwood has won 10 of his last 12 decisions since that talk.
</P>
<P>
   Then two-time Cy Young award-winner Tom Glavine pulled Sutton
aside following a disastrous performance against the Brewers on May
24 that left him with a 3-5 record and a 5.54 ERA. His question:
``Is this the point in my career when I should begin pitching
differently?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to him for reassurance more than anything else,''
Glavine said. ``I had my own thoughts on it and he pretty much
echoed what I felt and that was, no, I didn't have to start doing
things differently. There's a guy who's won an awful lot of
ballgames; who better to ask about changing your philosophy than a
guy who's been through the wars?''
</P>
<P>
   Sutton has worked quietly behind the scenes to ensure he doesn't
interfere with pitching coach Leo Mazzone. So far the ``I'm here if
you need me'' approach has worked perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I learned from Sandy Koufax and Don Drysdale and Claude
Osteen is that every one of us have something we can contribute to
someone else,'' Sutton said. ``That's the atmosphere I learned
in.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
