<SLUG> BC-BKL-SPARKS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPARKS WIN IN OT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAMELA LEWIS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Lisa Leslie scored nine of her 22 points in
overtime as the Sparks won their third consecutive game while
handing the aggressive New York Liberty its second loss in a row,
75-72, in front of 6,896 at the Forum Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Sparks' first win in nine games in front of a
national television audience, but it took some last-minute heroics
to pull it off.
</P>
<P>
   They rallied from a 16-point deficit in the first half, and then
in the last minute of regulation Sparks guard Gordana Grubin
answered New York's Crystal Robinson's 3-pointer with one of her
own to tie the score, 59-59. But then Crystal responded with
another shot from beyond the arc. Then it was Mwadi Mabika's turn.
She sent the game into overtime after launching an off-center
23-foot shot from near the right baseline with 7.8 seconds
remaining in regulation.
</P>
<P>
   Leslie then went to work, scoring the first six points on two
free throws, a layup, and a 3-pointer from the top of the key.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Robinson, who was 7 of 14 from long distance for 23
points, scored a pair of free throws and a 3-pointer after Vickie
Johnson's steal to make it a five point game (74-69) with 28.2 on
the clock.
</P>
<P>
   Grubin converted two free throws, but the red hot Robinson hit
her seventh 3-pointer with 24.8 seconds to play to make it a one
possession game (75-72). DeLisha Milton missed two crucial free
throws with 23 seconds to play, but the Liberty (10-8) was unable
to execute a last shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great team effort on the defensive end and we were
able to hit some clutch shots when we needed it,'' Sparks coach
Orlando Woolridge said. ``We were very fortunate because even
though we had a lead there were a few opportunities where we didn't
make the best decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks (13-6) struggled offensively behind the physical play
of New York, but matched that aggressiveness in the second half to
start with a 13-3 run that got them back in the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberty, 2-6 on the road, was at a disadvantage in the low
post after Kim Hampton fouled out with 2:36 to play in regulation.
But she couldn't have stopped Mwadi's 3-pointer anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very tough because we had the game and the shot that
Mabika made at the buzzer we couldn't have defended any better,''
New York coach Richie Adubato said.
</P>
<P>
   Mabika, who had her second career double-double with 15 points
and 11 rebounds, said she was a little bit uncomfortable taking the
shot, but ``I felt like it was going in, because I was high in the
air.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
