r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ALNOTES-LADN     07-24 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ALNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAFECO NOT HITTERS' HAVEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Ken Griffey Jr. had one home run in his first six
games at Seattle's new Safeco Field and swore he lost two more that
would have been out in the Kingdome. Alex Rodriguez hit two homers
during the same stretch. They aren't happy.
</P>
<P>
   Most Mariners players, and manager Lou Piniella, agree Safeco is
more of a pitcher's park. That might not help keep Griffey and
Rodriguez, free agents after the 2000 season, in Seattle, but no
one is happier with the place than Piniella. He has seen the team
flounder because of pitching since reaching the league championship
series in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans, the media, the players _ everyone has fallen in love
with the home run,'' Piniella said. ``This park puts a premium on
playing an all-around game, on defense and pitching and
manufacturing runs. This park will make you play better
baseball.'' &QL; 
Second-half blues
</P>
<P>
   The first-place Indians took a lot of heat for yawning their way
through a 39-38 second half last year. To prevent another letdown,
manager Mike Hargrove went to spring training with two goals _ win
100-plus games in the regular season and win the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   When the Indians reported to camp, they found a T-shirt in every
locker that read ``100 plus. Go Hard or Go Home.''
</P>
<P>
   So this year they've started the second half losing six of their
first eight games. Overall, they are 4-19 when they score three or
fewer runs. Injuries to Travis Fryman and Sandy Alomar have hurt,
but complacency has done more damage. It seems as though the whole
team is hoping GM John Hart makes a Chuck Finley-like trade to
re-energize them. &QL; 
Cone's the man
</P>
<P>
   David Cone's perfect game last Sunday only strengthened the
belief in the Yankees clubhouse that he, not Roger Clemens, is the
ace of the staff.
</P>
<P>
   Cone has an ERA more than two runs lower: 2.65 to Clemens' 4.90.
With runners in scoring position, Cone is holding hitters to a .155
average. Clemens is exactly 100 points higher, .255. Overall, the
AL is batting .206 against Cone, the lowest in the league. The AL
is batting 76 points higher against Clemens, .282.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees fans are beginning to boo Clemens. If the Yankees don't
repeat as World Series champs, management might have trouble
justifying re-negotiating Clemens' contract and paying him the $15
million a year he wants. Clemens is in the third year of a
four-year, $32 million deal and has the right to demand a trade at
season's end. &QL; 
Take it easy
</P>
<P>
   Following a poor start against Florida last Sunday in which he
allowed a career-high nine runs, Boston's Pedro Martinez was bumped
from his next scheduled turn at Detroit on Friday because of
shoulder soreness.
</P>
<P>
   The pitcher said he had been experiencing some discomfort in his
shoulder for roughly a month but acknowledged that he was unusually
sore following a historic performance in the July 13 All-Star Game.
Compounding Boston's rotation problems was the fact that
right-hander Mark Portugal was scratched Thursday because of back
spasms.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the Sox are going with a rotation of Bret
Saberhagen, Pat Rapp and rookies Brian Rose, Jin Ho Cho and
Tomokazu Ohka. Cho's first year of pro ball was 1998; Ohka was
signed before this season. &QL; 
Pan Am grounded
</P>
<P>
   It seemed like the perfect way to help the U.S. qualify for the
2000 Olympics in Sydney _ get minor-leaguers to play in the Pan
American Games in Winnipeg, Canada. Only players who are not on
40-man, major-league rosters were eligible. Not too many of those
players get called up during the season, but this year is
different.
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Nick Bierbrodt was chosen for the team before he was
recalled by Arizona. The same thing happened to Kansas City pitcher
Dan Reichert and Oakland's hard-throwing reliever, Chad Harville.
</P>
<P>
   There is the feeling Major League Baseball is wavering in its
support. The U.S. has to finish first or second in the Pan Am Games
to qualify for the Olympics. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
