<SLUG> BC-REFORM-PARTY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEROT TELLS DELEGATES HE WILL STAY ACTIVE IN REFORM PARTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds., this replaces an earlier agency story in NYT editions)  
 (HLW)  
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEARBORN, Mich. _ Rejecting calls that he step aside for fresh
faces, Ross Perot vowed Saturday night to remain active in the
Reform Party that he founded, but gave no hint as to whether or not
he would seek its presidential nomination next year.
</P>
<P>
   Perot, speaking at the midpoint of the party's three-day
national convention, avoided any reference to the bitter race for
chairman of the party. The contest, to be settled on Sunday, pits
his loyalists against those of the party's biggest success story,
Gov. Jesse Ventura of Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as I'm helpful to the organization, I am certainly
happy to help and participate in any constructive way,'' Perot
said. ``The last thing I want is all of these things that I see in
the paper day in and day out about cat fights and this and that and
the other.''
</P>
<P>
   Ventura, who addressed the 400 delegates on Friday night,
suggested that it was time for Perot to leave the party gracefully.
Ventura also personalized his endorsement of Jack Gargan, one of
the three candidates to replace the party's chairman, Russell J.
Verney, who is an aide to Perot.
</P>
<P>
   Perot, 69, reminded delegates that ``united teams win, divided
teams lose,'' and said that the path to victory lies in doing the
right thing for their country, and for their children and
grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we are well organized, get in position and wait for the
opportunity,'' he said, ``those opportunities will occur across our
country and over time all of you can make a huge contribution to
the future of our nation and that is also making a contribution to
the future of the entire planet. God bless you for all of your
great work.''
</P>
<P>
   Perot seemed to be alluding to his critics' contention that the
Reform Party is a cult of personality when he said, ``You have
worked your hearts out since 1992 for one reason _ because you love
this country, that's it.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of Perot's speech consisted of the populist applause lines
that helped propel his candidacies for president, in which he drew
19 percent of the vote in 1992 and 8 percent in 1996. Calling for
``the highest ethical standards'' for Congress and the White House,
he said, ``No more gifts, no more trips, no more junkets.''
</P>
<P>
   He began with an attack on unnamed special interests in
politics. ``The people who show up at the other two conventions are
saying, `Let's make a deal tonight for me,''' Perot said. Looking
straight into the cameras and praising his own delegates, he added,
``There's nothing in it for these people _ they're doing it for
their children and their grandchildren and this country. That's
it.''
</P>
<P>
   In an apparent reference to President Clinton, he said, ``We
will never have a candidate who would not be a good role model for
our children and grandchildren.''
</P>
<P>
   Perot also called for four-month presidential campaigns.
``Campaigns cost too much because they last too long,'' he said.
``I wish we could just have that up on every billboard in the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   A band played ``When the Saints Go Marching In,'' as he left the
stage without shaking a hand, simply calling over his shoulder,
``Keep up your good work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
