</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YOUNT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNT TO GET HIS WINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When Robin Yount walks to the podium this morning
in Cooperstown, he will look out at the expected record crowd and
see home.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the ``Cheeseheads'' from his adopted Milwaukee and fans
from across the country, there will be a collection of family,
friends and mentors who helped nurture Yount's memorable ride from
the San Fernando Valley to baseball's Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   There will be Yount's parents Phil and Marion, who came to the
Valley in the mid-1950s with three young boys and the promise of
defense contracts and wide-open spaces. His brothers Jim and Larry,
who taught him not to waste his gift. Little League coach Clem
Cohen, who watched the magic grow on the tiny field at Victory and
Winnetka. And Jim O'Connor, the coach who watched Yount make 13
errors during his junior year at Taft High in Woodland Hills but
knew he'd never seen anyone better.
</P>
<P>
   Together they gave him wings, which scouts often said made a
Robin Yount triple the most beautiful thing to watch in baseball.
And they grounded him enough so he was able to become a starting
big-league shortstop at the age of 18.
</P>
<P>
   Yount will acknowledge them all today from that podium, when he
is inducted along with Nolan Ryan, George Brett and Orlando Cepeda.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is still hard to grasp that this is all happening,'' Yount
said, with a humility that helped make one of the most admired
players of his generation. ``It is difficult to think that you
belong.''
</P>
<P>
   His body of work during 20 seasons with the Milwaukee Brewers
would suggest otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   _Yount was the third-fastest player to reach 3,000 hits,
surpassed only by Ty Cobb and Henry Aaron.
</P>
<P>
   _He was only the third player to win a Most Valuable Player
award at two positions.
</P>
<P>
   _He is the last shortstop to lead the majors in slugging
percentage (1982) and the first since Ernie Banks in 1958.
</P>
<P>
   _Yount is the second player in major-league history to record
3,000 hits, 200 home runs, 200 stolen bases and 100 triples. Willie
Mays is the other.
</P>
<P>
   _Lifetime, he batted .285 with 1,632 runs, 3,142 hits and 251
homers. When the Brewers made it to the World Series in 1982, he
batted .331 with 29 homers and 114 RBI during the regular season
and .414 during the Series.
</P>
<P>
   But if you only look at the numbers, you will miss the point.
</P>
<P>
   It was the way Yount carried the Brewers to their only World
Series appearance with a competitive fire that never flickered.
</P>
<P>
   It was the way that between 1978 and 1991 he never spent a day
on the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   It was the way he fought through shoulder and leg pain late in
his career, pain that forced him to move from shortstop to center
field. Perhaps his most lasting moment is the diving catch he made
in 1987 for the final out of Juan Nieves' no-hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he came up he was clocked at 4.1 second going to first,''
said longtime Brewers broadcaster Bob Uecker. ``Twenty years later
he was clocked at 4.2. This is a guy who just never gave up at
anything he did. All out, all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   But where did it come from?
</P>
<P>
   It began in the Valley of the 1960s and early 70s, an oasis long
since paved over, where ``The Kid'' was allowed to be a kid.
</P>
<P>
   He once snuck onto the golf course at the Woodland Hills Country
Club with some buddies and wound up sinking a hole-in-one. Then he
ran off.
</P>
<P>
   He would take his vast collection of dirt bikes and motorcycles
up into the foothills in Chatsworth and ride for hours. Yount has
been out of baseball since 1994, but his passion for cars and bikes
is stronger than ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can remember going to Larry's games, chasing foul balls,
bringing them back and getting a free snowcone,'' Yount said. ``I
loved living in the Valley. It's entirely different now than when I
was growing up. It's grown unbelievably. I mean, I can remember
playing ball on farmland out there in Warner Center where it's now
high-rise buildings and shopping malls.''
</P>
<P>
   Yount, now 44, lives in the affluent Phoenix suburb of Paradise
Valley with his wife Michele and four teen-age children. He races
Formula 1 cars during the winter and continues to push the envelope
the way he did as a child.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robin just beat to his own drum,'' said Rick Dempsey, the
Dodgers coach, who has known Yount since childhood. ``He loved to
take chances on the baseball field and in life. He was a very free
spirit, probably the greatest free spirit I've even known.''
</P>
<P>
   Dempsey said there were several ingredients to Yount's success.
The first was natural athletic ability, which sometimes gets
overlooked. He once considered a professional golf career after
getting injured in a dirt-bike accident just before spring
training.
</P>
<P>
   The second was a fierce competitive nature that developed with
his older brothers and a level of concentration that seemed to
almost will him through situations on the field.
</P>
<P>
   Yount's close relationship with his brother Larry, who is six
years older and was once a pitcher in the Houston organization,
taught him many lessons.
</P>
<P>
   Larry bought Robin a batting cage for the back yard, but also
stressed that talent would only get him so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `If you want to relax and take it easy, you can do
that on your own time. But when you're out there, give it
everything you've got,''' Yount said. ``When you're young, you
don't want to listen to your brother telling you stuff like that,
but it was true.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Yount never considered himself much of a student, he
had an analytical approach to the game that came from his father,
who was an engineer at Rocketdyne.
</P>
<P>
   All that plus boundless energy gave Young an almost unfair
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't leave after a practice without hitting him another
100 ground balls,'' O'Connor said. ``We wanted to work and he had
his sights well set.''
</P>
<P>
   Yount gives much of the credit for his early development to
Cohen, his coach in the Sunrise Little League in Woodland Hills.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt Clem Cohen was the start of my baseball
career,'' Yount once said. ``It was at the Little League level, but
that was the start. I was very fortunate to get off on the right
foot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, my dad was always there for me, but when it came to
the point of playing organized baseball, it was Clem Cohen who got
that ball rolling.''
</P>
<P>
   Yount rose through the Pony League and went on to Taft, where he
was just 5-foot-7 and 135 pounds as a sophomore.
</P>
<P>
   He started growing late in his junior year, but at times it made
him awkward and he committed 13 errors at short.
</P>
<P>
   But he always had his support group, which included his parents,
Larry and many of the notable players in the area. Dempsey, who
played 24 years in the majors, had gone to Crespi and played on the
same American Legion team as Larry Yount. Robin was the batboy.
</P>
<P>
   Other influences included Rick Auerbach, a Taft product who
later played in the big leagues. Kevin Kennedy, former manager of
the Texas Rangers and Boston Red Sox and now a baseball analyst for
Fox Sports, was a teammate at Taft.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were always guys around playing ball,'' said Dempsey.
``But I think the biggest change came after his junior year.''
</P>
<P>
   By that time, Larry Yount was at the Triple-A level for Houston.
He would later reach the majors but hurt his arm warming up in his
first game and had to leave. Larry Yount, now a successful real
estate developer in Phoenix, never made it back to the big leagues
and is believed to be the only pitcher in major-league history to
appear in a game but never throw a pitch.
</P>
<P>
   But back in the summer of 1972, Larry invited Robin to go on the
road with him. Robin shagged fly balls and took batting practice.
More importantly, he learned what it was like to be a professional.
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually lived the lifestyle of a minor-league baseball
player,'' Yount said. ``Whether you can handle it or not in the big
leagues _ well, you never know until you go through it. But I had
lived it before I even got into it. So I think in that respect it
was a big advantage to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Yount started his senior year two inches taller, 20 pounds
heavier and a whole lot wiser. After the season, he was the third
overall pick in the June amateur draft.
</P>
<P>
   He played 64 minor-league games in Newark, N.J. In 1974, Brewers
manager Del Crandall made Yount the starting shortstop, five months
before his 19th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-five years later, Yount is heading into the Hall of Fame
with lessons that have lasted a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had the attitude I wanted to play like it was the last time
I would play the game,'' he said. ``I gave it everything I had
every time I went out there. That's what I'm most proud of.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-99 2329EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
