<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENNEDY-BESSETTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOURNERS PAY RESPECTS TO THIRD VICTIM OF KENNEDY CRASH  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JULIAN E. BARNES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENWICH, Conn. _ More than 600 mourners gathered here Saturday
evening to pay respects to Lauren Bessette, the third victim of the
plane crash that also killed John F. Kennedy Jr. and Carolyn
Bessette Kennedy just over a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   Lauren Bessette, 34, was remembered as ``rich, vibrant and
multifaceted'' in a eulogy delivered by her uncle, Jack Messina.
Mourners also recalled her as a successful investment banker and a
lover of opera during a ceremony that lasted just over an hour. The
memorial Mass was held at Christ Church, a neo-Gothic Episcopal
church.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bessette's ashes were dropped into the sea on Thursday along
with those of her sister and Kennedy, who were mourned Friday
during a memorial service on Manhattan's Upper East Side.
</P>
<P>
   In the days since the crash, Ms. Bessette's life was curiously
both thrust into the open and draped in shadow. Among the three
crash victims, hers was a private life that has been mostly
overlooked as Americans lingered over images of Kennedy and his
wife.
</P>
<P>
   But Saturday, Greenwich turned its attention to Lauren Bessette,
in the place where she was raised and educated. Ms. Bessette and
her twin sister, Lisa Ann, attended Central Junior High and
Greenwich High School. After graduating from high school in 1982,
Lauren Bessette attended Hobart and William Smith Colleges in
Geneva, N.Y., where she majored in economics. In 1991, after
graduating from Wharton School of Business, Ms. Bessette joined
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, the investment bank, where she worked
as a financial adviser.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Ms. Bessette began a four-year stint in the company's
Hong Kong office, rising first to vice president and then to
principal when she returned to Manhattan in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   As guests began arriving around 5:45 p.m. until the service
began at 7 p.m., photographers called out the names of members of
the Kennedy family and snapped pictures from afar.
</P>
<P>
   In attendance were Ms. Bessette's sister, Lisa Ann, her father,
William Bessette, her mother, Ann Freeman, and her stepfather,
Richard Freeman. Many members of the Kennedy clan also attended,
including Edward M. Kennedy and Caroline Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   In a eulogy for Ms. Bessette, Messina offered the congregants
richly detailed memories about her, including the day she played
miniature golf in her backyard, dressed in pajamas and high heels.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the events of these past eight days have taught us anything
it is to honor the moment,'' he said. ``Cherish those around you.
Try to find a balance between work and family. Contribute something
to your community, and above all share the love you feel for each
other each and every day.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Hugh Tudor-Foley, an assistant to the rector at Christ
Church, said that Robert F. Kennedy Jr. read a quote from
Shakespeare during the service and two of Ms. Bessette's friends
offered remembrances. He said that Carole Radziwill delivered a
reading in honor of Carolyn Bessette Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tearful and it was joyful and it accomplished what the
family wanted, which was to celebrate the lives of their two
children,'' Turor-Foley said.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the church, a few Greenwich residents laid flowers on
the grass.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember her as an eclectic and fun person,'' said David
Dall, 35, a classmate of Ms. Bessette's at Greenwich High. ``She
was friends with everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Theo A. Constantine, 38, a member of Greenwich High's class of
1979, said he came to pay his respects to someone the world did not
know very well.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a community, we need to show our support. The Kennedys have
more than enough support and Carolyn was recognized through them,''
said Constantine. ``The focus hasn't been equal and this is a nice
way to remember Lauren as an individual.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
