A3042 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHICAGO-RELIANCE-REAL     07-24 1283
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHICAGO-RELIANCE-REAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESTORING A CENTURY-OLD GLASS TOWER IN CHICAGO  
(HLW)
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID W. DUNLAP   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Six decades ahead of its time, the crystalline
Reliance Building soared skyward in 1895 as a scintillating rebuke
to its somber masonry surroundings, like a diamond in the
rough-hewn Loop.
</P>
<P>
   Not until the late 1950s would Chicago again build an office
tower with so much glass.
</P>
<P>
   By then, the Reliance was a decrepit antique, worth more for its
retail space on State and Washington Streets than for the 13 small
floors of offices above. First stripped of its cornice, it was then
stripped of dignity when its delicate terra-cotta facade was
overwhelmed by a neon sign for a discount clothier.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the cornice is back. The terra cotta is crisp and
gleaming again. The clothier is gone, and the tea-leaf reader and
prostitutes who worked upstairs have been replaced by construction
crews.
</P>
<P>
   The Reliance Building is to reopen in September as a 122-room
boutique hotel, the Burnham, named for the architectural firm that
designed it: D.H. Burnham &AMP; Co., best known in New York for the
Flatiron Building.
</P>
<P>
   It is an astonishing transformation. Five years ago, the
Reliance Building ``was on the brink of falling apart,'' Mayor
Richard M. Daley said. The city acquired the landmark building by
eminent domain for $1.2 million and undertook a $6.6-million
exterior rehabilitation intended to jump-start redevelopment.
</P>
<P>
   The process was not without critics in the City Council, who
wondered why City Hall was pouring money into a building that
private real estate interests had abandoned. One alderman suggested
using the money to blow up the Reliance Building, allowing the city
to sell the land clear and free.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the Daley administration prevailed. More important,
it found a private development team _ the McCaffery Interests,
Mansur &AMP; Co. and the Granite Development Corp. _ willing to
undertake the last $19 million leg of the journey, with $2.5
million more in city assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Although city officials project a return on the investment in
the form of tax revenues and spending, Commissioner Christopher R.
Hill of the Planning and Development Department said the money was
almost beside the point.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the economics in the world really don't matter,'' he said.
``This building had to be saved to give people a better
understanding of the history of high-rise architecture in
Chicago.''
</P>
<P>
   The 5,500-square-foot floors did not make sense for modern
offices. But Dan McCaffery, president of McCaffery Interests, said,
``When we looked at it, we thought, `My goodness, you could lay
this out in pretty darn good hotel modules.'''
</P>
<P>
   The result _ already apparent on floors where major
reconstruction is nearing completion _ will be a remarkable
interior, with public hallways looking much the way they did a
century ago; not like a hotel at all but like a well-appointed hive
of business.
</P>
<P>
   The original white Carrara marble wainscoting and ceilings are
being kept, as are the mahogany trim, transoms and doors; the
terrazzo floors; the glass partitions (though there are new
fire-resistant walls behind them) and even the doorknobs, mail
slots and ornamental hinges, made of a metal called magnetite with
a coating that yields a blue-black finish.
</P>
<P>
   Winding through the upper floors will be the original open
cast-iron staircase, whose elegant balustrade carries the same
decorative device _ a four-petal Gothic flower, or quatrefoil _
that is used in the undulating ribbons of white terra cotta on the
exterior.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than enclosing this staircase, as current building codes
would require if it were the only means of exit in a fire, the
developers are building two new enclosed stairways through the
building. They also plan to recreate the ornate, two-story-high
elevator lobby.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, one of the original structural columns _ an open,
diamond-shaped riser built up from riveted steel sections _ will be
left exposed to show how the tower was constructed.
</P>
<P>
   The architects are Antunovich Associates of Chicago, working
with McClier Corp., an architectural and engineering concern based
in Chicago that also prepared a historical structural report on the
Reliance and oversaw the exterior restoration.
</P>
<P>
   Given the deteriorating condition of the terra cotta facade,
there was no time to lose. ``It's amazing that it wasn't raining
off the building,'' said Gunny Harboe, director of preservation at
McClier.
</P>
<P>
   About 2,000 of the 12,000 terra cotta pieces were replaced. The
cornice was recreated in cast aluminum. And the single layer
plate-glass windows were replaced with double-glazed insulated
windows.
</P>
<P>
   The operator will be the Kimpton Hotel and Restaurant Group of
San Francisco. In Chicago, Kimpton already runs the 489-room Hotel
Allegro (formerly the Bismarck) and the 193-room Hotel Monaco
(formerly the Oxford House), both downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Elements like the quatrefoil motif are being used in the new
furnishings and textiles, said Susan Caruso, president of
Intra-Spec of Marina del Rey, Calif., which is designing the lobby,
guest rooms and public corridors.
</P>
<P>
   Ranging from 350 to 450 square feet, the rooms are what a
hotelier would call intimate and a guest might call small. Rates
will begin at $145 a night for rooms, $195 for the larger suites.
</P>
<P>
   The 21-foot-high ground floor, originally occupied by the Carson
Pirie Scott &AMP; Co. department store, will become the 65-seat Cafe
Daniel. The tacky commercial accretions of recent decades have been
stripped away. The plan is to recreate the appearance of the
original uninterrupted window wall.
</P>
<P>
   You got the sense that the building was floating on this
double-height story of all glass,'' said Brian Goeken, senior
preservation planner in the landmarks division of the planning
agency. ``It's really going to glow. That's the intent, to play off
this transparency.''
</P>
<P>
   The transparency of the Reliance Building was made possible by
steel-frame construction, which allowed for vast expanses of glass
because exterior walls no longer had to bear the structural load,
as with traditional construction. The central panes in the
second-story bays measure almost 8 by 11 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Big windows were not merely an esthetic gesture. They helped
capture every bit of available daylight. Artificial illumination at
the time consisted of carbon filament bulbs, which gave off an
anemic golden glow not much stronger than candlelight.
</P>
<P>
   What glass-front buildings gained in illumination, however, they
sacrificed in climate control. And so it was not until the
development of modern heating, ventilating and air-conditioning
systems in the 1950s that they proliferated.
</P>
<P>
   The earliest designs for the Reliance Building were by John
Wellborn Root. After his death in 1891, the project was carried to
completion by Charles B. Atwood. The hotel will not carry their
names, however, but that of their more famous partner, Daniel
Hudson Burnham, author of the 1909 Chicago Plan, a sweeping attempt
at taming the chaotic metropolis through the development of orderly
transportation arteries and public amenities like a reclaimed
lakefront.
</P>
<P>
   Atwood does have his admirers. In ``The Chicago School of
Architecture'' (University of Chicago Press, 1964), the
architectural historian Carl W. Condit gave him credit for
extraordinary prescience. ``One short step further in the design of
the Reliance Building and he would have produced the transparent
tower that Mies van der Rohe imagined,'' Condit wrote. ``If any
work of structural art in the 19th century anticipated the future,
it is this one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
