<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-24 23:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3052 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS     07-24 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV01-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Aug. 1)  
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; AUTOBIOGRAPHY OF RED: A NOVEL IN VERSE &LR;  By Anne Carson. Vintage
Contemporaries, $12. In this literary hybrid, a poet and scholar
reimagines an ancient Greek myth as a destructive love affair
between Hercules and a winged red monster, who also happens to be a
gifted American boy. ``Carson writes in language any poet would
kill for: sensuous and funny, poignant, musical and tender,'' Ruth
Padel wrote last year in The New York Times Book Review.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SUMMER OF DELIVERANCE: A MEMOIR OF FATHER AND SON &LR;  By
Christopher Dickey. Touchstone/Simon &AMP; Schuster, $14. This angry,
affectionate account portrays the author's father, the brilliant
but unstable James Dickey, as a chronic liar and boozer who felt
compelled to reinvent himself every day. Yet Dickey, best known for
his novel ``Deliverance,'' was also a magnetic showman and an
enthusiastic parent who managed to earn the love of his children.
```Summer of Deliverance' contains more sex and violence and
alcohol and celebrity high jinks than a year's worth of tabloids,''
David Kirby wrote in 1998. ``But it contains poetry, too, and a
father-son conflict worthy of the pen of a Sophocles.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OYSTER &LR;  By Janette Turner Hospital. Norton, $14. At the center
of this dreamlike novel, set in a parched mining town in the
Australian outback, are a charismatic cult leader and his
followers, who may or may not be responsible for the disappearance
of strangers who turn up looking for lost sons and daughters. ``It
is both a rare story and an accomplished piece of writing,'' Dale
Peck wrote in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In  &UR; THE SERVICE OF CLOUDS &LR; , by Delia Falconer (Picador USA,
$13), a pharmacist's assistant falls in love with a half-mad
photographer who arrives in her frontier outpost in Australia's
Blue Mountains in 1907 to take pictures of clouds. Last year the
reviewer Deirdre McNamer called this first novel ``an exuberant
meditation on the `history of the air,' the art of seeing and the
end of romance as the pre-moderns knew it.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ECOLOGY OF FEAR: LOS ANGELES AND THE IMAGINATION OF DISASTER &LR; 
By Mike Davis. Vintage, $14. This fervid polemic on southern
California's alarming natural history _ and the social and
psychological forces it has unleashed _ raised a lot of hackles
among critics who attacked the author's methods and some of his
assertions. Last year the reviewer William Finnegan praised
``Davis' great intellectual breadth and agility.''
</P>
<P>
   In  &UR; PARADISE LOST: CALIFORNIA'S EXPERIENCE, AMERICA'S FUTURE &LR; ,
by Peter Schrag (University of California, $14.95), a journalist
links the decline in the state's public services and financial
health to the advent of rule by voter initiative. In 1998 in The
New York Times Book Review, Nicholas Lemann called this an ``angry
and persuasive book.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SAILING ALONE AROUND THE WORLD &LR;  By Joshua Slocum. Edited by
Thomas Philbrick. Penguin, $7.95. The author of this true-life
ripping yarn tells how he braved stormy seas, narrowly escaped
pirates and met the explorer Henry Stanley during his three-year,
46,000-mile circumnavigation in a 40-foot sloop at the turn of the
century. His lively memoir is ``full of interest to lovers of
adventures,'' The New York Times wrote in 1900.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OUT OF SHEER RAGE: WRESTLING WITH D.H. LAWRENCE &LR;  By Geoff Dyer.
North Point, $13. The author set out to write a scholarly study of
Lawrence but came up instead with this wild, meandering book, which
includes musings on everything from Italian drivers to his own
hatred of seafood. ``Unsystematically and with great humor, it
lights up what really matters to him about his hero,'' Christopher
Lehmann-Haupt wrote in The New York Times last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHITE BOYS: STORIES &LR;  By Reginald McKnight. Owl/Holt, $13. Most
of the characters in these stories are middle-class blacks seeking
to make connections across the color divide, and weary of the
script that society has given them. ``What wins you over ... is
McKnight's attentiveness to the complexities of racial
antagonism,'' Rand Richards Cooper wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE BIG CON: THE STORY OF THE CONFIDENCE MAN &LR;  By David W.
Maurer. Anchor/Doubleday, $12.95. A linguistics professor explores
the world of grifters and scam artists, and the many means by which
``marks'' (victims) are ``taken off'' (cheated). The book,
originally published in 1940, is ``entertainment for crime
literature addicts'' and ``a textbook for prospective confidence
men,'' Edward Frank Allen wrote in The New York Times Book Review.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CORDELIA UNDERWOOD: OR, THE MARVELOUS BEGINNINGS OF THE
MOOSEPATH LEAGUE &LR;  By Van Reid. Penguin, $12.95. This genial first
novel, which takes place in Maine in 1896, has to do with a young
woman who inherits some land from her seafaring uncle, but it's
laced with red herrings and a bunch of eccentric locals with
stories of their own. ``Reid's gazillion characters sparkle,'' Kit
Reed wrote in 1998. ``Escapists will be charmed.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE CLAIRVOYANT &LR;  By Marian Thurm. Harper Paperbacks, $6.50.
Victor Mackenzie is a psychic loose cannon who can't control what
he sees and who longs for a little mystery in his life. He gets his
wish when he gazes at the palm of a single mother whose future
involves not only her but him. In 1997 the reviewer Peter Lefcourt
called this an ``entertaining novel.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
